# Static Range Sum Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1646
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (staticrangesum.cpp)`](./staticrangesum.cpp)

## Problem

Answer many inclusive range-sum queries on an array that never changes.

## Reasoning

Summing each range directly is $O(nq)$ in the worst case. Since there are no updates, preprocess cumulative information once. Define

$$
P[i]=\sum_{j=1}^{i}x_j,\qquad P[0]=0.
$$

The prefix through $b$ contains both the desired range $[a,b]$ and the unwanted prefix $[1,a-1]$. Subtracting gives

$$
\sum_{j=a}^{b}x_j=P[b]-P[a-1].
$$

This identity turns every query into two array accesses.

## Algorithm

1. Build prefix sums from left to right.
2. For each query $[a,b]$, output `P[b]-P[a-1]`.

## Correctness

### Lemma

For every $i$, $P[i]$ equals the sum of the first $i$ array values.

#### Proof

$P[0]=0$. The recurrence $P[i]=P[i-1]+x_i$ appends exactly the next value, so induction proves the claim. $\square$

### Theorem

Every query answer is the sum of values in its requested range.

#### Proof

By the lemma, $P[b]$ sums indices 1 through $b$. Removing $P[a-1]$ cancels exactly indices 1 through $a-1$, leaving precisely $a$ through $b$. $\square$

### Complexity

Preprocessing takes $O(n)$ time. Each query takes $O(1)$ time, and the prefix array uses $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The zero prefix makes ranges beginning at 1 use the same formula. `long long` is required because a range sum can exceed 32-bit integer limits.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, q;
    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> p(n + 1, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        ll x; cin >> x;
        p[i] = p[i-1] + x;
    }

    while (q--){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        cout << p[b] - p[a-1] << '\n';
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $[3,1,4,1,5]$, prefixes are $[0,3,4,8,9,14]$. Query $[2,4]$ returns $P[4]-P[1]=9-3=6$, matching $1+4+1$.

## Takeaway

Static range queries often become constant time when the operation has an inverse that cancels an unwanted prefix.

### Related problems

Range Xor Queries uses the same idea with XOR. Dynamic Range Sum Queries replaces static prefixes with a Fenwick tree.

