# Static Range Minimum Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1647
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (staticrangemin.cpp)`](./staticrangemin.cpp)

## Problem

Answer many minimum queries on inclusive ranges of an immutable array.

## Reasoning

Minimum has no inverse, so two prefix minima cannot cancel an unwanted prefix. Its idempotence, $\min(x,x)=x$, suggests a sparse table instead.

Let `sp[k][i]` be the minimum of the length-$2^k$ interval beginning at $i$. Two half-length blocks give

$$
sp[k][i]=\min(sp[k-1][i],sp[k-1][i+2^{k-1}]).
$$

For a query of length $L$, choose $k=\lfloor\log_2L\rfloor$. A block of length $2^k$ from the left endpoint and another ending at the right endpoint cover the entire range. They may overlap, but duplicate elements do not change a minimum.

## Algorithm

1. Store array values as sparse-table level 0.
2. Build each larger power-of-two level from two halves.
3. For query $[a,b]$, compute $k=\lfloor\log_2(b-a+1)\rfloor$.
4. Return the minimum of the blocks starting at $a$ and ending at $b$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

`sp[k][i]` is the minimum of its stated power-of-two interval.

#### Proof

Level 0 contains one value. Each higher interval is the union of its two stored halves, so the recurrence is correct by induction. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The two query blocks cover $[a,b]$ and contain no index outside it.

#### Proof

Both have length $2^k\le L$ and are anchored at opposite endpoints, so they stay inside. Since $2^{k+1}>L$, their combined length $2^{k+1}$ exceeds $L$, forcing overlap or contact and hence complete coverage. $\square$

### Theorem

Every query returns the range minimum.

#### Proof

Lemma 1 gives each block minimum and Lemma 2 covers every range element. Overlap cannot affect minimum, so the minimum of the two block minima is exact. $\square$

### Complexity

Building takes $O(n\log n)$ time and space. Each query takes $O(1)$ time.

## Implementation

Inputs are converted to zero-based endpoints. `__builtin_clz` computes the floor logarithm for the positive range length. Only table cells whose full block fits are built.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, q;
    cin >> n >> q;

    int LOG = 1;
    while ((1 << LOG) < n) LOG++;
    LOG++;

    vector<vi> sp(LOG, vi(n));
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> sp[0][i];

    for (int k = 1; k < LOG; k++)
        for (int i = 0; i + (1 << k) <= n; i++)
            sp[k][i] = min(sp[k-1][i], sp[k-1][i + (1 << (k-1))]);

    while (q--){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        a--; b--;                       // 0-indexed
        int k = 31 - __builtin_clz(b - a + 1);
        cout << min(sp[k][a], sp[k][b - (1 << k) + 1]) << '\n';
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For a query of length 6, $k=2$ and each chosen block has length 4. The left block covers offsets 0 through 3 and the right block offsets 2 through 5. Their overlap is harmless, and together they cover all six values.

## Takeaway

Sparse tables answer static idempotent range queries in constant time because overlapping blocks may safely cover the interval.

### Related problems

Dynamic Range Minimum Queries uses a segment tree when values change. Lowest-common-ancestor sparse tables rely on a related doubling structure.

