# Dynamic Range Sum Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1648
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (dynamicrangesum.cpp)`](./dynamicrangesum.cpp)

## Problem

Support point assignments and inclusive range-sum queries on an array.

## Reasoning

Static prefix sums answer quickly but one assignment changes every later prefix. A Fenwick tree stores sums of power-of-two suffixes of prefixes, allowing both a point delta and a prefix sum in logarithmic time.

The tree supports addition, while the operation assigns a new value. Keep `cur[k]` and convert assignment to delta $u-cur[k]$. Adding that delta to every Fenwick aggregate containing $k$ makes the represented array value exactly $u$.

As in static prefix sums, range $[a,b]$ equals prefix $b$ minus prefix $a-1$.

## Algorithm

1. Insert all initial values into a Fenwick tree and save them in `cur`.
2. For assignment $x_k=u$, add $u-cur[k]$ at $k$, then set `cur[k]=u`.
3. For query $[a,b]$, output `pre(b)-pre(a-1)`.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After every assignment, the Fenwick tree represents the current array.

#### Proof

Initially every value is inserted. An assignment adds exactly the difference between new and old value to aggregates containing its position, changing that represented point to the new value and leaving every other point unchanged. $\square$

### Lemma 2

`pre(i)` equals the sum of current positions 1 through $i$.

#### Proof

Fenwick query indices partition this prefix into disjoint stored blocks. By Lemma 1 each block sum is current, so their sum is the prefix sum. $\square$

### Theorem

All range-sum answers are correct.

#### Proof

By Lemma 2, subtracting `pre(a-1)` from `pre(b)` cancels exactly the values before $a$ and leaves $[a,b]$. $\square$

### Complexity

Initialization is $O(n\log n)$ in this implementation. Every operation takes $O(\log n)$ time. Storage is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

Fenwick indices are one-based. Values and tree sums use `long long`. Retaining `cur` is necessary because an assignment is not itself an additive update.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q;
vector<ll> bit;

void upd(int i, ll v){
    for (; i <= n; i += i & -i) bit[i] += v;
}
ll pre(int i){
    ll r = 0;
    for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) r += bit[i];
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> cur(n + 1);
    bit.assign(n + 1, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        cin >> cur[i];
        upd(i, cur[i]);
    }

    while (q--){
        int t; cin >> t;
        if (t == 1){
            int k; ll u; cin >> k >> u;
            upd(k, u - cur[k]);         // apply delta
            cur[k] = u;
        } else {
            int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
            cout << pre(b) - pre(a-1) << '\n';
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $[2,5,1]$, assigning position 2 to 8 adds delta 3. The represented array becomes $[2,8,1]$, and query $[2,3]$ returns $9$ by prefix subtraction.

## Takeaway

When a data structure supports addition but the interface specifies assignment, store the old value and translate the operation into a delta.

### Related problems

Static Range Sum Queries needs no update structure. Range Update Queries reverses the roles of update and query using differences.

