# Dynamic Range Minimum Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1649
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (dynamicrangemin.cpp)`](./dynamicrangemin.cpp)

## Problem

Support point assignments and inclusive range-minimum queries.

## Reasoning

Minimum cannot be recovered by subtracting prefixes, and updates rule out a static sparse table. A segment tree stores the minimum of each recursively partitioned interval. Assigning one leaf changes only its $O(\log n)$ ancestors.

The iterative query uses a half-open interval $[l,r)$. When the left boundary is a right child, its node is a complete remaining block and is consumed. When the right boundary is a right boundary after decrement, that node is likewise consumed. Moving both boundaries upward repeats until the interval is exhausted.

## Algorithm

1. Round the leaf count `sz` up to a power of two and fill unused leaves with infinity.
2. Build internal minima bottom-up.
3. For an assignment, replace one leaf and recompute ancestors.
4. Convert query $[a,b]$ to zero-based half-open $[a-1,b)$ and combine its canonical segment-tree nodes.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

Every segment-tree node stores the minimum of its represented interval.

#### Proof

Leaves store their values or infinity padding. Each internal node stores the minimum of its two child intervals, whose union is its interval. Bottom-up construction and update recomputation preserve this invariant. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The query loop selects disjoint nodes whose intervals partition the requested range.

#### Proof

Boundary nodes are selected only when fully contained but their parents would cross a boundary. Removing them and moving upward preserves the unprocessed middle. The loop ends only when no middle remains, giving a disjoint complete partition. $\square$

### Theorem

Every query returns the current range minimum.

#### Proof

By Lemma 2 the selected nodes partition the range, and by Lemma 1 each supplies its interval minimum. Their minimum is therefore the minimum of all requested values. $\square$

### Complexity

Building takes $O(n)$ time. Each assignment and query takes $O(\log n)$ time. The tree uses $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

`LLONG_MAX` is the identity and padding value. The public range is inclusive, but `qry` receives a half-open interval. During update, the loop recomputes node 1 and then terminates when the index becomes zero.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q, sz;
vector<ll> t;

void upd(int p, ll v){
    for (t[p += sz] = v, p >>= 1; p >= 1; p >>= 1)
        t[p] = min(t[p<<1], t[p<<1|1]);
}
ll qry(int l, int r){                   // [l, r)
    ll res = LLONG_MAX;
    for (l += sz, r += sz; l < r; l >>= 1, r >>= 1){
        if (l & 1) res = min(res, t[l++]);
        if (r & 1) res = min(res, t[--r]);
    }
    return res;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    sz = 1;
    while (sz < n) sz <<= 1;
    t.assign(2*sz, LLONG_MAX);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> t[sz + i];
    for (int i = sz - 1; i >= 1; i--) t[i] = min(t[i<<1], t[i<<1|1]);

    while (q--){
        int op; cin >> op;
        if (op == 1){
            int k; ll u; cin >> k >> u;
            upd(k - 1, u);
        } else {
            int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
            cout << qry(a - 1, b) << '\n';
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

With eight leaves, query $[2,7)$ decomposes into the leaf at 2, the block $[3,5)$ as appropriate canonical nodes, and the remaining right block. Each is wholly contained; no outside leaf contributes.

## Takeaway

Segment trees support associative range aggregates under updates by maintaining one invariant per interval and decomposing queries into canonical nodes.

### Related problems

Static Range Minimum Queries exploits immutability for $O(1)$ queries. Hotel Queries augments a maximum segment tree with guided descent.

