# Range Xor Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1650
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (rangexor.cpp)`](./rangexor.cpp)

## Problem

Answer many inclusive range XOR queries on a fixed array.

## Reasoning

Define prefix XOR $P[i]=x_1\oplus\cdots\oplus x_i$. XOR is its own inverse: $v\oplus v=0$ and $v\oplus0=v$. Therefore

$$
P[b]\oplus P[a-1]
$$

cancels every value before $a$ twice and leaves every value in $[a,b]$ once. No update support is needed, so a prefix array is sufficient.

## Algorithm

1. Build prefix XORs with $P[0]=0$.
2. Answer $[a,b]$ with `P[b] ^ P[a-1]`.

## Correctness

### Theorem

The algorithm returns the XOR of exactly the requested range.

#### Proof

Expand both prefixes. Values $x_1$ through $x_{a-1}$ occur twice and cancel by $x\oplus x=0$. Values $x_a$ through $x_b$ occur once and remain. $\square$

### Complexity

Preprocessing takes $O(n)$ time and $O(n)$ space. Each query takes $O(1)$ time.

## Implementation

The array is one-indexed conceptually, and prefix 0 handles $a=1$. Parentheses around the XOR expression make the intended operation explicit in output.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, q;
    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> p(n + 1, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        ll x; cin >> x;
        p[i] = p[i-1] ^ x;
    }

    while (q--){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        cout << (p[b] ^ p[a-1]) << '\n';
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $[5,2,7]$, prefixes are $0,5,7,0$. Query $[2,3]$ returns $0\oplus5=5$, and indeed $2\oplus7=5$.

## Takeaway

Prefix cancellation works for any group-like operation. XOR is especially convenient because the operation and its inverse are identical.

### Related problems

Static Range Sum Queries uses subtraction for cancellation. Range Update Queries uses a difference representation instead.

