# Range Update Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1651
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (rangeupdate.cpp)`](./rangeupdate.cpp)

## Problem

Support adding a value to every element of an inclusive range and querying one current array position.

## Reasoning

The difference array $d$ of an array satisfies $x_k=x_k^{initial}+\sum_{i=1}^{k}d_i$ for accumulated updates. Adding $u$ to $[a,b]$ changes this update-difference representation only at two boundaries: add $u$ at $a$ and add $-u$ at $b+1$.

Updates arrive online, so store these boundary changes in a Fenwick tree. Its prefix sum at $k$ is the total contribution of all range additions covering $k$. The original array remains separate because it never changes directly.

## Algorithm

1. Save the initial array and initialize an empty Fenwick tree of update differences.
2. For update $[a,b]$ by $u$, add $u$ at $a$ and $-u$ at $b+1$.
3. For point query $k$, output `initial[k]+pre(k)`.

## Correctness

### Lemma

One range update contributes $u$ to the Fenwick prefix at $k$ exactly when $a\le k\le b$.

#### Proof

If $k<a$, neither boundary is included. If $a\le k\le b$, only $+u$ is included. If $k>b$, both $+u$ and $-u$ are included and cancel. $\square$

### Theorem

Every point query returns its current value after all prior range additions.

#### Proof

By the lemma, each prior update contributes exactly its addition when it covers $k$ and zero otherwise. Fenwick sums are additive, so `pre(k)` is their total contribution. Adding the initial value gives the current one. $\square$

### Complexity

Every update and query takes $O(\log n)$ time. The initial array and Fenwick tree use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

Calling `upd(n+1,...)` is safe: the Fenwick loop immediately does nothing because its bound is `i<=n`. All accumulated values use `long long`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q;
vector<ll> bit;

void upd(int i, ll v){
    for (; i <= n; i += i & -i) bit[i] += v;
}
ll pre(int i){
    ll r = 0;
    for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) r += bit[i];
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> cur(n + 1);
    bit.assign(n + 1, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> cur[i];

    while (q--){
        int t; cin >> t;
        if (t == 1){
            int a, b; ll u; cin >> a >> b >> u;
            upd(a, u);                  // diff array: +u from a
            upd(b + 1, -u);             // ...cancelled after b
        } else {
            int k; cin >> k;
            cout << cur[k] + pre(k) << '\n';
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Add 4 to positions 2 through 5. The difference structure receives $+4$ at 2 and $-4$ at 6. Prefixes at positions 2 through 5 include only the first marker, while position 6 and beyond include both and receive zero net change.

## Takeaway

Range add plus point query is the natural online form of a difference array: boundary updates and one prefix query.

### Related problems

Dynamic Range Sum Queries uses point updates and range queries, the Fenwick dual. Range Updates and Sums supports both range updates and range sums with lazy propagation.

