# Forest Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1652
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (forest.cpp)`](./forest.cpp)

## Problem

Given a fixed square grid, count trees inside many axis-aligned inclusive rectangles.

## Reasoning

Define the two-dimensional prefix sum $P[y][x]$ as the number of trees in rows 1 through $y$ and columns 1 through $x$. Its construction uses inclusion-exclusion:

$$
P[y][x]=cell[y][x]+P[y-1][x]+P[y][x-1]-P[y-1][x-1].
$$

For a query rectangle, start with the prefix ending at its lower-right corner, subtract the regions above and left, then add back their overlap because it was subtracted twice.

## Algorithm

1. Convert each grid cell to 1 for a tree and 0 otherwise.
2. Build the two-dimensional prefix table.
3. Answer rectangle $(y_1,x_1)$ through $(y_2,x_2)$ by
   `P[y2][x2]-P[y1-1][x2]-P[y2][x1-1]+P[y1-1][x1-1]`.

## Correctness

### Theorem

The query formula returns exactly the number of trees in the requested rectangle.

#### Proof

The large prefix contains the target plus cells above it and left of it. The two subtractions remove those outside strips. Their upper-left intersection was removed twice, so adding it once restores its net removal to one. Every target cell remains once and every outside cell zero times. $\square$

### Complexity

Preprocessing takes $O(n^2)$ time and space. Each query takes $O(1)$ time.

## Implementation

Row and column zero are globally zero-initialized sentinels, so border rectangles require no branches. Coordinates remain one-based throughout.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q;
int p[1001][1001];

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        string row; cin >> row;
        for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++){
            int a = (row[j-1] == '*');
            p[i][j] = a + p[i-1][j] + p[i][j-1] - p[i-1][j-1];
        }
    }

    while (q--){
        int y1, x1, y2, x2; cin >> y1 >> x1 >> y2 >> x2;
        cout << p[y2][x2] - p[y1-1][x2] - p[y2][x1-1] + p[y1-1][x1-1] << '\n';
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For rectangle rows 2 through 4 and columns 3 through 5, begin with prefix $(4,5)$, subtract prefixes $(1,5)$ and $(4,2)$, then restore prefix $(1,2)$. The remaining counted cells are exactly the $3\times3$ rectangle.

## Takeaway

Multidimensional prefix sums extend one-dimensional prefix cancellation through inclusion-exclusion over boundaries.

### Related problems

Forest Queries II replaces the static table with a two-dimensional Fenwick tree. Static Range Sum Queries is the one-dimensional version.

