# Hotel Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1143
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (hotel.cpp)`](./hotel.cpp)

## Problem

For each group size, place the group in the leftmost hotel with enough free rooms, decrease that capacity, and output its index or zero if none fits.

## Reasoning

Scanning hotels for each group is quadratic. A segment tree storing interval maximum answers the feasibility question: an interval contains a valid hotel exactly when its maximum is at least the group size.

This aggregate also guides a leftmost search. If the root maximum is too small, no hotel works. Otherwise begin at the root. If the left child's maximum is sufficient, the leftmost feasible leaf must lie there; if not, the whole left interval is impossible and the search moves right. At the leaf, subtract the group size and recompute maxima upward.

## Algorithm

1. Build a maximum segment tree over hotel capacities.
2. For group size $r$, return zero if the root maximum is below $r$.
3. Otherwise descend, preferring the left child whenever its maximum is at least $r$.
4. At the reached leaf, subtract $r$, rebuild ancestors, and output its one-based index.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

At each descent node, the chosen child contains the leftmost feasible hotel in that node's interval.

#### Proof

If the left maximum is at least $r$, some left hotel is feasible and every right hotel has a larger index, so choosing left is necessary. Otherwise no left hotel is feasible, and root feasibility of the current node guarantees one in the right child. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The reached leaf is the globally leftmost hotel with sufficient capacity.

#### Proof

The root covers all hotels, and repeated application of Lemma 1 preserves the leftmost feasible hotel until one leaf remains. $\square$

### Theorem

Every group is assigned exactly as required and all later capacities are correct.

#### Proof

If the root fails, its maximum proves no capacity is sufficient. Otherwise Lemma 2 gives the correct hotel. Subtracting the group size applies the assignment, and recomputing ancestors restores every interval maximum. $\square$

### Complexity

Building takes $O(n)$ time. Each group takes $O(\log n)$ time and the tree uses $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

Unused power-of-two leaves contain zero, which cannot be selected for positive groups. The same descent function performs the capacity update before rebuilding the path.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, m, sz;
vector<ll> t;

int descend(ll r){                      // leftmost leaf with value >= r, then decrement
    if (t[1] < r) return 0;
    int p = 1;
    while (p < sz){
        p <<= 1;
        if (t[p] < r) p |= 1;           // left can't fit -> go right
    }
    t[p] -= r;
    int idx = p - sz + 1;
    for (p >>= 1; p >= 1; p >>= 1) t[p] = max(t[p<<1], t[p<<1|1]);
    return idx;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> m;

    sz = 1;
    while (sz < n) sz <<= 1;
    t.assign(2*sz, 0);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> t[sz + i];
    for (int i = sz - 1; i >= 1; i--) t[i] = max(t[i<<1], t[i<<1|1]);

    while (m--){
        ll r; cin >> r;
        cout << descend(r) << ' ';
    }
    cout << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For capacities $[3,1,4,2]$ and group size 2, the left half maximum is 3, so descend left. Its left leaf has capacity 3 and is chosen. Capacities become $[1,1,4,2]$; the next group of size 2 is directed to hotel 3.

## Takeaway

If an interval aggregate can certify whether a solution exists inside, a segment tree can often descend to the first feasible position in logarithmic time.

### Related problems

List Removals performs order-statistic descent on a Fenwick tree. Dynamic Range Minimum Queries uses aggregation without guided search.

