# List Removals

- **CSES problem:** 1749
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (listremoval.cpp)`](./listremoval.cpp)

## Problem

Repeatedly remove and print the value at a given one-based position in the current shrinking list.

## Reasoning

Physical deletion from an array shifts many elements and can cost $O(n^2)$. Keep original positions fixed and store an indicator 1 for every still-present index. The current rank of original index $i$ is the prefix sum through $i$.

The requested $p$th remaining element is therefore the smallest index whose indicator prefix sum is at least $p$. Fenwick binary lifting finds it by constructing the largest position whose prefix remains below $p$. At each power of two, a Fenwick partial sum tells whether that whole next block can be skipped.

After finding the index, subtract one at that position to remove it.

## Algorithm

1. Initialize a Fenwick tree with value 1 at every original position.
2. For each requested rank $p$, binary-lift through Fenwick powers to find the smallest index with prefix sum $p$.
3. Print the original value there and update its indicator by $-1$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

At all times, the Fenwick prefix at $i$ equals the number of remaining elements among original positions 1 through $i$.

#### Proof

Initially all indicators are one. Every removal changes exactly its one indicator to zero using delta $-1$. Fenwick prefixes sum these indicators. $\square$

### Lemma 2

`findk(p)` returns the original index of the $p$th remaining element.

#### Proof

The lifting invariant keeps `pos` as a position whose accumulated prefix is below $p$. A candidate block is skipped only when its entire sum is still below the remaining rank, in which case subtracting that block count preserves the desired rank in the suffix. When no power remains, `pos` is the largest index below the target prefix, so `pos+1` is the smallest prefix reaching $p$. Lemma 1 identifies it as the $p$th present index. $\square$

### Theorem

The printed sequence is exactly the sequence of requested removals.

#### Proof

Lemma 2 selects the correct current list position. Printing its fixed original value and changing its indicator to zero removes precisely that element, preserving Lemma 1 for the next operation. $\square$

### Complexity

Initialization takes $O(n\log n)$ here. Each selection and removal takes $O(\log n)$ time. Space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The starting binary-lifting power is the highest power of two not exceeding $n$. Fenwick internal values, not repeated prefix queries, let the search remain logarithmic.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n;
vector<ll> bit;

void upd(int i, ll v){
    for (; i <= n; i += i & -i) bit[i] += v;
}
int findk(ll k){                        // smallest idx with prefix sum == k
    int pos = 0, LOG = 31 - __builtin_clz(n);
    for (int pw = 1 << LOG; pw; pw >>= 1){
        if (pos + pw <= n && bit[pos + pw] < k){
            pos += pw;
            k -= bit[pos];
        }
    }
    return pos + 1;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n;

    vector<ll> x(n + 1);
    bit.assign(n + 1, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        cin >> x[i];
        upd(i, 1);                      // present
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        ll p; cin >> p;
        int idx = findk(p);
        cout << x[idx] << ' ';
        upd(idx, -1);                   // remove
    }
    cout << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For values `[10,20,30,40]`, removing rank 3 finds original index 3 and prints 30. Indicators become `[1,1,0,1]`. Removing rank 3 again now finds original index 4 and prints 40.

## Takeaway

Represent a mutable ordered set of fixed positions by 0/1 frequencies. Prefix sums become ranks, and Fenwick binary lifting inverts rank to position.

### Related problems

Hotel Queries descends a segment tree by feasibility. Josephus Problem II uses a related order-statistic structure.

