# Salary Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1144
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (salary.cpp)`](./salary.cpp)

## Problem

Maintain employee salaries under assignments and answer how many current salaries lie in an inclusive value interval.

## Reasoning

The queries concern value order, not employee-index order. Store a frequency distribution over salary values. A Fenwick prefix then counts salaries at most a threshold, and interval $[a,b]$ is `count(<=b)-count(<a)`.

Salary coordinates can be large, but only initial salaries and future assigned values can ever occur. Read all operations first, collect those values, sort them, and remove duplicates. This coordinate compression preserves order while mapping the relevant domain to $1..V$.

An assignment removes one frequency at the employee's old compressed salary and adds one at the new salary.

## Algorithm

1. Read initial salaries and all operations, collecting every value that may be assigned.
2. Sort and deduplicate these coordinates.
3. Build a Fenwick frequency tree of initial salaries.
4. On assignment, decrement the old coordinate and increment the new one.
5. On query $[a,b]$, use binary searches to find the first compressed value at least $a$ and the number of compressed values at most $b$, then subtract Fenwick prefixes.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

The Fenwick frequency at each compressed coordinate equals the number of employees currently earning that salary.

#### Proof

Initialization inserts every employee once. An assignment removes exactly that employee from the old value and adds it to the new value, preserving all frequencies. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The query expression counts exactly salaries in $[a,b]$.

#### Proof

Order-preserving compression maps all values below $a$ before `lo` and all values at most $b$ through `hi`. The difference of frequency prefixes removes values below $a$ and retains precisely the inclusive interval. $\square$

### Theorem

Every reported employee count is correct.

#### Proof

Lemma 1 supplies current frequencies, and Lemma 2 selects exactly the requested value range. $\square$

### Complexity

Compression takes $O((n+q)\log(n+q))$ time. Each operation takes $O(\log(n+q))$ time. Stored operations, coordinates, salaries, and Fenwick data use $O(n+q)$ space.

## Implementation

All operations are buffered because future assignment values must enter compression. `lower_bound` handles the inclusive lower endpoint; `upper_bound` produces the count of coordinates at most the upper endpoint.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q, V;
vector<ll> bit;

void upd(int i, ll v){
    for (; i <= V; i += i & -i) bit[i] += v;
}
ll pre(int i){
    ll r = 0;
    for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) r += bit[i];
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> cur(n + 1);
    vector<ll> vals;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ cin >> cur[i]; vals.pb(cur[i]); }

    vector<char> op(q);
    vector<ll> A(q), B(q);              // op '!' : (k,x) ; op '?' : (a,b)
    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++){
        cin >> op[i] >> A[i] >> B[i];
        if (op[i] == '!') vals.pb(B[i]); // new salary value
    }

    sort(vals.begin(), vals.end());
    vals.erase(unique(vals.begin(), vals.end()), vals.end());
    V = vals.size();
    auto idx = [&](ll v){ return int(lower_bound(vals.begin(), vals.end(), v) - vals.begin()) + 1; };

    bit.assign(V + 1, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) upd(idx(cur[i]), 1);

    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++){
        if (op[i] == '!'){
            int k = (int)A[i]; ll x = B[i];
            upd(idx(cur[k]), -1);
            cur[k] = x;
            upd(idx(x), 1);
        } else {
            int lo = idx(A[i]);                                   // first index >= a
            int hi = int(upper_bound(vals.begin(), vals.end(), B[i]) - vals.begin()); // first index > b (0-based) = #vals <= b
            cout << pre(hi) - pre(lo - 1) << '\n';
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

With salaries $[4,7,7,10]$, query $[6,9]$ returns 2. Assigning employee 1 from 4 to 8 moves one frequency, and the same query then returns 3.

## Takeaway

When updates and queries operate on a large ordered value domain known offline, coordinate-compress all possible values and maintain their frequencies.

### Related problems

Range Interval Queries combines position and value restrictions offline. Distinct Values Queries uses a Fenwick tree over positions instead.

