# Pizzeria Queries

- **CSES problem:** 2206
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (pizzeria.cpp)`](./pizzeria.cpp)

## Problem

Maintain delivery prices $p_i$. For a customer at position $k$, return

$$
\min_i(p_i+|i-k|),
$$

under point assignments to prices.

## Reasoning

Split the absolute value by the shop's side. For $i\le k$,

$$
p_i+|i-k|=(p_i-i)+k.
$$

For $i\ge k$,

$$
p_i+|i-k|=(p_i+i)-k.
$$

Thus a query needs a prefix minimum of transformed values $p_i-i$ and a suffix minimum of $p_i+i$. Maintain both transformed arrays in minimum segment trees. A price assignment changes one point in each.

The shop at $k$ belongs to both cases, which is harmless because taking a minimum is idempotent.

## Algorithm

1. Build one segment tree over $p_i-i$ and another over $p_i+i$.
2. On assignment $p_k=x$, update position $k$ to $x-k$ and $x+k$ respectively.
3. For customer $k$, compute `min([1,k] of p_i-i)+k` and `min([k,n] of p_i+i)-k`.
4. Output the smaller value.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

The left-tree expression is the minimum delivery cost among shops $i\le k$.

#### Proof

For every such shop, the algebraic identity above rewrites its cost as $(p_i-i)+k$. The added $k$ is constant, so minimizing the transformed value gives exactly the minimum left-side cost. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The right-tree expression is the minimum delivery cost among shops $i\ge k$.

#### Proof

The symmetric identity gives $(p_i+i)-k$, and the same constant-separation argument applies. $\square$

### Theorem

Every query returns the minimum delivery cost over all shops.

#### Proof

Every index is on the left or right side of $k$. Lemmas 1 and 2 find the optimum in each exhaustive subset; their minimum is the global optimum. Point updates keep both transformed values current. $\square$

### Complexity

Building takes $O(n)$ time. Every update and query takes $O(\log n)$ time. The two trees use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

Leaves are zero-based but transformation formulas use one-based shop indices. Query ranges are half-open internally: `[0,k)` represents shops 1 through $k$, and `[k-1,n)` shops $k$ through $n$.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q, sz;
vector<ll> ta, tc;                      // a_b = p_b - b ; c_b = p_b + b

void upd(vector<ll>& t, int p, ll v){
    for (t[p += sz] = v, p >>= 1; p >= 1; p >>= 1)
        t[p] = min(t[p<<1], t[p<<1|1]);
}
ll qry(vector<ll>& t, int l, int r){    // [l, r)
    ll res = LLONG_MAX;
    for (l += sz, r += sz; l < r; l >>= 1, r >>= 1){
        if (l & 1) res = min(res, t[l++]);
        if (r & 1) res = min(res, t[--r]);
    }
    return res;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    sz = 1;
    while (sz < n) sz <<= 1;
    ta.assign(2*sz, LLONG_MAX);
    tc.assign(2*sz, LLONG_MAX);

    vector<ll> p(n + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        cin >> p[i];
        ta[sz + i - 1] = p[i] - i;       // 0-indexed leaf i-1 holds building i
        tc[sz + i - 1] = p[i] + i;
    }
    for (int i = sz - 1; i >= 1; i--){
        ta[i] = min(ta[i<<1], ta[i<<1|1]);
        tc[i] = min(tc[i<<1], tc[i<<1|1]);
    }

    while (q--){
        int op; cin >> op;
        if (op == 1){
            int k; ll x; cin >> k >> x;
            upd(ta, k - 1, x - k);
            upd(tc, k - 1, x + k);
        } else {
            int k; cin >> k;
            ll left  = qry(ta, 0, k) + k;        // b in [1,k]
            ll right = qry(tc, k - 1, n) - k;    // b in [k,n]
            cout << min(left, right) << '\n';
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For prices $[8,3,6]$ and customer $k=3$, left transformed values are $[7,1,3]$. Their minimum 1 plus 3 gives 4, achieved by shop 2 with price 3 and distance 1.

## Takeaway

When a cost contains an absolute value, split by relative order. Each side often becomes a transformed range minimum plus a query-dependent constant.

### Related problems

Prefix Sum Queries stores a richer segment-tree monoid. Dynamic Range Minimum Queries supplies the underlying point-update range-minimum structure.

