# Visible Buildings Queries

- **CSES problem:** 3304
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (visiblebuildings.cpp)`](./visiblebuildings.cpp)

## Problem

For each subarray of building heights, count buildings visible from its left, where a building is visible only if it is strictly taller than every earlier building in that subarray.

## Reasoning

For each position $j$, let $L_j$ be the nearest earlier index whose height is at least $h_j$, or zero. A monotonic stack computes these blockers: pop strictly smaller heights, leaving the nearest height that prevents $j$ from being a new strict maximum.

Within query $[a,b]$, building $j$ is visible exactly when $L_j<a$. If its nearest globally blocking building is before the query, then every building between $a$ and $j-1$ is shorter. If $L_j\ge a$, that blocker lies inside the query and hides $j$.

Process queries offline by increasing $b$. After positions through $b$ are active, a Fenwick tree over blocker values stores one count at coordinate $L_j+1$ for every active $j$. Prefix through coordinate $a$ counts active positions with $L_j<a$.

This count also includes all positions $j<a$. There are exactly $a-1$ of them, and each satisfies $L_j<j<a$. Subtracting $a-1$ leaves visible positions in $[a,b]$.

## Algorithm

1. Compute every nearest left blocker $L_j$ with a nonincreasing monotonic stack.
2. Sort query IDs by right endpoint.
3. Sweep $j$ through each query's $b$, adding one at Fenwick coordinate $L_j+1$.
4. Answer query $[a,b]$ as `prefix(a)-(a-1)`.
5. Restore input order using query IDs.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

The stack computes $L_j$, the nearest earlier position with height at least $h_j$.

#### Proof

All strictly smaller heights are popped because they cannot block $j$. The remaining top, if any, is at least $h_j$. Any nearer index either remains above it on the stack or was popped for being smaller, so the top is the nearest qualifying blocker. $\square$

### Lemma 2

For $j\in[a,b]$, building $j$ is visible exactly when $L_j<a$.

#### Proof

If $L_j\ge a$, that earlier building inside the query has height at least $h_j$, so $j$ is not strictly taller than all predecessors. If $L_j<a$, no position from $a$ through $j-1$ has height at least $h_j$, by nearest-blocker definition, so $j$ is visible. $\square$

### Theorem

The query formula returns the visible-building count.

#### Proof

After sweeping to $b$, the Fenwick prefix counts all $j\le b$ with $L_j<a$. By Lemma 2, those with $j\ge a$ are exactly the visible query buildings. Every one of the $a-1$ earlier positions also satisfies $L_j<j<a$, so subtracting them removes exactly the out-of-range count. $\square$

### Complexity

The monotonic stack is $O(n)$. Sorting queries costs $O(q\log q)$, and the sweep plus queries costs $O((n+q)\log n)$. Space is $O(n+q)$.

## Implementation

Equal-height buildings are not popped because visibility requires strict height; an equal predecessor blocks. Coordinate `L+1` represents blocker zero safely in the one-based Fenwick tree.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q, M;                            // M = L-domain size (n+1)
vector<ll> bit;

void upd(int i, ll v){
    for (; i <= M; i += i & -i) bit[i] += v;
}
ll pre(int i){
    ll r = 0;
    for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) r += bit[i];
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> h(n + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> h[i];

    vector<int> L(n + 1);               // nearest left idx with h >= h[j], else 0
    vector<int> st;                     // monotonic stack of indices
    for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++){
        while (!st.empty() && h[st.back()] < h[j]) st.pop_back();
        L[j] = st.empty() ? 0 : st.back();
        st.pb(j);
    }

    vector<int> A(q), B(q);
    vector<int> ord(q);
    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++){ cin >> A[i] >> B[i]; ord[i] = i; }
    sort(ord.begin(), ord.end(), [&](int x, int y){ return B[x] < B[y]; });

    M = n + 1;
    bit.assign(M + 1, 0);

    vector<ll> ans(q);
    int j = 1;                          // sweep pointer over positions
    for (int t : ord){
        int b = B[t], a = A[t];
        while (j <= b){ upd(L[j] + 1, 1); j++; }   // index L by +1 (L can be 0)
        ll Fba = pre(a);                            // count L_j <= a-1  ==  index <= a
        ans[t] = Fba - (a - 1);
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++) cout << ans[i] << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For heights `[4,1,2,2,3]`, blockers are `[0,1,1,3,1]`. In query `[2,5]`, positions 2, 3, and 5 have blockers below 2 and are visible; position 4 is blocked by equal-height position 3. The answer is 3.

## Takeaway

Record visibility can be characterized by the nearest previous element meeting a blocking inequality. Once blockers are known, offline range counting replaces repeated scans.

### Related problems

Nearest Smaller Values uses the same monotonic-stack pattern with the opposite inequality. Distinct Values Queries uses a similar right-endpoint sweep over representative positions.

problems.solution_cpp:
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q, M;                            // M = L-domain size (n+1)
vector<ll> bit;

void upd(int i, ll v){
    for (; i <= M; i += i & -i) bit[i] += v;
}
ll pre(int i){
    ll r = 0;
    for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) r += bit[i];
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> h(n + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> h[i];

    vector<int> L(n + 1);               // nearest left idx with h >= h[j], else 0
    vector<int> st;                     // monotonic stack of indices
    for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++){
        while (!st.empty() && h[st.back()] < h[j]) st.pop_back();
        L[j] = st.empty() ? 0 : st.back();
        st.pb(j);
    }

    vector<int> A(q), B(q);
    vector<int> ord(q);
    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++){ cin >> A[i] >> B[i]; ord[i] = i; }
    sort(ord.begin(), ord.end(), [&](int x, int y){ return B[x] < B[y]; });

    M = n + 1;
    bit.assign(M + 1, 0);

    vector<ll> ans(q);
    int j = 1;                          // sweep pointer over positions
    for (int t : ord){
        int b = B[t], a = A[t];
        while (j <= b){ upd(L[j] + 1, 1); j++; }   // index L by +1 (L can be 0)
        ll Fba = pre(a);                            // count L_j <= a-1  ==  index <= a
        ans[t] = Fba - (a - 1);
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++) cout << ans[i] << '\n';
    return 0;
}

