# Range Interval Queries

- **CSES problem:** 3163
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (rangeinterval.cpp)`](./rangeinterval.cpp)

## Problem

For each query $(a,b,c,d)$, count indices $i$ satisfying both $a\le i\le b$ and $c\le x_i\le d$.

## Reasoning

Define

$$
F(p,c,d)=\#\{i\le p:c\le x_i\le d\}.
$$

Then the desired two-dimensional rectangle count is

$$
F(b,c,d)-F(a-1,c,d).
$$

Create two signed events for every query at position thresholds $b$ and $a-1$, sort all events by threshold, and sweep array positions forward. A Fenwick tree over compressed values stores frequencies of values in the swept prefix. Each event obtains its value-interval count from two Fenwick prefixes and adds it with sign $+1$ or $-1$.

This is an offline two-dimensional orthogonal counting reduction: position is handled by the sweep and value by the data structure.

## Algorithm

1. Compress all array values.
2. Create event `(b,id,+1)` and `(a-1,id,-1)` for each query.
3. Sort events by their position threshold.
4. Sweep positions into a Fenwick frequency tree until reaching each threshold.
5. Count compressed values in $[c,d]$ with `upper_bound(d)` and `lower_bound(c)`, and add the signed result to the query answer.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

At an event threshold $p$, the Fenwick tree contains exactly the frequencies of $x_1,\ldots,x_p$.

#### Proof

Events are nondecreasing in $p$, and the sweep inserts each array position exactly when the pointer advances through it. No later position is inserted early and no earlier position is omitted. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The event's Fenwick expression equals $F(p,c,d)$.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1, the tree represents precisely indices at most $p$. Order-preserving compression and the two binary-search boundaries select exactly values between $c$ and $d$ inclusive. $\square$

### Theorem

Every query answer is correct.

#### Proof

Lemma 2 gives $F(b,c,d)$ at the positive event and $F(a-1,c,d)$ at the negative event. Their signed sum removes indices before $a$ and retains exactly those in $[a,b]$ with qualifying values. $\square$

### Complexity

Compression and event sorting take $O((n+q)\log(n+q))$ time. Sweeping and events take $O((n+q)\log n)$ time. Space is $O(n+q)$.

## Implementation

Only array values need compression; query bounds are mapped by `lower_bound` and `upper_bound` even when absent. Position-zero events are processed before any insertion. Answers are accumulated as signed `long long` values.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q, V;                            // V = value-domain size
vector<ll> bit;

void upd(int i, ll v){
    for (; i <= V; i += i & -i) bit[i] += v;
}
ll pre(int i){
    ll r = 0;
    for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) r += bit[i];
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> x(n + 1), vals;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ cin >> x[i]; vals.pb(x[i]); }

    sort(vals.begin(), vals.end());
    vals.erase(unique(vals.begin(), vals.end()), vals.end());
    V = vals.size();
    auto lo = [&](ll v){ return int(lower_bound(vals.begin(), vals.end(), v) - vals.begin()) + 1; };
    auto hi = [&](ll v){ return int(upper_bound(vals.begin(), vals.end(), v) - vals.begin()); };

    vector<int> A(q), C(q), D(q);
    vector<ll> ans(q, 0);
    // events: (pos, qid, sign), pos in [0,n]
    vector<array<int,3>> ev;
    ev.reserve(2*q);
    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++){
        int a, b, c, d; cin >> a >> b >> c >> d;
        A[i] = a; C[i] = c; D[i] = d;
        ev.pb({b, i, 1});
        ev.pb({a - 1, i, -1});
    }
    sort(ev.begin(), ev.end(), [](const array<int,3>&p, const array<int,3>&r){ return p[0] < r[0]; });

    bit.assign(V + 1, 0);

    int j = 1;                          // sweep pointer over positions
    for (auto& e : ev){
        int pos = e[0], qid = e[1], sgn = e[2];
        while (j <= pos){ upd(lo(x[j]), 1); j++; }   // insert value at index j
        ll cnt = pre(hi(D[qid])) - pre(lo(C[qid]) - 1);
        ans[qid] += sgn * cnt;
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++) cout << ans[i] << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For query positions `[2,5]` and values `[3,7]`, the positive event counts qualifying values in prefix 5. The negative event counts them in prefix 1. Subtraction leaves exactly qualifying indices 2 through 5.

## Takeaway

A rectangle query over index and value can often be decomposed into signed prefix events in one dimension and a Fenwick frequency query in the other.

### Related problems

Distinct Values Queries also sweeps right endpoints. Salary Queries maintains a value-frequency Fenwick tree online without position restrictions.

