# Subarray Sum Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1190
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (subarraysum.cpp)`](./subarraysum.cpp)

## Problem

After each point assignment, output the maximum subarray sum of the entire array, allowing the empty subarray with sum zero.

## Reasoning

An interval's maximum subarray may lie wholly in either half or cross their boundary. To merge two adjacent intervals, store four quantities: total sum, maximum prefix sum, maximum suffix sum, and maximum subarray sum. Prefix, suffix, and best are clamped to zero to represent the allowed empty choice.

For left summary $A$ and right summary $B$,

$$
pref=\max(A.pref,A.sum+B.pref),
$$

$$
suf=\max(B.suf,B.sum+A.suf),
$$

$$
best=\max(A.best,B.best,A.suf+B.pref).
$$

These cases describe every possible prefix, suffix, and subarray of the concatenation. A segment tree maintains this summary under point changes.

## Algorithm

1. Represent leaf $v$ as `(v,max(0,v),max(0,v),max(0,v))`.
2. Build a segment tree with the four-field merge.
3. After assigning one leaf, recompute its ancestors.
4. Output the root's `best`.

## Correctness

### Lemma

Merging valid summaries of adjacent intervals produces a valid summary of their concatenation.

#### Proof

Totals add. A prefix stops in the left half or contains all of it plus a right prefix; suffixes are symmetric. A subarray lies in the left half, right half, or crosses the boundary as a left suffix plus right prefix. The formulas maximize exactly these exhaustive cases, including empty values. $\square$

### Theorem

After every update, the printed value is the maximum allowed subarray sum.

#### Proof

Leaves are valid summaries. The lemma proves by induction that every rebuilt node, including the root, correctly summarizes its interval. The root covers the entire array, so its `best` is the required answer. $\square$

### Complexity

Building takes $O(n)$ time. Each assignment takes $O(\log n)$ time. Space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The identity summary is all zeros and also represents unused leaves. `long long` is required for sums. The problem asks for output after each update, not before the first.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

struct Node { ll sum, pref, suf, best; };   // all clamped >= 0 except sum
Node mrg(const Node&a, const Node&b){
    return {
        a.sum + b.sum,
        max(a.pref, a.sum + b.pref),
        max(b.suf, b.sum + a.suf),
        max({a.best, b.best, a.suf + b.pref})
    };
}
Node leaf(ll v){ ll g = max(0LL, v); return { v, g, g, g }; }
const Node ID = {0, 0, 0, 0};

int n, m, sz;
vector<Node> t;

void upd(int p, ll v){
    for (t[p += sz] = leaf(v), p >>= 1; p >= 1; p >>= 1)
        t[p] = mrg(t[p<<1], t[p<<1|1]);
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> m;

    sz = 1;
    while (sz < n) sz <<= 1;
    t.assign(2*sz, ID);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++){ ll x; cin >> x; t[sz + i] = leaf(x); }
    for (int i = sz - 1; i >= 1; i--) t[i] = mrg(t[i<<1], t[i<<1|1]);

    while (m--){
        int k; ll x; cin >> k >> x;
        upd(k - 1, x);
        cout << t[1].best << '\n';
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For left interval `[-2,5]` and right interval `[-1,4]`, the crossing candidate is left suffix 5 plus right prefix 3, totaling 8. It beats either half's best and corresponds to subarray `[5,-1,4]`.

## Takeaway

Maximum-subarray segment trees arise from classifying how an optimum intersects a concatenation boundary. Store exactly the boundary summaries needed by the crossing case.

### Related problems

Subarray Sum Queries II queries arbitrary ranges with the same monoid. Prefix Sum Queries needs only total and best-prefix fields.

