# Subarray Sum Queries II

- **CSES problem:** 3226
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (subarraysum2.cpp)`](./subarraysum2.cpp)

## Problem

For each inclusive range, find its maximum subarray sum, with the empty subarray of sum zero allowed.

## Reasoning

Use the four-field maximum-subarray summary: total sum, best prefix, best suffix, and best internal subarray. The concatenation merge is the same as in the dynamic whole-array variant.

The subtlety is iterative range order. This merge is associative but not commutative. Nodes taken from the left boundary append to a left accumulator. Nodes taken from the right boundary must be prepended to a right accumulator. Only after the traversal are the two sides concatenated.

## Algorithm

1. Build a segment tree of four-field summaries.
2. Convert query $[a,b]$ to half-open range $[a-1,b)$.
3. Accumulate selected left nodes with `merge(left,node)` and right nodes with `merge(node,right)`.
4. Merge both accumulators and output `best`.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

The four-field merge correctly summarizes concatenation.

#### Proof

Prefixes and suffixes either remain in one side or cross after including an entire side. A maximum subarray is wholly left, wholly right, or a left suffix followed by a right prefix. The merge maximizes exactly these cases. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The query returns the summary of the requested elements in their original order.

#### Proof

Canonical nodes form a disjoint partition of the range. Left nodes are discovered from left to right and appended. Right nodes are discovered from right to left and prepended. Their final concatenation is therefore the original range order. $\square$

### Theorem

Every answer is the requested maximum subarray sum.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1 each node and merge summary is valid. Lemma 2 shows the final summary describes exactly the queried range, whose `best` field is the definition of the answer. $\square$

### Complexity

Building takes $O(n)$ time. Every query takes $O(\log n)$ time. Space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The all-zero identity permits an empty side and encodes the allowed empty subarray. Reversing the right-accumulator merge silently breaks answers because prefix and suffix fields are directional.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

struct Node { ll sum, pref, suf, best; };   // all clamped >= 0 except sum
Node mrg(const Node&a, const Node&b){
    return {
        a.sum + b.sum,
        max(a.pref, a.sum + b.pref),
        max(b.suf, b.sum + a.suf),
        max({a.best, b.best, a.suf + b.pref})
    };
}
Node leaf(ll v){ ll g = max(0LL, v); return { v, g, g, g }; }
const Node ID = {0, 0, 0, 0};

int n, q, sz;
vector<Node> t;

ll qry(int l, int r){                   // [l, r)
    Node rl = ID, rr = ID;
    for (l += sz, r += sz; l < r; l >>= 1, r >>= 1){
        if (l & 1) rl = mrg(rl, t[l++]);
        if (r & 1) rr = mrg(t[--r], rr);
    }
    return mrg(rl, rr).best;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    sz = 1;
    while (sz < n) sz <<= 1;
    t.assign(2*sz, ID);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++){ ll x; cin >> x; t[sz + i] = leaf(x); }
    for (int i = sz - 1; i >= 1; i--) t[i] = mrg(t[i<<1], t[i<<1|1]);

    while (q--){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        cout << qry(a - 1, b) << '\n';
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

On range `[2,5,1,-2]`, the maximum subarray is the first three values with sum 8. Canonical nodes may split this range, but ordered merging reconstructs the same prefix, suffix, and crossing candidates as a direct scan.

## Takeaway

An associative segment summary need not be commutative. Iterative queries over directional data must preserve concatenation order explicitly.

### Related problems

Subarray Sum Queries adds point updates and reads the whole-tree answer. Prefix Sum Queries stores a smaller directional summary.

