# Distinct Values Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1734
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (distinctvalues.cpp)`](./distinctvalues.cpp)

## Problem

For every static array range, count its distinct values.

## Reasoning

Process queries offline by increasing right endpoint $b$. After sweeping positions 1 through $b$, keep one marker for each value: place it at that value's latest occurrence. Then a value occurs inside $[a,b]$ exactly when its unique marker lies at position at least $a$.

When processing new position $j$, remove the marker at the previous occurrence of $x_j$, if any, and add one at $j$. A Fenwick range sum over $[a,b]$ counts the latest markers within the query range, one per distinct value.

Sorting queries is valid because the array is static and answers are stored by original ID.

## Algorithm

1. Sort query IDs by right endpoint.
2. Sweep array position `j` forward to each query's $b$.
3. For value $x_j$, subtract one at its previous marker and add one at $j$; record $j$ as latest.
4. Answer query $[a,b]$ by the Fenwick sum over that interval.
5. Print answers in input order.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After sweeping through $b$, exactly the latest occurrence at or before $b$ of every seen value has marker one.

#### Proof

The first occurrence adds its marker. Each later occurrence removes the former latest marker and adds the new one, preserving exactly one at the latest position. Other values are unchanged. $\square$

### Lemma 2

A value occurs in $[a,b]$ if and only if its marker after the $b$ sweep lies in $[a,b]$.

#### Proof

If it occurs in the range, its latest occurrence at or before $b$ cannot be before $a$, so its marker lies inside. If its marker lies inside, that marked position is itself an occurrence in the range. $\square$

### Theorem

Every query answer equals its number of distinct values.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1 there is at most one marker per value, and by Lemma 2 exactly the values present in the query contribute markers to its Fenwick range sum. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting takes $O(q\log q)$. Each array position causes at most two Fenwick updates and each query one range sum, for $O((n+q)\log n)$ total time. Space is $O(n+q)$ plus the last-occurrence map.

## Implementation

The sweep pointer never moves backward because queries are sorted by $b$. `unordered_map` avoids coordinate compression and is reserved in advance. Answers use query IDs to restore input order.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q;
vector<ll> bit;

void upd(int i, ll v){
    for (; i <= n; i += i & -i) bit[i] += v;
}
ll pre(int i){
    ll r = 0;
    for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) r += bit[i];
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<int> x(n + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> x[i];

    vector<int> A(q), B(q), ord(q);
    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++){ cin >> A[i] >> B[i]; ord[i] = i; }
    sort(ord.begin(), ord.end(), [&](int u, int v){ return B[u] < B[v]; });

    bit.assign(n + 1, 0);
    unordered_map<int,int> last;        // value -> last marked position
    last.reserve(2*n);

    vector<ll> ans(q);
    int j = 1;                          // sweep pointer
    for (int t : ord){
        int a = A[t], b = B[t];
        while (j <= b){
            auto it = last.find(x[j]);
            if (it != last.end()) upd(it->second, -1);  // unmark old occurrence
            upd(j, 1);
            last[x[j]] = j;
            j++;
        }
        ans[t] = pre(b) - pre(a - 1);
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++) cout << ans[i] << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For prefix `[2,1,2,3]`, markers after position 4 are at 2 for value 1, 3 for value 2, and 4 for value 3. Query `[2,4]` sees all three markers; query `[3,4]` sees only values 2 and 3.

## Takeaway

Offline right-endpoint sweeps often turn distinct counting into maintaining one representative, usually the latest occurrence, for each value.

### Related problems

Distinct Values Queries II maintains predecessor information under updates. Counting Paths uses a different offline accumulation on trees.

