# Distinct Values Queries II

- **CSES problem:** 3356
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (distinctvalues2.cpp)`](./distinctvalues2.cpp)

## Problem

Support point assignments and determine whether all values in each queried range are pairwise distinct.

## Reasoning

For every position $i$, define `pv[i]` as the previous position holding the same value, or zero. A duplicate exists in $[a,b]$ exactly when some $i\in[a,b]$ has `pv[i]>=a`: then both $i$ and its predecessor lie in the range. Therefore all values are distinct exactly when

$$
\max_{i\in[a,b]}pv[i]<a.
$$

Maintain this predecessor array in a range-maximum segment tree. For each value, an ordered set stores all of its current positions. Changing position $k$ affects only local predecessor links: the successor in the old value set now points to $k$'s old predecessor; $k$ points to its predecessor in the new set; and its new successor points to $k$.

No other position's nearest equal predecessor changes.

## Algorithm

1. Build an ordered set of positions for each value and compute every predecessor.
2. Build a maximum segment tree over `pv`.
3. For update at $k$, detach it from its old set and repair the old successor. Insert it into the new set, set its predecessor, and repair the new successor. Update each changed segment-tree leaf.
4. For query $[a,b]$, answer `YES` iff the maximum predecessor on that range is below $a$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After every update, `pv[i]` is the nearest earlier position with value $x_i$, or zero.

#### Proof

Ordered sets store exactly all positions of each value. Removing $k$ changes only the next position's predecessor from $k$ to $k$'s former predecessor. Inserting $k$ places it between its ordered predecessor and successor, so exactly their two relevant links are assigned. All other consecutive relationships remain unchanged. $\square$

### Lemma 2

Range $[a,b]$ contains a duplicate if and only if its maximum `pv` value is at least $a$.

#### Proof

If `pv[i]>=a` for some $i\le b$, positions `pv[i]` and $i$ are equal-valued and both in the range. Conversely, take the second occurrence of any duplicated value within the range; its nearest earlier equal occurrence is no earlier than the first range occurrence, so its predecessor is at least $a$. $\square$

### Theorem

Every type 2 answer is correct.

#### Proof

Lemma 1 makes the segment-tree leaves current. Its maximum detects the condition in Lemma 2, and the algorithm returns `YES` exactly when that duplicate condition is false. $\square$

### Complexity

Each update performs $O(1)$ ordered-set and segment-tree operations, taking $O(\log n)$. Each query takes $O(\log n)$. Initialization takes $O(n\log n)$ and space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The segment tree stores zero for absent predecessors. Update positions passed to it are zero-based, while stored predecessor values and query endpoints remain one-based. Assigning the same value is skipped.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q, sz;
vector<int> t;                          // range-max over prev[]

void upd(int p, int v){
    for (t[p += sz] = v, p >>= 1; p >= 1; p >>= 1)
        t[p] = max(t[p<<1], t[p<<1|1]);
}
int qry(int l, int r){                  // [l, r)
    int res = 0;
    for (l += sz, r += sz; l < r; l >>= 1, r >>= 1){
        if (l & 1) res = max(res, t[l++]);
        if (r & 1) res = max(res, t[--r]);
    }
    return res;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<int> x(n + 1), pv(n + 1, 0);
    map<int, set<int>> pos;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        cin >> x[i];
        auto& S = pos[x[i]];
        if (!S.empty()) pv[i] = *S.rbegin();   // predecessor = current max < i
        S.insert(i);
    }

    sz = 1;
    while (sz < n) sz <<= 1;
    t.assign(2*sz, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) t[sz + i - 1] = pv[i];
    for (int i = sz - 1; i >= 1; i--) t[i] = max(t[i<<1], t[i<<1|1]);

    while (q--){
        int op; cin >> op;
        if (op == 1){
            int k, u; cin >> k >> u;
            if (x[k] != u){
                // detach k from its old value's set
                auto& S = pos[x[k]];
                auto it = S.find(k);
                auto nx = next(it);
                int suc = (nx != S.end()) ? *nx : 0;
                int prd = (it != S.begin()) ? *prev(it) : 0;
                S.erase(it);
                if (suc){ pv[suc] = prd; upd(suc - 1, prd); }
                // attach k to new value's set
                x[k] = u;
                auto& T = pos[u];
                auto jt = T.lower_bound(k);             // first > k (k absent)
                int suc2 = (jt != T.end()) ? *jt : 0;
                int prd2 = (jt != T.begin()) ? *prev(jt) : 0;
                T.insert(k);
                pv[k] = prd2; upd(k - 1, prd2);
                if (suc2){ pv[suc2] = k; upd(suc2 - 1, k); }
            }
        } else {
            int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
            cout << (qry(a - 1, b) < a ? "YES" : "NO") << '\n';
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `[3,2,7,2,8]`, predecessor values are `[0,0,0,2,0]`. Query `[2,5]` has maximum predecessor 2, which is at least its left endpoint, so it contains duplicate 2. Query `[3,5]` has maximum 2 below 3 and is distinct.

## Takeaway

Dynamic distinctness can be reduced to a range maximum over nearest-equal predecessors. Under point updates, only neighboring occurrences of the changed values need repair.

### Related problems

Distinct Values Queries counts values offline. Salary Queries also maintains ordered value information but aggregates frequencies rather than predecessor links.

