# Increasing Array Queries

- **CSES problem:** 2416
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (increasingarray.cpp)`](./increasingarray.cpp)

## Problem

For each subarray $[a,b]$, find the minimum total number of unit increments needed to make it nondecreasing.

## Reasoning

The optimal final value at position $i$ is the maximum original value seen from $a$ through $i$. Any smaller value would violate monotonicity, while any larger value wastes increments. Thus the cost is

$$
\sum_{i=a}^{b}\max(x_a,\ldots,x_i)-\sum_{i=a}^{b}x_i.
$$

Process queries offline by decreasing left endpoint $a$. Maintain the prefix-maximum frontier for the suffix starting at $a$. It consists of constant-value runs with strictly increasing run values from left to right.

When prepending $x_a$, every initial run whose value is at most $x_a$ is absorbed and becomes $x_a$. A monotonic stack stores these runs. Their union is one interval $[a,R]$, so a lazy segment tree range-assigns $x_a$ there. The tree then stores the sum of prefix maxima for any query interval. Static original prefix sums supply the subtracted term.

## Algorithm

1. Group queries by their left endpoint and build original prefix sums.
2. Sweep $a$ from $n$ down to 1.
3. Pop stack runs with value at most $x_a$, extending $R$ through their right ends.
4. Range-assign $x_a$ to frontier positions $[a,R]$, then push the merged run.
5. For every query starting at $a$, query the frontier sum on $[a,b]$ and subtract the original subarray sum.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

For fixed $a$, the minimum feasible final value at position $i\ge a$ is $m_i=\max_{j=a}^{i}x_j$.

#### Proof

Any nondecreasing result formed only by increments must be at least every earlier original value, hence at least $m_i$. The sequence $m_i$ is itself nondecreasing and never below $x_i$, so it is feasible. Therefore it is componentwise minimal and minimizes total increments. $\square$

### Lemma 2

After sweep step $a$, the segment tree stores $m_i$ at every position $i\ge a$.

#### Proof

Before prepending, stack runs represent prefix maxima from $a+1$. New prefix maxima equal $x_a$ until the first old run value greater than $x_a$, and thereafter equal the old values. Exactly the popped initial runs have value at most $x_a$; assigning their contiguous union plus position $a$ produces this sequence. $\square$

### Theorem

Every query answer is the minimum required number of increments.

#### Proof

By Lemma 2, the segment-tree range sum is $\sum m_i$. Lemma 1 proves these are the optimal final values. Subtracting the original values counts exactly their total increments. $\square$

### Complexity

Each run is pushed and popped once, for $O(n)$ stack work. There are $O(n)$ range assignments and $q$ range queries, each $O(\log n)$, so total time is $O((n+q)\log n)$. Space is $O(n+q)$.

## Implementation

Lazy value `-1` means no assignment, valid because input values are positive. Stack entries store `(value,left,right)`. Answers are kept by query ID. Original prefix sums and tree sums use `long long`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q;
vector<ll> sm, lz;                      // lazy assign; lz=-1 means none

void app(int nd, int l, int r, ll v){ sm[nd] = v * (r - l + 1); lz[nd] = v; }
void push(int nd, int l, int r){
    if (lz[nd] != -1){
        int m = (l + r) >> 1;
        app(nd<<1, l, m, lz[nd]);
        app(nd<<1|1, m+1, r, lz[nd]);
        lz[nd] = -1;
    }
}
void assign(int nd, int l, int r, int ql, int qr, ll v){
    if (qr < l || r < ql) return;
    if (ql <= l && r <= qr){ app(nd, l, r, v); return; }
    push(nd, l, r);
    int m = (l + r) >> 1;
    assign(nd<<1, l, m, ql, qr, v);
    assign(nd<<1|1, m+1, r, ql, qr, v);
    sm[nd] = sm[nd<<1] + sm[nd<<1|1];
}
ll query(int nd, int l, int r, int ql, int qr){
    if (qr < l || r < ql) return 0;
    if (ql <= l && r <= qr) return sm[nd];
    push(nd, l, r);
    int m = (l + r) >> 1;
    return query(nd<<1, l, m, ql, qr) + query(nd<<1|1, m+1, r, ql, qr);
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> x(n + 1), psum(n + 1, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ cin >> x[i]; psum[i] = psum[i-1] + x[i]; }

    vector<vector<ii>> byA(n + 1);      // byA[a] = list of (b, query-id)
    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        byA[a].pb({b, i});
    }

    sm.assign(4*n, 0);
    lz.assign(4*n, -1);

    vector<array<int,3>> stk;           // runs (val, l, r) over current frontier
    vector<ll> ans(q);

    for (int a = n; a >= 1; a--){
        int R = a;                                  // merged right end
        while (!stk.empty() && stk.back()[0] <= x[a]){ R = max(R, stk.back()[2]); stk.pop_back(); }
        assign(1, 1, n, a, R, x[a]);                // prefmax over [a,R] becomes x[a]
        stk.pb({ (int)x[a], a, R });
        for (auto& Qr : byA[a]){
            int b = Qr.f, id = Qr.s;
            ll S = query(1, 1, n, a, b);
            ans[id] = S - (psum[b] - psum[a-1]);
        }
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < q; i++) cout << ans[i] << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For subarray `[10,4,2,5]`, prefix maxima are `[10,10,10,10]`. Their sum is 40 and the original sum is 21, so 19 increments are necessary. When 10 is prepended, every following frontier run of value at most 10 is popped and the whole interval is assigned 10.

## Takeaway

Offline left-endpoint sweeps are powerful when prepending one element changes only an initial portion of a monotone frontier. Store that frontier as runs and update its aggregate with lazy assignment.

### Related problems

Polynomial Queries also applies structured range updates lazily. Nearest Smaller Values uses a simpler monotonic stack without offline queries.

