# Forest Queries II

- **CSES problem:** 1739
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (forest2.cpp)`](./forest2.cpp)

## Problem

Maintain a square grid under cell toggles and answer tree counts in inclusive axis-aligned rectangles.

## Reasoning

A static two-dimensional prefix table cannot absorb toggles efficiently. A two-dimensional Fenwick tree generalizes prefix sums: each cell `bit[i][j]` stores a rectangular block determined by the lowest set bits of both coordinates.

A point delta updates every stored rectangle containing that point by advancing each coordinate with `i += i&-i`. A prefix query partitions rectangle $[1,y]\times[1,x]$ into disjoint stored rectangles by decreasing both coordinates.

Rectangle queries then use the same four-term inclusion-exclusion as static prefixes. A toggle is an additive delta: $+1$ when an empty cell becomes a tree, and $-1$ in the reverse direction.

## Algorithm

1. Insert every initial tree into a two-dimensional Fenwick tree and store current cell bits.
2. To toggle $(y,x)$, choose delta $1$ or $-1$, flip the stored bit, and point-update the tree.
3. Compute any prefix count with nested Fenwick query loops.
4. Answer a rectangle using four prefix counts.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After every toggle, the Fenwick structure represents exactly the current tree indicator of every cell.

#### Proof

Initialization inserts each tree once. A toggle adds the exact difference between new and old indicator at its one cell, and the Fenwick update modifies exactly all aggregates containing it. Other cells remain unchanged. $\square$

### Lemma 2

`pre(y,x)` equals the number of current trees in $[1,y]\times[1,x]$.

#### Proof

The nested Fenwick traversal partitions the requested prefix into disjoint stored rectangles. Lemma 1 makes each stored rectangle sum current, so their total is exact. $\square$

### Theorem

Every rectangle query is correct.

#### Proof

By Lemma 2, the four queried prefixes are exact. Inclusion-exclusion leaves every target cell once and cancels every outside cell. $\square$

### Complexity

Initialization is $O(n^2\log^2 n)$ in this implementation. Each toggle and rectangle query takes $O(\log^2 n)$ time. Storage is $O(n^2)$.

## Implementation

Both coordinates are one-based. `cur` determines the toggle delta before its bit is flipped. Prefix queries naturally return zero when either coordinate is zero.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q;
int bit[1001][1001];
int cur[1001][1001];                    // current cell state (1 = tree)

void upd(int y, int x, int v){
    for (int i = y; i <= n; i += i & -i)
        for (int j = x; j <= n; j += j & -j)
            bit[i][j] += v;
}
int pre(int y, int x){                  // sum over [1..y][1..x]
    int r = 0;
    for (int i = y; i > 0; i -= i & -i)
        for (int j = x; j > 0; j -= j & -j)
            r += bit[i][j];
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        string row; cin >> row;
        for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++){
            if (row[j-1] == '*'){ cur[i][j] = 1; upd(i, j, 1); }
        }
    }

    while (q--){
        int op; cin >> op;
        if (op == 1){
            int y, x; cin >> y >> x;
            int d = cur[y][x] ? -1 : 1;         // toggle
            cur[y][x] ^= 1;
            upd(y, x, d);
        } else {
            int y1, x1, y2, x2; cin >> y1 >> x1 >> y2 >> x2;
            cout << pre(y2, x2) - pre(y1-1, x2) - pre(y2, x1-1) + pre(y1-1, x1-1) << '\n';
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Toggling an empty cell $(3,4)$ adds one to every Fenwick rectangle whose row block contains 3 and column block contains 4. A later query of rows 2 through 5 and columns 4 through 7 includes that contribution exactly once through inclusion-exclusion.

## Takeaway

When point updates and rectangle sums coexist, lift the Fenwick prefix decomposition independently into each dimension.

### Related problems

Forest Queries uses static two-dimensional prefixes. Dynamic Range Sum Queries is the one-dimensional Fenwick analogue.

