# Polynomial Queries

- **CSES problem:** 1736
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (polynomial.cpp)`](./polynomial.cpp)

## Problem

An update on $[a,b]$ adds $1,2,\ldots,b-a+1$ respectively to its positions. Support these updates and range-sum queries.

## Reasoning

At global index $i\in[a,b]$, the addition is

$$
i-a+1=1\cdot i+(1-a).
$$

Thus every update is an affine function $s i+c$ over an interval. Lazy tags store accumulated coefficients `(s,c)`. Affine additions compose by coefficient addition.

For a node covering $[l,r]$, the total change is

$$
s\sum_{i=l}^{r}i+c(r-l+1),
$$

and the arithmetic index sum is $(l+r)(r-l+1)/2$. This lets a fully covered node update in constant time.

## Algorithm

1. Build a range-sum segment tree.
2. Represent an update beginning at $a$ by coefficients $s=1$ and $c=1-a$.
3. On full coverage, add its closed-form affine sum and accumulate both lazy coefficients.
4. Push coefficients unchanged to child intervals before partial recursion.
5. Answer sums by standard lazy segment-tree queries.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

Applying coefficients $(s,c)$ to node $[l,r]$ changes its sum by exactly the total pointwise affine update.

#### Proof

Summing $si+c$ over all indices separates by linearity into $s\sum i+c\sum1$, which is exactly the implemented formula. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The coefficients $(1,1-a)$ add the required progression to $[a,b]$.

#### Proof

At index $i$, they evaluate to $i+1-a$, which is 1 at $a$ and increases by one at every following position through $b$. $\square$

### Theorem

All updates and range-sum queries are correct.

#### Proof

Lemma 2 maps each problem update to the stored affine function. Lemma 1 applies it exactly on every canonical covered node. Coefficients add because all operations are additive. Pushing preserves the same pointwise function on children, so queried node sums represent the current array and sum to the requested range. $\square$

### Complexity

Building takes $O(n)$ time. Each update or query takes $O(\log n)$ time. The segment tree and two lazy arrays use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

All tree intervals use one-based global indices, which is required by the affine formula. `sumIdx` and products use `long long`. Zero coefficients mean no pending update.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q;
vector<ll> sm, ls, lc;                  // lazy: add s*i + c over node's index range

ll sumIdx(int l, int r){ return (ll)(l + r) * (r - l + 1) / 2; }

void app(int nd, int l, int r, ll s, ll c){
    sm[nd] += s * sumIdx(l, r) + c * (r - l + 1);
    ls[nd] += s; lc[nd] += c;
}
void push(int nd, int l, int r){
    if (ls[nd] || lc[nd]){
        int m = (l + r) >> 1;
        app(nd<<1, l, m, ls[nd], lc[nd]);
        app(nd<<1|1, m+1, r, ls[nd], lc[nd]);
        ls[nd] = lc[nd] = 0;
    }
}
void build(int nd, int l, int r, vector<ll>& a){
    if (l == r){ sm[nd] = a[l]; return; }
    int m = (l + r) >> 1;
    build(nd<<1, l, m, a);
    build(nd<<1|1, m+1, r, a);
    sm[nd] = sm[nd<<1] + sm[nd<<1|1];
}
void upd(int nd, int l, int r, int ql, int qr, ll s, ll c){
    if (qr < l || r < ql) return;
    if (ql <= l && r <= qr){ app(nd, l, r, s, c); return; }
    push(nd, l, r);
    int m = (l + r) >> 1;
    upd(nd<<1, l, m, ql, qr, s, c);
    upd(nd<<1|1, m+1, r, ql, qr, s, c);
    sm[nd] = sm[nd<<1] + sm[nd<<1|1];
}
ll query(int nd, int l, int r, int ql, int qr){
    if (qr < l || r < ql) return 0;
    if (ql <= l && r <= qr) return sm[nd];
    push(nd, l, r);
    int m = (l + r) >> 1;
    return query(nd<<1, l, m, ql, qr) + query(nd<<1|1, m+1, r, ql, qr);
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    vector<ll> a(n + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> a[i];

    sm.assign(4*n, 0);
    ls.assign(4*n, 0);
    lc.assign(4*n, 0);
    build(1, 1, n, a);

    while (q--){
        int op, aa, bb; cin >> op >> aa >> bb;
        if (op == 1){
            upd(1, 1, n, aa, bb, 1, 1 - aa);    // f(i) = i + (1-a)
        } else {
