# Range Queries and Copies

- **CSES problem:** 1737
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (rangecopies.cpp)`](./rangecopies.cpp)

## Problem

Maintain several arrays. Point-assign within a chosen array, query a range sum in one array, or create a copy of an existing array.

## Reasoning

Copying all $n$ values per type 3 operation is too slow. A persistent segment tree represents each array by a root pointer. Copying an array copies only that pointer, so unchanged nodes are shared.

When one version is updated, copy every node on the root-to-leaf path and reuse the untouched sibling at each level. Only $O(\log n)$ new nodes are created. Replacing the selected array's root makes the update visible there, while other roots still reference the original nodes.

This is path copying with immutable historical nodes. Even though a named array is updated in place at the root-vector level, its shared tree nodes are never mutated.

## Algorithm

1. Build one segment-tree root for the initial array.
2. To copy array $k$, append its root ID to the root list.
3. To assign position $p$ in array $k$, recursively create a new root-to-leaf path, share untouched children, and replace `root[k-1]`.
4. To query, recurse over the chosen root and sum covered nodes.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

An update returns a root representing the old version with exactly position $p$ replaced.

#### Proof

At the leaf for $p$, the new node stores the assigned value. At each ancestor, the recursive side uses the newly returned child while the other side reuses the old child. Hence only the path position changes, and recomputed sums are exact. $\square$

### Lemma 2

Copying a root creates an independent logical array equal to its source.

#### Proof

Both roots initially reach identical immutable nodes, so every value matches. A future update creates new path nodes and changes only the selected root entry, leaving the other root and its reachable nodes unchanged. $\square$

### Theorem

Every operation observes exactly the specified array version.

#### Proof

Lemma 2 proves copy semantics. Lemma 1 proves assignments alter only the chosen logical array at the chosen point. Standard segment-tree recursion sums exactly the requested interval of the root representing that array. $\square$

### Complexity

Initial construction takes $O(n)$ time and nodes. Copying takes $O(1)$. An assignment or query takes $O(\log n)$ time; each assignment allocates $O(\log n)$ nodes. Total space is $O(n+u\log n)$ for $u$ assignments, plus array roots.

## Implementation

Node 0 is a reserved sentinel, so `newNode` returns the vector slot just appended. Root entries are zero-based internally while problem array numbers are one-based. Vectors reserve a worst-case node estimate to reduce reallocations.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, q;
vector<ll> sm;
vector<int> lc, rc;
int cnt = 0;

int newNode(){
    sm.pb(0); lc.pb(0); rc.pb(0);
    // return ++cnt;                    // bug: id one ahead of slot index
    return cnt++;                       // id == slot index; sentinel -> 0
}
int build(int l, int r, vector<ll>& a){
    int nd = newNode();
    if (l == r){ sm[nd] = a[l]; return nd; }
    int m = (l + r) >> 1;
    lc[nd] = build(l, m, a);
    rc[nd] = build(m+1, r, a);
    sm[nd] = sm[lc[nd]] + sm[rc[nd]];
    return nd;
}
int upd(int prev, int l, int r, int p, ll v){
    int nd = newNode();
    if (l == r){ sm[nd] = v; return nd; }
    int m = (l + r) >> 1;
    if (p <= m){ lc[nd] = upd(lc[prev], l, m, p, v); rc[nd] = rc[prev]; }
    else       { rc[nd] = upd(rc[prev], m+1, r, p, v); lc[nd] = lc[prev]; }
    sm[nd] = sm[lc[nd]] + sm[rc[nd]];
    return nd;
}
ll query(int nd, int l, int r, int ql, int qr){
    if (qr < l || r < ql || !nd) return 0;
    if (ql <= l && r <= qr) return sm[nd];
    int m = (l + r) >> 1;
    return query(lc[nd], l, m, ql, qr) + query(rc[nd], m+1, r, ql, qr);
}

int main(){
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;

    int cap = 2*n + (q + 5) * (__lg(max(n,1)) + 2) + 10;
    sm.reserve(cap); lc.reserve(cap); rc.reserve(cap);
    newNode();                          // node 0 sentinel

    vector<ll> a(n + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> a[i];

    vector<int> root;                   // root[k] = version root for array k
    root.pb(build(1, n, a));            // array index 0 == "array 1"

    while (q--){
        int op; cin >> op;
        if (op == 1){
            int k, p; ll x; cin >> k >> p >> x;
            root[k-1] = upd(root[k-1], 1, n, p, x);
        } else if (op == 2){
            int k, aa, bb; cin >> k >> aa >> bb;
            cout << query(root[k-1], 1, n, aa, bb) << '\n';
        } else {
            int k; cin >> k;
            root.pb(root[k-1]);         // copy-on-write: share root
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Copy array A to B, then assign position 3 only in A. Both roots still share every node outside the path to position 3. A's new path ends at the replacement leaf, while B's root retains the old path and old value.

## Takeaway

When versions differ by sparse updates, persistence replaces full copies with shared immutable structure and path copying.

### Related problems

Missing Coin Sum Queries uses prefix-version persistent trees for subarray value queries. Dynamic Range Sum Queries keeps only one mutable version.

