# Company Queries I

- **Source:** [CSES 1687, Company Queries I](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1687/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (companyqueries1.cpp)`](./companyqueries1.cpp)

## Problem

For each query $(x,k)$, find the boss obtained by moving exactly $k$ steps upward from employee $x$, or print $-1$ if that ancestor does not exist.

Walking one boss at a time is too slow when both $q$ and $k$ are large.

## Reasoning

Precompute powers of the parent function. Define

$$
up[j][v]=\text{the }2^j\text{-th ancestor of }v,
$$

using vertex 0 as a sentinel above the root. The recurrence is

$$
up[j][v]=up[j-1][up[j-1][v]],
$$

because two jumps of length $2^{j-1}$ form one jump of length $2^j$.

Every $k$ is a sum of powers of two. For each set bit $j$, replace the current employee by `up[j][current]`. Once the sentinel zero is reached, every further jump remains zero because all global table entries at vertex 0 are zero.

The official query bound requires bits 0 through 29, so the repaired implementation uses 30 layers. Eighteen layers would cover the maximum tree depth but would silently ignore high bits of $k$ and answer large impossible jumps incorrectly.

## Algorithm

1. Store each direct boss in `up[0]`, with `up[0][1] = 0`.
2. Build layers 1 through 29 using the doubling recurrence.
3. For each query $(x,k)$:
   - scan all bits of $k$;
   - for every set bit $j$, assign `x = up[j][x]`;
   - stop early if `x` becomes zero.
4. Print $x$ if nonzero, otherwise print $-1$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

`up[j][v]` is the ancestor exactly $2^j$ edges above $v$, or zero if it does not exist.

#### Proof

Layer zero stores the one-edge parent. Assuming the statement for $j-1$, the recurrence moves $2^{j-1}$ edges to an intermediate ancestor and then the same number again, totaling $2^j$. The zero sentinel remains zero when either segment leaves the tree. $\square$

### Lemma 2

After processing some bits of $k$, the current vertex is the ancestor at distance equal to the sum of their powers.

#### Proof

Initially the sum is zero. An unset bit changes nothing. For a set bit $j$, Lemma 1 applies exactly $2^j$ additional parent edges. Induction preserves the invariant. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm answers every query correctly.

#### Proof

After all bits, Lemma 2 gives an upward distance equal to the binary value $k$. A nonzero result is exactly that ancestor. Zero means the path passed above the director, so no such ancestor exists and $-1$ is correct. $\square$

### Complexity

Preprocessing takes $O(n\log K)$ time and space with $\log K=30$. Each query takes $O(\log K)$ time.

## Implementation

The table is layer-major: `up[j][v]`. Global zero initialization makes `up[j][0] = 0` automatically.

The query loop tests `k >> j & 1`. Thirty layers are necessary for all values below $2^{30}$.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
const int LOG = 30;
int n, q;
int up[LOG][200005];
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) cin >> up[0][i];
    up[0][1] = 0;   // director has no boss

    for (int j = 1; j < LOG; j++)
        for (int v = 1; v <= n; v++)
            up[j][v] = up[j-1][ up[j-1][v] ];   // up[*][0]=0 sentinel

    while (q--) {
        int x, k; cin >> x >> k;
        for (int j = 0; j < LOG && x; j++)
            if (k >> j & 1) x = up[j][x];
        cout << (x ? x : -1) << '\n';
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

If the boss chain is $5\to4\to2\to1$, query $(5,3)$ has binary distance $3=2+1$. The two-step jump reaches 2 and the one-step jump reaches 1. Query $(5,7)$ reaches sentinel zero and prints $-1$.

## Takeaway

For repeated application of a static parent or successor function, binary lifting precomputes powers of the function. Size the table from the query magnitude, not only the structure depth.

### Related problems

Company Queries II uses the same table for lowest common ancestors. Planets Queries I applies binary lifting to a functional graph.

