# Company Queries II

- **Source:** [CSES 1688, Company Queries II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1688/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (companyqueries2.cpp)`](./companyqueries2.cpp)

## Problem

For each pair of employees, find their lowest common boss: the deepest vertex that is an ancestor of both.

This is the lowest common ancestor, or LCA, problem on a rooted tree.

## Reasoning

Binary lifting stores each $2^j$-th ancestor. To compare two vertices, first move the deeper one upward until both have equal depth. If they coincide, that vertex is the LCA.

Otherwise, move them upward together while keeping them distinct. Process jump powers from largest to smallest. Whenever their $2^j$-th ancestors differ, both jumps are safe: the LCA lies strictly above those ancestors, so neither jump passes it. When no such jump remains, the two vertices are distinct children of the LCA, and their direct parents are equal.

Depths are computed directly from input order because every boss index is given before its employee in this problem's hierarchy representation.

## Algorithm

1. Read direct parents and compute depths.
2. Build the 18-layer ancestor table.
3. For each query $(a,b)$:
   - swap them if needed so $a$ is deeper;
   - lift $a$ by the depth difference;
   - if $a=b$, print it;
   - otherwise scan powers downward and lift both whenever `up[j][a] != up[j][b]`;
   - print their common direct parent.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After depth alignment, both query vertices have equal depth and their LCA is unchanged.

#### Proof

Only the deeper vertex is moved upward by the depth difference. Any common ancestor lies at or above the shallower depth, so this movement cannot pass the LCA. The aligned vertex remains on the original ancestor chain, preserving the set of common ancestors. $\square$

### Lemma 2

During the descending simultaneous-lift loop, the vertices remain below their LCA and at equal depth.

#### Proof

They are moved by equal distances, preserving depth equality. A jump occurs only when the proposed ancestors differ. If either proposed ancestor were at or above the LCA, equal-depth ancestor uniqueness would make both proposed ancestors equal. Therefore every accepted jump stops strictly below the LCA. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm prints the lowest common ancestor of every queried pair.

#### Proof

If aligned vertices coincide, Lemma 1 makes that vertex their deepest common ancestor. Otherwise, Lemma 2 keeps both below the LCA. After all powers are considered, no positive jump can keep their ancestors different; in particular their direct parents coincide. Since the vertices themselves remain distinct below the LCA, this common parent is exactly the LCA. $\square$

### Complexity

Preprocessing uses $O(n\log n)$ time and space. Each query takes $O(\log n)$ time. Eighteen layers suffice because every depth is below $2^{18}$ for $n\le2\cdot10^5$.

## Implementation

The direct parent array doubles as lifting layer zero. Root depth and parent are both zero-initialized.

The first query loop scans bits upward because it applies an exact distance. The second scans downward because it greedily makes the largest safe simultaneous jumps.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
const int LOG = 18;
int n, q;
int up[LOG][200005], dep[200005];

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) cin >> up[0][i];
    up[0][1] = 0;
    for (int v = 2; v <= n; v++) dep[v] = dep[up[0][v]] + 1;  // par precedes child

    for (int j = 1; j < LOG; j++)
        for (int v = 1; v <= n; v++)
            up[j][v] = up[j-1][ up[j-1][v] ];

    while (q--) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        if (dep[a] < dep[b]) swap(a, b);          // a is deeper
        int d = dep[a] - dep[b];
        for (int j = 0; j < LOG; j++)
            if (d >> j & 1) a = up[j][a];
        if (a == b) { cout << a << '\n'; continue; }
        for (int j = LOG - 1; j >= 0; j--)
            if (up[j][a] != up[j][b]) { a = up[j][a]; b = up[j][b]; }
        cout << up[0][a] << '\n';
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Suppose vertices 4 and 5 are children of 2, while 2 and 3 are children of 1. For query $(4,3)$, depths are aligned by lifting 4 to 2. Their largest differing safe ancestors leave them at 2 and 3, whose common direct parent is 1. For $(4,5)$, they already have equal depth and their direct common parent is 2.

## Takeaway

LCA by binary lifting has two stages: equalize depth, then lift both vertices as far as possible while their ancestors remain different.

### Related problems

Company Queries I provides ancestor jumps. Distance Queries combines LCA with the tree-distance formula.

