# Counting Paths

- **Source:** [CSES 1136, Counting Paths](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1136/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (countingpaths.cpp)`](./countingpaths.cpp)

## Problem

Given many vertex pairs in a tree, count for every vertex how many of the corresponding unique paths pass through it.

Updating every vertex of every path can be quadratic. Tree differences turn each path update into four point changes followed by one global accumulation.

## Reasoning

Root the tree. Suppose a value placed at a vertex is later added upward from every subtree to its parent. Then a $+1$ at endpoint $a$ contributes to every ancestor of $a$.

For path endpoints $a,b$ and $l=\operatorname{lca}(a,b)$, use updates

$$
cnt[a]++,\qquad cnt[b]++,\qquad cnt[l]--,
$$

and, if $l$ is not the root,

$$
cnt[parent(l)]--.
$$

After subtree-to-parent accumulation, consider a vertex $v$. Endpoint $a$ contributes to $v$ exactly when $v$ is an ancestor of $a$; similarly for $b$. The two negative marks cancel contributions strictly above the LCA while retaining one contribution at the LCA itself. Thus exactly the vertices on the path receive one.

This is the vertex-counting variant. For counting edges, one would instead subtract twice at the LCA.

Binary lifting answers all LCAs, and reverse BFS order accumulates children before parents.

## Algorithm

1. Root the tree at 1 by BFS, recording parent, depth, and parent-before-child order.
2. Build the binary-lifting table.
3. For every path query $(a,b)$:
   - compute $l=\operatorname{lca}(a,b)$;
   - increment `cnt[a]` and `cnt[b]`;
   - decrement `cnt[l]`;
   - decrement `cnt[parent(l)]` when that parent exists.
4. Scan vertices in reverse BFS order and add each `cnt[u]` into its parent.
5. Print the accumulated counts.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After reverse accumulation, the final value at vertex $v$ equals the sum of all initial difference marks in the subtree of $v$.

#### Proof

Reverse BFS processes every child before its parent. Adding each child total to its parent therefore aggregates all and only descendants. Induction from leaves proves the subtree-sum interpretation. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The four difference updates for one query contribute one after accumulation exactly to vertices on its path and zero elsewhere.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1, vertex $v$ receives the endpoint mark at $a$ exactly when it is an ancestor of $a$, and likewise for $b$. Below the LCA, exactly one endpoint lies in the relevant child branch, so path vertices receive one and off-path branches receive zero.

At $l$, both endpoint marks contribute two and the mark at $l$ subtracts one, leaving one. Every strict ancestor of $l$ receives both endpoint marks and both negative marks, leaving zero. Vertices outside these ancestor chains receive no marks. Thus precisely the path is marked. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm prints for every vertex the number of queried paths containing it.

#### Proof

Lemma 2 proves the contribution of each individual query. Difference marks add linearly, so accumulating all queries simultaneously gives at each vertex the sum of their indicator contributions, which is exactly the desired count. $\square$

### Complexity

Preprocessing takes $O(n\log n)$. Each of the $m$ queries takes $O(\log n)$, and final accumulation takes $O(n)$. Total time is $O((n+m)\log n)$ and space is $O(n\log n)$.

## Implementation

`cnt` uses `long long` because one vertex may belong to every query path.

The root has no parent, so the parent-of-LCA decrement is skipped when `up[0][l] == 0`. The LCA decrement itself is always applied.

The BFS order array supports both parent construction and the final reverse accumulation.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
const int LOG = 18;
int n, m;
vector<int> g[200005];
int up[LOG][200005], dep[200005], ord[200005];
ll cnt[200005];

int lca(int a, int b) {
    if (dep[a] < dep[b]) swap(a, b);
    int d = dep[a] - dep[b];
    for (int j = 0; j < LOG; j++) if (d >> j & 1) a = up[j][a];
    if (a == b) return a;
    for (int j = LOG - 1; j >= 0; j--)
        if (up[j][a] != up[j][b]) { a = up[j][a]; b = up[j][b]; }
    return up[0][a];
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> m;
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        g[a].push_back(b);
        g[b].push_back(a);
    }

    int head = 0, tail = 0;
    ord[tail++] = 1; up[0][1] = 0; dep[1] = 0;
    static bool vis[200005];
    vis[1] = true;
    while (head < tail) {
        int u = ord[head++];
        for (int v : g[u]) if (!vis[v]) {
            vis[v] = true; up[0][v] = u; dep[v] = dep[u] + 1;
            ord[tail++] = v;
        }
    }

    for (int j = 1; j < LOG; j++)
        for (int v = 1; v <= n; v++)
            up[j][v] = up[j-1][ up[j-1][v] ];

    while (m--) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        int l = lca(a, b);
        cnt[a]++; cnt[b]++; cnt[l]--;
        if (up[0][l]) cnt[up[0][l]]--;   // -1 at parent(LCA); root has no parent
    }

    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {   // reverse BFS = children before parent
        int u = ord[i];
        if (up[0][u]) cnt[up[0][u]] += cnt[u];
    }

    for (int v = 1; v <= n; v++) {
        cout << cnt[v];
        cout << (v == n ? '\n' : ' ');
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For path query $(4,5)$ with LCA 2, updates are $+1$ at 4 and 5, $-1$ at 2, and $-1$ at parent 1. After accumulation, vertices 4 and 5 each have one, vertex 2 receives $1+1-1=1$, and root 1 receives $1-1=0$. These are exactly the vertices of path $4-2-5$.

## Takeaway

Offline path aggregation on trees often needs only endpoint marks, LCA cancellation, and one postorder sum. Choose the LCA correction carefully depending on whether vertices or edges are being counted.

### Related problems

Distance Queries supplies LCA machinery. Range-add difference arrays are the one-dimensional analogue of this tree technique.

