# Subtree Queries

- **Source:** [CSES 1137, Subtree Queries](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1137/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (subtreequeries.cpp)`](./subtreequeries.cpp)

## Problem

Each tree vertex has a value. Support point assignments and queries asking for the sum of all values in a vertex's rooted subtree.

The tree is rooted at vertex 1. Directly traversing a subtree per query can take linear time.

## Reasoning

In depth-first entry order, every subtree occupies one contiguous interval. When DFS enters vertex $u$, assign time `tin[u]`. All descendants are entered before DFS exits $u$, and no outside vertex can be entered during that interval. If `tout[u]` is the last timer value before exit, then

$$
v\text{ is in the subtree of }u
\iff
tin[u]\le tin[v]\le tout[u].
$$

Flatten the tree into an array where position `tin[v]` stores vertex $v$'s value. A subtree sum becomes an ordinary range sum, and an assignment becomes one point difference update. A Fenwick tree supports both in $O(\log n)$.

Recursive DFS is unsafe on a chain of $2\cdot10^5$ vertices. The implementation stores each active vertex and its next adjacency index explicitly. `tout[u]` is assigned when that frame has no more children; the current timer then marks the final entry within its subtree.

## Algorithm

1. Perform iterative DFS from root 1, recording `tin`, `tout_`, and inverse entry array `pos`.
2. Initialize a Fenwick tree at flattened position $t$ with value of vertex `pos[t]`.
3. For assignment `value[s] = x`:
   - add `x - oldValue[s]` at position `tin[s]`;
   - store the new value.
4. For a subtree query at $s$, return the Fenwick range sum

   $$
   prefix(tout[s])-prefix(tin[s]-1).
   $$

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

The vertices in the subtree of $u$ occupy exactly flattened interval $[tin[u],tout[u]]$.

#### Proof

DFS assigns `tin[u]` upon entry. It completely explores every child subtree before removing $u$ from the explicit stack, so every descendant receives a consecutive later time no greater than the timer at exit. A vertex outside the subtree cannot be entered until DFS has left $u$, or was entered before $u$. Thus the interval contains exactly the subtree. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The Fenwick tree stores the current vertex value at every Euler position.

#### Proof

Initialization adds each original value once at its unique entry time. An assignment adds precisely new minus old at that same position, changing its represented value to the new one and leaving all other positions unchanged. $\square$

### Theorem

Every reported subtree sum is correct.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1, the queried interval contains exactly the subtree vertices. By Lemma 2, each interval position stores its current value. The Fenwick range query sums exactly those values. $\square$

### Complexity

Flattening and initialization take $O(n\log n)$ with the implemented individual Fenwick inserts. Each update or query takes $O(\log n)$. Space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

`it[u]` is the next adjacency entry for the active DFS frame. When it reaches the end, `tout_[u] = timer` records the last descendant entry.

`val` is `int`, but Fenwick nodes and query results are `long long` because a subtree sum may be $\Theta(n\cdot10^9)$.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int n, q;
vector<int> g[200005];
int val[200005], tin[200005], tout_[200005], pos[200005];
ll bit[200005];

void upd(int i, ll d) { for (; i <= n; i += i & -i) bit[i] += d; }
ll qry(int i) { ll s = 0; for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) s += bit[i]; return s; }

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> val[i];
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        g[a].push_back(b);
        g[b].push_back(a);
    }

    // iterative DFS for tin/tout
    static int st[200005], it[200005];
    static int par[200005];
    int timer = 0, sp = 0;
    st[sp] = 1; par[1] = 0; it[1] = 0;
    tin[1] = ++timer; pos[timer] = 1;
    while (sp >= 0) {
        int u = st[sp];
        if (it[u] < (int)g[u].size()) {
            int v = g[u][it[u]++];
            if (v == par[u]) continue;
            par[v] = u; it[v] = 0;
            tin[v] = ++timer; pos[timer] = v;
            st[++sp] = v;
        } else {
            tout_[u] = timer;
            sp--;
        }
    }

    for (int t = 1; t <= n; t++) upd(t, val[pos[t]]);

    while (q--) {
        int type; cin >> type;
        if (type == 1) {
            int s, x; cin >> s >> x;
            upd(tin[s], (ll)x - val[s]);
            val[s] = x;
        } else {
            int s; cin >> s;
            cout << qry(tout_[s]) - qry(tin[s] - 1) << '\n';
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

If entry order is $1,2,4,5,3$, subtree 2 occupies positions 2 through 4. With values $(5,2,7,1,3)$ on vertices 1 through 5, its flattened entries hold 2, 1, and 3, summing to 6. Assigning vertex 4 from 1 to 10 adds 9 at its one Euler position, and the next subtree-2 query returns 15.

## Takeaway

DFS entry order converts rooted subtrees into array intervals. Once flattened, standard range data structures solve dynamic subtree aggregation.

### Related problems

Path Queries uses the same subtree intervals for descendant range additions. Distinct Colors exploits the same Euler contiguity offline.

