# Path Queries

- **Source:** [CSES 1138, Path Queries](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1138/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (pathqueries.cpp)`](./pathqueries.cpp)

## Problem

Each tree vertex has a value. Support value assignments and queries asking for the sum along the path from root 1 to a given vertex.

Updating one vertex changes the answer for every descendant, which suggests reversing the usual point-update viewpoint.

## Reasoning

Let

$$
S(v)=\sum_{u\text{ ancestor of }v}value[u].
$$

If `value[u]` changes by $\Delta$, then $S(v)$ changes by $\Delta$ exactly for descendants $v$ of $u$. In Euler entry order, those descendants form interval $[tin[u],tout[u]]$.

Thus each vertex value contributes a range addition over its subtree, and a root-path query is a point query at `tin[v]`.

A Fenwick tree over a difference array supports range addition and point query:

- add $\Delta$ at $l$;
- add $-\Delta$ at $r+1$;
- the prefix sum at position $p$ is the total of all ranges covering $p$.

Initialization applies one subtree range update for every vertex. This directly builds all root-path sums without separately computing them.

## Algorithm

1. Flatten the rooted tree by iterative DFS, obtaining `tin` and `tout_`.
2. For each vertex $v$, range-add `value[v]` to interval `[tin[v], tout[v]]` in a Fenwick difference structure.
3. For assignment of vertex $s$ to $x$:
   - compute $\Delta=x-value[s]$;
   - range-add $\Delta$ over $s$'s subtree;
   - store the new value.
4. For a query at $s$, print the Fenwick prefix sum at `tin[s]`.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

A vertex $u$ is an ancestor of $v$ exactly when `tin[v]` lies in interval `[tin[u], tout[u]]`.

#### Proof

Iterative DFS enters all and only descendants of $u$ between its entry and exit, giving the standard contiguous-subtree property. $\square$

### Lemma 2

At any time, the point value represented at `tin[v]` equals the sum of current values on the root-to-$v$ path.

#### Proof

Each vertex $u$ adds its value over its subtree interval. By Lemma 1, position `tin[v]` is covered by this update exactly when $u$ is an ancestor of $v$. Summing all covering range additions therefore gives exactly the root-path sum. Assignments replace the old contribution by adding the difference over the same interval, preserving the statement. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm answers every root-path sum query correctly.

#### Proof

A Fenwick prefix query on the difference representation returns the total of all range additions covering that point. Lemma 2 identifies this total at `tin[s]` with the requested root-to-$s$ sum. $\square$

### Complexity

Euler flattening takes $O(n)$. The implemented initialization performs $n$ range updates for $O(n\log n)$ time. Each assignment or query takes $O(\log n)$, and space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

`radd(l,r,d)` performs the two difference updates, skipping `r+1` when the interval reaches position $n$.

The Fenwick `qry` operation is a point query in the logical range-add structure, even though mechanically it is a prefix sum.

Both stored values and Fenwick nodes are `long long` because a root path can contain many large values.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int n, q;
vector<int> g[200005];
ll val[200005];
int tin[200005], tout_[200005];
ll bit[200005];

void upd(int i, ll d) { for (; i <= n; i += i & -i) bit[i] += d; }
ll qry(int i) { ll s = 0; for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) s += bit[i]; return s; }
void radd(int l, int r, ll d) { upd(l, d); if (r + 1 <= n) upd(r + 1, -d); }

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> val[i];
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        g[a].push_back(b);
        g[b].push_back(a);
    }

    static int st[200005], it[200005], par[200005];
    int timer = 0, sp = 0;
    st[sp] = 1; par[1] = 0; it[1] = 0;
    tin[1] = ++timer;
    while (sp >= 0) {
        int u = st[sp];
        if (it[u] < (int)g[u].size()) {
            int v = g[u][it[u]++];
            if (v == par[u]) continue;
            par[v] = u; it[v] = 0;
            tin[v] = ++timer;
            st[++sp] = v;
        } else {
            tout_[u] = timer;
            sp--;
        }
    }

    for (int v = 1; v <= n; v++) radd(tin[v], tout_[v], val[v]);

    while (q--) {
        int type; cin >> type;
        if (type == 1) {
            int s; ll x; cin >> s >> x;
            radd(tin[s], tout_[s], x - val[s]);
            val[s] = x;
        } else {
            int s; cin >> s;
            cout << qry(tin[s]) << '\n';
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

In a rooted tree with path $1-2-4$, values 5, 3, and 2 contribute subtree intervals covering `tin[4]`. Its point query is therefore $5+3+2=10$. If vertex 2 changes from 3 to 8, delta 5 is added over subtree 2, and the query at 4 becomes 15 while vertices outside subtree 2 remain unchanged.

## Takeaway

When a vertex update affects all descendant queries, flatten subtrees and reinterpret each vertex as a range contribution. Difference Fenwick trees turn subtree range adds into root-path point queries.

### Related problems

Subtree Queries uses point updates and subtree range sums, the dual Euler-tour arrangement. Path Queries II handles arbitrary path maxima with heavy-light decomposition.

