# Path Queries II

- **CSES problem:** 2134
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (pathqueriesII.cpp)`](./pathqueriesII.cpp)

## Problem

A tree has a value at every vertex. Two operations must be supported: assign a new value to one vertex, and report the maximum value on the unique simple path between two given vertices.

## Reasoning

The limits allow roughly logarithmic work per operation, but a path may contain all $n$ vertices. A direct walk is therefore too slow. An Euler tour makes every subtree contiguous, yet an arbitrary path is not generally one Euler interval, so subtree flattening alone does not solve the query.

The useful distinction is between heavy and light edges. Root the tree at vertex 1, let $sz[u]$ be the size of the subtree of $u$, and designate a child of maximum subtree size as the heavy child. Every other child edge is light. Maximal runs of heavy edges form heavy chains.

Whenever a rootward walk crosses a light edge from a child $v$ to its parent, the containing subtree at least doubles: because $v$ was not the heavy child, $sz[v] \le (sz[parent[v]]-1)/2$. Thus any root path crosses at most $O(\log n)$ light edges and meets at most $O(\log n)$ chains.

Assign consecutive array positions along each heavy chain. The segment of a tree path lying inside one chain becomes one contiguous array interval. To query a path from $a$ to $b$, repeatedly process the deeper chain head and jump above it. Once both vertices share a chain, one final interval completes the path.

The implementation builds parent and depth arrays iteratively, accumulates subtree sizes in reverse traversal order, and then performs an iterative heavy-first decomposition. Since the heavy child is pushed last onto a LIFO stack, it is processed next and receives the position immediately following its parent.

## Algorithm

1. Root the tree at 1 and record `par`, `dep`, and a traversal order.
2. Process that order backwards to compute subtree sizes and each vertex's heavy child.
3. Assign every vertex a chain head and a position, visiting a heavy child immediately after its parent.
4. Build an iterative maximum segment tree over the values in position order.
5. For an assignment, replace the leaf at the vertex's position and recompute its ancestors.
6. For a path query, while the chain heads differ, query from the deeper head to its vertex and move that endpoint to the head's parent. Query the remaining interval when both endpoints share a chain.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

Vertices of every heavy chain occupy consecutive positions in increasing depth order.

#### Proof

The decomposition assigns a vertex its next free position. Its heavy child inherits the same head and, because it is pushed last, is popped and assigned immediately afterward. This continues until the chain ends. Light children start new chains and cannot interrupt those assignments. Hence each chain is contiguous and ordered from its head downward. $\square$

### Lemma 2

Each iteration of a path query processes exactly a previously unprocessed segment of the path.

#### Proof

Suppose the endpoints have different heads, and let $a$ have the deeper head after a possible swap. The path from `head_[a]` to $a$ lies wholly in one chain, so Lemma 1 maps it to the queried interval. The lowest common ancestor cannot lie strictly below this head on $a$'s chain while $b$ has another head. Therefore this whole segment belongs to the desired path. Replacing $a$ by the parent of its head removes precisely that segment and leaves the unprocessed path between the new $a$ and $b$. $\square$

### Lemma 3

When both endpoints have the same head, the interval between their positions represents exactly their remaining tree path.

#### Proof

Both vertices lie on one heavy chain, whose vertices are ordered by depth and contiguous by Lemma 1. The unique path between them is exactly the chain segment from the shallower endpoint to the deeper endpoint. $\square$

### Theorem

Every type 2 operation returns the maximum value on the requested path.

#### Proof

By Lemma 2, each loop iteration removes one disjoint valid segment of the path without omitting any remaining vertex. Lemma 3 identifies the final segment. These segments partition the complete path, and the segment tree returns the maximum on each. Taking their maximum therefore returns exactly the path maximum. Point assignments keep the segment tree value at every position equal to the current vertex value. $\square$

### Complexity

Preprocessing takes $O(n)$ time and $O(n)$ space. A point assignment takes $O(\log n)$ time. A path meets $O(\log n)$ chains, and every segment-tree query costs $O(\log n)$, so a path query takes $O(\log^2 n)$ time.

## Implementation

`head_[u]` names the top of $u$'s heavy chain and `pos_[u]` is its segment-tree index. The range query uses an inclusive interface even though its internal loop converts the right boundary to a half-open boundary. `LLONG_MIN` is the identity for maximum and also makes the structure valid independently of sign restrictions.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int n, q;
vector<int> g[200005];
int val[200005], par[200005], dep[200005], sz[200005], heavy[200005];
int head_[200005], pos_[200005], ord[200005];
int N;
ll seg[1<<19];

inline void supd(int p, ll v) {
    for (seg[p += N] = v, p >>= 1; p; p >>= 1)
        seg[p] = max(seg[p<<1], seg[p<<1|1]);
}
inline ll sqry(int l, int r) {            // inclusive [l,r], 0-indexed
    ll res = LLONG_MIN;
    for (l += N, r += N + 1; l < r; l >>= 1, r >>= 1) {
        if (l & 1) res = max(res, seg[l++]);
        if (r & 1) res = max(res, seg[--r]);
    }
    return res;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> q;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> val[i];
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        g[a].push_back(b);
        g[b].push_back(a);
    }

    int hd = 0, tl = 0;
    ord[tl++] = 1; par[1] = 0; dep[1] = 0;
    static bool vis[200005];
    vis[1] = true;
    while (hd < tl) {
        int u = ord[hd++];
        for (int v : g[u]) if (!vis[v]) {
            vis[v] = true; par[v] = u; dep[v] = dep[u] + 1;
            ord[tl++] = v;
        }
    }
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) sz[i] = 1, heavy[i] = 0;
    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        int u = ord[i];
        if (par[u]) {
            sz[par[u]] += sz[u];
            if (heavy[par[u]] == 0 || sz[u] > sz[heavy[par[u]]])
                heavy[par[u]] = u;
        }
    }

    int timer = 0;
    static int stk[200005];
    int sp = 0;
    head_[1] = 1;
    stk[sp++] = 1;
    while (sp) {
        int u = stk[--sp];
        pos_[u] = timer++;
        ord[timer - 1] = u;
        for (int v : g[u]) if (v != par[u] && v != heavy[u]) {
            head_[v] = v;
            stk[sp++] = v;
        }
        if (heavy[u]) {
            head_[heavy[u]] = head_[u];
            stk[sp++] = heavy[u];
        }
    }

    N = 1; while (N < n) N <<= 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < 2*N; i++) seg[i] = LLONG_MIN;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) seg[N + pos_[ord[i]]] = val[ord[i]];
    for (int i = N - 1; i; i--) seg[i] = max(seg[i<<1], seg[i<<1|1]);

    string out;
    out.reserve(1 << 22);
    char buf[24];

    while (q--) {
        int type; cin >> type;
        if (type == 1) {
            int s, x; cin >> s >> x;
            val[s] = x;
            supd(pos_[s], x);
        } else {
            int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
            ll res = LLONG_MIN;
            while (head_[a] != head_[b]) {
                if (dep[head_[a]] < dep[head_[b]]) swap(a, b);
                res = max(res, sqry(pos_[head_[a]], pos_[a]));
                a = par[head_[a]];
            }
            if (dep[a] > dep[b]) swap(a, b);
            res = max(res, sqry(pos_[a], pos_[b]));
            int len = 0; ll t = res;
            if (t == 0) buf[len++] = '0';
            while (t) { buf[len++] = char('0' + t % 10); t /= 10; }
            while (len) out += buf[--len];
            out += '\n';
        }
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Suppose the path from 7 to 5 crosses chains as $7,6$, then $3,1$, then $2,5$. The query first takes the interval for the deeper chain segment $6$ through $7$ and jumps to `par[6]`. It next removes whichever remaining chain head is deeper. Once both endpoints share a head, one final interval is queried. Every path vertex appears in exactly one of these intervals.

## Takeaway

Heavy-light decomposition is the standard bridge from arbitrary tree paths to a logarithmic number of array intervals. It is most useful when a data structure already solves the corresponding interval operation.

### Related problems

Path Queries needs only root-to-vertex sums and admits a simpler Euler-tour solution. Subtree Queries uses subtree contiguity directly. Company Queries II supplies the same path geometry through lowest common ancestors.

