# Distinct Colors

- **CSES problem:** 1139
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (distinctcolors.cpp)`](./distinctcolors.cpp)

## Problem

Each vertex of a rooted tree has a color. For every vertex $u$, determine how many distinct colors occur in the subtree of $u$.

## Reasoning

Computing a fresh set for every subtree can repeat nearly the same work at many ancestors. On a path, the subtree sizes are $1,2,\ldots,n$, so explicitly rebuilding all sets costs $\Theta(n^2)$ insertions.

Root the tree at 1 and process children before parents. Once every child subtree has been solved, the color set for $u$ is

$$
\{color[u]\}\cup\bigcup_{v\text{ child of }u} S_v.
$$

The union formula is immediate, but its implementation determines the complexity. Always merge the smaller set into the larger set. If an element is moved, the destination set is at least twice as large as the source set that held it. A color occurrence can therefore move only $O(\log n)$ times before reaching a set of size at most $n$.

The source uses one mutable `set<int>` object per active subtree, referenced through pointers. Swapping pointers makes the larger child's set become the parent's accumulator without copying it. Reverse breadth-first order ensures that all descendants have already contributed when `ans[u]` is recorded.

## Algorithm

1. Root the tree at 1 and store vertices in parent-before-child order.
2. Traverse that order backwards.
3. Insert `col[u]` into $u$'s current set.
4. Record the current set size as `ans[u]`.
5. If $u$ has a parent $p$, ensure the larger of $S_p$ and $S_u$ is referenced by $S_p$, insert every element of the smaller set into it, and clear the smaller set.
6. Output all recorded answers.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

Immediately before `ans[u]` is recorded, `S[u]` contains exactly the colors appearing in the subtree of $u$.

#### Proof

Proceed in reverse traversal order. Every child $v$ is processed before $u$ and merges all colors of its subtree into $S[u]$. By induction, those merged sets contain exactly the child-subtree colors. The algorithm also inserts `col[u]`. A rooted subtree consists of $u$ and the disjoint subtrees of its children, so their union is exactly the set stored at $u$. $\square$

### Lemma 2

Swapping set pointers and clearing the smaller source does not change the set of colors delivered to the parent.

#### Proof

The pointer swap changes ownership only. The subsequent insertions form the union of the two sets, and set insertion removes duplicate color values by definition. Clearing the now-unused smaller object occurs only after every one of its elements has been inserted into the union. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs the number of distinct colors in every vertex's subtree.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1, at the moment `ans[u]` is assigned, its set contains precisely the subtree colors. Its size is therefore the required distinct count. Lemma 2 shows that later merging preserves exactly the information needed by ancestors and cannot corrupt an already recorded answer. $\square$

### Complexity

Every successful small-to-large move at least doubles the containing set size, so each stored color participates in $O(\log n)$ moves. Each `std::set` insertion costs $O(\log n)$, giving the implemented bound $O(n\log^2 n)$ time and $O(n)$ total stored elements. The tree arrays also use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

`S[u]` is a pointer because exchanging two pointers is constant time, whereas copying two sets would defeat the optimization. The answer is saved before $u$'s set is merged upward. The traversal is iterative to avoid recursion depth failure on a tree that is one long path.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int n;
vector<int> g[200005];
int col[200005], par[200005], ord[200005];
set<int>* S[200005];
int ans[200005];

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> col[i];
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        g[a].push_back(b);
        g[b].push_back(a);
    }

    int hd = 0, tl = 0;
    ord[tl++] = 1; par[1] = 0;
    static bool vis[200005];
    vis[1] = true;
    while (hd < tl) {
        int u = ord[hd++];
        for (int v : g[u]) if (!vis[v]) {
            vis[v] = true; par[v] = u;
            ord[tl++] = v;
        }
    }

    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {   // children before parent
        int u = ord[i];
        if (!S[u]) S[u] = new set<int>();
        S[u]->insert(col[u]);
        ans[u] = (int)S[u]->size();
        int p = par[u];
        if (p) {
            if (!S[p]) S[p] = new set<int>();
            if (S[p]->size() < S[u]->size()) swap(S[p], S[u]);  // small into large
            for (int c : *S[u]) S[p]->insert(c);
            S[u]->clear();
        }
    }

    for (int v = 1; v <= n; v++) {
        cout << ans[v];
        cout << (v == n ? '\n' : ' ');
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Let vertex 1 have children 2 and 3. Suppose their solved sets are $S_2=\{1,4,7\}$ and $S_3=\{4,9\}$, while vertex 1 has color 7. Processing the smaller second set inserts 4 and 9 into the larger first set. Color 4 is already present and is not duplicated. The resulting set is $\{1,4,7,9\}$, so the answer for vertex 1 is 4.

## Takeaway

When every parent needs the union of its children's collections, merge small collections into large ones. The doubling argument often turns repeated subtree aggregation from quadratic work into near-linear work.

### Related problems

Subtree Queries also aggregates rooted subtrees but supports online numeric updates. Distinct Values Queries solves the analogous distinct-count problem on array intervals.

