# Finding a Centroid

- **CSES problem:** 2079
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (findingcentroid.cpp)`](./findingcentroid.cpp)

## Problem

Find a vertex whose removal divides an $n$-vertex tree into connected components of size at most $\lfloor n/2\rfloor$. Such a vertex is called a centroid.

## Reasoning

Root the tree temporarily at vertex 1 and compute subtree sizes. Removing a vertex $v$ produces one component of size $sz[u]$ for every child $u$, plus an upward component of size $n-sz[v]$ when $v$ is not the root.

If a child subtree of the current vertex contains more than half the tree, the current vertex cannot be a centroid, and every centroid must lie inside that child subtree. Indeed, moving anywhere outside it leaves that entire oversized subtree connected after removal.

This suggests a descent: start at the root and repeatedly move into a child whose current component size exceeds $n/2$. There can be at most one such neighbor because two disjoint components cannot both contain more than half the vertices. When no such neighbor exists, every component produced by removal has acceptable size.

The implementation updates sizes while moving. If it descends from $v$ to `nxt`, then with the tree viewed from `nxt`, the component through $v$ has size $n-sz[nxt]$. Assigning this to `sz[v]` reorients the one traversed edge and keeps later neighbor-size tests meaningful.

## Algorithm

1. Root the tree at 1, recording parents and a traversal order.
2. Process the order backwards to compute initial subtree sizes.
3. Set $v=1$.
4. If a child-side component of $v$ has size greater than $n/2$, reorient the traversed edge's size information and move to that child.
5. Otherwise output $v$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

If removing $v$ creates a component $C$ with more than $n/2$ vertices, every centroid lies in $C$.

#### Proof

Choose any vertex $x$ outside $C$. Removing $x$ does not disconnect the vertices of $C$ from one another, because their unique connecting paths remain inside $C$ and meet the rest of the tree only through $v$. Thus the component containing $C$ after removing $x$ has more than $n/2$ vertices, so $x$ is not a centroid. $\square$

### Lemma 2

At every descent step, the maintained size for each neighbor of the current vertex equals the size of the component reached through that neighbor.

#### Proof

The initial rooted subtree sizes have this meaning at vertex 1. When moving from $v$ into `nxt`, all sizes strictly inside the new side remain unchanged. The only reversed side is the edge back to $v$, whose component contains every vertex outside the former `nxt` subtree and therefore has size $n-sz[nxt]$. The assignment `sz[v] = n - sz[nxt]` stores exactly this value. $\square$

### Theorem

The output vertex is a centroid.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1, every move into an oversized component preserves at least one possible centroid and is necessary for the current vertex to become valid. The walk never revisits an edge and must terminate. At termination, Lemma 2 and the failed search for an oversized neighbor show that every component remaining after removal has size at most $n/2$. This is precisely the centroid condition. $\square$

### Complexity

Rooting and size computation take $O(n)$ time. The descent scans adjacency lists of vertices on one simple path, so it also takes $O(n)$ total time. The arrays and adjacency lists use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The reverse traversal loop computes subtree sizes without recursive DFS. During descent, `par` describes the locally reoriented direction: the previous vertex becomes the upward neighbor and is excluded from the child scan. The accompanying size update represents that upward component.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int n;
vector<int> g[200005];
int par[200005], sz[200005], ord[200005];

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n;
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        g[a].push_back(b);
        g[b].push_back(a);
    }

    int hd = 0, tl = 0;
    ord[tl++] = 1; par[1] = 0;
    static bool vis[200005];
    vis[1] = true;
    while (hd < tl) {
        int u = ord[hd++];
        for (int v : g[u]) if (!vis[v]) {
            vis[v] = true; par[v] = u;
            ord[tl++] = v;
        }
    }
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) sz[i] = 1;
    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        int u = ord[i];
        if (par[u]) sz[par[u]] += sz[u];
    }

    int v = 1, half = n / 2;
    while (true) {
        int nxt = -1;
        for (int u : g[v]) if (u != par[v] && sz[u] > half) { nxt = u; break; }
        // upward part n - sz[v] is checked implicitly: if it exceeded half we'd
        // have descended from there; from root there is no upward part
        if (nxt == -1) break;
        par[nxt] = v;          // reorient so the previous node becomes "up"
        sz[v] = n - sz[nxt];   // v's size as seen from nxt's rooting
        v = nxt;
    }

    cout << v << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Consider a seven-vertex tree where child 2 of root 1 has subtree size 5. Vertex 1 is invalid, so the algorithm moves to 2 and changes the size associated with the side through 1 to $7-5=2$. If every other neighbor-side of 2 has size at most 3, then removing 2 leaves components no larger than $\lfloor7/2\rfloor=3$, and 2 is returned.

## Takeaway

For balance conditions on a tree, express the result of deleting a vertex as neighbor-side component sizes. An oversized side gives both a certificate of failure and a forced direction in which to move.

### Related problems

Fixed-Length Paths I and II repeatedly find centroids inside smaller components. Tree Matching uses the same child-before-parent preprocessing pattern for a different invariant.

