# Exponentiation II

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1712: Exponentiation II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1712/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (exponentiation2.cpp)`](./exponentiation2.cpp)

For each query, compute $a^{b^c}$ modulo $p=10^9+7$.

## Reasoning

The exponent $b^c$ is far too large to construct. When $a$ is not divisible by prime $p$, Fermat's theorem gives $a^{p-1}\equiv1\pmod p$, so only $b^c\bmod(p-1)$ is needed. Binary exponentiation can compute this reduced exponent modulo $p-1$, followed by the outer power modulo $p$.

Reduction of the exponent is not valid for base zero modulo $p$. The code handles it separately. The true exponent is zero exactly when $b=0$ and $c>0$; under the problem's adopted convention, $0^0=1$, while a positive exponent gives zero.

## Algorithm

Reduce $a$ modulo $p$. If it is zero, determine whether the true exponent is zero and return 1 or 0. Otherwise compute $e=b^c\bmod(p-1)$ and return $a^e\bmod p$, with an explicit true-zero-exponent check.

## Correctness

If $p\mid a$, the direct case distinction evaluates $0^{b^c}$ correctly. Otherwise $a$ is invertible modulo $p$, and Fermat's theorem implies exponents congruent modulo $p-1$ produce the same residue. The inner binary exponentiation returns $e\equiv b^c\pmod{p-1}$, so the outer one returns $a^{b^c}\bmod p$.

The explicit zero-exponent case returns the multiplicative identity even when the reduced residue is zero. Thus every possible query is handled correctly.

### Complexity

Each query takes $O(\log c+\log p)$ time and $O(1)$ space.

## Implementation

The generic `power` accepts a modulus, allowing exponent reduction modulo $p-1$. Normalizing a negative base is supported even though official inputs are nonnegative. Zero-base handling occurs before Fermat reduction.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

ll power(ll a, ll b, ll mod) {
    a %= mod;
    if (a < 0) a += mod;
    ll r = 1 % mod;
    while (b > 0) {
        if (b & 1) r = r * a % mod;
        a = a * a % mod;
        b >>= 1;
    }
    return r;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    string out;
    out.reserve(1 << 21);

    while (n--) {
        ll a, b, c; cin >> a >> b >> c;

        // determine exponent E = b^c, both reduced mod (p-1) and its zero/one status
        ll am = a % MOD;

        // zero base handling
        if (am == 0) {
            // result is 0^(b^c); 0^0 = 1, else 0
            // b^c == 0  iff b==0 and c>0
            bool expIsZero = (b == 0 && c > 0);
            out += (expIsZero ? "1" : "0");
            out += '\n';
            continue;
        }

        // a not divisible by p: reduce exponent mod (p-1)
        ll e = power(b % (MOD - 1), c, MOD - 1);   // b^c mod (p-1)
        // if true exponent is 0 (b^c==0 => b==0,c>0), a^0 = 1
        if (b == 0 && c > 0) { out += "1"; out += '\n'; continue; }
        out += to_string(power(am, e, MOD));
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $2^{3^4}$, compute $3^4=81$ modulo $p-1$, then binary exponentiation returns $2^{81}\bmod p$. For a base divisible by $p$ and exponent zero, the separate branch returns 1 rather than incorrectly applying exponent reduction.

## Takeaway

For modular power towers, reduce an exponent modulo the group order only after confirming the base is invertible modulo the outer modulus.

### Related problems

Euler's theorem generalizes exponent reduction to composite moduli when the base is coprime to the modulus.

