# Binomial Coefficients

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1079: Binomial Coefficients](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1079/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (binomialcoeff.cpp)`](./binomialcoeff.cpp)

Answer many queries for $\binom ab$ modulo $10^9+7$, with $a\le10^6$.

## Reasoning

The identity

$$
\binom ab=\frac{a!}{b!(a-b)!}
$$

becomes multiplication by modular inverses. Since every factorial involved is smaller than the prime modulus, it is nonzero modulo the prime and invertible. Fermat's theorem gives $z^{-1}\equiv z^{p-2}\pmod p$.

Precompute all factorials. One exponentiation finds the inverse of the largest factorial, then the recurrence

$$
(i-1)!^{-1}=i\cdot i!^{-1}
$$

builds every smaller inverse factorial in linear time.

## Algorithm

Precompute `fact[0..10^6]`. Compute `invfact[10^6]` by binary exponentiation and fill inverse factorials downward. Answer each query by multiplying `fact[a]`, `invfact[b]`, and `invfact[a-b]` modulo $p$.

## Correctness

The factorial loop computes $i!$ for every index. Fermat's theorem makes the initial inverse factorial correct. If `invfact[i]` equals $(i!)^{-1}$, multiplying it by $i$ yields $((i-1)!)^{-1}$, so downward induction proves all inverse factorials correct.

Substituting these values into the factorial formula gives exactly $\binom ab$ modulo $p$ for every query.

### Complexity

Precomputation takes $O(V+\log p)$ time and $O(V)$ space for $V=10^6$. Each query takes $O(1)$ time.

## Implementation

All products use `long long`. The code assumes official queries satisfy $0\le b\le a\le10^6$. Buffered output avoids repeated flushing costs.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int V = 1000000;
ll fact[V + 1], invfact[V + 1];

ll power(ll a, ll b) {
    a %= MOD; ll r = 1;
    while (b) { if (b & 1) r = r * a % MOD; a = a * a % MOD; b >>= 1; }
    return r;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    fact[0] = 1;
    for (int i = 1; i <= V; i++) fact[i] = fact[i-1] * i % MOD;
    invfact[V] = power(fact[V], MOD - 2);
    for (int i = V; i >= 1; i--) invfact[i-1] = invfact[i] * i % MOD;

    int n; cin >> n;
    string out;
    out.reserve(1 << 21);
    while (n--) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        ll c = fact[a] * invfact[b] % MOD * invfact[a-b] % MOD;
        out += to_string(c);
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $\binom52$, the formula uses $5!/(2!3!)=120/(2\cdot6)=10$. Modular inverse multiplication produces the same residue without integer division.

## Takeaway

For many binomial queries below a prime modulus, factorial and inverse-factorial tables turn each answer into constant-time multiplication.

### Related problems

Distributing Apples applies the same table to stars and bars. Creating Strings II uses a multinomial coefficient.

