# Creating Strings II

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1715: Creating Strings II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1715/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (creatingstrings2.cpp)`](./creatingstrings2.cpp)

Count distinct permutations of a lowercase string modulo $10^9+7$.

## Reasoning

If all $n$ characters were distinguishable, there would be $n!$ permutations. For a letter appearing $c$ times, permuting those identical copies among their selected positions does not change the string, so each distinct string is counted $c!$ times. Applying this independently to every letter gives the multinomial coefficient

$$
\frac{n!}{\prod_{q=0}^{25}c_q!}.
$$

Because the modulus is prime and $n$ is below it, every denominator factorial has a modular inverse computed by Fermat's theorem.

## Algorithm

Count each letter and precompute factorials through the string length. Start with `fact[n]` and multiply by `fact[count]^(p-2)` for every present letter.

## Correctness

Label equal occurrences temporarily. Every distinct output string has exactly $\prod_q c_q!$ labeled permutations, one for each rearrangement of labels among equal-character positions. These classes partition all $n!$ labeled permutations, so the quotient counts distinct strings exactly.

Fermat inverses implement this quotient modulo the prime, hence the algorithm returns the required count.

### Complexity

Factorial construction and counting take $O(n)$ time. At most 26 exponentiations take $O(26\log p)$ time. Space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

Only present letters require an inverse. Counts are stored in a fixed array of size 26. Each modular product uses `long long`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

ll power(ll a, ll b) {
    a %= MOD; ll r = 1;
    while (b) { if (b & 1) r = r * a % MOD; a = a * a % MOD; b >>= 1; }
    return r;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string s; cin >> s;
    int n = s.size();
    vector<ll> fact(n + 1);
    fact[0] = 1;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) fact[i] = fact[i-1] * i % MOD;

    ll cnt[26] = {0};
    for (char ch : s) cnt[ch - 'a']++;

    ll ans = fact[n];
    for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++)
        if (cnt[i]) ans = ans * power(fact[cnt[i]], MOD - 2) % MOD;

    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `AAB` conceptually, there are $3!$ labeled orders, but swapping the two copies of `A` changes nothing. The number of distinct strings is $3!/2!=3$: `AAB`, `ABA`, and `BAA`.

## Takeaway

When permutations contain repeated indistinguishable objects, divide the full factorial by one factorial for each multiplicity class.

### Related problems

Multiset combinations and anagram counting use the same orbit-size argument.

