# Counting Divisors

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1713: Counting Divisors](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1713/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (countingdivisors.cpp)`](./countingdivisors.cpp)

For each query value $x\le10^6$, output its number of positive divisors.

## Reasoning

If

$$
x=p_1^{e_1}p_2^{e_2}\cdots p_k^{e_k},
$$

then a divisor independently chooses an exponent from 0 through $e_i$ for each prime. The product rule gives

$$
\tau(x)=\prod_{i=1}^k(e_i+1).
$$

Many queries make trial division wasteful. Precompute the smallest prime factor of every value through $10^6$. Repeatedly dividing by `spf[x]` then extracts the prime factorization in time proportional to its number of prime factors.

## Algorithm

Build a smallest-prime-factor sieve. For each query, repeatedly take the current smallest prime, count its exponent while dividing it out, and multiply the answer by one more than that exponent.

## Correctness

The sieve assigns each composite number its smallest prime divisor because primes are processed increasingly and an entry is written only once. Repeated division therefore recovers the unique prime factorization of every query value.

For each prime exponent $e_i$, a divisor has exactly $e_i+1$ choices. These choices are independent and uniquely determine a divisor, so multiplying them yields exactly the divisor count printed by the algorithm.

### Complexity

The sieve takes $O(V\log\log V)$ standard harmonic-sieve time up to constant factors and $O(V)$ space for $V=10^6$. Each query factorization takes $O(\log x)$ divisions.

## Implementation

Primes are recognized by an unset `spf` entry. The nested multiple loop writes only previously unset entries. The maximum divisor count below $10^6$ fits in `int`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
const int V = 1000000;
int spf[V + 1];

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    for (int i = 2; i <= V; i++) {
        if (spf[i] == 0)
            for (int j = i; j <= V; j += i)
                if (spf[j] == 0) spf[j] = i;
    }

    int n; cin >> n;
    string out;
    out.reserve(1 << 20);

    while (n--) {
        int x; cin >> x;
        int tau = 1;
        while (x > 1) {
            int p = spf[x], e = 0;
            while (x % p == 0) { x /= p; e++; }
            tau *= (e + 1);
        }
        out += to_string(tau);
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $72=2^3\cdot3^2$, a divisor chooses the exponent of 2 in four ways and of 3 in three ways. The answer is $4\cdot3=12$.

## Takeaway

Prime factorization converts divisor enumeration into independent choices of exponents. A smallest-prime-factor table amortizes factorization across many bounded queries.

### Related problems

Divisor Analysis applies the same exponent independence to divisor counts, sums, and products.

