# Common Divisors

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1081: Common Divisors](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1081/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (commondivisors.cpp)`](./commondivisors.cpp)

Find the largest integer that divides at least two input values.

## Reasoning

Testing every pair and computing its gcd costs $O(n^2)$. Instead, reverse the quantifiers. For a candidate divisor $g$, the values divisible by it are exactly its multiples $g,2g,3g,\ldots$. A frequency table lets us count how many input values lie among those multiples.

Candidates are scanned from largest to smallest. The first one dividing at least two occurrences is automatically the largest possible answer. Duplicate input values are handled because their frequency contributes more than one at a single multiple.

## Algorithm

Count occurrences of every value up to $10^6$. For $g$ descending from $10^6$ to 1, sum frequencies at multiples of $g$, stopping once the count reaches two. Output the first successful $g$.

## Correctness

For fixed $g$, the inner loop visits exactly the positive multiples of $g$ in the value range. Its accumulated frequency is therefore exactly the number of input elements divisible by $g$. The candidate succeeds precisely when some pair shares divisor $g$.

Because candidates are examined in descending order, every larger integer has already been proved not to divide two values when the algorithm stops. The returned candidate is thus the largest common divisor of some pair.

### Complexity

The multiple loops perform

$$
\sum_{g=1}^{V}\left\lfloor\frac Vg\right\rfloor=O(V\log V)
$$

iterations in the worst case, with $O(V+n)$ time overall and $O(V)$ space.

## Implementation

The early break at count two can substantially reduce work and is valid because only existence of a pair matters. The fallback output 1 is guaranteed for at least two positive inputs.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
const int V = 1000000;
int cnt[V + 1];

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int x; cin >> x;
        cnt[x]++;
    }

    for (int g = V; g >= 1; g--) {
        int c = 0;
        for (int m = g; m <= V; m += g) {
            c += cnt[m];
            if (c >= 2) break;
        }
        if (c >= 2) { cout << g << '\n'; return 0; }
    }

    cout << 1 << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $6,10,15$, candidate 5 sees multiples 5, 10, and 15 and counts two values, while every larger successful candidate is absent. The algorithm returns 5, the gcd of 10 and 15.

## Takeaway

When asking whether several bounded values share a divisor, aggregate frequencies over multiples instead of examining pairs.

### Related problems

The sieve of Eratosthenes and divisor zeta transforms use the same traversal over multiples.

