# Prime Multiples

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 2185: Prime Multiples](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2185/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (primemultiples.cpp)`](./primemultiples.cpp)

Count integers from 1 through $n$ divisible by at least one of $k$ given primes.

## Reasoning

For each prime $p_i$, there are $\lfloor n/p_i\rfloor$ multiples. Adding these counts double-counts numbers divisible by two primes, so inclusion-exclusion is required. For every nonempty subset $S$ of primes, its common multiples are multiples of their product because the primes are distinct:

$$
\left\lfloor\frac{n}{\prod_{i\in S}p_i}\right\rfloor.
$$

Add this term for odd subset size and subtract it for even size. With $k\le20$, all $2^k$ subsets are feasible.

Products may exceed 64-bit range. We only need to know that a product exceeds $n$, because then its contribution is zero. Before multiplying by $p_i$, test `prod > n / p_i`.

## Algorithm

Enumerate every nonempty bitmask. Multiply its selected primes while counting selected bits, abandoning the subset if the product would exceed $n$. Add or subtract `n / product` according to parity.

## Correctness

For any integer $y\le n$ divisible by exactly $r\ge1$ listed primes, inclusion-exclusion contributes

$$
\binom r1-\binom r2+\cdots+(-1)^{r+1}\binom rr=1.
$$

An integer divisible by none contributes zero. Thus every desired integer is counted exactly once. Skipped subsets have product greater than $n$ and therefore no positive common multiple in the range, so skipping them changes nothing.

### Complexity

The implementation takes $O(k2^k)$ time and $O(k)$ input space.

## Implementation

The division-based overflow check simultaneously proves the subset contribution is zero. The signed accumulator handles alternating inclusion-exclusion terms.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
typedef unsigned long long ull;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    ll n; int k;
    cin >> n >> k;
    vector<ll> a(k);
    for (auto& v : a) cin >> v;

    ll ans = 0;
    for (int mask = 1; mask < (1 << k); mask++) {
        ll prod = 1;
        bool overflow = false;
        int bits = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) if (mask >> i & 1) {
            bits++;
            if (prod > n / a[i]) { overflow = true; break; }   // prod*a[i] would exceed n
            prod *= a[i];
        }
        if (overflow) continue;     // floor(n/prod) == 0
        ll cnt = n / prod;
        if (bits & 1) ans += cnt;
        else ans -= cnt;
    }

    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $n=20$ and primes 2 and 5, there are 10 multiples of 2 and 4 multiples of 5. Their intersection contains 2 multiples of 10, so the answer is $10+4-2=12$.

## Takeaway

When counting a union of a small number of divisibility sets, inclusion-exclusion over subsets is direct. Guard products by comparing before multiplication.

### Related problems

Counting Coprime Pairs uses Möbius inversion, a compressed inclusion-exclusion over all prime divisors.

