# Counting Coprime Pairs

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 2417: Counting Coprime Pairs](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2417/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (countingcoprimes.cpp)`](./countingcoprimes.cpp)

Count unordered pairs of input values whose greatest common divisor is one.

## Reasoning

The Möbius identity

$$
[\gcd(x,y)=1]=\sum_{d\mid x,\ d\mid y}\mu(d)
$$

turns a gcd condition into divisibility counts. Let $c_d$ be the number of input values divisible by $d$. Then $\binom{c_d}{2}$ pairs have both values divisible by $d$, so

$$
\text{answer}=\sum_{d=1}^{V}\mu(d)\binom{c_d}{2}.
$$

A linear sieve computes all Möbius values. Frequencies over multiples compute each $c_d$.

## Algorithm

Build the Möbius function through $10^6$ with a linear sieve. Count input frequencies. For each $d$ with nonzero Möbius value, sum frequencies of its multiples and add $\mu(d)c_d(c_d-1)/2$.

## Correctness

Fix one unordered input pair with gcd $g$. Its total coefficient in the algorithm is

$$
\sum_{d\mid g}\mu(d),
$$

which equals 1 when $g=1$ and 0 otherwise. Therefore coprime pairs contribute exactly once and all other pairs cancel. Summing over divisors and pairs in the opposite order proves the formula and the algorithm.

### Complexity

The linear sieve is $O(V)$. The multiple sums take $O(V\log V)$ time, and arrays use $O(V)$ space.

## Implementation

The linear sieve sets Möbius value zero when a squared prime divides a number and otherwise flips the sign. Terms with zero Möbius value are skipped. The pair count and signed sum use `long long`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
const int V = 1000000;
int mu[V + 1], freq[V + 1];
bool comp[V + 1];

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    // linear sieve for mobius
    vector<int> primes;
    mu[1] = 1;
    for (int i = 2; i <= V; i++) {
        if (!comp[i]) { primes.push_back(i); mu[i] = -1; }
        for (int p : primes) {
            if ((ll)i * p > V) break;
            comp[i * p] = true;
            if (i % p == 0) { mu[i * p] = 0; break; }
            else mu[i * p] = -mu[i];
        }
    }

    int n; cin >> n;
    int mx = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int x; cin >> x;
        freq[x]++;
        mx = max(mx, x);
    }

    ll ans = 0;
    for (int d = 1; d <= mx; d++) {
        if (mu[d] == 0) continue;
        ll cd = 0;
        for (int m = d; m <= mx; m += d) cd += freq[m];
        ans += (ll)mu[d] * (cd * (cd - 1) / 2);
    }

    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For values $2,3,4$, all three pairs are considered at $d=1$. At $d=2$, the pair $(2,4)$ is subtracted because $\mu(2)=-1$. No other nonzero term affects it, leaving exactly the two coprime pairs.

## Takeaway

Möbius inversion converts a gcd-equals-one predicate into a signed sum of easy divisibility predicates.

### Related problems

Common Divisors also aggregates over multiples but searches for existence rather than applying Möbius weights.

