# Nim Game I

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1730: Nim Game I](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1730/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (nimgame1.cpp)`](./nimgame1.cpp)

Several heaps contain sticks. Players alternately remove any positive number from one heap. Determine the winner under optimal play.

## Reasoning

Let the nim sum be

$$
X=a_1\oplus a_2\oplus\cdots\oplus a_n.
$$

If $X=0$, any move changing heap $a_i$ to $b<a_i$ produces new xor $X\oplus a_i\oplus b=a_i\oplus b\ne0$. Thus every move leaves a nonzero position.

If $X\ne0$, let its highest set bit be $q$. Some heap $a_i$ has bit $q$ set. Replacing it by $b=a_i\oplus X$ clears that bit, so $b<a_i$, and the new xor is zero. Therefore nonzero positions can move to zero positions, while zero positions cannot remain zero.

The terminal all-zero position has xor zero, establishing the losing and winning classes by induction on the total sticks.

## Algorithm

Xor all heap sizes. Print `first` if the result is nonzero and `second` otherwise.

## Correctness

The zero-position argument proves every move from nim sum zero goes to nonzero. The highest-bit construction proves every nonzero position has a legal move to zero. Since the terminal position is zero, induction over game moves shows zero nim sum is losing and nonzero nim sum is winning. The algorithm prints the corresponding player.

### Complexity

Each test case takes $O(n)$ time and $O(1)$ auxiliary space.

## Implementation

Xor is accumulated while reading, so heaps need not be stored. Output is buffered across test cases.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int t; cin >> t;
    string out;
    while (t--) {
        int n; cin >> n;
        int x = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int v; cin >> v;
            x ^= v;
        }
        out += (x != 0 ? "first" : "second");
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For heaps $3,4,5$, the xor is $3\oplus4\oplus5=2$. Changing heap 3 to $3\oplus2=1$ leaves xor zero, so the first player has a winning move.

## Takeaway

For ordinary Nim, xor is the complete invariant: zero positions cannot move to zero, and every nonzero position can.

### Related problems

Nim Game II replaces each heap by its own Grundy value before xoring. Stair Game reduces alternating levels to Nim heaps.

