# Stick Game

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1729: Stick Game](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1729/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (stickgame.cpp)`](./stickgame.cpp)

For every initial pile size from 1 through $n$, determine whether the first player wins when each move removes one allowed number of sticks.

## Reasoning

A position is winning exactly when it has a move to a losing position. It is losing when every legal move reaches a winning position. Because every move decreases the pile, positions form a directed acyclic graph ordered by pile size.

Define `dp[s]` as `W` or `L` for pile size $s$. The empty pile is losing. For each larger pile, inspect all allowed removals $p_i\le s$ and mark it winning if any predecessor `dp[s-p_i]` is losing.

## Algorithm

Initialize `dp[0] = L`. Compute states from 1 through $n$. For each state, scan allowed moves until finding a losing destination. Concatenate the states for output.

## Correctness

Assume all smaller states are classified correctly. If the algorithm marks $s$ winning, it found a legal move to a losing state, so the current player can force victory. If it leaves $s$ losing, every legal move reaches a winning state, allowing the opponent to force victory. This exactly matches optimal play.

Induction over increasing pile size proves every printed classification correct.

### Complexity

Time is $O(nk)$ for $k$ allowed moves, and space is $O(n+k)$.

## Implementation

The DP array is initialized to `L`, including state zero. The move loop stops at the first losing destination because existence is sufficient. The output string contains no separators, matching the required format.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, k; cin >> n >> k;
    vector<int> p(k);
    for (auto& v : p) cin >> v;

    vector<char> dp(n + 1, 'L');   // dp[0] = L
    for (int s = 1; s <= n; s++) {
        char res = 'L';
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            if (p[i] <= s && dp[s - p[i]] == 'L') { res = 'W'; break; }
        }
        dp[s] = res;
    }

    string out(n, ' ');
    for (int s = 1; s <= n; s++) out[s-1] = dp[s];
    cout << out << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

With moves 1 and 3, state 0 is losing, states 1 and 3 are winning by moving to zero, and state 2 is losing because its only legal move reaches state 1. The pattern begins `WLW`.

## Takeaway

For finite impartial games whose moves strictly decrease a state, compute winning and losing positions in topological order using the move-to-losing criterion.

### Related problems

Grundy's Game needs full Grundy values because a move splits one component into two subgames.

