# Stair Game

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1099: Stair Game](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1099/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (stairgame.cpp)`](./stairgame.cpp)

Coins lie on consecutive stairs. A move transfers any positive number of coins from one stair to the stair immediately below. Determine the winner.

## Reasoning

Pair stairs from the floor upward. Coins on odd-distance stairs from the floor behave as independent Nim heaps; coins on the intervening stairs do not affect the xor invariant because moves into and out of each pair can be answered locally.

With the input indexed from the top convention used by CSES, these active stairs are the even one-based indices. The Sprague-Grundy value of the full position is therefore

$$
a_2\oplus a_4\oplus a_6\oplus\cdots.
$$

This reduction can also be proved by pairing moves: a transfer from an inactive stair changes no heap value, while a transfer from an active stair changes exactly its corresponding Nim heap by an arbitrary smaller amount; intervening responses restore the canonical paired form.

## Algorithm

Read the stair counts and xor values at even one-based indices. Print `first` for nonzero xor and `second` for zero.

## Correctness

The stair position is equivalent under the pairing reduction to ordinary Nim with heap sizes on even-indexed stairs. The Nim theorem proves xor zero is losing and xor nonzero is winning. The algorithm computes exactly this xor, so it prints the optimal winner.

### Complexity

Each test case uses $O(n)$ time and $O(1)$ space.

## Implementation

The loop is one-based, making the condition `i % 2 == 0` match the active stair parity directly. Values on other stairs are read but do not enter the xor.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int t; cin >> t;
    string out;
    while (t--) {
        int n; cin >> n;
        int x = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            int v; cin >> v;
            if (i % 2 == 0) x ^= v;     // even 1-based stairs = odd distance from floor
        }
        out += (x != 0 ? "first" : "second");
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For stair counts $5,2,7,3$, the active heap sizes are 2 and 3. Their xor is 1, so the first player wins.

## Takeaway

Some transfer games collapse to Nim after pairing adjacent levels. Identify which levels represent independent net resources and xor only those heaps.

### Related problems

Nim Game I supplies the final xor theorem. Similar parity reductions appear in coin-sliding and Green Hackenbush stalk games.

