# Nim Game II

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1098: Nim Game II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1098/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (nimgame2.cpp)`](./nimgame2.cpp)

Several heaps contain sticks. A move removes 1, 2, or 3 sticks from one heap. Determine the winner under optimal play.

## Reasoning

For one heap of size $v$, its Grundy value is

$$
g(v)=\operatorname{mex}\{g(v-1),g(v-2),g(v-3)\}.
$$

Starting from $g(0)=0$, the values repeat $0,1,2,3$, so $g(v)=v\bmod4$. This follows by induction: the preceding three residues are exactly the three values in $\{0,1,2,3\}$ other than the current residue, whose mex is the current residue.

The Sprague-Grundy theorem says the disjoint sum of heaps has Grundy value equal to the xor of individual values. Hence the position is losing exactly when

$$
(a_1\bmod4)\oplus\cdots\oplus(a_n\bmod4)=0.
$$

## Algorithm

Xor every heap size modulo 4. Print `first` for a nonzero xor and `second` for zero.

## Correctness

Induction on heap size proves each heap's Grundy value is its residue modulo 4. A move changes exactly one independent heap, so the Sprague-Grundy theorem makes the total position's value their xor. Positions with Grundy value zero are losing and all others are winning. The algorithm computes this value exactly.

### Complexity

Each test case takes $O(n)$ time and $O(1)$ auxiliary space.

## Implementation

Reducing each value before xor is mathematically required; xoring full heap sizes would solve ordinary Nim instead. Output is buffered across test cases.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int t; cin >> t;
    string out;
    while (t--) {
        int n; cin >> n;
        int x = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int v; cin >> v;
            x ^= (v % 4);
        }
        out += (x != 0 ? "first" : "second");
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For heaps $5,7,2,5$, the Grundy values are $1,3,2,1$. Their xor is 1, so the first player wins.

## Takeaway

For a sum of impartial games, compute the Grundy value of each component, then xor those values. The heap size itself is a Grundy value only in ordinary Nim.

### Related problems

Nim Game I permits every smaller heap size and therefore has Grundy value $v$. Stick Game computes win states for an arbitrary subtraction set.

