# Another Game

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 2208: Another Game](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2208/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (anothergame.cpp)`](./anothergame.cpp)

On each move, choose any nonempty collection of nonempty heaps and remove one coin from each chosen heap. Determine the winner.

## Reasoning

The losing positions are exactly those in which every heap size is even.

From an all-even position, every legal move changes at least one chosen heap from even to odd, so it cannot move to another all-even position. From any position containing odd heaps, choose exactly all heaps whose sizes are odd. Removing one coin from each makes every heap even, producing a losing position.

These two closure properties, together with the all-zero terminal position being all-even, completely classify the game.

## Algorithm

Check whether any heap size is odd. Print `first` if one exists and `second` otherwise.

## Correctness

Every move from an all-even position makes each selected heap odd, and at least one heap is selected, so the result contains an odd heap. Conversely, from a position with odd heaps, selecting all and only odd heaps is legal and makes all sizes even.

Thus every nonclassified position has a move into the all-even class, while no position in that class can remain there after a move. Since the terminal position belongs to it, all-even positions are losing and the others are winning. The algorithm prints accordingly.

### Complexity

Each test case takes $O(n)$ time and $O(1)$ space.

## Implementation

Only parity is needed, so the code records a Boolean while still consuming every input value. Any odd heap suffices to establish a winning position.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;	
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int t; cin >> t;
    string out;
    out.reserve(1 << 20);
    while (t--) {
        int n; cin >> n;
        bool anyOdd = false;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int v; cin >> v;
            if (v & 1) anyOdd = true;
        }
        out += (anyOdd ? "first" : "second");
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For heaps $5,5,4,5$, select the three odd heaps and remove one coin from each, leaving $4,4,4,4$. Every reply must create at least one odd heap again.

## Takeaway

Before computing full Grundy values, look for a simple candidate losing class that no move preserves and every outside position can reach.

### Related problems

Parity kernels also solve some take-away games where one move may act on several components simultaneously.

