# Bracket Sequences I

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 2064: Bracket Sequences I](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2064/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (bracketsequences1.cpp)`](./bracketsequences1.cpp)

Count balanced parenthesis strings of length $n$ modulo $10^9+7$.

## Reasoning

An odd length cannot contain equal numbers of opening and closing brackets. For $n=2m$, balanced strings are counted by the Catalan number

$$
C_m=\frac{1}{m+1}\binom{2m}{m}.
$$

One derivation starts with all $\binom{2m}{m}$ strings containing $m$ brackets of each kind. By the reflection principle, strings whose prefix balance becomes negative are in bijection with strings containing $m-1$ opening brackets and $m+1$ closing brackets. Subtracting gives

$$
\binom{2m}{m}-\binom{2m}{m-1}=\frac{1}{m+1}\binom{2m}{m}.
$$

Factorials and Fermat inverses evaluate the formula modulo the prime.

## Algorithm

Precompute factorials and inverse factorials. Return zero for odd $n$. Otherwise compute the central binomial coefficient and multiply by the modular inverse of $m+1$.

## Correctness

The reflection bijection counts exactly the equal-count strings that first cross below balance zero, so subtracting them leaves precisely balanced sequences. The resulting Catalan formula is evaluated correctly by factorial and modular-inverse arithmetic. Therefore the algorithm returns the exact count.

### Complexity

Precomputation takes $O(10^6)$ time and space. The final calculation takes $O(\log n)$ time for one modular inverse.

## Implementation

The odd-length check occurs after table construction but before any Catalan indexing. Since $m+1$ is below the modulus, its inverse exists.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int V = 1000000;
ll fact[V + 1], invfact[V + 1];

ll power(ll a, ll b) {
    a %= MOD; ll r = 1;
    while (b) { if (b & 1) r = r * a % MOD; a = a * a % MOD; b >>= 1; }
    return r;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    fact[0] = 1;
    for (int i = 1; i <= V; i++) fact[i] = fact[i-1] * i % MOD;
    invfact[V] = power(fact[V], MOD - 2);
    for (int i = V; i >= 1; i--) invfact[i-1] = invfact[i] * i % MOD;

    int n; cin >> n;
    if (n & 1) { cout << 0 << '\n'; return 0; }

    int m = n / 2;
    // C_m = C(2m, m) * inv(m+1)
    ll binom = fact[2*m] * invfact[m] % MOD * invfact[m] % MOD;
    ll cat = binom * power(m + 1, MOD - 2) % MOD;

    cout << cat << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $n=6$, $m=3$ and $C_3=\binom63/4=20/4=5$. These are the five balanced strings with three bracket pairs.

## Takeaway

Balanced prefix constraints often turn central binomial counts into Catalan numbers through reflection.

### Related problems

Bracket Sequences II applies the same reflection principle after a fixed prefix.

