# Graph Paths I

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1723: Graph Paths I](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1723/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (graphpaths1.cpp)`](./graphpaths1.cpp)

Count directed walks of exactly $K$ edges from vertex 1 to vertex $n$, modulo $10^9+7$.

## Reasoning

Let adjacency matrix $A$ store the number of directed edges from $i$ to $j$, including parallel edges. Matrix multiplication composes walks:

$$
(A^2)_{ij}=\sum_k A_{ik}A_{kj}
$$

counts all two-edge walks by their intermediate vertex. Inductively, $(A^K)_{ij}$ counts walks of exactly $K$ edges. Binary exponentiation computes this power logarithmically in $K$.

## Algorithm

Build the adjacency-count matrix. Binary-exponentiate it to $K$ using ordinary modular matrix multiplication and the identity matrix. Output entry $(1,n)$.

## Correctness

We prove by induction on $q$ that $(A^q)_{ij}$ counts $q$-edge walks from $i$ to $j$. It is true for $q=1$. Multiplying a $q$-walk matrix by $A$ partitions every $(q+1)$-edge walk by its penultimate vertex, counting it exactly once.

Binary exponentiation returns the algebraic power $A^K$, so the selected entry is exactly the required walk count.

### Complexity

Each matrix multiplication takes $O(n^3)$ time and exponentiation uses $O(\log K)$ multiplications. Space is $O(n^2)$.

## Implementation

Parallel edges increment the same adjacency entry rather than overwriting it. The identity matrix represents zero-edge walks, so $K=0$ is handled algebraically. The multiplication skips zero left factors as a constant-factor optimization.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
int n, m, K;

struct Mat { vector<vector<ll>> a; Mat(): a(n, vector<ll>(n, 0)) {} };

Mat mul(const Mat& A, const Mat& B) {
    Mat C;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (int k = 0; k < n; k++) {
            if (!A.a[i][k]) continue;
            ll aik = A.a[i][k];
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++)
                C.a[i][j] = (C.a[i][j] + aik * B.a[k][j]) % MOD;
        }
    return C;
}

Mat matpow(Mat base, ll e) {
    Mat r;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) r.a[i][i] = 1;
    while (e) {
        if (e & 1) r = mul(r, base);
        base = mul(base, base);
        e >>= 1;
    }
    return r;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> m >> K;
    Mat A;
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        A.a[a-1][b-1] = (A.a[a-1][b-1] + 1) % MOD;   // parallel edges accumulate
    }

    Mat R = matpow(A, K);
    cout << R.a[0][n-1] << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

If edges are $1\to2$, $2\to3$, and $1\to3$, then $(A^2)_{1,3}=A_{1,2}A_{2,3}=1$. The direct edge does not contribute because exactly two edges are required.

## Takeaway

Adjacency-matrix powers count fixed-length walks because matrix multiplication sums over the vertex where two walk segments meet.

### Related problems

Graph Paths II uses the same power construction over the min-plus semiring to optimize cost instead of count.

