# Graph Paths II

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1724: Graph Paths II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1724/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (graphpaths2.cpp)`](./graphpaths2.cpp)

Find the minimum cost of a directed walk using exactly $K$ edges from vertex 1 to vertex $n$, or report that none exists.

## Reasoning

Replace ordinary matrix arithmetic with min-plus operations. Matrix entry $A_{ij}$ is the cheapest direct edge from $i$ to $j$, or infinity. Define product

$$
(A\otimes B)_{ij}=\min_k(A_{ik}+B_{kj}).
$$

It combines a walk represented by $A$ with one represented by $B$, choosing their meeting vertex. Thus the min-plus power $A^{\otimes K}$ contains minimum costs of exactly-$K$-edge walks.

Min-plus multiplication is associative and has identity zero on the diagonal and infinity elsewhere, so binary exponentiation remains valid.

## Algorithm

Build a minimum-edge-cost matrix, retaining the lightest parallel edge. Exponentiate it to $K$ with min-plus multiplication. Output entry $(1,n)$, or `-1` if it is infinite.

## Correctness

Inductively, a min-plus matrix for $q$ edges stores the cheapest such walk for every vertex pair. Multiplication with a matrix for $r$ edges partitions each $(q+r)$-edge walk at its vertex after $q$ edges and minimizes over all partitions. Hence it produces exact optimum costs.

Binary exponentiation composes powers whose edge counts sum to $K$, so the result represents exactly $K$ edges. The selected entry is therefore the required optimum, and infinity correctly denotes absence.

### Complexity

Time is $O(n^3\log K)$ and space is $O(n^2)$.

## Implementation

The min-plus identity has diagonal zero. Infinite factors are skipped before addition. `INF = 4e18` is above every valid official path cost, and skipped infinities prevent overflowing it. Parallel edges retain their minimum cost.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
const ll INF = (ll)4e18;
int n, m;
ll K;

struct Mat { vector<vector<ll>> a; Mat(): a(n, vector<ll>(n, INF)) {} };

Mat mul(const Mat& A, const Mat& B) {
    Mat C;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (int k = 0; k < n; k++) {
            if (A.a[i][k] == INF) continue;
            ll aik = A.a[i][k];
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                if (B.a[k][j] == INF) continue;
                ll v = aik + B.a[k][j];
                if (v < C.a[i][j]) C.a[i][j] = v;
            }
        }
    return C;
}

Mat matpow(Mat base, ll e) {
    Mat r;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) r.a[i][i] = 0;   // (min,+) identity
    while (e) {
        if (e & 1) r = mul(r, base);
        base = mul(base, base);
        e >>= 1;
    }
    return r;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> m >> K;
    Mat A;
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        int a, b; ll c; cin >> a >> b >> c;
        A.a[a-1][b-1] = min(A.a[a-1][b-1], c);   // keep lightest parallel edge
    }

    Mat R = matpow(A, K);
    ll ans = R.a[0][n-1];
    cout << (ans >= INF ? -1 : ans) << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

With edges $1\to2$ of cost 5, $2\to3$ of cost 4, and $1\to3$ of cost 2, the cheapest exactly-two-edge walk from 1 to 3 costs 9. The cheaper direct edge is irrelevant because it uses one edge.

## Takeaway

Matrix exponentiation works over any associative semiring. Replace addition and multiplication by minimum and addition to optimize fixed-length walk costs.

### Related problems

Graph Paths I uses the ordinary counting semiring. Floyd-Warshall similarly changes the interpretation of matrix-style transitions.

