# System of Linear Equations

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 3154: System of Linear Equations](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3154/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (linearequations.cpp)`](./linearequations.cpp)

Solve a system of linear equations modulo $10^9+7$, outputting one solution or `-1` if inconsistent.

## Reasoning

Over a prime modulus, nonzero values form a field, so Gaussian elimination applies. Process variable columns from left to right. Find a row with nonzero coefficient, swap it into the next pivot row, multiply by the coefficient's modular inverse to normalize the pivot to one, then eliminate that column from every other row.

The resulting matrix is reduced with respect to pivot columns. Variables without pivots are free; setting them to zero yields one solution whenever the system is consistent. A row with all zero coefficients and nonzero constant is exactly a contradiction.

## Algorithm

Perform modular Gauss-Jordan elimination, recording the pivot row for each variable. Set free variables to zero and pivot variables to their reduced constants. Reject any zero-coefficient row with nonzero constant; otherwise output the constructed vector.

## Correctness

Row swaps, scaling by a nonzero field element, and adding a multiple of one row to another preserve the solution set. Thus elimination produces an equivalent system.

In the reduced system, each pivot equation has pivot coefficient one and zero coefficients in other pivot columns. With free variables set to zero, assigning each pivot variable its row constant satisfies every noncontradictory row. If a zero row has nonzero constant, no assignment can satisfy it. Therefore the algorithm outputs a valid solution exactly when one exists.

### Complexity

With $n$ equations and $m$ variables, pivot searches and eliminations take $O(nm\min(n,m))$ arithmetic operations in the dense case. Storage is $O(nm)$.

## Implementation

Pivot inverses use Fermat exponentiation. Subtractions add `MOD` before reduction. The first consistency loop computes unused values and has no effect; the following explicit zero-row test is the operative check. Free variables remain zero by initialization.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

ll power(ll a, ll b) {
    a %= MOD; if (a < 0) a += MOD;
    ll r = 1;
    while (b) { if (b & 1) r = r * a % MOD; a = a * a % MOD; b >>= 1; }
    return r;
}
ll inv(ll a) { return power(a, MOD - 2); }

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m; cin >> n >> m;
    vector<vector<ll>> A(n, vector<ll>(m + 1));
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (int j = 0; j <= m; j++) cin >> A[i][j];

    vector<int> where(m, -1);    // pivot column -> row
    int row = 0;
    for (int col = 0; col < m && row < n; col++) {
        // find pivot
        int sel = -1;
        for (int i = row; i < n; i++) if (A[i][col] != 0) { sel = i; break; }
        if (sel == -1) continue;
        swap(A[sel], A[row]);
        // normalize pivot row
        ll iv = inv(A[row][col]);
        for (int j = col; j <= m; j++) A[row][j] = A[row][j] * iv % MOD;
        // eliminate from all other rows
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (i == row || A[i][col] == 0) continue;
            ll f = A[i][col];
            for (int j = col; j <= m; j++)
                A[i][j] = (A[i][j] - f * A[row][j] % MOD + MOD) % MOD;
        }
        where[col] = row;
        row++;
    }

    // build solution (free vars = 0)
    vector<ll> x(m, 0);
    for (int col = 0; col < m; col++)
        if (where[col] != -1) x[col] = A[where[col]][m];

    // consistency check
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        ll s = 0;
        for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) s = (s + A[i][j] * x[j]) % MOD;
        // after RREF this reduces to checking zero rows, but verify directly
    }
    // detect 0 = nonzero rows
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        bool allzero = true;
        for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) if (A[i][j] != 0) { allzero = false; break; }
        if (allzero && A[i][m] != 0) { cout << -1 << '\n'; return 0; }
    }

    string out;
    for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) { out += to_string(x[j]); out += (j == m-1 ? '\n' : ' '); }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For equations $x+y=3$ and $x-y=1$ modulo the prime, elimination normalizes pivots and yields $x=2$, $y=1$. If elimination instead produced a row $0=1$, the system would be rejected.

## Takeaway

Gaussian elimination works unchanged over a finite field once division is replaced by multiplication with modular inverses.

### Related problems

Xor linear systems use elimination over the two-element field and can be optimized with bitsets.

