# Moving Robots

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 1726: Moving Robots](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1726/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (movingrobots.cpp)`](./movingrobots.cpp)

One robot starts on every cell of an $8\times8$ board. Each independently makes $k$ uniformly random legal moves. Find the expected number of empty cells afterward.

## Reasoning

For each cell $c$, define indicator $I_c=1$ when no robot ends there. Linearity of expectation gives

$$
\mathbb E[\text{empty cells}]=\sum_c\Pr(c\text{ is empty}).
$$

For a robot starting at $s$, compute $p_{s,c}$, its probability of ending at $c$ after $k$ steps. Robots move independently, so

$$
\Pr(c\text{ empty})=\prod_s(1-p_{s,c}).
$$

Each starting robot's distribution is obtained by a small Markov DP. At a cell, its probability is divided equally among legal neighboring cells, whose count depends on board position.

## Algorithm

Initialize an empty-cell probability product of one for every destination. For each of 64 starts, run $k$ transition layers over the board, then multiply `1 - probability` into every destination product. Sum the 64 products.

## Correctness

The movement DP conditions on the robot's current cell and distributes its probability among exactly its legal, equally likely moves, so induction on steps proves every $p_{s,c}$ correct.

For fixed destination $c$, events that individual robots do not end there are independent, making their probability product exact. Indicator linearity does not require emptiness events of different cells to be independent. Summing these probabilities therefore yields the expected empty-cell count.

### Complexity

There are 64 starts, $k$ steps, 64 cells, and at most four transitions per cell. Time is $O(k)$ with board size treated as constant, and space is $O(1)$.

## Implementation

The number of valid directions is recomputed for each board cell so corners and edges receive correct transition probabilities. `nxt` is cleared before every step. Products are accumulated independently for each destination.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int dx[] = {1,-1,0,0}, dy[] = {0,0,1,-1};

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int k; cin >> k;

    // prob[s][c]: probability robot from start s is at cell c after k steps
    // store as 8x8 distribution per start
    static double notland[8][8];   // product over starts of (1 - p_{s->c})
    for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++) notland[i][j] = 1.0;

    for (int sx = 0; sx < 8; sx++)
        for (int sy = 0; sy < 8; sy++) {
            static double cur[8][8], nxt[8][8];
            for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++) cur[i][j] = 0;
            cur[sx][sy] = 1.0;

            for (int step = 0; step < k; step++) {
                for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++) nxt[i][j] = 0;
                for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++)
                    for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++) {
                        if (cur[i][j] == 0) continue;
                        // count valid directions
                        int cnt = 0;
                        for (int d = 0; d < 4; d++) {
                            int ni = i + dx[d], nj = j + dy[d];
                            if (ni >= 0 && ni < 8 && nj >= 0 && nj < 8) cnt++;
                        }
                        double share = cur[i][j] / cnt;
                        for (int d = 0; d < 4; d++) {
                            int ni = i + dx[d], nj = j + dy[d];
                            if (ni >= 0 && ni < 8 && nj >= 0 && nj < 8) nxt[ni][nj] += share;
                        }
                    }
                for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++) cur[i][j] = nxt[i][j];
            }

            // multiply (1 - p) into notland
            for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++)
                for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++)
                    notland[i][j] *= (1.0 - cur[i][j]);
        }

    double ans = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++)
        for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++)
            ans += notland[i][j];

    cout << fixed << setprecision(6) << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

At $k=0$, each robot remains at its unique starting cell. For every destination, one robot has landing probability one, making the empty probability product zero. The expected number of empty cells is therefore zero.

## Takeaway

To count expected empty locations under independent agents, multiply non-arrival probabilities per location and then use linearity of expectation across locations.

### Related problems

Random-walk distributions are repeated applications of a Markov transition matrix; small fixed boards can be simulated directly.

