# Permutation Rounds

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 3398: Permutation Rounds](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3398/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (permutationrounds.cpp)`](./permutationrounds.cpp)

Repeatedly apply a permutation to all array positions. Find the first positive number of rounds after which every element returns to its starting position, modulo $10^9+7$.

## Reasoning

A permutation decomposes uniquely into disjoint cycles. Elements on a cycle of length $L$ return exactly after multiples of $L$. All elements return simultaneously after

$$
\operatorname{lcm}(L_1,L_2,\ldots,L_q).
$$

The lcm itself may be enormous, and reducing intermediate lcm values modulo $10^9+7$ would destroy divisibility information. Instead factor each cycle length. The lcm contains every prime at the maximum exponent appearing in any cycle length. Only after assembling these prime powers may the product be reduced modulo the requested modulus.

## Algorithm

Precompute smallest prime factors through $n$. Traverse each permutation cycle and factor its length, recording maximum exponents by prime. Multiply the corresponding prime powers modulo $10^9+7$.

## Correctness

Cycle decomposition partitions all positions, and a position returns precisely when the round count is divisible by its cycle length. Therefore the first simultaneous return is their lcm.

For every prime $p$, an integer is divisible by all cycle lengths exactly when its exponent of $p$ is at least the maximum exponent among them. The product constructed by the algorithm has exactly these minimum required exponents, so it equals the lcm before modular reduction. The output is consequently correct.

### Complexity

The sieve takes $O(n\log\log n)$ time, cycle traversal and factorization take $O(n\log n)$ in a safe bound, and space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The visitation array ensures each cycle is measured once. Prime exponents are stored in a map, and binary exponentiation forms each prime power modulo the output modulus.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int V = 200000;
int spf[V + 1];

ll power(ll a, ll b) {
    a %= MOD; ll r = 1;
    while (b) { if (b & 1) r = r * a % MOD; a = a * a % MOD; b >>= 1; }
    return r;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    for (int i = 2; i <= V; i++)
        if (!spf[i])
            for (int j = i; j <= V; j += i)
                if (!spf[j]) spf[j] = i;

    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<int> p(n + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> p[i];

    vector<char> vis(n + 1, 0);
    unordered_map<int,int> maxe;     // prime -> max exponent across cycle lengths

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        if (vis[i]) continue;
        int len = 0, j = i;
        while (!vis[j]) { vis[j] = 1; j = p[j]; len++; }
        // factorize len, update max exponents
        int x = len;
        while (x > 1) {
            int q = spf[x], e = 0;
            while (x % q == 0) { x /= q; e++; }
            auto it = maxe.find(q);
            if (it == maxe.end() || it->second < e) maxe[q] = e;
        }
    }

    ll ans = 1;
    for (auto& [q, e] : maxe) ans = ans * power(q, e) % MOD;

    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Cycle lengths 6 and 4 factor as $2\cdot3$ and $2^2$. Maximum exponents give $2^2\cdot3=12$, so the permutation first returns after 12 rounds.

## Takeaway

For the order of a permutation, decompose into cycles and compute the lcm of their lengths through maximum prime exponents.

### Related problems

Functional graphs use the same cycle decomposition, with trees feeding into cycles rather than every vertex lying on one.

