# Next Prime

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 3396: Next Prime](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3396/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (nextprime.cpp)`](./nextprime.cpp)

For each $n\le10^{12}$, find the smallest prime strictly greater than $n$.

## Reasoning

Trial division through $\sqrt n$ for every candidate can be too slow. Miller-Rabin tests compositeness using the decomposition

$$
n-1=d2^r,
$$

where $d$ is odd. For a prime and any base $a$ not divisible by it, repeated squaring from $a^d$ must begin at 1 or eventually reach $-1$ modulo $n$. Failure proves compositeness.

For values near the official $10^{12}$ bound, testing the fixed prime bases through 37 is deterministic: known strong-pseudoprime bounds guarantee every composite in this range is rejected by at least one listed base. Small prime divisibility is checked first.

## Algorithm

Starting at $n+1$, test successive integers. Reject numbers below two and composites divisible by a small listed prime. For other candidates, run Miller-Rabin with all listed bases using binary modular exponentiation. Stop at the first prime.

## Correctness

Small prime candidates are recognized directly. Any other prime passes every Miller-Rabin round by the square-root structure of unity modulo a prime. By the deterministic-base bound for candidates in the official range, every composite fails some tested base. Thus `isPrime` is exact on all candidates encountered.

The outer loop checks integers in strictly increasing order beginning at $n+1$, so the first accepted candidate is precisely the next prime.

### Complexity

Each primality test uses $O(\log n)$ modular squarings for a constant number of bases. If the next-prime gap is $g$, total time is $O(g\log n)$ and space is $O(1)$.

## Implementation

`unsigned __int128` computes modular products without 64-bit overflow. The factorization of $n-1$ extracts all powers of two. Output buffering supports all test cases.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
typedef __int128 u128;

ull mulmod(ull a, ull b, ull m) { return (u128)a * b % m; }

ull power(ull a, ull b, ull m) {
    ull r = 1 % m;
    a %= m;
    while (b) {
        if (b & 1) r = mulmod(r, a, m);
        a = mulmod(a, a, m);
        b >>= 1;
    }
    return r;
}

bool isPrime(ull n) {
    if (n < 2) return false;
    for (ull p : {2ull,3ull,5ull,7ull,11ull,13ull,17ull,19ull,23ull,29ull,31ull,37ull})
        if (n % p == 0) return n == p;
    ull d = n - 1;
    int r = 0;
    while ((d & 1) == 0) { d >>= 1; r++; }
    for (ull a : {2ull,3ull,5ull,7ull,11ull,13ull,17ull,19ull,23ull,29ull,31ull,37ull}) {
        ull x = power(a, d, n);
        if (x == 1 || x == n - 1) continue;
        bool comp = true;
        for (int i = 0; i < r - 1; i++) {
            x = mulmod(x, x, n);
            if (x == n - 1) { comp = false; break; }
        }
        if (comp) return false;
    }
    return true;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int t; cin >> t;
    string out;
    while (t--) {
        ull n; cin >> n;
        ull m = n + 1;
        while (!isPrime(m)) m++;
        out += to_string(m);
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

After 42, candidate 43 is not divisible by a small prime and passes every Miller-Rabin witness test, so it is returned immediately.

## Takeaway

For bounded 64-bit primality, Miller-Rabin becomes deterministic when paired with a proven base set for the numeric range.

### Related problems

Pollard rho combines Miller-Rabin with randomized factorization for large composite integers.

