# Triangle Number Sums

## Problem

- **Source:** [CSES 3406: Triangle Number Sums](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3406/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (trianglenumbersums.cpp)`](./trianglenumbersums.cpp)

Find the minimum number of positive triangular numbers whose sum is $n$.

## Reasoning

A triangular number has form $T_k=k(k+1)/2$. The identity

$$
8T_k+1=(2k+1)^2
$$

shows that $n$ itself is triangular exactly when $8n+1$ is a square.

Gauss's theorem states every nonnegative integer is a sum of three triangular numbers, so the answer is at most three. Two triangular numbers satisfy

$$
n=T_a+T_b
\iff
8n+2=(2a+1)^2+(2b+1)^2.
$$

For $8n+2\equiv2\pmod8$, any square representation necessarily uses two odd squares, so the ordinary sum-of-two-squares criterion is sufficient. Fermat's theorem says an integer is a sum of two squares exactly when every prime congruent to 3 modulo 4 has even exponent.

## Algorithm

Return 1 if $8n+1$ is a perfect square. Otherwise factor $8n+2$; return 2 if every prime factor congruent to 3 modulo 4 has even exponent, and 3 otherwise.

## Correctness

The square identity proves the answer is one exactly in the first case. The transformed two-term identity and parity observation prove the sum-of-two-squares test is equivalent to representation by two triangular numbers. Fermat's theorem makes the factorization test exact.

If neither case applies, one or two terms are impossible. Gauss's theorem guarantees three terms suffice, so the returned value 3 is minimal.

### Complexity

The sieve through three million is $O(L\log\log L)$ time and $O(L)$ space. Each query factors up to $8\cdot10^{12}+2$ using primes through its square root, taking $O(\pi(\sqrt n))$ trial divisions in the worst case.

## Implementation

`isSquare` corrects floating square-root rounding in both directions. The factorization function checks odd exponents only for primes congruent to 3 modulo 4 and also handles a leftover prime factor.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
bool isSquare(ll x) {
    if (x < 0) return false;
    ll r = (ll)sqrtl((long double)x);
    while (r * r > x) r--;
    while ((r+1)*(r+1) <= x) r++;
    return r * r == x;
}

vector<int> primes;
void sieve(int LIM) {
    vector<bool> comp(LIM + 1, false);
    for (int i = 2; i <= LIM; i++) {
        if (!comp[i]) {
            primes.push_back(i);
            for (ll j = (ll)i*i; j <= LIM; j += i) comp[j] = true;
        }
    }
}

// is N a sum of two squares? every prime p≡3 (mod 4) appears to even power
bool sumTwoSquares(ll N) {
    for (int p : primes) {
        if ((ll)p * p > N) break;
        if (N % p == 0) {
            int e = 0;
            while (N % p == 0) { N /= p; e++; }
            if (p % 4 == 3 && (e & 1)) return false;
        }
    }
    // leftover prime N (if >1)
    if (N > 1 && N % 4 == 3) return false;
    return true;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    sieve(3000000);

    int t; cin >> t;
    string out;
    while (t--) {
        ll n; cin >> n;
        if (isSquare(8*n + 1)) out += '1';
        else if (sumTwoSquares(8*n + 2)) out += '2';
        else out += '3';
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $n=2$, $8n+1=17$ is not square. But $8n+2=18=3^2+3^2$, so two triangular numbers suffice: $2=1+1$.

## Takeaway

Classical polygonal-number identities can transform additive representation questions into square representations governed by prime-factor criteria.

### Related problems

Sum of Four Squares uses Lagrange and Legendre theorems constructively rather than only deciding the minimum count.

