# Word Combinations

- **CSES problem:** 1731
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (wordcombinations.cpp)`](./wordcombinations.cpp)

## Problem

Given a target string and a dictionary, count modulo $10^9+7$ how many sequences of dictionary words concatenate to exactly the target.

## Reasoning

Let $dp[i]$ count decompositions of the prefix $s[0..i)$. If a dictionary word equals $s[i..j)$, every decomposition counted by $dp[i]$ extends to one counted by $dp[j]$. The recurrence is simple; finding all matching words efficiently is the real task.

Comparing every dictionary word at every position repeats prefixes and can be too slow. Store the dictionary in a trie. Starting at target position $i$, follow one trie edge per subsequent target character. If an edge is absent, no longer dictionary word can match from $i$, so the scan stops. Whenever the current trie node marks a complete word, apply the DP transition.

The state order is left to right. Every transition goes from $i$ to a larger position, so when $dp[i]$ is processed, all ways to reach it have already been accumulated.

## Algorithm

1. Insert every dictionary word into a trie and mark terminal nodes.
2. Set $dp[0]=1$ and all other states to zero.
3. For each position $i$ with $dp[i]>0$, walk through the trie along $s[i],s[i+1],\ldots$.
4. Stop at the first missing edge. At each terminal node reached after position $j$, add $dp[i]$ to $dp[j+1]$ modulo $10^9+7$.
5. Output $dp[n]$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

The trie walk from $i$ reaches a terminal node after $s[j]$ exactly when $s[i..j]$ is a dictionary word.

#### Proof

A trie path spells precisely the edge labels traversed from its root. Terminal nodes are exactly endpoints of inserted words. Therefore the reached terminal condition is equivalent to membership of that substring in the dictionary. $\square$

### Lemma 2

After position $i$ is processed, every decomposition whose final word ends at any $j+1$ is added once through its unique preceding boundary $i$.

#### Proof

Removing the final word of such a decomposition leaves a decomposition of $s[0..i)$, counted by $dp[i]$. Lemma 1 finds its final word and performs the transition. Conversely, every transition appends one dictionary word to a valid prefix decomposition, so it creates a valid and unique decomposition. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs the number of dictionary-word decompositions of the target.

#### Proof

Induct over prefix length. The empty prefix has one decomposition. Lemma 2 establishes a bijection between decompositions of each nonempty prefix and transitions formed by choosing its last word. Hence $dp[n]$ is exact. $\square$

### Complexity

Let $L$ be the total dictionary length and let $W$ be the total number of target characters examined by all trie walks. Construction takes $O(L)$ time and space, and the DP takes $O(W)$ time with $W\le n^2$. Under the official word-length bounds, the walk stops after the maximum dictionary length, giving $O(n\ell_{max}+L)$ time. The arrays use $O(n+L)$ space.

## Implementation

Trie children are initialized to `-1`, distinguishing a missing edge from node 0. A Boolean terminal marker is sufficient because the dictionary contains words as choices, not separately labeled copies. Positions with zero ways are skipped.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
struct Trie {
    vector<array<int,26>> ch;
    vector<bool> end;
    Trie() { newNode(); }
    int newNode() {
        ch.push_back({});
        ch.back().fill(-1);
        end.push_back(false);
        return ch.size() - 1;
    }
    void insert(const string& w) {
        int cur = 0;
        for (char c : w) {
            int x = c - 'a';
            if (ch[cur][x] == -1) ch[cur][x] = newNode();
            cur = ch[cur][x];
        }
        end[cur] = true;
    }
};

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string s;
    cin >> s;
    int n = s.size();

    int k;
    cin >> k;

    Trie trie;
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
        string w;
        cin >> w;
        trie.insert(w);
    }

    vector<long long> dp(n + 1, 0);
    dp[0] = 1;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (dp[i] == 0) continue;
        int cur = 0;
        for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {
            int x = s[j] - 'a';
            if (trie.ch[cur][x] == -1) break;
            cur = trie.ch[cur][x];
            if (trie.end[cur]) dp[j + 1] = (dp[j + 1] + dp[i]) % MOD;
        }
    }

    cout << dp[n] << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For target `abab` and words `a`, `ab`, `b`, begin with $dp[0]=1$. From 0, terminal nodes after `a` and `ab` add to $dp[1]$ and $dp[2]$. From 1, `b` adds to $dp[2]$, making it 2. Extending both ways from position 2 ultimately gives $dp[4]=4$.

## Takeaway

When a DP transition asks which dictionary words match at one position, a trie shares their common prefixes and turns failed continuation into an immediate stop.

### Related problems

Required Substring combines prefix matching with DP over automaton states. Finding Patterns uses Aho-Corasick when many patterns must be matched throughout one text.

