# String Matching

- **CSES problem:** 1753
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (stringmatching.cpp)`](./stringmatching.cpp)

## Problem

Given a text $s$ and a pattern $p$, count every starting position where $p$ occurs in $s$. Overlapping occurrences count separately.

## Reasoning

Trying the pattern at every text position costs $O(nm)$, which can reach $10^{12}$ comparisons for lengths up to $10^6$. The wasted work occurs after a mismatch: a matched prefix of the pattern often contains a suffix that is itself a shorter prefix, so part of the match can be reused.

Define $fail[i]$ as the length of the longest proper prefix of $p[0..i]$ that is also its suffix. Suppose `len` pattern characters currently match a suffix of the processed text. If the next character disagrees with $p[len]$, any viable shorter match must be a border of the already matched prefix. The longest candidate is `fail[len-1]`; repeating this fallback enumerates all candidates from longest to shortest without moving backwards in the text.

After a complete match, falling back once is also necessary. It preserves the longest suffix that may begin an overlapping occurrence. For example, after matching `aaa` inside `aaaa`, the next viable matched length is 2, not 0.

## Algorithm

1. Build the failure array of the pattern using the same border fallback rule.
2. Scan the text while maintaining `len`, the length of the pattern prefix matching the current text suffix.
3. On mismatch, repeatedly replace `len` by `fail[len-1]` until matching is possible or `len` becomes zero.
4. On equality, increment `len`.
5. Whenever `len==m`, increment the answer and set `len=fail[m-1]`.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After processing a text prefix, `len` is the maximum length such that the corresponding pattern prefix equals a suffix of that text prefix.

#### Proof

Induct on processed characters. Extending by an equal character extends the maximum match by one. On mismatch, any surviving match must be a border of the former matched prefix; failure links test those borders in decreasing length. The first extendable border is therefore the longest possible new match. If none extends, only the empty prefix remains. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The algorithm increments the answer exactly at the ending position of every occurrence.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1, `len==m` precisely when the full pattern is a suffix of the processed text, which is precisely an occurrence ending at that position. The fallback after counting retains every possible overlapping continuation and cannot create an additional occurrence at the same ending position. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs the number of pattern occurrences in the text, including overlaps.

#### Proof

Lemma 2 gives a one-to-one correspondence between answer increments and occurrence ending positions. $\square$

### Complexity

Failure construction and text scanning each take linear time because every increase of the matched length can pay for at most one later fallback. The total is $O(n+m)$ time and $O(m)$ space.

## Implementation

Both strings are zero-indexed. `fail[i]` stores a length, so the next fallback from length `len` reads `fail[len-1]`. Resetting after a match to that value, rather than zero, is the detail that preserves overlaps.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string s, p;
    cin >> s >> p;
    int n = s.size(), m = p.size();

    vector<int> fail(m, 0);
    for (int i = 1, len = 0; i < m; ) {
        if (p[i] == p[len]) {
            fail[i++] = ++len;
        } else if (len > 0) {
            len = fail[len - 1];
        } else {
            fail[i++] = 0;
        }
    }

    int count = 0;
    for (int i = 0, len = 0; i < n; i++) {
        while (len > 0 && s[i] != p[len]) len = fail[len - 1];
        if (s[i] == p[len]) len++;
        if (len == m) {
            count++;
            len = fail[len - 1];
        }
    }

    cout << count << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For text `aaaaa` and pattern `aaa`, the failure array is $[0,1,2]$. The first three text characters produce a match. Falling back to length 2 lets the fourth character complete the second match, and the fifth completes the third. The answer is 3.

## Takeaway

When a sequential match fails, ask which suffix of the work already done is also a valid prefix state. Failure links encode exactly this reusable information.

### Related problems

Finding Borders exposes the failure-link chain directly. Finding Patterns extends the same automaton idea to many patterns with Aho-Corasick.

