# Finding Borders

- **CSES problem:** 1732
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (findingborders.cpp)`](./findingborders.cpp)

## Problem

Output the lengths of all nonempty proper prefixes of a string that are also suffixes, in increasing order.

## Reasoning

Such a prefix is called a border. Checking every length character by character is quadratic. The KMP failure array already records the longest border of every prefix: `fail[i]` is the longest proper border length of $s[0..i]$.

For the whole string, the longest border has length `fail[n-1]`. Every shorter border of the whole string must also be a border of that longest border. Otherwise its prefix and suffix copies inside the full string would not both fit inside the longest border copy. Therefore all borders form a chain

$$
b_1=fail[n-1],\qquad b_{j+1}=fail[b_j-1].
$$

This chain is generated from longest to shortest, so it is stored and printed backwards.

## Algorithm

1. Compute the KMP failure array for the entire string.
2. Start with $b=fail[n-1]$.
3. While $b>0$, store $b$ and replace it by `fail[b-1]`.
4. Print the stored lengths in reverse order.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

For every index $i$, `fail[i]` equals the longest proper border of $s[0..i]$.

#### Proof

The construction extends the previous longest border when the next characters agree. On disagreement, every possible border must be a border of the previous candidate, so following failure links examines candidates in decreasing length. The first extension found is maximal; if none exists, the border length is zero. $\square$

### Lemma 2

Following failure links from `fail[n-1]` enumerates every border of the full string exactly once.

#### Proof

The first value is the longest border by Lemma 1. If $b$ is a border of the full string, its own borders are also prefixes and suffixes of the full string. Conversely, every full-string border shorter than $b$ is a border of the prefix of length $b$, because its prefix copy begins there and its suffix copy ends there. Thus the next value is exactly the longest remaining border, and induction enumerates the complete strictly decreasing chain. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm prints exactly all requested border lengths in increasing order.

#### Proof

Lemma 2 proves completeness and uniqueness. Reversing its decreasing enumeration gives increasing output order. $\square$

### Complexity

The failure array takes $O(n)$ time and space. The chain contains at most $n-1$ values, so total time remains $O(n)$.

## Implementation

Failure values are lengths, while vector indices are zero-based. Hence a border of length $b$ falls back through `fail[b-1]`. Length $n$ is never emitted because `fail[n-1]` is defined as a proper border.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string s;
    cin >> s;
    int n = s.size();

    vector<int> fail(n, 0);
    for (int i = 1, len = 0; i < n; ) {
        if (s[i] == s[len]) {
            fail[i++] = ++len;
        } else if (len > 0) {
            len = fail[len - 1];
        } else {
            fail[i++] = 0;
        }
    }

    vector<int> borders;
    for (int b = fail[n - 1]; b > 0; b = fail[b - 1])
        borders.push_back(b);

    for (int i = borders.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--)
        cout << borders[i] << " ";
    cout << "\n";

    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `abcababcab`, the longest border is `abcab` of length 5. That prefix has border `ab` of length 2, whose failure value is 0. The chain is $5,2$, and reversing it prints `2 5`.

## Takeaway

Failure links do more than accelerate matching: they form a tree of nested borders. Repeatedly following them enumerates every border without additional comparisons.

