# Finding Periods

- **CSES problem:** 1733
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (findingperiods.cpp)`](./findingperiods.cpp)

## Problem

Output every positive length $p$ such that the string can be formed by repeating its prefix of length $p$, with the final repetition allowed to be incomplete.

## Reasoning

For a candidate $p$, positions $p,p+1,\ldots,n-1$ must reproduce positions $0,1,\ldots,n-p-1$. Equivalently,

$$
s[p..n-1]=s[0..n-p-1].
$$

The Z-value $z[p]$ is the length of the longest prefix match beginning at $p$. Thus $p$ is a period exactly when $z[p]\ge n-p$. Since a Z-value cannot extend beyond the string, the implementation tests the equivalent equality $p+z[p]=n$. Length $n$ is always a period and is handled separately because `z[n]` does not exist.

The Z-algorithm maintains a half-open interval $[l,r)$ known to match the prefix. If $i<r$, the mirrored value `z[i-l]` supplies a safe initial match, capped at `r-i`. Direct comparisons then extend beyond the known interval.

## Algorithm

1. Compute all Z-values in linear time using the rightmost prefix-match interval.
2. For each $p$ from 1 through $n-1$, output $p$ if $p+z[p]=n$.
3. Output $n$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After processing index $i$, `z[i]` is the longest length for which $s[0..z[i)-1]=s[i..i+z[i)-1]$.

#### Proof

Inside the current Z-box, the mirrored prefix match is valid up to either its known length or the box boundary. The algorithm starts with exactly this guaranteed portion and compares further characters until the first mismatch or string end. Therefore the resulting value is both valid and maximal. $\square$

### Lemma 2

A length $p<n$ is a period if and only if $p+z[p]=n$.

#### Proof

The period definition requires every character from position $p$ onward to equal the character $p$ positions earlier, which is exactly a prefix match of length $n-p$ at position $p$. By Lemma 1 this holds exactly when $z[p]\ge n-p$. The maximum possible value is $n-p$, so equality with $n-p$ is equivalent. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs exactly all periods.

#### Proof

Lemma 2 proves the test for every $p<n$. Length $n$ always needs only one complete copy and is explicitly included. $\square$

### Complexity

The right boundary of the Z-box advances at most $n$ times, so Z construction and the final scan take $O(n)$ time. The Z-array uses $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The maintained box is half-open: `r` is the first position outside the known match. This explains both `r-i` and the update `r=i+z[i]`. The output buffer's final space is replaced with a newline.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string s; cin >> s;
    int n = s.size();
    vector<int> z(n, 0);
    for (int i = 1, l = 0, r = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (i < r) z[i] = min(r - i, z[i - l]);
        while (i + z[i] < n && s[z[i]] == s[i + z[i]]) z[i]++;
        if (i + z[i] > r) { l = i; r = i + z[i]; }
    }

    string out;
    out.reserve(1 << 21);
    for (int p = 1; p <= n; p++)
        if (p == n || p + z[p] == n) { out += to_string(p); out += ' '; }
    if (!out.empty()) out.back() = '\n';
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `abcabca`, $z[3]=4$, so $3+4=7$ and length 3 is a period: the repetitions are `abc`, `abc`, and the incomplete `a`. Length 6 fails because $z[6]=1$ gives 7 only if the last character equals the first; here it does, so 6 is also valid. Length 7 is always included.

## Takeaway

Translate periodicity into a suffix-versus-prefix equality. Once written that way, a whole family of candidate checks becomes one Z-array lookup each.

### Related problems

Finding Borders studies full prefix-suffix matches. String Functions derives the Z-array and prefix function together.

