# Minimal Rotation

- **CSES problem:** 1110
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (minimalrotation.cpp)`](./minimalrotation.cpp)

## Problem

Among all cyclic rotations of a string, output the lexicographically smallest rotation.

## Reasoning

Every rotation of a length-$n$ string is a length-$n$ substring of $s+s$ starting at an index below $n$. Sorting all rotations costs at least $O(n^2)$ just to materialize them.

Booth's algorithm maintains `k`, the start of the best candidate seen so far, and a failure array for comparisons against that candidate. At doubled-string position $j$, it compares the new character with the corresponding candidate character. On mismatch, the failure links skip borders of the already equal segment. If the new character is smaller, every candidate start between the old start and the mismatch-derived new start shares the equal prefix and then has a larger character, so all are eliminated at once. If it is larger, the current candidate survives.

This is the same amortization as KMP, augmented with lexicographic elimination. Candidate starts only move right, and failure links only retreat through previously computed borders.

## Algorithm

1. Form $t=s+s$ and initialize candidate start $k=0$.
2. Scan $j=1$ through $2n-1$, maintaining failure information relative to the current candidate.
3. On each mismatch, follow failure links. If $t[j]$ is smaller than its compared candidate character, advance $k$ to the first start not already disproved.
4. Store the new border information and continue.
5. Output $n$ characters of $s$ cyclically starting at $k$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

Whenever the algorithm advances $k$ after a mismatch, every skipped start is lexicographically larger than the new candidate.

#### Proof

The failure-chain state certifies that the compared rotations agree before the mismatch. At the first differing position, the character belonging to the new candidate is smaller. Lexicographic order is decided at this first difference, so the old candidate is worse. Starts skipped between them correspond to borders already examined by the failure chain and encounter the same decisive mismatch; they are worse as well. $\square$

### Lemma 2

No start that could be the minimum is discarded.

#### Proof

A start is discarded only under the comparison in Lemma 1, which supplies a surviving candidate strictly smaller than it. Hence a globally minimal start is never removed unless an equal minimal rotation remains, which is sufficient because any minimum may be output. $\square$

### Theorem

The rotation beginning at the returned index $k$ is lexicographically minimal.

#### Proof

After scanning the doubled string, every possible rotation start has either survived as $k$ or been discarded. By Lemma 2, every discarded start is no better than a surviving minimum. Thus the length-$n$ rotation at $k$ is minimal. $\square$

### Complexity

The scan is $O(n)$ amortized: the candidate moves only right and failure-link traversals are paid for by prior extensions. The doubled string and failure array use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The failure array uses `-1` as the empty-border sentinel. The algorithm scans all $2n$ doubled positions so comparisons near the end wrap naturally. Output uses modular indexing into the original string rather than retaining a doubled result.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int leastRotation(const string& s) {
    int n = s.size();
    string t = s + s;
    vector<int> f(2 * n, -1);
    int k = 0;
    for (int j = 1; j < 2 * n; j++) {
        char sj = t[j];
        int i = f[j - k - 1];
        while (i != -1 && sj != t[k + i + 1]) {
            if (sj < t[k + i + 1]) k = j - i - 1;
            i = f[i];
        }
        if (sj != t[k + i + 1]) {
            if (sj < t[k + i + 1]) k = j;   // i == -1 here
            f[j - k] = -1;
        } else {
            f[j - k] = i + 1;
        }
    }
    return k;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string s; cin >> s;
    int k = leastRotation(s);
    int n = s.size();

    string out;
    out.reserve(n + 1);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) out += s[(k + i) % n];
    out += '\n';
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `baca`, the rotations are `baca`, `acab`, `caba`, and `abac`. Comparing the candidates eventually eliminates starts 0 and 2 because they begin with larger letters. Starts 1 and 3 both begin with `a`, but their second characters are `c` and `b`; start 3 survives and produces `abac`.

## Takeaway

When lexicographically comparing many highly overlapping strings, seek a failure-function style method that reuses equal-prefix information and discards ranges of candidates at once.

### Related problems

String Matching uses failure links without candidate elimination. Inverse Suffix Array also turns lexicographic constraints into local comparisons of suffix ranks.

