# All Palindromes

- **CSES problem:** 3138
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (allpalindromes.cpp)`](./allpalindromes.cpp)

## Problem

For every ending position $j$ of a string, output the maximum length of a palindromic substring ending at $j$.

## Reasoning

Manacher's algorithm finds the maximum palindrome around every center in linear time, but the requested grouping is by right endpoint rather than center. A maximal palindrome of transformed radius $p[i]$ corresponds to an original palindrome of length $p[i]$ ending at

$$
e=\frac{i+p[i]}2-1.
$$

Recording this radius at `ans[e]` handles every center's longest palindrome. It does not directly record shorter palindromes with the same center. Those shorter palindromes are obtained by peeling one character from each end. If a palindrome of length $L$ ends at $j$, its inner palindrome has length $L-2$ and ends at $j-1$.

Therefore a right-to-left propagation

$$
ans[j-1]\gets\max(ans[j-1],ans[j]-2)
$$

recovers all inner candidates. Processing right to left is essential because a newly improved value at $j-1$ must itself propagate farther left.

## Algorithm

1. Build the separator-transformed string and compute all Manacher radii.
2. For each center with positive radius $L$, compute its original ending index $e$ and maximize `ans[e]` with $L$.
3. Scan $j=n-1$ down to 1 and maximize `ans[j-1]` with `ans[j]-2`.
4. Output the array.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After the center scan, `ans[e]` contains the maximum length among center-maximal palindromes ending at $e$.

#### Proof

Manacher's radius is the exact maximum palindrome length for its center. The endpoint formula maps that palindrome to its original right endpoint. Taking a maximum over all centers mapped to $e$ gives precisely the stated quantity. $\square$

### Lemma 2

If a palindrome of length $L\ge2$ ends at $j$, then a palindrome of length $L-2$ ends at $j-1$.

#### Proof

Removing the equal first and last characters leaves a string equal to its reverse. Its right endpoint moves left once and its length decreases by two. $\square$

### Lemma 3

After right-to-left propagation, `ans[j]` is the maximum length of any palindrome ending at $j$.

#### Proof

Every palindrome is obtained by repeatedly peeling a center's maximal palindrome, since expansion around its center continues until that maximal one. Lemma 1 records the maximal member, and repeated applications of Lemma 2 propagate its inner members to their endpoints. Right-to-left order permits the entire chain to propagate. All propagated candidates are genuine palindromes by Lemma 2, so the maximum is exact. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs the required longest ending-palindrome length at every position.

#### Proof

This is exactly the statement established by Lemma 3 for all indices. $\square$

### Complexity

Manacher's scan, center mapping, and endpoint propagation each take $O(n)$ time. The transformed string, radii, and answer array use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The transformed radius equals original palindrome length. The endpoint formula uses integer division and works for both original character centers and separator centers. Propagation checks `ans[j]-2`; negative values cannot improve the nonnegative array.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);   

    string s; cin >> s;
    int n = s.size();

    string t;
    t.reserve(2 * n + 3);
    t += '^';
    for (char ch : s) { t += '#'; t += ch; }
    t += '#';
    t += '$';

    int m = t.size();
    vector<int> p(m, 0);
    int c = 0, r = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i < m - 1; i++) {
        if (i < r) p[i] = min(r - i, p[2 * c - i]);
        while (t[i + p[i] + 1] == t[i - p[i] - 1]) p[i]++;
        if (i + p[i] > r) { c = i; r = i + p[i]; }
    }

    vector<int> ans(n, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i < m - 1; i++) {
        if (p[i] == 0) continue;
        int len = p[i];                 // palindrome length in original
        int e = (i + p[i]) / 2 - 1;     // ending index in s
        ans[e] = max(ans[e], len);
    }
    for (int j = n - 1; j >= 1; j--)
        if (ans[j] - 2 > ans[j - 1]) ans[j - 1] = ans[j] - 2;   // peel co-centered

    string out;
    out.reserve(1 << 21);
    for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) { out += to_string(ans[j]); out += (j == n - 1 ? '\n' : ' '); }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `abac`, Manacher records the maximal palindrome `aba`, length 3, ending at index 2. Propagation sends length 1 to index 1, representing the inner palindrome `b`. Independently, the single characters record length 1 at every endpoint. The final answers are $[1,1,3,1]$.

## Takeaway

When maximal objects are easy to compute but all endpoint answers are required, ask whether smaller objects arise by a fixed local contraction. A directional propagation can recover them without enumeration.

### Related problems

Longest Palindrome selects the largest Manacher radius globally. Palindrome Queries replaces static center information with updateable forward and reverse hashes.

