# Finding Patterns

- **CSES problem:** 2102
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (findingpatterns.cpp)`](./findingpatterns.cpp)

## Problem

Given one text and many patterns, report for each pattern whether it occurs as a substring of the text.

## Reasoning

Running KMP separately for every pattern repeats the text scan. Aho-Corasick combines all pattern prefixes in one trie. A state represents the longest trie string that is a suffix of the text processed so far. Its failure link points to the longest proper suffix that is also a trie prefix.

Completing missing transitions during breadth-first construction makes every text character one constant-time automaton step. If scanning lands at state $u$, the text suffix equals $u$'s trie string, but shorter patterns may also end there. They are precisely the states on $u$'s failure-link chain.

Rather than walking that chain after every character, mark only the states directly visited. Failure links form a rooted tree directed toward shorter strings. Propagating Boolean OR from deeper states to failure parents marks every suffix pattern that occurred. Reverse BFS order is valid because failure links always lead to smaller depth.

## Algorithm

1. Insert every pattern into a trie and remember its terminal node.
2. Build failure links by BFS. Replace every missing transition with the transition of the failure state.
3. Scan the text once, following completed transitions and marking each reached state.
4. Process automaton states in reverse BFS order, propagating every mark to its failure parent.
5. A pattern occurs exactly when its remembered terminal node is marked.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After each text character, the automaton state represents the longest pattern prefix that is a suffix of the processed text.

#### Proof

Trie edges extend the current suffix when possible. A completed fallback transition repeatedly follows failure links until it finds the longest suffix that can accept the character, exactly mirroring KMP fallback. BFS construction stores the resulting transition directly. $\square$

### Lemma 2

A pattern ending at state $v$ occurs in the text if and only if some directly visited state lies in the failure subtree of $v$.

#### Proof

If state $u$ is visited, its represented string is a text suffix. Following failure links enumerates suffixes of that string which are trie prefixes, so every ancestor terminal pattern ends there. Conversely, if pattern $v$ ends at a text position, the longest represented suffix state at that position has $v$ on its failure chain. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm reports every pattern's occurrence correctly.

#### Proof

Reverse propagation marks a state exactly when its failure subtree contains a visited state. Lemma 2 makes this equivalent to occurrence of the pattern represented by that state. $\square$

### Complexity

Let $L$ be total pattern length and $N$ text length. Trie construction, BFS over 26 transitions per state, scanning, and propagation take $O(26L+N)$ time, customarily written $O(L+N)$ for a fixed alphabet. The automaton uses $O(26L)$ space.

## Implementation

Node 0 is the root, while zero also denotes an initially missing transition. This is safe because new nodes begin at index 1. Root transitions left as zero correctly loop to the root. Duplicate patterns share one terminal node and receive the same answer.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
const int MX = 500005;
int go[MX][26];
int fail_[MX], cnt;
bool vis[MX];

int newnode() { int u = cnt++; memset(go[u], 0, sizeof(go[u])); fail_[u] = 0; vis[u] = 0; return u; }

int add(const string& p) {              // returns end-node id
    int u = 0;
    for (char c : p) {
        int d = c - 'a';
        if (!go[u][d]) go[u][d] = newnode();
        u = go[u][d];
    }
    return u;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string T; cin >> T;
    int k; cin >> k;

    cnt = 0; newnode();                 // root = 0
    vector<int> endId(k);
    vector<string> pat(k);
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) { cin >> pat[i]; endId[i] = add(pat[i]); }

    // BFS to build fail links + automaton goto; record bfs order
    vector<int> order; order.reserve(cnt);
    queue<int> q;
    for (int c = 0; c < 26; c++) if (go[0][c]) { fail_[go[0][c]] = 0; q.push(go[0][c]); }
    while (!q.empty()) {
        int u = q.front(); q.pop(); order.push_back(u);
        for (int c = 0; c < 26; c++) {
            int v = go[u][c];
            if (v) { fail_[v] = go[fail_[u]][c]; q.push(v); }
            else   go[u][c] = go[fail_[u]][c];   // goto redirection
        }
    }

    // single pass over text
    int u = 0;
    for (char ch : T) { u = go[u][ch - 'a']; vis[u] = 1; }

    // subtree-OR over fail tree, reverse BFS order (child before fail-parent)
    for (int i = (int)order.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        int x = order[i];
        if (vis[x]) vis[fail_[x]] = 1;
    }

    string out; out.reserve(2 * k);
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) out += vis[endId[i]] ? "YES\n" : "NO\n";
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

With patterns `he`, `she`, and `hers`, scanning text `ushers` reaches the state for `she`. Its failure chain includes `he`, so reverse propagation marks both. Later the state for `hers` is visited directly. All three answers are `YES`.

## Takeaway

Aho-Corasick separates text scanning from suffix reporting. Scan once, then aggregate over the failure tree with the operation required by the query.

### Related problems

Counting Patterns propagates sums instead of OR. Pattern Positions propagates minimum ending positions.

