# Counting Patterns

- **CSES problem:** 2103
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (countingpatterns.cpp)`](./countingpatterns.cpp)

## Problem

For each of many patterns, count how many times it occurs in one text. Overlapping occurrences are included.

## Reasoning

Build the Aho-Corasick automaton of all patterns. During the text scan, increment only the reached state. This count records how many text prefixes have that state as their longest recognized suffix.

A pattern state $v$ also matches whenever the reached state is a failure-tree descendant of $v$. Thus its total occurrence count is the sum of direct visit counts over its failure subtree. Since every failure link points to a shallower state, reverse BFS order processes a child before its failure parent. Adding `c[x]` into `c[fail[x]]` computes every subtree sum without explicitly storing the tree.

Overlaps require no special case. Each text ending position contributes one visit, and propagation credits every pattern ending at that position.

## Algorithm

1. Insert patterns and save terminal state IDs.
2. Build failure links and completed transitions using BFS.
3. Scan the text and increment the count of every reached state.
4. Traverse states in reverse BFS order and add each count to its failure parent.
5. Output the accumulated count at every pattern's terminal state.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

For each text ending position, the directly visited state is a failure-tree descendant of exactly the pattern states that match at that position.

#### Proof

The visited state represents the longest trie prefix that is a suffix of the processed text. Its failure chain enumerates all shorter trie-prefix suffixes. A terminal state lies on that chain exactly when its pattern is a suffix ending at the current position. $\square$

### Lemma 2

After reverse propagation, `c[v]` equals the number of text positions at which the pattern represented by state $v$ ends.

#### Proof

Each position contributes one unit to its visited state. Reverse propagation moves that unit once to every failure ancestor. By Lemma 1, those ancestors are exactly the patterns ending at that position. No unit reaches an unrelated state. $\square$

### Theorem

Every reported pattern count is correct.

#### Proof

Applying Lemma 2 to each remembered terminal state gives exactly its number of occurrences. $\square$

### Complexity

For total pattern length $L$ and text length $N$, time is $O(26L+N)$ and space is $O(26L)$. Counts use `long long`, though each individual answer is at most $N$.

## Implementation

The BFS order excludes the root, but every child eventually adds into it and no pattern needs the root count. Terminal IDs allow duplicate patterns to reuse one state. Completed transitions eliminate failure loops during text scanning.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;

const int MX = 500005;
int go[MX][26];
int fail_[MX], cnt;
ll c[MX];                               // hit counts per state

int newnode() { int u = cnt++; memset(go[u], 0, sizeof(go[u])); fail_[u] = 0; c[u] = 0; return u; }

int add(const string& p) {              // returns end-node id
    int u = 0;
    for (char ch : p) {
        int d = ch - 'a';
        if (!go[u][d]) go[u][d] = newnode();
        u = go[u][d];
    }
    return u;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string T; cin >> T;
    int k; cin >> k;

    cnt = 0; newnode();                 // root = 0
    vector<int> endId(k);
    vector<string> pat(k);
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) { cin >> pat[i]; endId[i] = add(pat[i]); }

    // BFS to build fail links + automaton goto; record bfs order
    vector<int> order; order.reserve(cnt);
    queue<int> q;
    for (int ch = 0; ch < 26; ch++) if (go[0][ch]) { fail_[go[0][ch]] = 0; q.push(go[0][ch]); }
    while (!q.empty()) {
        int u = q.front(); q.pop(); order.push_back(u);
        for (int ch = 0; ch < 26; ch++) {
            int v = go[u][ch];
            if (v) { fail_[v] = go[fail_[u]][ch]; q.push(v); }
            else   go[u][ch] = go[fail_[u]][ch];   // goto redirection
        }
    }

    // single pass over text: tally a hit at each visited state
    int u = 0;
    for (char ch : T) { u = go[u][ch - 'a']; c[u]++; }

    // subtree-SUM over fail tree, reverse BFS order (child before fail-parent)
    for (int i = (int)order.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        int x = order[i];
        c[fail_[x]] += c[x];
    }

    string out; out.reserve(7 * k);
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) { out += to_string(c[endId[i]]); out += '\n'; }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For text `aaaa` and patterns `a`, `aa`, `aaa`, the automaton visits progressively deeper `a` states. Reverse failure propagation yields counts 4, 3, and 2. These include the overlapping occurrences beginning at consecutive positions.

## Takeaway

Visits in a pattern automaton often become answers only after failure-tree aggregation. Choose OR for existence, sum for frequency, and other associative operations for other query types.

### Related problems

Finding Patterns uses Boolean propagation. Pattern Positions uses minimum propagation to recover earliest matches.

