# Pattern Positions

- **CSES problem:** 2104
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (patternpositions.cpp)`](./patternpositions.cpp)

## Problem

For each pattern, output the one-indexed starting position of its first occurrence in the text, or $-1$ if it never occurs.

## Reasoning

Aho-Corasick identifies all patterns ending at each text position. Record at each directly visited automaton state the earliest one-indexed text ending position that reaches it. A shorter pattern may not be visited directly even when it matches, because the automaton stores only the longest suffix state. Its terminal state is then a failure ancestor of the visited state.

Consequently, the earliest ending position for state $v$ is the minimum direct ending position over the failure subtree of $v$. Reverse BFS propagation with minimum computes these values. If a pattern of length $m$ first ends at $e$, its first starting position is $e-m+1$.

Only the first direct visit to a state is stored because text positions are scanned in increasing order. Later visits cannot improve its minimum.

## Algorithm

1. Build the Aho-Corasick trie, failure links, and completed transitions.
2. Scan the text from left to right. At state $u$ after position $i$, set `best[u]=i+1` if it is still infinity.
3. In reverse BFS order, minimize every failure parent's value with its child's value.
4. For each pattern terminal, output $-1$ if its value is infinity; otherwise output `best-terminal - pattern-length + 1`.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

A pattern state $v$ matches ending at position $e$ exactly when the state visited at $e$ belongs to the failure subtree of $v$.

#### Proof

Failure ancestors are exactly trie strings that are suffixes of the visited state's string. Those are exactly pattern prefixes, including terminals, that end at the same text position. $\square$

### Lemma 2

After reverse propagation, `best[v]` is the minimum ending position of any occurrence of the string represented by $v$.

#### Proof

Direct values supply ending positions for visited states. Propagating minima upward takes the minimum over every failure subtree. By Lemma 1, that subtree contains exactly the visits at which $v$ matches. Infinity remains precisely when there are none. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs every pattern's first starting position, or $-1$ when absent.

#### Proof

Lemma 2 provides its earliest ending position $e$. All occurrences have the fixed pattern length $m$, so minimizing $e$ also minimizes $e-m+1$. The conversion is one-indexed and exact. $\square$

### Complexity

For total pattern length $L$ and text length $N$, time is $O(26L+N)$ and space is $O(26L)$ for the fixed lowercase alphabet.

## Implementation

`INF` represents no occurrence. Pattern lengths are saved separately because automaton states may represent several duplicate patterns but the duplicates necessarily have the same spelling and length. BFS order guarantees failure children are processed first when reversed.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;

const int MX = 500005;
const int INF = 1e9;
int go[MX][26];
int fail_[MX], cnt;
int best[MX];                           // first text end-position landing on this state

int newnode() { int u = cnt++; memset(go[u], 0, sizeof(go[u])); fail_[u] = 0; best[u] = INF; return u; }

int add(const string& p) {              // returns end-node id
    int u = 0;
    for (char ch : p) {
        int d = ch - 'a';
        if (!go[u][d]) go[u][d] = newnode();
        u = go[u][d];
    }
    return u;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string T; cin >> T;
    int k; cin >> k;

    cnt = 0; newnode();                 // root = 0
    vector<int> endId(k), plen(k);
    vector<string> pat(k);
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) { cin >> pat[i]; endId[i] = add(pat[i]); plen[i] = pat[i].size(); }

    // BFS to build fail links + automaton goto; record bfs order
    vector<int> order; order.reserve(cnt);
    queue<int> q;
    for (int ch = 0; ch < 26; ch++) if (go[0][ch]) { fail_[go[0][ch]] = 0; q.push(go[0][ch]); }
    while (!q.empty()) {
        int u = q.front(); q.pop(); order.push_back(u);
        for (int ch = 0; ch < 26; ch++) {
            int v = go[u][ch];
            if (v) { fail_[v] = go[fail_[u]][ch]; q.push(v); }
            else   go[u][ch] = go[fail_[u]][ch];   // goto redirection
        }
    }

    // single pass: record earliest end-position (1-indexed) at each visited state
    int u = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)T.size(); i++) {
        u = go[u][T[i] - 'a'];
        if (best[u] == INF) best[u] = i + 1;        // first landing only
    }

    // subtree-MIN over fail tree, reverse BFS (child before fail-parent)
    for (int i = (int)order.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        int x = order[i];
        if (best[x] < best[fail_[x]]) best[fail_[x]] = best[x];
    }

    string out; out.reserve(7 * k);
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
        int e = best[endId[i]];
        out += (e == INF) ? "-1" : to_string(e - plen[i] + 1);
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

In text `ushers`, pattern `he` is not necessarily the directly visited state after reading `she`; the visited `she` state has `he` as a failure ancestor. The ending position 4 propagates to `he`, and subtracting length 2 gives starting position 3.

## Takeaway

Earliest occurrence is a failure-subtree minimum. More generally, once multi-pattern matching becomes a failure tree, many per-pattern questions reduce to one bottom-up aggregation.

### Related problems

Finding Patterns aggregates reachability, while Counting Patterns aggregates visit counts over the same automaton.

