# Distinct Substrings

- **CSES problem:** 2105
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (distinctsubstrings.cpp)`](./distinctsubstrings.cpp)

## Problem

Count the number of distinct nonempty substrings of a lowercase string.

## Reasoning

A suffix automaton groups substrings by their `endpos` set, the positions where they can end. For each state $u$, `len[u]` is the maximum length in its class, and its suffix link points to the class containing the longest proper suffix with a different end-position set.

The crucial interval property is that state $u$ represents exactly one distinct substring of every length

$$
len[link[u]]+1,\ldots,len[u].
$$

All of these strings follow the same path endpoint and share the same occurrences. Shorter suffixes belong to the suffix-link state or its ancestors; longer strings cannot end at $u$ by definition of `len`.

Therefore state $u$ contributes `len[u]-len[link[u]]` distinct substrings. Summing over every nonroot state counts every nonempty substring once.

During extension, a clone is needed when an existing transition reaches a state whose maximum length is too large to serve as the direct suffix link. Copying its transitions and shortening its `len` splits one end-position class while preserving recognized substrings.

## Algorithm

1. Initialize the suffix automaton with its root.
2. Extend it by every character, creating a primary state and, when required, a clone state.
3. Redirect transitions and suffix links according to the standard extension procedure.
4. Sum `len[u]-len[link[u]]` for all states except the root.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After processing the string, every substring labels a path from the root to exactly one automaton state endpoint.

#### Proof

Each extension adds transitions necessary for substrings ending at the new position. Suffix-link traversal installs the new transition from every suffix state lacking it. Cloning preserves all existing path labels while separating states whose suffix-link length condition would fail. This is the standard suffix-automaton invariant recognizing exactly all substrings. $\square$

### Lemma 2

A nonroot state $u$ represents exactly `len[u]-len[link[u]]` distinct substrings.

#### Proof

The represented lengths form the integer interval strictly above the maximum length of its suffix-link class and at most `len[u]`. For each such length, the suffix of a longest representative is unique. No other state represents it because states partition end-position equivalence classes. $\square$

### Theorem

The sum computed by the algorithm is the number of distinct nonempty substrings.

#### Proof

Lemma 1 ensures every substring is represented, and Lemma 2 partitions them among nonroot states with the stated contribution. Summation therefore counts each exactly once. $\square$

### Complexity

A suffix automaton has at most $2n-1$ states and is built in $O(n)$ amortized time for a fixed alphabet. The final sum is linear. The transition table uses $O(26n)$ space.

## Implementation

Missing transitions use `-1`. Clone states copy transitions and suffix links but do not represent a newly appended prefix. The global arrays are sized for twice the maximum input length.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;

const int MX = 200005;                  // up to 2n states
int nxt[MX][26], link_[MX], len_[MX];
int sz, last;

void sa_init() {
    sz = 0; last = 0;
    memset(nxt[0], -1, sizeof(nxt[0]));
    link_[0] = -1; len_[0] = 0; sz++;
}

void sa_extend(int c) {
    int cur = sz++;
    memset(nxt[cur], -1, sizeof(nxt[cur]));
    len_[cur] = len_[last] + 1; link_[cur] = -1;
    int p = last;
    while (p != -1 && nxt[p][c] == -1) { nxt[p][c] = cur; p = link_[p]; }
    if (p == -1) { link_[cur] = 0; }
    else {
        int q = nxt[p][c];
        if (len_[p] + 1 == len_[q]) link_[cur] = q;
        else {
            int cl = sz++;
            len_[cl] = len_[p] + 1;
            memcpy(nxt[cl], nxt[q], sizeof(nxt[q]));
            link_[cl] = link_[q];
            while (p != -1 && nxt[p][c] == q) { nxt[p][c] = cl; p = link_[p]; }
            link_[q] = link_[cur] = cl;
        }
    }
    last = cur;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string s; cin >> s;
    sa_init();
    for (char ch : s) sa_extend(ch - 'a');

    ll ans = 0;
    for (int u = 1; u < sz; u++) ans += len_[u] - len_[link_[u]];   // distinct substrings in u's class
    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `ababa`, one state may have `len=5` and suffix-link length 3. It contributes the two new represented lengths 4 and 5. Repeating this interval contribution over all states counts repeated strings such as `aba` only once because all occurrences share one state class.

## Takeaway

Suffix automata turn distinct substrings into disjoint length intervals attached to states. The expression `len[u]-len[link[u]]` is the fundamental counting identity.

### Related problems

Substring Distribution applies these state intervals to every length. Repeating Substring augments states with occurrence counts.

