# Repeating Substring

- **CSES problem:** 2106
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (repeatingsubstring.cpp)`](./repeatingsubstring.cpp)

## Problem

Output any longest substring that occurs at least twice, allowing the two occurrences to overlap, or $-1$ if none exists.

## Reasoning

In a suffix automaton, all strings represented by one state have the same set of ending positions. Thus a state represents repeating substrings exactly when its end-position set has size at least two. Among those strings, the longest has length `len[u]`, so the answer is the maximum `len[u]` over states with occurrence count at least two.

Each primary state created while appending a character corresponds to one new prefix ending position and starts with count 1. A clone is structural and receives count 0. Every ending position belonging to a state also belongs to its suffix-link ancestors. Processing states in decreasing `len` and adding each count to its suffix link therefore computes end-position set sizes.

`pos[u]` stores an ending position of a longest representative. Clones copy this witness from the cloned state. Once the best state is chosen, the substring ending there with length `len[u]` is a valid answer.

## Algorithm

1. Build a suffix automaton, assigning occurrence 1 and current position to primary states, and occurrence 0 to clones.
2. Counting-sort states by `len`.
3. Process them from longest to shortest, adding each occurrence count to its suffix-link parent.
4. Find a nonroot state with count at least 2 and maximum `len`.
5. Extract that length ending at its stored position, or print $-1$ if no state qualifies.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After propagation, `cnt[u]` equals the number of ending positions shared by substrings represented by state $u$.

#### Proof

Every original prefix endpoint contributes one unit at its primary state. A state's end-position set is the union of contributions in its suffix-link subtree. Suffix links strictly decrease `len`, so decreasing-length processing aggregates every descendant before its parent. Clones add no artificial endpoint. $\square$

### Lemma 2

A substring represented by $u$ repeats if and only if `cnt[u]>=2`.

#### Proof

All substrings of a state share exactly its end-position set. Two distinct ending positions correspond to two occurrences, including overlapping ones; fewer than two cannot repeat. Apply Lemma 1. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs a longest repeating substring, or $-1$ when none exists.

#### Proof

For every qualifying state, its longest representative has length `len[u]` and repeats by Lemma 2. Every repeating substring belongs to some qualifying state and has length at most that state's `len`. Maximizing these values therefore gives the global optimum, and `pos` extracts one representative. $\square$

### Complexity

Automaton construction, counting sort, propagation, and selection take $O(n)$ time for a fixed alphabet. The automaton and auxiliary arrays use $O(26n)$ space.

## Implementation

Counting sort by `len` avoids an $O(n\log n)$ state sort. The propagation loop skips the root because its suffix link is `-1`. Extraction uses the inclusive ending position `pos[best]`, hence start `pos-bestLen+1`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;

const int MX = 200005;                  // up to 2n states
int nxt[MX][26], link_[MX], len_[MX], cnt[MX], pos[MX];
int sz, last;

void sa_init() {
    sz = 0; last = 0;
    memset(nxt[0], -1, sizeof(nxt[0]));
    link_[0] = -1; len_[0] = 0; cnt[0] = 0; pos[0] = 0; sz++;
}

void sa_extend(int c, int i) {
    int cur = sz++;
    memset(nxt[cur], -1, sizeof(nxt[cur]));
    len_[cur] = len_[last] + 1; link_[cur] = -1;
    cnt[cur] = 1; pos[cur] = i;                  // primary state: one endpos, ends at i (0-indexed)
    int p = last;
    while (p != -1 && nxt[p][c] == -1) { nxt[p][c] = cur; p = link_[p]; }
    if (p == -1) link_[cur] = 0;
    else {
        int q = nxt[p][c];
        if (len_[p] + 1 == len_[q]) link_[cur] = q;
        else {
            int cl = sz++;
            len_[cl] = len_[p] + 1;
            memcpy(nxt[cl], nxt[q], sizeof(nxt[q]));
            link_[cl] = link_[q];
            cnt[cl] = 0; pos[cl] = pos[q];       // clone: no own endpos
            while (p != -1 && nxt[p][c] == q) { nxt[p][c] = cl; p = link_[p]; }
            link_[q] = link_[cur] = cl;
        }
    }
    last = cur;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string s; cin >> s;
    int n = s.size();
    sa_init();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) sa_extend(s[i] - 'a', i);

    // counting sort states by len, then propagate cnt up the link tree
    vector<int> ord(sz), bk(n + 1, 0);
    for (int u = 0; u < sz; u++) bk[len_[u]]++;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) bk[i] += bk[i-1];
    for (int u = sz - 1; u >= 0; u--) ord[--bk[len_[u]]] = u;
    for (int i = sz - 1; i >= 1; i--) { int u = ord[i]; cnt[link_[u]] += cnt[u]; }

    int best = -1, bestLen = 0;
    for (int u = 1; u < sz; u++) if (cnt[u] >= 2 && len_[u] > bestLen) { bestLen = len_[u]; best = u; }

    if (best == -1) { cout << -1 << '\n'; return 0; }
    // substring of length bestLen ending at pos[best] (0-indexed inclusive)
    cout << s.substr(pos[best] - bestLen + 1, bestLen) << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `banana`, substring `ana` ends at positions 3 and 5, so its state receives occurrence count 2 after propagation. No repeating represented string is longer than 3, and the stored ending witness extracts `ana`.

## Takeaway

Occurrence questions on a suffix automaton usually become subtree aggregation over suffix links. Primary states contribute endpoints; clones contribute structure only.

### Related problems

Distinct Substrings counts state length intervals without occurrences. Substring Order II weights lexicographic paths by these same occurrence counts.

