# Substring Distribution

- **CSES problem:** 2110
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (substringdivision.cpp)`](./substringdivision.cpp)

## Problem

For every length $L=1,2,\ldots,n$, output the number of distinct substrings of length $L$.

## Reasoning

Each nonroot suffix-automaton state $u$ represents exactly one substring of every length in

$$
[len[link[u]]+1,\ len[u]].
$$

Thus the answer for length $L$ is the number of state intervals covering $L$. Updating every covered length separately could be quadratic, but these are range additions of one. A difference array records an interval $[a,b]$ by adding one at $a$ and subtracting one at $b+1$. Prefix sums then recover all coverage counts.

This is a useful second layer over the standard identity for total distinct substrings: instead of summing interval lengths, retain their full coverage distribution.

## Algorithm

1. Build the suffix automaton of the string.
2. For every nonroot state $u$, add one at `len[link[u]]+1` and subtract one at `len[u]+1` in a difference array.
3. Prefix-sum the difference array from length 1 through $n$.
4. Output each running sum.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

State $u$ contributes one distinct substring to every length in its stated interval and none outside it.

#### Proof

Suffix-automaton states partition substrings by end-position equivalence. The lengths in one state are all integers greater than the maximum length of its suffix-link state and at most its own maximum length. Each such length identifies one suffix of a longest representative. $\square$

### Lemma 2

After prefix summation, the running value at $L$ equals the number of state intervals containing $L$.

#### Proof

Each interval contributes $+1$ beginning at its left endpoint and $-1$ immediately after its right endpoint. Its contribution to the prefix sum is therefore one exactly inside the interval and zero elsewhere. Summing intervals preserves this property. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs the number of distinct substrings of every length.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1, distinct length-$L$ substrings are partitioned one per state interval covering $L$. Lemma 2 computes exactly the number of such intervals. $\square$

### Complexity

Suffix-automaton construction and the difference scan take $O(n)$ time for a fixed alphabet. The automaton uses $O(26n)$ space and the difference array uses $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The file name uses `substringdivision`, while the official task is Substring Distribution. The difference array has two spare entries so decrementing at `len[u]+1` is always in bounds, including length $n+1$.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;

const int MX = 200005;                  // up to 2n states
int nxt[MX][26], link_[MX], len_[MX];
int sz, last;

void sa_init() {
    sz = 0; last = 0;
    memset(nxt[0], -1, sizeof(nxt[0]));
    link_[0] = -1; len_[0] = 0; sz++;
}

void sa_extend(int c) {
    int cur = sz++;
    memset(nxt[cur], -1, sizeof(nxt[cur]));
    len_[cur] = len_[last] + 1; link_[cur] = -1;
    int p = last;
    while (p != -1 && nxt[p][c] == -1) { nxt[p][c] = cur; p = link_[p]; }
    if (p == -1) link_[cur] = 0;
    else {
        int q = nxt[p][c];
        if (len_[p] + 1 == len_[q]) link_[cur] = q;
        else {
            int cl = sz++;
            len_[cl] = len_[p] + 1;
            memcpy(nxt[cl], nxt[q], sizeof(nxt[q]));
            link_[cl] = link_[q];
            while (p != -1 && nxt[p][c] == q) { nxt[p][c] = cl; p = link_[p]; }
            link_[q] = link_[cur] = cl;
        }
    }
    last = cur;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string s; cin >> s;
    int n = s.size();

    sa_init();
    for (char ch : s) sa_extend(ch - 'a');

    vector<ll> d(n + 2, 0);             // difference array over lengths
    for (int u = 1; u < sz; u++) {
        d[len_[link_[u]] + 1]++;        // range (len(link), len(u)] gets +1 each length
        d[len_[u] + 1]--;
    }

    string out; out.reserve(7 * n);
    ll run = 0;
    for (int L = 1; L <= n; L++) {
        run += d[L];
        if (L > 1) out += ' ';
        out += to_string(run);
    }
    out += '\n';
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `aaa`, the distinct substrings are `a`, `aa`, and `aaa`. The automaton state intervals cover lengths so that the prefix sums are $1,1,1$. For `ab`, the distinct substrings are `a`, `b`, and `ab`, giving distribution $2,1$.

## Takeaway

When suffix-automaton states contribute length intervals, a difference array converts statewise interval information into answers for every length.

### Related problems

Distinct Substrings sums the lengths of these intervals. Substring Order I traverses automaton paths instead of aggregating state intervals.

