# Line Segment Intersection

- **CSES problem:** 2190
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (linesegmentconstruction.cpp)`](./linesegmentconstruction.cpp)

## Problem

Determine whether each pair of closed line segments has at least one common point.

## Reasoning

For a proper crossing, the endpoints of each segment lie on opposite sides of the supporting line of the other. Using orientation signs, this means

$$
o(A,B,C)o(A,B,D)<0
$$

and symmetrically for segment $CD$ against line $AB$.

This strict test excludes endpoint contact and collinear overlap. Handle those cases explicitly: whenever an orientation is zero, the corresponding point lies on the other segment exactly when both coordinates fall inside its endpoint bounding box. Collinearity plus the bounding box avoids incorrectly accepting a point elsewhere on the infinite line.

## Algorithm

1. Compute the four endpoint orientation signs.
2. Accept if both pairs of signs are strictly opposite.
3. Otherwise, for every zero orientation, test whether that endpoint lies in the closed bounding box of the other segment.
4. Reject if none of these cases applies.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

If both endpoint pairs lie on strict opposite sides, the segments intersect in their interiors.

#### Proof

Along segment $CD$, signed orientation relative to line $AB$ changes sign continuously, so it crosses that line. The symmetric condition ensures this crossing lies within segment $AB$, not merely on its extension. $\square$

### Lemma 2

When an endpoint is collinear with the other segment, it belongs to that segment exactly when it lies in its coordinate bounding box.

#### Proof

A closed segment consists of convex combinations of its endpoints. On its supporting line, these are exactly the points whose coordinates lie between the endpoint coordinates in both axes. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm answers `YES` exactly for intersecting closed segments.

#### Proof

A noncollinear intersection is a proper crossing and is accepted by Lemma 1. Any remaining intersection must include a collinear endpoint or collinear overlap, in which case some endpoint lies on the other segment and Lemma 2 accepts it. Every accepted case supplies an actual common point. $\square$

### Complexity

Each pair is processed in $O(1)$ time and space.

## Implementation

`sgn` normalizes the cross product to $-1,0,1$, so multiplying signs cannot overflow. Bounding checks are inclusive to accept touching endpoints.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
inline int sgn(ll x) { return (x > 0) - (x < 0); }

inline int ori(ll ax, ll ay, ll bx, ll by, ll cx, ll cy) {
    return sgn((bx - ax) * (cy - ay) - (by - ay) * (cx - ax));
}

inline bool onseg(ll ax, ll ay, ll bx, ll by, ll px, ll py) {
    return min(ax, bx) <= px && px <= max(ax, bx) &&
           min(ay, by) <= py && py <= max(ay, by);
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int t; cin >> t;
    string out;
    out.reserve(1 << 20);

    while (t--) {
        ll x1, y1, x2, y2, x3, y3, x4, y4;
        cin >> x1 >> y1 >> x2 >> y2 >> x3 >> y3 >> x4 >> y4;

        int d1 = ori(x1, y1, x2, y2, x3, y3);
        int d2 = ori(x1, y1, x2, y2, x4, y4);
        int d3 = ori(x3, y3, x4, y4, x1, y1);
        int d4 = ori(x3, y3, x4, y4, x2, y2);

        bool hit = false;
        if (d1 * d2 < 0 && d3 * d4 < 0) hit = true;
        else if (d1 == 0 && onseg(x1, y1, x2, y2, x3, y3)) hit = true;
        else if (d2 == 0 && onseg(x1, y1, x2, y2, x4, y4)) hit = true;
        else if (d3 == 0 && onseg(x3, y3, x4, y4, x1, y1)) hit = true;
        else if (d4 == 0 && onseg(x3, y3, x4, y4, x2, y2)) hit = true;

        out += hit ? "YES" : "NO";
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Segments $(0,0)$ to $(4,0)$ and $(2,0)$ to $(6,0)$ have all orientations zero. Endpoint $(2,0)$ lies inside the first segment's bounding box, so their overlap is correctly accepted.

## Takeaway

Robust segment intersection is orientation for the general case plus an explicit collinear-on-segment test for degeneracies.

### Related problems

Point Location Test supplies the orientation predicate. Point in Polygon uses a related boundary test before ray casting.

