# Minimum Euclidean Distance

- **CSES problem:** 2194
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (minimumeuclidiandistance.cpp)`](./minimumeuclidiandistance.cpp)

## Problem

Find the minimum squared Euclidean distance between any two input points.

## Reasoning

Checking all pairs is $O(n^2)$. Sort points by $x$ and sweep left to right while maintaining points whose horizontal distance from the current point has square at most the best distance found.

If current best squared distance is $D$, a better partner must satisfy both $|dx|\le\sqrt D$ and $|dy|\le\sqrt D$. Store active points ordered by $(y,x)$, remove points too far left, and inspect only the active $y$ interval around the current point.

Why is the candidate count bounded? Partition the surrounding rectangle into constant-many cells of side roughly $\sqrt D/2$. Two active points in one cell would be closer than the current best, contradicting its definition before the current insertion. This packing argument yields constant candidates per point and $O(n\log n)$ total time.

## Algorithm

1. Sort points by $x$, then $y$.
2. Maintain an ordered set of prior active points keyed by $(y,x)$ and a left pointer.
3. Remove points whose squared horizontal distance exceeds current best.
4. Query active points with $y$ within `ceil(sqrt(best))` of the current $y$ and test their exact squared distances.
5. Insert the current point and continue.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

No removed point can improve the current best distance.

#### Proof

Its squared horizontal separation alone exceeds the best squared distance. Euclidean squared distance adds a nonnegative vertical term, so it is even larger. $\square$

### Lemma 2

Every prior point capable of improving the best is examined.

#### Proof

Such a point is not removed by Lemma 1. Its squared vertical separation is also below the best, so its $y$ lies inside the queried interval using the ceiling radius. Therefore the set iteration reaches it. $\square$

### Theorem

The final value is the minimum squared distance among all point pairs.

#### Proof

Consider each pair when its later point is processed. If it could improve the then-current best, Lemma 2 examines it and updates the best. If not, ignoring it cannot affect the optimum. Thus no globally closest pair is missed and every stored value is an actual pair distance. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting and ordered-set operations take $O(n\log n)$ time; the packing argument bounds candidate comparisons by $O(n)$. The active set and points use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The algorithm compares squared integer distances and uses square root only to choose a conservative $y$ window. The set key is `(y,x)`, matching range iteration. Duplicate coordinates immediately produce answer zero.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<pair<ll,ll>> p(n);
    for (auto& [x, y] : p) cin >> x >> y;
    sort(p.begin(), p.end());

    ll best = LLONG_MAX;
    set<pair<ll,ll>> act;   // ordered by (y, x)
    int left = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        // integer ceil(sqrt(best)) for window radius
        ll d = (ll)ceil(sqrt((long double)best));
        // shrink window in x
        while (left < i && (p[i].first - p[left].first) * (p[i].first - p[left].first) > best) {
            act.erase({p[left].second, p[left].first});
            left++;
        }
        ll lo = p[i].second - d, hi = p[i].second + d;
        auto it1 = act.lower_bound({lo, LLONG_MIN});
        auto it2 = act.upper_bound({hi, LLONG_MAX});
        for (auto it = it1; it != it2; ++it) {
            ll dx = p[i].first - it->second;
            ll dy = p[i].second - it->first;
            ll dist = dx*dx + dy*dy;
            if (dist < best) best = dist;
        }
        act.insert({p[i].second, p[i].first});
    }

    cout << best << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

If current best squared distance is 25, only active points with $x$ and $y$ differences at most 5 can improve it. A point 6 units left is removed even if its $y$ is equal, since its squared distance is already at least 36.

## Takeaway

Closest-pair sweeps combine geometric exclusion by the current optimum with an ordered active window and a packing bound on local density.

### Related problems

Maximum Manhattan Distances becomes simpler after a coordinate transform. Intersection Points is another sweep line with an ordered structure.

