# Convex Hull

- **CSES problem:** 2195
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (convexhull.cpp)`](./convexhull.cpp)

## Problem

Output every input point lying on the boundary of the convex hull, including points collinear along hull edges.

## Reasoning

Sort points lexicographically. The lower boundary must turn counterclockwise or remain collinear as it moves left to right. If the last two hull points and the new point form a clockwise turn, the middle point lies above the required lower convex boundary and can never belong to it, so pop it.

Using the strict condition `cross<0` is essential: a zero cross product retains collinear boundary points. Repeating the scan in reverse constructs the upper boundary. The final repeated start point is removed.

When all points are collinear, lower and upper walks contain the same interior points. The implementation deduplicates by coordinate while preserving first traversal order, so every boundary input point appears once.

## Algorithm

1. Sort points by $x$, then $y$.
2. Build the lower walk, popping while the newest turn is clockwise.
3. Build the upper walk by scanning back, with the same rule.
4. Remove the repeated closing point and discard later duplicate coordinates while preserving order.
5. Output the resulting boundary points.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After processing a prefix of sorted points, the lower walk is the lower convex boundary of those points and contains all collinear points on its edges.

#### Proof

A clockwise last turn violates convexity and places the middle point strictly above the segment connecting its neighbors, so popping it is necessary. The process repeats until all turns are nonclockwise. A collinear point is retained because it lies on the boundary edge. Standard monotone-chain induction then gives the complete lower boundary. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The reverse scan constructs the complete upper boundary under the same inclusion rule.

#### Proof

Reversing lexicographic direction exchanges upper and lower roles. The identical turn invariant from Lemma 1 therefore produces the upper boundary. $\square$

### Theorem

The output contains exactly every convex-hull boundary input point once.

#### Proof

Lemmas 1 and 2 cover the lower and upper boundaries, whose union is the entire hull boundary. Any repeated coordinate arises from their shared endpoints or the all-collinear overlap; order-preserving deduplication removes only repeated copies, not distinct boundary points. No interior point survives either convex-boundary construction. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting takes $O(n\log n)$ time. Stack construction and deduplication take $O(n\log n)$ with the implemented ordered set. Storage is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The cross product uses `long long` under the official coordinate limits. `lower=k+1` sets the stopping size for upper-hull popping. The final `k--` drops the repeated first point before deduplication.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
struct P { ll x, y; };

ll cross(const P& O, const P& A, const P& B) {
    return (A.x - O.x) * (B.y - O.y) - (A.y - O.y) * (B.x - O.x);
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<P> p(n);
    for (auto& pt : p) cin >> pt.x >> pt.y;
    sort(p.begin(), p.end(), [](const P& a, const P& b){
        return a.x < b.x || (a.x == b.x && a.y < b.y);
    });

    vector<P> h(2 * n);
    int k = 0;

    // lower hull
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        while (k >= 2 && cross(h[k-2], h[k-1], p[i]) < 0) k--;
        h[k++] = p[i];
    }
    // upper hull
    int lower = k + 1;
    for (int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
        while (k >= lower && cross(h[k-2], h[k-1], p[i]) < 0) k--;
        h[k++] = p[i];
    }
    k--;   // drop last (== first)

    // Deduplicate while preserving boundary traversal order. In the all-collinear
    // case, the lower and upper walks contain the same interior points.
    vector<P> hull;
    set<pair<ll,ll>> used;
    for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
        if (used.insert({h[i].x, h[i].y}).second)
            hull.push_back(h[i]);
    }

    string out = to_string(hull.size());
    out += '\n';
    for (auto& pt : hull) { out += to_string(pt.x); out += ' '; out += to_string(pt.y); out += '\n'; }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For rectangle corners plus point $(1,0)$ on its bottom edge, sorted lower-hull processing sees a zero turn along the bottom and retains $(1,0)$. A point strictly inside the rectangle eventually forms a clockwise violation on one of the boundary walks and is removed.

## Takeaway

In monotone-chain hulls, the strictness of the pop inequality decides whether collinear boundary points are excluded or retained.

### Related problems

Point Location Test supplies orientation. Polygon Area can measure the hull polygon after construction.

