# Lines and Queries I

- **CSES problem:** 3429
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (linesqueries1.cpp)`](./linesqueries1.cpp)

## Problem

Process online operations that insert a line $y=ax+b$ and query the maximum value at a coordinate $x$ in a fixed integer domain.

## Reasoning

The lines are not monotone by slope or insertion order, so convex-hull pointer methods do not apply. A Li Chao tree needs only the single-crossing property of two lines.

Each node stores the line better at its interval midpoint. During insertion, swap lines if the newcomer wins there. The displaced line can beat the stored one on at most one side because their difference is linear. Comparing at the left endpoint and midpoint identifies that side.

A coordinate query follows its segment-tree path and evaluates every stored line on it. The insertion invariant guarantees any line that can be optimal at the coordinate was retained somewhere on that path.

## Algorithm

1. Initialize a Li Chao tree over integer domain $[0,100000]$ with negative-infinity lines.
2. Insert each type 1 line using midpoint comparison and one-sided recursion.
3. For a type 2 operation, follow the root-to-leaf path for $x$ and return the maximum evaluated line.

## Correctness

### Lemma

After inserting a line, for every coordinate where it can improve the envelope, either it is stored at the current node or it is recursively retained in the child containing that coordinate.

#### Proof

The midpoint winner stays. Since two lines cross at most once, the loser can win only on one side. The endpoint-midpoint sign comparison selects precisely that possible side; elsewhere it cannot improve the envelope. $\square$

### Theorem

Every query returns the maximum of all previously inserted lines at $x$.

#### Proof

Repeated application of the lemma keeps every potential winner on the path containing $x$. Querying the maximum of all path lines therefore includes a global winner, while every evaluated candidate is an inserted line and cannot exceed the true maximum. $\square$

### Complexity

Every insertion and query takes $O(\log X)$ time for domain size $X=100001$. The tree uses $O(X)$ space.

## Implementation

`Line{0,NEG}` acts as negative infinity. All evaluations use `long long`. The output is buffered because operations may be numerous.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
const ll NEG = LLONG_MIN / 4;
const int X = 100000;
struct Line { ll k, b; ll val(ll x) const { return k * x + b; } };
vector<Line> tree;

void insert_line(int node, int l, int r, Line nw) {
    int mid = (l + r) >> 1;
    bool lef = nw.val(l) > tree[node].val(l);
    bool midb = nw.val(mid) > tree[node].val(mid);
    if (midb) swap(tree[node], nw);
    if (l == r) return;
    if (lef != midb) insert_line(node<<1, l, mid, nw);
    else insert_line(node<<1|1, mid+1, r, nw);
}

ll query(int node, int l, int r, int x) {
    ll res = tree[node].val(x);
    if (l == r) return res;
    int mid = (l + r) >> 1;
    if (x <= mid) return max(res, query(node<<1, l, mid, x));
    else return max(res, query(node<<1|1, mid+1, r, x));
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    tree.assign(4 * (X + 1), Line{0, NEG});

    string out;
    out.reserve(1 << 21);

    while (n--) {
        int type; cin >> type;
        if (type == 1) {
            ll a, b; cin >> a >> b;
            insert_line(1, 0, X, Line{a, b});
        } else {
            int x; cin >> x;
            out += to_string(query(1, 0, X, x));
            out += '\n';
        }
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Insert $y=2x+1$ and $y=-x+10$. At $x=2$, values are 5 and 8, so the query returns 8; at $x=5$, they are 11 and 5, so it returns 11. The Li Chao tree represents their one crossing implicitly.

## Takeaway

Li Chao trees handle arbitrary online line order when the query domain is known, without sorting slopes or computing intersection coordinates.

### Related problems

Lines and Queries II adds finite validity intervals. Line Segments Trace I queries the entire integer domain after batch insertion.

