# Area of Rectangles

- **CSES problem:** 1741
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (areaofrectangles.cpp)`](./areaofrectangles.cpp)

## Problem

Compute the total area covered by the union of many axis-aligned rectangles.

## Reasoning

Sweep from left to right across rectangle vertical edges. Between consecutive event coordinates, the active set of rectangles is unchanged, so the covered vertical length $L$ is constant and contributes area

$$
L\cdot(x_{next}-x_{current}).
$$

Each rectangle adds coverage on $[y_1,y_2)$ at its left edge and removes it at its right edge. Compress all rectangle $y$ endpoints. Segment-tree leaf $i$ represents the elementary interval $[ys_i,ys_{i+1})$, whose geometric length may differ from one.

Each node stores a cover count and covered length. If its cover count is positive, its entire coordinate interval is covered regardless of children. Otherwise its covered length is zero at a leaf or the sum of child lengths internally. Processing all events at one $x$ together ensures no zero-width strip contributes area.

## Algorithm

1. Create add and remove events at each rectangle's left and right edges; collect all $y$ endpoints.
2. Compress endpoints into elementary vertical intervals.
3. Sort events by $x$.
4. Before applying events at coordinate $x$, add `covered_y*(x-prev_x)` to area.
5. Range-add each event's type over its elementary $y$ intervals and recompute covered lengths.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

After processing one event group, the segment-tree root stores the union length of all active rectangles on the $y$ axis.

#### Proof

For any node with positive cover count, at least one active rectangle covers its entire interval, so its full geometric length is correct. With zero count, coverage comes only from descendants; their disjoint union lengths add. Leaves with zero count are uncovered. Induction over the tree proves the root value. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The area added between consecutive event coordinates equals the rectangle-union area in that vertical strip.

#### Proof

No rectangle starts or ends inside the open strip, so the active vertical union is constant. Lemma 1 gives its length $L$; multiplying by strip width gives exactly its area. $\square$

### Theorem

The final accumulated value is the total union area.

#### Proof

Consecutive event coordinates partition all covered area into disjoint vertical strips. Lemma 2 computes each strip exactly, and summing them counts every union point once up to measure-zero boundaries. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting events and coordinates takes $O(n\log n)$ time. Each of $2n$ range updates takes $O(\log n)$, so total time is $O(n\log n)$. The events, coordinates, and segment tree use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

Leaves index gaps between coordinates, so endpoint indices `[yl,yr)` map to leaf range `[yl,yr-1]`. `cov` and area use `long long`. The official input guarantees positive rectangle height, so at least one elementary interval exists.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
struct Edge { int x, yl, yr, type; };

int n;
vector<ll> ys;
vector<int> cnt;
vector<ll> cov;

int LEN;             // number of elementary intervals = ys.size()-1

void build(int node, int l, int r) {
    cnt[node] = 0; cov[node] = 0;
    if (l == r) return;
    int mid = (l + r) >> 1;
    build(node<<1, l, mid);
    build(node<<1|1, mid+1, r);
}

void pull(int node, int l, int r) {
    if (cnt[node] > 0) cov[node] = ys[r+1] - ys[l];
    else if (l == r) cov[node] = 0;
    else cov[node] = cov[node<<1] + cov[node<<1|1];
}

void update(int node, int l, int r, int ql, int qr, int v) {
    if (qr < l || r < ql) return;
    if (ql <= l && r <= qr) { cnt[node] += v; pull(node, l, r); return; }
    int mid = (l + r) >> 1;
    update(node<<1, l, mid, ql, qr, v);
    update(node<<1|1, mid+1, r, ql, qr, v);
    pull(node, l, r);
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n;
    vector<Edge> ev;
    ev.reserve(2 * n);
    ys.reserve(2 * n);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int x1, y1, x2, y2; cin >> x1 >> y1 >> x2 >> y2;
        ev.push_back({x1, y1, y2, +1});
        ev.push_back({x2, y1, y2, -1});
        ys.push_back(y1); ys.push_back(y2);
    }

    sort(ys.begin(), ys.end());
    ys.erase(unique(ys.begin(), ys.end()), ys.end());
    LEN = (int)ys.size() - 1;       // elementary intervals [ys[i], ys[i+1])

    sort(ev.begin(), ev.end(), [](const Edge& a, const Edge& b){ return a.x < b.x; });

    cnt.assign(4 * LEN, 0);
    cov.assign(4 * LEN, 0);
    build(1, 0, LEN - 1);

    ll area = 0, prevx = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)ev.size(); ) {
        int cx = ev[i].x;
        if (i > 0) area += cov[1] * (ll)(cx - prevx);
        while (i < (int)ev.size() && ev[i].x == cx) {
            int yl = (int)(lower_bound(ys.begin(), ys.end(), ev[i].yl) - ys.begin());
            int yr = (int)(lower_bound(ys.begin(), ys.end(), ev[i].yr) - ys.begin());
            // cover elementary intervals [yl, yr-1]
            update(1, 0, LEN - 1, yl, yr - 1, ev[i].type);
            i++;
        }
        prevx = cx;
    }

    cout << area << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

If active rectangles cover vertical intervals `[1,4)` and `[3,6)`, the tree reports union length 5, not their summed length 6. If the next event is 3 units rightward, this slab contributes area 15.

## Takeaway

Rectangle-union area is a sweep of constant-width slabs. The essential segment-tree invariant is covered geometric length under overlapping range cover counts.

### Related problems

Intersection Points sweeps orthogonal segments with active frequencies. Rectangle Cutting concerns partitioning one rectangle rather than union measure.

