# Robot Path

- **CSES problem:** 1742
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (robotpath.cpp)`](./robotpath.cpp)

## Problem

A robot follows axis-aligned movement commands from the origin and stops at the first point it has visited before. Output the total distance traveled before stopping, or the full path length if no revisit occurs.

## Reasoning

Each completed command adds a closed horizontal or vertical segment to the visited path. For the current movement segment, the first revisited point can arise in two ways:

1. It crosses a previously completed perpendicular segment.
2. It overlaps a previously completed collinear segment on the same row or column.

The current starting point is already visited and must not cause an immediate stop. Searches therefore exclude a perpendicular segment at the starting coordinate and treat a collinear interval ending exactly at the start as harmless. Moving back into a previously covered interval beyond the start correctly gives collision distance zero.

For perpendicular intersections, the source builds two offline segment trees of Fenwick trees. The vertical structure is keyed by compressed $x$. A completed vertical interval $[lo,hi]$ is inserted at its $x$: along each segment-tree ancestor, a Fenwick tree indexed by interval lower endpoint stores the maximum upper endpoint. Predicate `has(node,y)` asks whether some stored interval has $lo\le y\le hi$. Guided `first` or `last` descent finds the nearest qualifying coordinate in the movement direction. The horizontal structure is symmetric, keyed by $y$.

For collinear intersections, each occupied row and column stores a map of disjoint merged intervals. `hitR` and `hitL` find the first already covered coordinate ahead, while `add` merges a newly completed interval with every touching or overlapping interval.

All command segments are read first only to precompute the coordinate and lower-endpoint lists required by the nested Fenwick structures. Segments become active strictly in execution order.

## Algorithm

1. Convert commands to endpoint segments and collect coordinates used by vertical and horizontal segments.
2. Prepare and build the segment-tree-of-Fenwick structures with every lower endpoint that may later be inserted.
3. Execute commands in order.
4. For the current segment, query the nearest active perpendicular intersection strictly ahead and the nearest active collinear overlap ahead.
5. If the minimum hit distance is within the command length, output prior completed distance plus that hit distance.
6. Otherwise insert the full segment into both its perpendicular-query structure and its row or column interval union, then continue.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

`has(p,y)` is true exactly when node $p$ contains an active interval covering coordinate $y$.

#### Proof

Intervals are indexed by lower endpoint. The Fenwick prefix through $y$ considers exactly intervals with $lo\le y$, and stores the maximum of their upper endpoints. Such an interval covers $y$ exactly when this maximum is at least $y$. $\square$

### Lemma 2

Guided `first` and `last` return the nearest perpendicular segment intersecting the current movement, if one exists.

#### Proof

The coordinate range is clipped to positions strictly ahead and within the command. Lemma 1 prunes precisely nodes containing no interval that crosses the fixed movement coordinate. Descending left first for increasing motion or right first for decreasing motion returns the smallest or largest qualifying coordinate, hence the nearest intersection in that direction. $\square$

### Lemma 3

The interval maps return the nearest collinear revisited point and maintain exactly the union of completed collinear segments.

#### Proof

`add` merges every existing interval touching or overlapping the new one, leaving a disjoint ordered union with unchanged covered points. The predecessor and successor checks in `hitR` and `hitL` examine exactly the interval containing the start beyond its harmless endpoint, or the next covered interval ahead. Thus the returned coordinate is the first collinear point already visited. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs exactly the distance traveled before the robot first revisits a point.

#### Proof

Before a command, the active structures represent exactly all completed path segments by Lemmas 1 and 3. Every prior segment is perpendicular or collinear to the current one. Lemmas 2 and 3 find the nearest revisit of each kind; their minimum is therefore the first revisit along the command. If it lies within the command, adding its distance to completed length is exact. Otherwise no point of the command was previously visited, so inserting the whole segment preserves the invariant. $\square$

### Complexity

Preparation, insertion, and guided perpendicular searches take $O(\log^2 n)$ per segment, while interval-map operations are amortized $O(\log n)$ plus deletions of intervals that can be merged only a limited number of times. Total time is $O(n\log^2 n)$ and space is $O(n\log n)$.

## Implementation

The maximum-Fenwick trees require offline preparation because each node compresses its own possible lower endpoints. `INF` represents no collision. Strict `upper_bound` or `lower_bound` ranges exclude the current coordinate for perpendicular searches. The custom hash protects large signed row and column keys in unordered maps.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

using ll = long long;
const ll INF = (1LL << 62);

struct BIT {
    vector<ll> bit;

    BIT() {}
    BIT(int n) : bit(n + 1, -INF) {}

    void upd(int i, ll v) {
        for (int n = bit.size(); i < n; i += i & -i) bit[i] = max(bit[i], v);
    }

    ll qry(int i) const {
        ll r = -INF;
        for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i) r = max(r, bit[i]);
        return r;
    }
};

struct Seg {
    int m, n;
    vector<ll> c;
    vector<vector<ll>> ys;
    vector<BIT> fw;

    Seg() {}

    Seg(vector<ll> _c) : c(_c) {
        m = c.size();
        n = 1;
        while (n < m) n <<= 1;
        ys.assign(2 * n, {});
    }

    void prep(ll x, ll lo) {
        int id = lower_bound(c.begin(), c.end(), x) - c.begin();
        for (int p = id + n; p; p >>= 1) ys[p].push_back(lo);
    }

    void build() {
        fw.resize(2 * n);
        for (int i = 1; i < 2 * n; i++) {
            auto &v = ys[i];
            sort(v.begin(), v.end());
            v.erase(unique(v.begin(), v.end()), v.end());
            fw[i] = BIT(v.size());
        }
    }

    void add(ll x, ll lo, ll hi) {
        int id = lower_bound(c.begin(), c.end(), x) - c.begin();
        for (int p = id + n; p; p >>= 1) {
            int q = lower_bound(ys[p].begin(), ys[p].end(), lo) - ys[p].begin() + 1;
            fw[p].upd(q, hi);
        }
    }

    bool has(int p, ll y) const {
        if (ys[p].empty()) return false;
        int q = upper_bound(ys[p].begin(), ys[p].end(), y) - ys[p].begin();
        if (!q) return false;
        return fw[p].qry(q) >= y;
    }

    int first(int p, int l, int r, int ql, int qr, ll y) const {
        if (r < ql || qr < l || !has(p, y)) return -1;
        if (l == r) return l < m ? l : -1;
        int md = (l + r) >> 1;
        int z = first(p << 1, l, md, ql, qr, y);
        if (z != -1) return z;
        return first(p << 1 | 1, md + 1, r, ql, qr, y);
    }

    int last(int p, int l, int r, int ql, int qr, ll y) const {
        if (r < ql || qr < l || !has(p, y)) return -1;
        if (l == r) return l < m ? l : -1;
        int md = (l + r) >> 1;
        int z = last(p << 1 | 1, md + 1, r, ql, qr, y);
        if (z != -1) return z;
        return last(p << 1, l, md, ql, qr, y);
    }

    int first(int l, int r, ll y) const {
        if (!m || l > r) return -1;
        l = max(l, 0), r = min(r, m - 1);
        if (l > r) return -1;
        return first(1, 0, n - 1, l, r, y);
    }

    int last(int l, int r, ll y) const {
        if (!m || l > r) return -1;
        l = max(l, 0), r = min(r, m - 1);
        if (l > r) return -1;
        return last(1, 0, n - 1, l, r, y);
    }
};

struct Line {
    map<ll, ll> mp;

    ll hitR(ll x, ll r) const {
        auto it = mp.upper_bound(x);
        if (it != mp.begin()) {
            auto p = prev(it);
            if (p->second > x) return x;
        }
        if (it != mp.end() && it->first <= r) return it->first;
        return INF;
    }

    ll hitL(ll x, ll l) const {
        auto it = mp.lower_bound(x);
        if (it != mp.begin()) {
            auto p = prev(it);
            if (p->first < x && p->second >= x) return x;
            if (p->second < x && p->second >= l) return p->second;
        }
        return INF;
    }

    void add(ll l, ll r) {
        auto it = mp.lower_bound(l);

        if (it != mp.begin()) {
            auto p = prev(it);
            if (p->second >= l) {
                l = min(l, p->first);
                r = max(r, p->second);
                it = mp.erase(p);
            }
        }

        while (it != mp.end() && it->first <= r) {
            r = max(r, it->second);
            it = mp.erase(it);
        }

        mp[l] = r;
    }
};

struct Hsh {
    size_t operator()(ll x) const {
        x += 0x9e3779b97f4a7c15;
        x = (x ^ (x >> 30)) * 0xbf58476d1ce4e5b9;
        x = (x ^ (x >> 27)) * 0x94d049bb133111eb;
        return x ^ (x >> 31);
    }
};

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n;
    cin >> n;

    vector<char> d(n);
    vector<ll> a(n), x0(n), y0(n), x1(n), y1(n);
    vector<ll> xs, ys;

    ll x = 0, y = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> d[i] >> a[i];

        x0[i] = x;
        y0[i] = y;

        if (d[i] == 'U') y += a[i];
        else if (d[i] == 'D') y -= a[i];
        else if (d[i] == 'R') x += a[i];
        else x -= a[i];

        x1[i] = x;
        y1[i] = y;

        if (x0[i] == x1[i]) xs.push_back(x0[i]);
        else ys.push_back(y0[i]);
    }

    sort(xs.begin(), xs.end());
    xs.erase(unique(xs.begin(), xs.end()), xs.end());

    sort(ys.begin(), ys.end());
    ys.erase(unique(ys.begin(), ys.end()), ys.end());

    Seg V(xs), H(ys);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (x0[i] == x1[i]) V.prep(x0[i], min(y0[i], y1[i]));
        else H.prep(y0[i], min(x0[i], x1[i]));
    }

    V.build();
    H.build();

    unordered_map<ll, Line, Hsh> hh, vv;
    hh.reserve(2 * n + 1);
    vv.reserve(2 * n + 1);

    x = y = 0;
    ll ans = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        ll nx = x, ny = y;

        if (d[i] == 'U') ny += a[i];
        else if (d[i] == 'D') ny -= a[i];
        else if (d[i] == 'R') nx += a[i];
        else nx -= a[i];

        ll best = INF;

        if (y == ny) {
            if (nx > x) {
                int l = upper_bound(xs.begin(), xs.end(), x) - xs.begin();
                int r = upper_bound(xs.begin(), xs.end(), nx) - xs.begin() - 1;

                int id = V.first(l, r, y);
                if (id != -1) best = min(best, xs[id] - x);

                auto it = hh.find(y);
                if (it != hh.end()) {
                    ll p = it->second.hitR(x, nx);
                    if (p != INF) best = min(best, p - x);
                }
            } else {
                int l = lower_bound(xs.begin(), xs.end(), nx) - xs.begin();
                int r = lower_bound(xs.begin(), xs.end(), x) - xs.begin() - 1;

                int id = V.last(l, r, y);
                if (id != -1) best = min(best, x - xs[id]);

                auto it = hh.find(y);
                if (it != hh.end()) {
                    ll p = it->second.hitL(x, nx);
                    if (p != INF) best = min(best, x - p);
                }
            }
        } else {
            if (ny > y) {
                int l = upper_bound(ys.begin(), ys.end(), y) - ys.begin();
                int r = upper_bound(ys.begin(), ys.end(), ny) - ys.begin() - 1;

                int id = H.first(l, r, x);
                if (id != -1) best = min(best, ys[id] - y);

                auto it = vv.find(x);
                if (it != vv.end()) {
                    ll p = it->second.hitR(y, ny);
                    if (p != INF) best = min(best, p - y);
                }
            } else {
                int l = lower_bound(ys.begin(), ys.end(), ny) - ys.begin();
                int r = lower_bound(ys.begin(), ys.end(), y) - ys.begin() - 1;

                int id = H.last(l, r, x);
                if (id != -1) best = min(best, y - ys[id]);

                auto it = vv.find(x);
                if (it != vv.end()) {
                    ll p = it->second.hitL(y, ny);
                    if (p != INF) best = min(best, y - p);
                }
            }
        }

        if (best <= a[i]) {
            cout << ans + best << '\n';
            return 0;
        }

        if (y == ny) {
            ll l = min(x, nx), r = max(x, nx);
            hh[y].add(l, r);
            H.add(y, l, r);
        } else {
            ll l = min(y, ny), r = max(y, ny);
            vv[x].add(l, r);
            V.add(x, l, r);
        }

        ans += a[i];
        x = nx;
        y = ny;
    }

    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Suppose the robot has already traversed a vertical segment at $x=3$ covering $y=0$ through 4, then begins moving right from $(0,2)$ for length 5. The vertical structure finds coordinate 3 as the first crossing, so the robot stops after 3 additional units. A farther crossing at $x=4$ is irrelevant.

## Takeaway

First self-intersection of an orthogonal path separates into perpendicular stabbing queries and collinear interval-union queries. Directional nearest-hit search matters more than merely detecting an intersection.

### Related problems

Intersection Points counts all perpendicular crossings offline. Line Segment Intersection supplies the geometric classification, while Robot Path adds temporal activation and nearest-hit order.

