# Corner Subgrid Count

- **Problem:** [CSES 2137](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2137)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (cornercount.cpp)](./cornercount.cpp)

## Problem

Count axis-aligned subgrids of height and width at least two whose four corner cells are black.

## Reasoning

Choose the top and bottom rows first. Let $c$ be the number of columns black in both rows. Any two of those shared columns determine one rectangle, so this row pair contributes

$$\binom c2=\frac{c(c-1)}2.$$

The remaining operation is intersection cardinality for every row pair. Store each row as a bitset. Bitwise AND finds shared black columns in $n/64$ word operations, and population count gives $c$.

## Algorithm

Convert every row into an $n$-bit bitset. For each unordered pair of rows, compute the population count of their bitwise intersection and add $c(c-1)/2$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** For fixed distinct rows, the formula $\binom c2$ counts exactly the beautiful subgrids using those rows.

**Proof.** A valid subgrid needs two distinct columns black in both rows. Choosing any two shared columns produces one unique subgrid, and every such subgrid determines that pair.

**Theorem.** The algorithm counts every beautiful subgrid exactly once.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 counts all subgrids for each row pair. Every subgrid has a unique top-bottom row pair, so summing over unordered pairs neither omits nor duplicates one.

### Complexity

There are $O(n^2)$ row pairs and each bitset intersection scans $O(n/64)$ words. Time is $O(n^3/64)$ and space is $O(n^2/64)$ words.

## Implementation

The fixed bitset size matches the maximum $n=3000$. The answer uses `long long` because the number of rectangles can be on the order of $n^4$.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2,popcnt")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

const int N = 3000;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n;
    cin >> n;

    vector<bitset<N>> r(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        string s; cin >> s;
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) if (s[j] == '1') r[i].set(j);
    }

    ll ans = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
            ll c = (r[i] & r[j]).count();      // columns black in both rows
            ans += c * (c - 1) / 2;            // choose 2 shared columns
        }

    cout << ans << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

If two rows have black cells in columns $1,3,4$, then $c=3$ and they contribute $\binom32=3$ subgrids, using column pairs $(1,3)$, $(1,4)$, and $(3,4)$.

## Takeaway

Count rectangles by fixing two parallel sides. Shared valid coordinates determine the other sides, and bitsets accelerate all pairwise intersections.

### Related problems

Corner Subgrid Check, Intersection Points, Border Subgrid Count I.

