# Cut and Paste

- **Problem:** [CSES 2072](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2072)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (cutandpaste.cpp)](./cutandpaste.cpp)

## Problem

Repeatedly cut substring $[a,b]$ from a string and append it to the end. Output the final string.

## Reasoning

Array storage makes one operation linear because the middle suffix must shift. An implicit treap stores characters in in-order sequence. Nodes have random heap priorities and subtree sizes; position is derived from left-subtree size instead of an explicit key.

`split(t,k)` separates the first $k$ sequence elements from the rest. `merge(a,b)` concatenates two sequences while preserving priority heap order. Expected tree height is logarithmic, so isolating three pieces and reassembling them is logarithmic.

## Algorithm

Build the treap by merging characters in order. For operation $[a,b]$, split before $a$ into $A,T$, split $T$ after length $b-a+1$ into $B,C$, then set the root to $A+C+B$. Finally output an in-order traversal.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** `split(t,k)` returns sequences containing exactly the first $k$ elements and the remaining elements.

**Proof.** Comparing $k$ with left-subtree size decides whether the boundary lies left or right of the root. The recursive split adjusts the one affected child, preserving in-order order. Induction on subtree size proves the partition.

**Lemma 2.** `merge(a,b)` returns the concatenation of sequences $a$ and $b$.

**Proof.** The larger-priority root is chosen. Recursively merging only its boundary child preserves that every element of $a$ precedes every element of $b$, while maintaining heap order.

**Theorem.** Every operation and the final output are correct.

**Proof.** By Lemma 1, $A,B,C$ are exactly the prefix, cut substring, and suffix. Lemma 2 makes $A+C+B$, precisely the requested operation. Induction over operations proves the final in-order sequence.

### Complexity

Each operation takes expected $O(\log n)$ time. Construction is expected $O(n\log n)$ and output is $O(n)$. Space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

Node zero is a null sentinel with size zero. Every structural change calls `upd` to restore subtree size. Final traversal is iterative to avoid recursion depth dependence during output.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

const int MX = 200005;
int lc[MX], rc[MX], sz[MX];
unsigned pr[MX];
char val[MX];
int cnt = 0, root = 0;                          // node 0 = null sentinel

mt19937 rng(998244353);

int mk(char c) {
    int t = ++cnt;
    lc[t] = rc[t] = 0; sz[t] = 1; pr[t] = rng(); val[t] = c;
    return t;
}
inline void upd(int t) { if (t) sz[t] = sz[lc[t]] + sz[rc[t]] + 1; }

void split(int t, int k, int &a, int &b) {      // first k nodes -> a, rest -> b
    if (!t) { a = b = 0; return; }
    if (sz[lc[t]] < k) {
        a = t;
        split(rc[t], k - sz[lc[t]] - 1, rc[t], b);
        upd(a);
    } else {
        b = t;
        split(lc[t], k, a, lc[t]);
        upd(b);
    }
}
int merge(int a, int b) {
    if (!a || !b) return a | b;
    if (pr[a] > pr[b]) { rc[a] = merge(rc[a], b); upd(a); return a; }
    else { lc[b] = merge(a, lc[b]); upd(b); return b; }
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    string str; cin >> str;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) root = merge(root, mk(str[i]));

    while (m--) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        int A, T, B, C;
        split(root, a - 1, A, T);               // A = [1,a-1]
        split(T, b - a + 1, B, C);              // B = [a,b], C = [b+1,end]
        root = merge(merge(A, C), B);           // A + C + B
    }

    string out; out.reserve(n);
    vector<int> st;                             // iterative in-order, avoid deep recursion
    int cur = root;
    while (cur || !st.empty()) {
        while (cur) { st.pb(cur); cur = lc[cur]; }
        cur = st.back(); st.pop_back();
        out += val[cur];
        cur = rc[cur];
    }
    cout << out << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

For `abcdef` and interval $[2,4]$, splitting gives $A=$ `a`, $B=$ `bcd`, and $C=$ `ef`. Reassembly $A+C+B$ produces `aefbcd`.

## Takeaway

Implicit treaps turn positional sequence edits into split and merge operations. Express the edit as a rearrangement of contiguous pieces.

### Related problems

Substring Reversals, Reversals and Sums, List Removals.

