# Distinct Routes II

- **Problem:** [CSES 2130](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2130)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (distinctroutes2.cpp)](./distinctroutes2.cpp)

## Problem

Find $k$ edge-disjoint directed routes from vertex $1$ to vertex $n$ whose total number of edges is minimum, or report impossibility.

## Reasoning

Give every original edge capacity one and cost one. A value-$k$ integral flow then uses no edge more than once, and its cost is the total length of its path decomposition. The task is exactly minimum-cost flow of value $k$.

Residual reverse edges allow an augmentation to reroute previously selected paths. After the optimum flow is found, saturated original edges carry one unit. Flow conservation guarantees they decompose into $k$ source-to-sink routes, possibly plus cycles. Positive original costs make an optimum cycle-free, so repeatedly following used outgoing edges extracts the routes.

## Algorithm

Run successive shortest augmenting paths on the unit-capacity, unit-cost network until $k$ units are sent. If impossible, print $-1$. Otherwise, repeat $k$ times: start at vertex $1$, follow a saturated original forward edge, mark it consumed by restoring capacity one, and stop at $n$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Integral value-$k$ flows correspond to $k$ edge-disjoint routes, with flow cost equal to total route length after cycles are removed.

**Proof.** Unit capacities give edge disjointness. Flow decomposition yields source-to-sink paths and cycles. Removing a cycle preserves value and strictly lowers cost, so a minimum flow has none.

**Lemma 2.** Successive shortest residual augmentations produce a minimum-cost value-$k$ flow.

**Proof.** The residual network encodes every possible addition and cancellation. Choosing a cheapest augmenting path gives the least marginal cost; a cheaper resulting flow would imply a cheaper residual change from the previous optimum.

**Lemma 3.** The extraction loop outputs every unit of the final flow exactly once.

**Proof.** At each internal vertex, used-flow conservation balances incoming and outgoing units. Starting from an unconsumed source unit therefore always continues to the sink. Restoring each traversed forward capacity removes precisely that unit from later extraction.

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs $k$ edge-disjoint routes of minimum total length, or correctly reports none.

**Proof.** Lemmas 1 and 2 establish optimal flow equivalence; Lemma 3 constructs the required routes from it.

### Complexity

There are $k$ shortest-path augmentations. With SPFA, worst-case time is $O(knm)$ and space is $O(n+m)$.

## Implementation

Even edge IDs are original forward edges and odd IDs are residual reverses. During extraction, only saturated even edges are eligible. Restoring their capacity prevents reuse by later routes.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const ll INF = 1e18;

int n, m, k;
struct Edge { int to, cap; ll cost; int nxt; };
vector<Edge> ed;
vi hd;

void ae(int u, int v, int cap, ll cost) {       // add edge + residual
    ed.pb({v, cap, cost, (int)hd[u]}); hd[u] = ed.size() - 1;
    ed.pb({u, 0, -cost, (int)hd[v]}); hd[v] = ed.size() - 1;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> m >> k;
    hd.assign(n + 1, -1);
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        ae(a, b, 1, 1);                          // teleporter: cap 1, cost 1
    }

    int S = 1, T = n;
    ll cost = 0; int flow = 0;
    vi dist(n + 1), inq(n + 1), pe(n + 1);

    while (flow < k) {
        fill(dist.begin(), dist.end(), INF);
        fill(inq.begin(), inq.end(), 0);
        dist[S] = 0;
        deque<int> q; q.pb(S); inq[S] = 1;
        while (!q.empty()) {                     // SPFA: cheapest residual path
            int u = q.front(); q.pop_front(); inq[u] = 0;
            for (int e = hd[u]; e != -1; e = ed[e].nxt) {
                if (ed[e].cap > 0 && dist[u] + ed[e].cost < dist[ed[e].to]) {
                    dist[ed[e].to] = dist[u] + ed[e].cost;
                    pe[ed[e].to] = e;
                    if (!inq[ed[e].to]) { inq[ed[e].to] = 1; q.pb(ed[e].to); }
                }
            }
        }
        if (dist[T] == INF) break;

        int push = k - flow;
        for (int v = T; v != S; v = ed[pe[v] ^ 1].to) push = min(push, ed[pe[v]].cap);
        for (int v = T; v != S; v = ed[pe[v] ^ 1].to) {
            ed[pe[v]].cap -= push;
            ed[pe[v] ^ 1].cap += push;
        }
        flow += push;
        cost += (ll)push * dist[T];
    }

    if (flow < k) { cout << -1 << "\n"; return 0; }

    // decompose unit flow into k routes: follow saturated forward edges (cap now 0)
    string out = to_string(cost) + "\n";
    for (int r = 0; r < k; r++) {
        vector<int> path = {1};
        int u = 1;
        while (u != n) {
            for (int e = hd[u]; e != -1; e = ed[e].nxt) {
                if (!(e & 1) && ed[e].cap == 0) {     // even id = real forward edge, used
                    ed[e].cap = 1;                    // consume so next route won't reuse
                    u = ed[e].to;
                    path.pb(u);
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        out += to_string(path.size()) + "\n";
        for (int i = 0; i < (int)path.size(); i++) {
            out += to_string(path[i]);
            out += (i + 1 < (int)path.size()) ? ' ' : '\n';
        }
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

For edges $1\to2$, $2\to4$, $1\to3$, $3\to4$, and $2\to3$, two edge-disjoint routes of total length four are $1\to2\to4$ and $1\to3\to4$.

## Takeaway

Minimum-total-length disjoint paths are a direct min-cost flow model: capacity enforces disjointness and unit edge cost measures length.

### Related problems

Distinct Routes, Parcel Delivery, Task Assignment.

