# Eulerian Subgraphs

- **Problem:** [CSES 2078](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2078)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (eulariansubgraphs.cpp)](./eulariansubgraphs.cpp)

## Problem

Count edge subsets of an undirected graph for which every vertex has even degree, modulo $10^9+7$.

## Reasoning

Represent a chosen edge set by a binary vector $x\in\mathbb F_2^m$. The even-degree condition is

$$Bx=0,$$

where $B$ is the vertex-edge incidence matrix over $\mathbb F_2$. Thus valid subgraphs form the cycle space, the kernel of $B$.

For a graph with $n$ vertices and $c$ connected components, the incidence matrix has rank $n-c$. A spanning forest supplies $n-c$ independent columns, and within each component the sum of all vertex rows is zero, proving no larger rank is possible. Rank-nullity gives cycle-space dimension

$$m-(n-c)=m-n+c.$$

A vector space of dimension $d$ over $\mathbb F_2$ has $2^d$ elements.

## Algorithm

Use DSU to count connected components $c$. Compute exponent $m-n+c$ and multiply by two that many times modulo $10^9+7$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Eulerian edge subsets are exactly vectors in the kernel of the incidence matrix over $\mathbb F_2$.

**Proof.** The row equation for a vertex is the parity of selected incident edges. It equals zero exactly when that degree is even.

**Lemma 2.** The kernel dimension is $m-n+c$.

**Proof.** In each connected component with $v$ vertices, a spanning tree gives $v-1$ independent incidence columns, while the sum of its vertex rows is zero, so rank is exactly $v-1$. Summing components gives rank $n-c$, and rank-nullity gives the claim.

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the number of Eulerian subgraphs.

**Proof.** By Lemmas 1 and 2, valid subsets form a binary vector space of dimension $m-n+c$, which contains exactly $2^{m-n+c}$ vectors.

### Complexity

DSU processing takes $O((n+m)\alpha(n))$ time and $O(n)$ space. The exponent loop is $O(m)$.

## Implementation

The empty edge set is included, corresponding to the zero vector. Isolated vertices increase both $n$ and $c$ by one, leaving the exponent unchanged as required.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int par[100005], sz[100005];

int find(int x) { while (par[x] != x) x = par[x] = par[par[x]]; return x; }
void uni(int a, int b) {
    a = find(a); b = find(b);
    if (a == b) return;
    if (sz[a] < sz[b]) swap(a, b);
    par[b] = a; sz[a] += sz[b];
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) { par[i] = i; sz[i] = 1; }

    for (int e = 0; e < m; e++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        uni(a, b);
    }

    int c = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) if (find(i) == i) c++;

    ll pw = 1;                                  // 2^(m-n+c)
    int ex = m - n + c;
    for (int i = 0; i < ex; i++) pw = pw * 2 % MOD;

    cout << pw << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

A triangle has $n=3,m=3,c=1$, so the dimension is one and there are two Eulerian subgraphs: the empty set and all three cycle edges.

## Takeaway

Parity constraints on selected graph edges are linear equations over $\mathbb F_2$. The solution count follows from the dimension of the cycle space.

### Related problems

Even Outdegree Edges, Necessary Roads, Graph Girth.

