# Hamming Distance

- **Problem:** [CSES 2136](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2136)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (hammeringdistance.cpp)](./hammeringdistance.cpp)

## Problem

Find the minimum Hamming distance between any two of $n$ binary strings of length $k$.

## Reasoning

The Hamming distance between bit vectors $a$ and $b$ is the number of one bits in $a\oplus b$: XOR marks exactly the differing positions. Since $k\le30$, an entire string fits in a 32-bit unsigned integer, and hardware population count evaluates one pair in constant time.

The quadratic pair loop is intended by the constraints: compressing each comparison to XOR plus `popcount` makes all $\binom n2$ comparisons practical. Distance zero is an absolute lower bound, so the search may stop as soon as duplicate strings are found.

## Algorithm

Pack every string into an unsigned integer by shifting left and adding each input bit. For every unordered pair, compute `popcount(a[i] ^ a[j])` and minimize the answer. Stop early at zero.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** `popcount(a ^ b)` equals the Hamming distance between packed strings $a$ and $b$.

**Proof.** XOR bit $p$ is one exactly when the two original bits at $p$ differ. Population count sums these indicators.

**Theorem.** The algorithm returns the minimum Hamming distance.

**Proof.** The nested loops inspect every unordered pair exactly once. Lemma 1 computes each pair's distance exactly, so their minimum is the required answer. Early termination is safe because no distance is negative.

### Complexity

Packing costs $O(nk)$. Pair comparisons cost $O(n^2)$ hardware operations, and storage is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

Bits are read as characters, so whitespace-separated and contiguous input behave identically under formatted extraction. The `popcnt` compilation target maps population count to the relevant machine instruction.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2,popcnt")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, k;
    cin >> n >> k;

    vector<unsigned> a(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        unsigned v = 0;
        for (int j = 0; j < k; j++) {          // pack bits MSB-first
            char ch; cin >> ch;
            v = (v << 1) | (ch - '0');
        }
        a[i] = v;
    }

    int best = INT_MAX;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        unsigned ai = a[i];
        for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
            int d = __builtin_popcount(ai ^ a[j]);
            if (d < best) best = d;
        }
        if (best == 0) break;                   // can't beat identical strings
    }

    cout << best << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

Strings `0011`, `1010`, and `1111` pack to integers $3,10,15$. XOR values for the pairs have population counts $2,2,1$, so the minimum distance is one.

## Takeaway

Small fixed-width binary objects should be packed into machine words. Symmetric difference becomes XOR, and cardinality becomes population count.

### Related problems

Counting Bits, One Bit Positions, XOR Subarray.

