# Monster Game I

- **Problem:** [CSES 2084](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2084)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (monstergame1.cpp)](./monstergame1.cpp)

## Problem

Process monsters in order. The cost of defeating monster $i$ depends on its strength $s_i$ and the factor chosen by the last defeated monster. Minimize the cost through monster $n$.

## Reasoning

Let $dp[i]$ be the minimum cost after monster $i$. If $j<i$ is the previous chosen state, then

$$dp[i]=\min_{0\le j<i}\bigl(dp[j]+f_j s_i\bigr),$$

where the artificial state $j=0$ has $dp[0]=0$ and $f_0=x$.

Each previous state is a line $y=f_jq+dp[j]$, queried at $q=s_i$. The first version guarantees monotone factors and strengths. Lines therefore arrive in slope order and query points arrive in order. Maintain the lower envelope as a deque. A middle line is removed when the intersection with its predecessor is no earlier than the intersection of its successor; it can never become uniquely minimum.

## Algorithm

Insert the initial line $(x,0)$. For monsters in order, query the hull at $s_i$ to obtain $dp[i]$, then insert line $(f_i,dp[i])$. Remove redundant lines from the back and advance the query head while the next line is no worse.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Every inserted line represents exactly one legal previous state.

**Proof.** At query $s_i$, line $(f_j,dp[j])$ evaluates to $dp[j]+f_js_i$, the recurrence cost using $j$ before $i$.

**Lemma 2.** Hull maintenance preserves the minimum value for every future query.

**Proof.** With monotone slopes, the redundancy cross-product detects when the middle of three lines has no interval on which it is strictly best. With monotone query points, once the next front line is no worse, the old front cannot become better again.

**Theorem.** The algorithm returns the minimum final cost.

**Proof.** Lemma 2 makes each hull query the exact minimum over all earlier lines. Lemma 1 identifies that minimum with the DP recurrence, so induction over $i$ proves every $dp[i]$.

### Complexity

Each line enters and leaves the hull at most once. Time is $O(n)$ and space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The active hull begins at index `head`, avoiding costly front erasure. The redundancy test uses `long double` products to avoid overflow while preserving the required intersection ordering.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

struct Line { ll k, b; ll eval(ll x) { return k * x + b; } };   // y = k x + b

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; ll x;
    cin >> n >> x;
    vi s(n + 1), fa(n + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> s[i];
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> fa[i];

    auto bad = [](const Line &a, const Line &b, const Line &c) {     // b redundant on envelope
        return (long double)(c.b - a.b) * (a.k - b.k)
             <= (long double)(b.b - a.b) * (a.k - c.k);
    };

    vector<Line> hull;
    int head = 0;
    auto add = [&](Line ln) {                   // slopes non-increasing
        while ((int)hull.size() - head >= 2 &&
               bad(hull[hull.size() - 2], hull[hull.size() - 1], ln))
            hull.pop_back();
        hull.pb(ln);
    };
    auto query = [&](ll xq) {                    // queries non-decreasing
        while ((int)hull.size() - head >= 2 &&
               hull[head].eval(xq) >= hull[head + 1].eval(xq))
            head++;
        return hull[head].eval(xq);
    };

    add({x, 0});                                // implicit kill-0: pay s_i * x
    ll dp = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        dp = query(s[i]);                       // dp[i] = min_{j<i} dp[j] + s_i f_j
        add({fa[i], dp});                       // monster i as a future "previous kill"
    }

    cout << dp << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

With initial factor $10$, strengths $(2,5)$, and factors $(4,1)$, the first cost is $20$. For the second monster, the initial line costs $50$ and the first monster's line costs $20+4\cdot5=40$, so $dp[2]=40$.

## Takeaway

DP transitions of the form $dp[i]=\min_j(m_jx_i+b_j)$ are line-container problems. Monotone slopes and queries permit the simplest linear convex hull trick.

### Related problems

Monster Game II, Subarray Squares, Line Container.

