# Monster Game II

- **Problem:** [CSES 2085](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2085)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (monstergame2.cpp)](./monstergame2.cpp)

## Problem

Compute the same monster DP as in Monster Game I, but without monotonicity guarantees on line slopes or query strengths.

## Reasoning

The recurrence remains

$$dp[i]=\min_{0\le j<i}\bigl(dp[j]+f_js_i\bigr).$$

Each earlier state is still a line, but a deque hull is invalid when insertions and queries arrive in arbitrary order. A Li Chao tree stores one line at every segment of the fixed integer domain. At a node midpoint, keep the line that is better there. Two lines cross at most once, so the displaced line can only beat the stored line on one side; recurse only into that child.

A query follows the root-to-leaf path for its coordinate and takes the minimum of all stored lines encountered.

## Algorithm

Build a Li Chao tree on $[1,10^6]$. Insert the artificial line $(x,0)$. For each monster, query at $s_i$ to get $dp[i]$, then insert $(f_i,dp[i])$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** After inserting a line into a Li Chao node interval, the minimum of lines stored along every coordinate's search path is unchanged or improved by that line where appropriate.

**Proof.** The better line at the midpoint is retained. Since two lines cross once, the displaced line can be better only in the half indicated by the endpoint comparison, where it is recursively inserted. It cannot affect the other half's minimum.

**Lemma 2.** A query returns the minimum value among all inserted lines at its coordinate.

**Proof.** Repeated application of Lemma 1 ensures every inserted line is represented on the query path wherever it can win. Taking the minimum of stored evaluations therefore equals the global minimum.

**Theorem.** The algorithm computes the optimum game cost.

**Proof.** Each inserted line represents one recurrence candidate. Lemma 2 evaluates their exact minimum, so induction proves all DP states.

### Complexity

The coordinate domain has height $O(\log 10^6)$. Time is $O(n\log 10^6)$ and the static tree uses $O(10^6)$ space.

## Implementation

`has[node]` distinguishes an empty tree node from a legitimate zero line. Evaluations use `long long`. At insertion, swapping at the midpoint keeps the currently better line in place and recurses with the worse one.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

const int V = 1000000;                           // query domain x in [1, V]
const ll INF = 4e18;

struct Line { ll k, b; ll eval(ll x) { return k * x + b; } };

Line tr[4 * V + 5];                             // Li Chao node lines, init to +inf
bool has[4 * V + 5];

void insert(int nd, int lo, int hi, Line ln) {  // min Li Chao
    int mid = (lo + hi) >> 1;
    if (!has[nd]) { tr[nd] = ln; has[nd] = true; return; }
    bool lf = ln.eval(lo) < tr[nd].eval(lo);
    bool md = ln.eval(mid) < tr[nd].eval(mid);
    if (md) swap(tr[nd], ln);                    // ln now the worse line at mid
    if (lo == hi) return;
    if (lf != md) insert(nd << 1, lo, mid, ln);          // crossing on left half
    else          insert(nd << 1 | 1, mid + 1, hi, ln);  // crossing on right half
}
ll query(int nd, int lo, int hi, int x) {
    if (!has[nd]) return INF;
    ll r = tr[nd].eval(x);
    if (lo == hi) return r;
    int mid = (lo + hi) >> 1;
    if (x <= mid) return min(r, query(nd << 1, lo, mid, x));
    else          return min(r, query(nd << 1 | 1, mid + 1, hi, x));
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; ll x;
    cin >> n >> x;
    vi s(n + 1), fa(n + 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> s[i];
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> fa[i];

    insert(1, 1, V, {x, 0});                     // implicit kill-0: pay s_i * x
    ll dp = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        dp = query(1, 1, V, s[i]);               // dp[i] = min_{j<i} dp[j] + s_i f_j
        insert(1, 1, V, {fa[i], dp});            // monster i as a future "previous kill"
    }

    cout << dp << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

Suppose current lines are $y=8x+0$ and $y=2x+20$. At midpoint $x=5$, their values tie. For large $x$, the slope-two line wins; for small $x$, the slope-eight line may win. Li Chao keeps one at the node and sends the other only toward the side where it can improve an answer.

## Takeaway

When convex hull trick monotonicity disappears but query coordinates lie in a known range, a Li Chao tree retains logarithmic line insertion and minimum queries.

### Related problems

Monster Game I, Subarray Squares, Line Container.

