# Necessary Cities

- **Problem:** [CSES 2077](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2077)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (necessarycities.cpp)](./necessarycities.cpp)

## Problem

Find every articulation vertex of an undirected graph: a city whose removal increases the number of connected components.

## Reasoning

Root a DFS forest. Let `num[u]` be the discovery time and `low[u]` the smallest discovery time reachable from the subtree of $u$ using tree edges followed by at most one back edge.

For a non-root vertex $u$, a child $v$ becomes separated from $u$'s ancestors after deleting $u$ exactly when

$$low[v]\ge num[u].$$

If the inequality fails, the child's subtree has a back edge reaching strictly above $u$. DFS roots need a separate rule: a root is an articulation vertex exactly when it has at least two DFS-tree children.

## Algorithm

Run iterative DFS from every unvisited vertex. Maintain explicit stacks for vertices, next-neighbor indices, and parents. On finishing a child, propagate its low-link value to the parent and apply the non-root articulation test. Count each DFS root's tree children and apply the root rule.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** On completion of $u$, `low[u]` is the minimum discovery time reachable from its DFS subtree without using the parent tree edge.

**Proof.** Initialization includes $u$. Scanned back edges contribute their endpoint times, and each completed child contributes every route available through its subtree. These are exactly the permitted routes.

**Lemma 2.** A non-root $u$ is an articulation vertex exactly when some child $v$ satisfies $low[v]\ge num[u]$.

**Proof.** Under the inequality, the child's subtree has no edge reaching an ancestor of $u$, so deleting $u$ isolates it. If every child has a route above $u$, all child subtrees remain connected through those ancestor routes after deletion.

**Lemma 3.** A DFS root is an articulation vertex exactly when it has at least two tree children.

**Proof.** Different root-child subtrees have no edges between them, or DFS would have discovered one through the other. Removing the root separates them precisely when at least two exist.

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs exactly all necessary cities.

**Proof.** Lemmas 2 and 3 cover every non-root and root respectively, using the correct low values from Lemma 1.

### Complexity

Every vertex and edge is processed a constant number of times. Time is $O(n+m)$ and space is $O(n+m)$.

## Implementation

The explicit stacks reproduce recursive entry and exit events. The input guarantee of no parallel edges lets the city implementation skip the parent vertex directly; edge-ID tracking would be required otherwise.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

const int N = 100005;
vector<int> adj[N];
int num[N], low[N], idx;
bool art[N];

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    for (int e = 0; e < m; e++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        adj[a].pb(b); adj[b].pb(a);
    }

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) num[i] = -1;

    vector<int> cstk, pstk, par;                // node, child-ptr, parent stacks
    for (int s0 = 1; s0 <= n; s0++) {
        if (num[s0] != -1) continue;
        int rootChildren = 0;
        cstk.pb(s0); pstk.pb(0); par.pb(0);
        while (!cstk.empty()) {
            int u = cstk.back();
            int &pi = pstk.back();
            int p = par.back();
            if (pi == 0) { num[u] = low[u] = idx++; }
            if (pi < (int)adj[u].size()) {
                int v = adj[u][pi++];
                if (v == p) continue;                   // skip parent (single edge guaranteed)
                if (num[v] == -1) {
                    if (u == s0) rootChildren++;        // count root's tree children
                    cstk.pb(v); pstk.pb(0); par.pb(u);
                } else {
                    low[u] = min(low[u], num[v]);       // back-edge
                }
            } else {                                    // finished u
                cstk.pop_back(); pstk.pop_back(); par.pop_back();
                if (p != 0) {                           // u has a parent
                    low[p] = min(low[p], low[u]);
                    if (p != s0 && low[u] >= num[p]) art[p] = true;  // non-root cut
                }
            }
        }
        if (rootChildren >= 2) art[s0] = true;          // root cut rule
    }

    vector<int> res;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) if (art[i]) res.pb(i);

    string out = to_string(res.size()) + "\n";
    for (int v : res) { out += to_string(v); out += '\n'; }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

For edges $1-2$, $2-3$, $2-4$, and $3-4$, the subtree containing $3,4$ has no route above $2$, so $2$ is an articulation vertex. Neither $3$ nor $4$ is necessary because their cycle provides an alternate route.

## Takeaway

Low-link values answer whether a DFS subtree can escape above its parent. The strictness of the comparison distinguishes bridge tests from articulation tests.

### Related problems

Necessary Roads, Forbidden Cities, Strongly Connected Edges.

