# Necessary Roads

- **Problem:** [CSES 2076](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2076)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (necessaryroads.cpp)](./necessaryroads.cpp)

## Problem

Find every bridge of an undirected graph: an edge whose removal increases the number of connected components.

## Reasoning

In a DFS tree, consider the tree edge from parent $p$ to child $u$. The edge is avoidable exactly when the subtree of $u$ has a back edge to $p$ or an ancestor of $p$. With discovery and low-link times, this becomes

$$low[u]\le num[p].$$

Therefore the tree edge is a bridge exactly when $low[u]>num[p]$. Non-tree edges cannot be bridges because the DFS-tree path between their endpoints already supplies an alternate route.

## Algorithm

Run iterative DFS over every component. Store a unique edge ID in each adjacency entry and in each DFS frame. When a vertex finishes, propagate its low value to its parent. If the child's low value is greater than the parent's discovery time, output the parent edge.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** On DFS exit from $u$, `low[u]` is the smallest discovery time reachable from $u$'s subtree without using its parent edge.

**Proof.** The value combines $u$ itself, every scanned back edge, and the already-computed low values of all DFS children, which enumerate exactly such routes.

**Lemma 2.** Tree edge $(p,u)$ is a bridge exactly when $low[u]>num[p]$.

**Proof.** If the inequality holds, no vertex in $u$'s subtree reaches $p$ or above without the parent edge, so removing it separates the subtree. Otherwise a back edge plus tree paths forms a cycle containing $(p,u)$, providing an alternate route.

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs exactly all necessary roads.

**Proof.** Lemma 2 classifies every tree edge, and every non-tree edge already lies on a cycle. Thus no bridge is missed and no non-bridge is output.

### Complexity

Time is $O(n+m)$ and space is $O(n+m)$.

## Implementation

Skipping by edge ID rather than parent vertex correctly handles parallel roads: only the exact DFS edge is ignored, while a parallel edge becomes a valid back edge. Stored original endpoints are used for output.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

const int N = 100005;
vector<ii> adj[N];                              // (neighbor, edge id)
int num[N], low[N], idx;
int pe[N];                                      // parent edge id, to skip once
vii bridges;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    vector<ii> edges(m);
    for (int e = 0; e < m; e++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        adj[a].pb({b, e}); adj[b].pb({a, e});
        edges[e] = {a, b};
    }

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) num[i] = -1;

    vector<int> cstk, pstk, est;                // node, child-ptr, parent-edge stacks
    for (int s0 = 1; s0 <= n; s0++) {
        if (num[s0] != -1) continue;
        cstk.pb(s0); pstk.pb(0); est.pb(-1);
        while (!cstk.empty()) {
            int u = cstk.back();
            int &pi = pstk.back();
            if (pi == 0) { num[u] = low[u] = idx++; }
            if (pi < (int)adj[u].size()) {
                auto [v, eid] = adj[u][pi++];
                if (eid == est.back()) continue;        // skip the edge we came in on
                if (num[v] == -1) {
                    cstk.pb(v); pstk.pb(0); est.pb(eid);
                } else {
                    low[u] = min(low[u], num[v]);       // back-edge
                }
            } else {                                    // finished u
                cstk.pop_back(); pstk.pop_back();
                int eid = est.back(); est.pop_back();
                if (!cstk.empty()) {
                    int p = cstk.back();
                    low[p] = min(low[p], low[u]);
                    if (low[u] > num[p]) bridges.pb(edges[eid]);  // tree edge is a bridge
                }
            }
        }
    }

    string out = to_string(bridges.size()) + "\n";
    for (auto &e : bridges) { out += to_string(e.f); out += ' '; out += to_string(e.s); out += '\n'; }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

In triangle $1-2-3-1$ with an extra edge $3-4$, the triangle edges all have back-edge alternatives. For child $4$, `low[4]=num[4]>num[3]`, so only $3-4$ is reported.

## Takeaway

An undirected DFS tree edge is a bridge precisely when its child subtree cannot reach the parent or anything above it. Track parent edge IDs when multiedges are possible.

### Related problems

Necessary Cities, Network Renovation, Strongly Connected Edges.

