# New Roads Queries

- **Problem:** [CSES 2101](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2101)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (newroadsqueries.cpp)](./newroadsqueries.cpp)

## Problem

Roads are added to an initially empty undirected graph, one per day. For each pair of cities, report the first day on which they become connected, or $-1$ if this never happens.

## Reasoning

Whenever an edge joins two previously separate DSU components on day $d$, create a new internal node labeled $d$ and make the two component trees its children. This is a Kruskal reconstruction forest, except the ordering key is time rather than weight.

The leaves are original cities. An internal node represents the union that first combined all leaves in its subtree. Therefore, for connected cities $a$ and $b$, their lowest common ancestor is exactly the union event that first placed them in one component. Its label is the required day.

## Algorithm

Process roads chronologically with DSU. Ignore edges already internal to one component. For every genuine merge, create a reconstruction node with the current day and attach the two component roots. After all roads, build binary-lifting tables on the reconstruction forest. Answer a query with the day label of the LCA, after first checking final DSU connectivity.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** After every day, the leaves below each current reconstruction root are exactly one DSU component.

**Proof.** Initially each root contains one city. A genuine road merge creates a parent whose leaves are the union of exactly the two components joined that day. Redundant roads change neither structure.

**Lemma 2.** For connected cities $a,b$, their reconstruction-tree LCA was created on the first day they became connected.

**Proof.** Before that union event the cities lie below different component roots. The event creates the first node containing both. Every later merge creates only ancestors of that node, so it is their lowest common ancestor.

**Theorem.** Every query answer is correct.

**Proof.** Different final DSU roots mean the cities never connect. Otherwise Lemma 2 identifies the first connection day as the LCA label returned by the algorithm.

### Complexity

Construction costs $O(m\alpha(n))$. Lifting preprocessing costs $O(n\log n)$ because at most $2n-1$ reconstruction nodes exist. Each query takes $O(\log n)$ time, and space is $O(n\log n)$.

## Implementation

The `root` array is sized for internal nodes up to $2n-1$. Node zero is explicitly given a lifting row as a sentinel. Original leaves carry day zero, so a city queried with itself correctly returns zero.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int par[400005];                                // DSU over reconstruction-tree nodes
int find(int x) { while (par[x] != x) x = par[x] = par[par[x]]; return x; }

int LOG;
vector<int> up[400005];                         // binary lifting (per-node ancestor table)
int dep[400005], day_[400005], top[400005];     // node creation day; current tree-root rep
vector<int> children[400005];

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m, q;
    cin >> n >> m >> q;

    int tot = n;                                // cities are nodes 1..n; internal nodes after
    // vector<int> root(n + 1);                 // OOB: nn can reach 2n-1 -> heap corruption
    vector<int> root(2 * n + 5);                // internal nodes go up to 2n-1
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) { par[i] = i; root[i] = i; day_[i] = 0; }
    for (int d = 1; d <= m; d++) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        int ra = find(a), rb = find(b);
        if (ra == rb) continue;                 // already connected; this day irrelevant
        int rta = root[ra], rtb = root[rb];     // current tree-roots of the two components
        int nn = ++tot;                         // new internal node for this union
        day_[nn] = d;
        par[nn] = nn;
        children[nn].pb(rta); children[nn].pb(rtb);
        par[ra] = nn; par[rb] = nn;
        root[nn] = nn;
    }

    // build parent/up tables via DFS over each reconstruction tree
    LOG = 1; while ((1 << LOG) <= tot) LOG++;
    // for (int i = 1; i <= tot; i++) up[i].assign(LOG, 0);   // left up[0] unsized -> up[0][..] OOB in doubling
    for (int i = 0; i <= tot; i++) up[i].assign(LOG, 0);      // node 0 = self-ancestor sentinel

    vector<int> par0(tot + 1, 0);
    vector<char> vis(tot + 1, 0);
    for (int u = 1; u <= tot; u++)
        for (int c : children[u]) par0[c] = u;

    // iterative DFS to set depth and up[][0]
    for (int r = 1; r <= tot; r++) {
        if (par0[r] != 0 || vis[r]) continue;   // r is a forest root
        vector<int> st = {r};
        dep[r] = 0; up[r][0] = 0; vis[r] = 1;
        for (int qi = 0; qi < (int)st.size(); qi++) {
            int u = st[qi];
            for (int c : children[u]) {
                dep[c] = dep[u] + 1; up[c][0] = u; vis[c] = 1;
                st.pb(c);
            }
        }
    }
    for (int j = 1; j < LOG; j++)
        for (int i = 1; i <= tot; i++)
            up[i][j] = up[ up[i][j-1] ][j-1];

    auto lca = [&](int a, int b) -> int {
        if (find(a) != find(b)) return -1;      // different reconstruction trees -> never
        if (dep[a] < dep[b]) swap(a, b);
        int diff = dep[a] - dep[b];
        for (int j = 0; j < LOG; j++) if (diff >> j & 1) a = up[a][j];
        if (a == b) return a;
        for (int j = LOG - 1; j >= 0; j--)
            if (up[a][j] != up[b][j]) { a = up[a][j]; b = up[b][j]; }
        return up[a][0];
    };

    string out;
    while (q--) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        int l = lca(a, b);
        out += to_string(l < 0 ? -1 : day_[l]);
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

Road $1-2$ arrives on day $1$, road $3-4$ on day $2$, and road $2-3$ on day $3$. The first two merges create separate internal nodes; day $3$ creates their common parent. Thus query $(1,4)$ returns $3$, while $(1,2)$ returns $1$.

## Takeaway

When components only merge and queries ask when two items first became related, record the merge history as a reconstruction tree and turn time queries into LCA queries.

### Related problems

Dynamic Connectivity, Network Breakdown, MST Edge Cost.

