# Parcel Delivery

- **Problem:** [CSES 2121](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2121)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (parceldiscovery.cpp)](./parceldiscovery.cpp)

## Problem

Send exactly $k$ parcels from city $1$ to city $n$ through directed routes with capacities and per-parcel costs, minimizing total cost.

## Reasoning

This is minimum-cost flow. A flow unit represents one parcel. Route capacity limits total parcels, and linear edge cost makes flow cost equal delivery cost.

After sending some flow, residual reverse edges with negative cost permit canceling earlier routing decisions. Therefore each next augmentation must use a shortest path in the full residual graph, not merely the original network. Successive shortest augmenting paths preserve minimum cost for each achieved flow value.

## Algorithm

Build forward edges with input capacity and cost, plus zero-capacity reverse edges of negated cost. Repeatedly find a shortest residual path from $1$ to $n$ with SPFA, push its bottleneck up to the remaining demand, and add path cost times pushed flow. Print $-1$ if no path exists before $k$ units are sent.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Feasible integral flows of value $k$ correspond to feasible parcel routings of the same total cost.

**Proof.** Decomposing an integral flow into source-to-sink paths routes individual parcels within every capacity. Conversely, parcel paths induce such a flow. Edge flow times unit cost sums identically in both models.

**Lemma 2.** Every augmentation preserves minimum cost for the new flow value.

**Proof.** The residual network represents all additions and cancellations relative to the current optimum. A cheaper flow of the new value would differ by an augmenting path together with residual cycles of negative total improvement, contradicting the shortest chosen path and optimality of the prior flow.

**Theorem.** The algorithm prints the minimum delivery cost, or $-1$ exactly when delivery is impossible.

**Proof.** Lemma 2 proves optimality when value $k$ is reached, and Lemma 1 transfers it to parcel routing. If no residual source-to-sink path exists, max-flow theory shows no greater feasible flow exists.

### Complexity

At most $k$ augmentations occur. With SPFA's $O(nm)$ worst-case shortest path bound, time is $O(knm)$ and space is $O(n+m)$.

## Implementation

Forward and reverse edges occupy consecutive indices, so XOR with one finds the mate. One augmentation may push several parcels when the path bottleneck permits it. Total cost uses `long long`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const ll INF = 1e18;

int n, m, k;
struct Edge { int to, cap; ll cost; int nxt; };
vector<Edge> ed;
vi hd;                                          // head_[u] -> first edge id (long for vi)

void ae(int u, int v, int cap, ll cost) {       // add edge + residual
    ed.pb({v, cap, cost, (int)hd[u]}); hd[u] = ed.size() - 1;
    ed.pb({u, 0, -cost, (int)hd[v]}); hd[v] = ed.size() - 1;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> m >> k;
    hd.assign(n + 1, -1);
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        int a, b, r; ll c;
        cin >> a >> b >> r >> c;
        ae(a, b, r, c);
    }

    int S = 1, T = n;
    ll cost = 0; int flow = 0;
    vi dist(n + 1), inq(n + 1), pe(n + 1);      // pe = parent edge id

    while (flow < k) {
        fill(dist.begin(), dist.end(), INF);
        fill(inq.begin(), inq.end(), 0);
        dist[S] = 0;
        deque<int> q; q.pb(S); inq[S] = 1;
        while (!q.empty()) {                     // SPFA: cheapest residual path
            int u = q.front(); q.pop_front(); inq[u] = 0;
            for (int e = hd[u]; e != -1; e = ed[e].nxt) {
                if (ed[e].cap > 0 && dist[u] + ed[e].cost < dist[ed[e].to]) {
                    dist[ed[e].to] = dist[u] + ed[e].cost;
                    pe[ed[e].to] = e;
                    if (!inq[ed[e].to]) { inq[ed[e].to] = 1; q.pb(ed[e].to); }
                }
            }
        }
        if (dist[T] == INF) break;               // no augmenting path

        int push = k - flow;                     // bottleneck clamped to remaining need
        for (int v = T; v != S; v = ed[pe[v] ^ 1].to) push = min(push, ed[pe[v]].cap);
        for (int v = T; v != S; v = ed[pe[v] ^ 1].to) {
            ed[pe[v]].cap -= push;
            ed[pe[v] ^ 1].cap += push;
        }
        flow += push;
        cost += (ll)push * dist[T];
    }

    cout << (flow == k ? cost : -1) << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

If route $1\to2\to4$ costs $4$ per parcel with capacity one and $1\to3\to4$ costs $6$ with capacity two, sending three parcels costs $1\cdot4+2\cdot6=16$.

## Takeaway

Capacitated routing with linear per-unit costs is min-cost flow. Residual reverse edges are essential because they let later augmentations revise earlier routes.

### Related problems

Task Assignment, Distinct Routes II, Download Speed.

