# Signal Processing

- **Problem:** [CSES 2110](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2110)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (signalprocessing.cpp)](./signalprocessing.cpp)

## Problem

Compute all alignments of two integer signals, where each output is the sum of products of overlapping entries.

## Reasoning

An alignment score is a cross-correlation: one signal moves while the other keeps its orientation. Polynomial multiplication naturally computes sums indexed by $i+j$, not $i-j$. Reverse the second signal. Then coefficient $s$ of the convolution is

$$C_s=\sum_i a_i b_{m-1-(s-i)},$$

which is exactly the overlap score for one relative shift. As $s$ ranges from $0$ to $n+m-2$, it covers every partial and full alignment in order.

## Algorithm

Reverse the second signal, pad both arrays to a power of two at least $n+m-1$, transform with FFT, multiply pointwise, inverse transform, and round the first $n+m-1$ coefficients.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Each convolution coefficient equals the score of its corresponding signal alignment.

**Proof.** A product $a_i b_j$ contributes to coefficient $s$ exactly when $i+(m-1-j)=s$, which is precisely the index relation for entries overlapping at that shift.

**Lemma 2.** The computed transform recovers the linear convolution.

**Proof.** Pointwise multiplication in the Fourier domain corresponds to convolution. Padding beyond degree $n+m-2$ prevents cyclic aliasing, so inverse FFT recovers every ordinary coefficient.

**Theorem.** The printed sequence contains all alignment scores in the required order.

**Proof.** Lemma 2 computes all coefficients, and Lemma 1 maps coefficient indices bijectively to shifts.

### Complexity

For $N$ the next power of two above $n+m-1$, time is $O(N\log N)$ and space is $O(N)$.

## Implementation

The second input is stored at reversed indices before transformation. Output includes all $n+m-1$ partial overlaps. Integer coefficients are recovered with `llround`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

typedef complex<double> cd;
const double PI = acos(-1.0);

void fft(vector<cd> &a, bool inv) {
    int n = a.size();
    for (int i = 1, j = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int bit = n >> 1;
        for (; j & bit; bit >>= 1) j ^= bit;
        j ^= bit;
        if (i < j) swap(a[i], a[j]);
    }
    for (int len = 2; len <= n; len <<= 1) {
        double ang = 2 * PI / len * (inv ? -1 : 1);
        cd wl(cos(ang), sin(ang));
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i += len) {
            cd w(1);
            for (int k = 0; k < len / 2; k++) {
                cd u = a[i + k], v = a[i + k + len / 2] * w;
                a[i + k] = u + v;
                a[i + k + len / 2] = u - v;
                w *= wl;
            }
        }
    }
    if (inv) for (cd &x : a) x /= n;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    vector<ll> a(n), b(m);
    for (auto &v : a) cin >> v;
    for (auto &v : b) cin >> v;

    int need = n + m - 1;
    int sz = 1; while (sz < need) sz <<= 1;
    vector<cd> fa(sz, 0), fb(sz, 0);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) fa[i] = (double)a[i];
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) fb[m - 1 - i] = (double)b[i];   // reversed mask

    fft(fa, false); fft(fb, false);
    for (int i = 0; i < sz; i++) fa[i] *= fb[i];
    fft(fa, true);

    string out;
    for (int s = 0; s < need; s++) {
        ll v = llround(fa[s].real());
        out += to_string(v);
        out += ' ';
    }
    out += '\n';
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

For $a=(1,2)$ and $b=(3,4)$, reverse $b$ to $(4,3)$. Their convolution is $(4,11,6)$, representing the three alignments: $1\cdot4$, $1\cdot3+2\cdot4$, and $2\cdot3$.

## Takeaway

Convolution handles sums over equal index sums; correlation handles equal index differences. Reversing one sequence is the bridge between them.

### Related problems

Apples and Bananas, One Bit Positions, String Matching.

