# Subarray Squares

- **Problem:** [CSES 2086](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2086)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (subarraysquares.cpp)](./subarraysquares.cpp)

## Problem

Partition an array into exactly $K$ nonempty contiguous subarrays, minimizing the sum of the square of each subarray sum.

## Reasoning

Let $P_i=\sum_{t=1}^i a_t$ and define

$$dp_k[i]=\text{minimum cost to partition the first }i\text{ values into }k\text{ parts}.$$

If the final part begins after $j$,

$$dp_k[i]=\min_{j<i}\left(dp_{k-1}[j]+(P_i-P_j)^2\right).$$

Expanding the square gives

$$dp_k[i]=P_i^2+\min_j\left((-2P_j)P_i+dp_{k-1}[j]+P_j^2\right).$$

Each split point is a line with slope $-2P_j$ and intercept $dp_{k-1}[j]+P_j^2$, queried at $x=P_i$. Nonnegative array values make prefix sums nondecreasing, so slopes are inserted monotonically and query points are monotone. A deque-style convex hull supports amortized constant time per transition.

## Algorithm

Initialize $dp_1[i]=P_i^2$. For each layer $k=2,\ldots,K$, scan $i$ from $k$ to $n$. Before querying $i$, insert the newly legal split $j=i-1$. Query the lower hull at $P_i$ and add $P_i^2$. Keep only the previous and current DP layers.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The DP recurrence gives the optimum for every state.

**Proof.** Every valid partition has one unique last split $j$, and its cost is an optimal $(k-1)$-part prefix plus the squared sum of the last part. Trying every legal $j$ covers all partitions.

**Lemma 2.** A hull query at $P_i$ returns the minimum transition term over every legal $j$.

**Proof.** The line built from $j$ evaluates to $-2P_jP_i+dp_{k-1}[j]+P_j^2$, exactly the nonconstant transition expression. The redundancy test removes a line only when its intersection order proves it cannot be minimal for any future monotone query. Advancing the head discards a line only after the next line is no worse at the current and all later query points.

**Theorem.** The algorithm returns the minimum cost for exactly $K$ parts.

**Proof.** Lemma 2 evaluates every recurrence minimum exactly. Induction over DP layers using Lemma 1 proves the stored states, including $dp_K[n]$, are optimal.

### Complexity

Every line is inserted once and removed at most once per layer. Time is $O(Kn)$ and space is $O(n)$ beyond prefix sums and the hull.

## Implementation

The split $j=i-1$ is inserted before querying $i$, ensuring the final part may contain one element while no empty part is admitted. Cross-products in the redundancy check use `long double` to avoid overflowing 64-bit multiplication.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

struct Line { ll k, b; ll eval(ll x) { return k * x + b; } };   // y = k x + b

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, K;
    cin >> n >> K;
    vi P(n + 1, 0);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) { ll v; cin >> v; P[i] = P[i - 1] + v; }

    auto bad = [](const Line &a, const Line &b, const Line &c) {     // b redundant
        return (long double)(c.b - a.b) * (a.k - b.k)
             <= (long double)(b.b - a.b) * (a.k - c.k);
    };

    const ll INF = 4e18;
    vector<ll> prev(n + 1, INF), cur(n + 1, INF);
    prev[0] = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) prev[i] = P[i] * P[i];   // k=1: one block [1..i]

    vector<Line> hull;
    for (int k = 2; k <= K; k++) {
        hull.clear();
        int head = 0;
        auto add = [&](Line ln) {               // slopes -2P_j inserted descending
            while ((int)hull.size() - head >= 2 &&
                   bad(hull[hull.size() - 2], hull[hull.size() - 1], ln))
                hull.pop_back();
            hull.pb(ln);
        };
        auto query = [&](ll xq) {                // queries P_i ascending
            while ((int)hull.size() - head >= 2 &&
                   hull[head].eval(xq) >= hull[head + 1].eval(xq))
                head++;
            return hull[head].eval(xq);
        };

        fill(cur.begin(), cur.end(), INF);
        // j must be >= k-1 (need k-1 parts before), and dp_{k-1}[j] finite
        for (int i = k; i <= n; i++) {
            int j = i - 1;                       // newly available split point for this i
            if (prev[j] < INF) add({-2 * P[j], prev[j] + P[j] * P[j]});
            cur[i] = query(P[i]) + P[i] * P[i];  // dp_k[i] = min_j prev[j] + (P_i-P_j)^2
        }
        swap(prev, cur);
    }

    cout << prev[n] << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

For $(1,2,3)$ and $K=2$, possible splits cost $1^2+5^2=26$ or $3^2+3^2=18$. In the second layer, the line for $j=2$ evaluates to the smaller transition at $P_3=6$, so the algorithm returns $18$.

## Takeaway

When a quadratic partition cost expands into a term depending only on $i$, a term depending only on $j$, and a product of the two, rewrite DP transitions as line queries.

### Related problems

Monster Game I, Monster Game II, Houses and Schools.

