# Substring Reversals

- **Problem:** [CSES 2073](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2073)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (substringreversals.cpp)](./substringreversals.cpp)

## Problem

Apply many substring reversals to a string and output the result.

## Reasoning

Use an implicit treap to isolate any position interval with two splits. Reversing every pointer inside that interval would still be linear. Instead, attach a lazy reversal flag to its root. Applying the flag swaps the root's children and toggles the flags of both children; postponing deeper work preserves the logical reversed sequence.

Before a split, merge, or traversal descends through a node, `push` materializes its pending swap one level downward. This maintains the invariant that in-order traversal, after lazy propagation, equals the represented sequence.

## Algorithm

Build one treap node per character. For reversal $[a,b]$, split into $A,B,C$, toggle `rev[B]`, and merge $A+B+C$. At the end, perform in-order traversal while pushing lazy flags.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Toggling `rev` at a subtree root represents reversal of that subtree's sequence.

**Proof.** Reversal exchanges the reversed right sequence, root, and reversed left sequence. Swapping children and toggling both child flags encodes exactly this transformation. XOR correctly combines repeated reversals.

**Lemma 2.** Split and merge preserve represented sequences under lazy flags.

**Proof.** Each function calls `push` before inspecting children, so its structural reasoning uses the current logical order. Standard implicit-treap split and merge then preserve the requested partition or concatenation.

**Theorem.** The output equals the string after all reversals.

**Proof.** Splits isolate exactly $[a,b]$; Lemma 1 reverses it and Lemma 2 reassembles unchanged surrounding pieces. Induction over operations and pushed in-order traversal prove the result.

### Complexity

Each reversal takes expected $O(\log n)$ time. Output takes $O(n)$ and storage is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

`push` must run before using child sizes in recursive descent. The lazy flag is toggled with XOR, since two reversals cancel. Subtree sizes do not change under reversal.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

const int MX = 200005;
int lc[MX], rc[MX], sz[MX];
unsigned pr[MX];
char val[MX];
bool rev[MX];                                   // lazy reversal flag
int cnt = 0, root = 0;                           // node 0 = null sentinel

mt19937 rng(998244353);

int mk(char c) {
    int t = ++cnt;
    lc[t] = rc[t] = 0; sz[t] = 1; pr[t] = rng(); val[t] = c; rev[t] = false;
    return t;
}
inline void upd(int t) { if (t) sz[t] = sz[lc[t]] + sz[rc[t]] + 1; }
inline void push(int t) {                        // apply pending reversal to children
    if (t && rev[t]) {
        swap(lc[t], rc[t]);
        if (lc[t]) rev[lc[t]] ^= 1;
        if (rc[t]) rev[rc[t]] ^= 1;
        rev[t] = false;
    }
}

void split(int t, int k, int &a, int &b) {       // first k nodes -> a, rest -> b
    if (!t) { a = b = 0; return; }
    push(t);
    if (sz[lc[t]] < k) {
        a = t;
        split(rc[t], k - sz[lc[t]] - 1, rc[t], b);
        upd(a);
    } else {
        b = t;
        split(lc[t], k, a, lc[t]);
        upd(b);
    }
}
int merge(int a, int b) {
    if (!a || !b) return a | b;
    push(a); push(b);
    if (pr[a] > pr[b]) { rc[a] = merge(rc[a], b); upd(a); return a; }
    else { lc[b] = merge(a, lc[b]); upd(b); return b; }
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    string str; cin >> str;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) root = merge(root, mk(str[i]));

    while (m--) {
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        int A, T, B, C;
        split(root, a - 1, A, T);                // A = [1,a-1]
        split(T, b - a + 1, B, C);               // B = [a,b], C = [b+1,end]
        rev[B] ^= 1;                             // lazily reverse B
        root = merge(merge(A, B), C);            // A + B + C
    }

    string out; out.reserve(n);
    vector<int> st;                              // iterative in-order with push-down
    int cur = root;
    while (cur || !st.empty()) {
        while (cur) { push(cur); st.pb(cur); cur = lc[cur]; }
        cur = st.back(); st.pop_back();
        out += val[cur];
        cur = rc[cur];
    }
    cout << out << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

Starting from `abcdef`, reverse $[2,5]$ to obtain `aedcbf`. The middle treap is isolated, one lazy bit is toggled, and no character node is individually moved at update time.

## Takeaway

For range reversals in a mutable sequence, combine implicit split-merge trees with a lazy flag that swaps children.

### Related problems

Cut and Paste, Reversals and Sums, Palindrome Queries.

