# Third Permutation

- **Source:** [CSES 3422, Third Permutation](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3422/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (thirdpermutation.cpp)`](./thirdpermutation.cpp)

## Problem

Two permutations $a$ and $b$ of length $n$ satisfy $a_i\ne b_i$ at every position. Construct a third permutation $c$ such that

$$
c_i\ne a_i
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
c_i\ne b_i
$$

for every position $i$, or print `IMPOSSIBLE`.

## Reasoning

Use permutation $a$ as a coordinate system. Let `pos[x]` be the position of value $x$ in $a$, and define

$$
s(i)=\operatorname{pos}(b_i).
$$

Because $b$ is a permutation, $s$ is a permutation of the indices. Because $a_i\ne b_i$, it has no fixed points.

Suppose we construct another index permutation $t$ satisfying

$$
t(i)\ne i
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
t(i)\ne s(i).
$$

Then setting $c_i=a_{t(i)}$ solves the original problem. The first inequality avoids $a_i$; the second avoids $a_{s(i)}=b_i$. Since $t$ is a permutation, so is $c$.

Now decompose $s$ into directed cycles.

For a cycle of length at least 3, choose $t=s^2$ on that cycle. Moving two positions forward is neither staying in place nor moving one position forward, so both forbidden values are avoided.

A 2-cycle $(x,y)$ is the exceptional case: $s^2$ is the identity. If there are at least two 2-cycles, arrange them cyclically and map the first endpoint of each cycle to the first endpoint of the next, and likewise for the second endpoints. Each image belongs to another cycle, so it is neither the vertex itself nor its partner.

If exactly one 2-cycle exists, then for $n>2$ at least one cycle has length at least 3. The implementation splices the two-cycle into that larger cycle, creating one index permutation that avoids all forbidden edges. When $n=2$, the only two values at each position are both forbidden, so no solution exists.

## Algorithm

1. Build `pos` from permutation $a$, then set `s[i] = pos[b[i]]`.
2. If $n=2$, print `IMPOSSIBLE`.
3. Decompose permutation $s$ into cycles.
4. For every cycle of length at least 3, initially assign each vertex to the vertex two steps ahead.
5. Collect all 2-cycles.
   - If there are at least two, cyclically map corresponding endpoints to the next 2-cycle.
   - If there is exactly one, splice its endpoints into the last longer cycle using the assignments in the implementation.
6. Print `a[ans[i]]` for every position $i$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

For every cycle of $s$ with length at least 3, assigning each vertex to the vertex two steps ahead defines a permutation on that cycle and avoids both forbidden images.

#### Proof

Rotation by two positions is a bijection on a cycle. For cycle length at least 3, a two-step rotation is not the zero-step identity and not the one-step map $s$. Hence `ans[i]` differs from both $i$ and $s(i)$ for every vertex in the cycle. $\square$

### Lemma 2

When there are at least two 2-cycles, the cyclic endpoint mapping is a bijection that avoids both forbidden images on all of them.

#### Proof

Write the 2-cycles as $(x_i,y_i)$ for $i$ modulo $z$, where $z\ge2$. The construction maps $x_i\mapsto x_{i+1}$ and $y_i\mapsto y_{i+1}$. These two cyclic shifts are bijections over disjoint endpoint sets. Each image lies in a different 2-cycle, so it equals neither the original vertex nor its partner under $s$. $\square$

### Lemma 3

When exactly one 2-cycle $(x,y)$ is spliced into a longer cycle $(c_0,c_1,\ldots,c_{m-1})$, the resulting assignments are bijective and avoid identity and $s$.

#### Proof

The implementation assigns

$$
x\mapsto c_0,\quad y\mapsto c_1,
$$

$$
c_i\mapsto c_{i+2}\quad(0\le i\le m-3),
$$

and

$$
c_{m-2}\mapsto x,\quad c_{m-1}\mapsto y.
$$

Every vertex in the combined set appears exactly once as an image, so the map is bijective. The two-cycle vertices map outside their cycle, avoiding themselves and each other. For $c_i$ with $i\le m-3$, the image is two steps ahead and is neither $c_i$ nor $s(c_i)=c_{i+1}$. The final two cycle vertices map outside the longer cycle, again avoiding both forbidden images. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm prints a valid third permutation whenever one exists, and rejects exactly the case $n=2$.

#### Proof

For $n=2$, $a_i$ and $b_i$ are the two distinct available values at each position, leaving no valid value for $c_i$.

For $n>2$, the fixed-point-free permutation $s$ consists only of cycles of length at least 2. Lemma 1 handles all longer cycles. Lemma 2 handles multiple 2-cycles, while Lemma 3 handles the only remaining case of one 2-cycle plus a longer cycle. Thus `ans` is a permutation and avoids both $i$ and $s(i)$ everywhere. Consequently $c_i=a_{ans[i]}$ is a permutation avoiding both $a_i$ and $b_i$. $\square$

### Complexity

Building the relative permutation, decomposing its cycles, and printing the result each take $O(n)$ time. All arrays and cycle storage use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

`s[i] = pos[b[i]]` is the crucial normalization. The output uses `a[ans[i]]`, so `ans` stores indices, not final values.

Cycles of size 2 are postponed because the generic two-step rotation would map every vertex to itself. If exactly one is postponed, `big.back()` is safe: with $n>2$ and no fixed points, some remaining cycle must have length at least 3.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n;
    cin >> n;

    vector<int> a(n + 1), b(n + 1), pos(n + 1), s(n + 1), ans(n + 1), vis(n + 1);

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        cin >> a[i];
        pos[a[i]] = i;
    }

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        cin >> b[i];
        s[i] = pos[b[i]];
    }

    if (n == 2) {
        cout << "IMPOSSIBLE\n";
        return 0;
    }

    vector<array<int, 2>> two;
    vector<vector<int>> big;

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        if (vis[i]) continue;

        vector<int> cyc;
        int v = i;

        while (!vis[v]) {
            vis[v] = 1;
            cyc.push_back(v);
            v = s[v];
        }

        int m = cyc.size();

        if (m == 2) {
            two.push_back({cyc[0], cyc[1]});
        } else {
            for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) ans[cyc[j]] = cyc[(j + 2) % m];
            big.push_back(cyc);
        }
    }

    int z = two.size();

    if (z >= 2) {
        for (int i = 0; i < z; i++) {
            int j = (i + 1) % z;
            ans[two[i][0]] = two[j][0];
            ans[two[i][1]] = two[j][1];
        }
    } else if (z == 1) {
        auto p = two[0];
        auto &c = big.back();

        int x = p[0], y = p[1], m = c.size();

        ans[x] = c[0];
        ans[y] = c[1];

        for (int i = 0; i + 2 < m; i++) ans[c[i]] = c[i + 2];

        ans[c[m - 2]] = x;
        ans[c[m - 1]] = y;
    }

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cout << a[ans[i]] << ' ';
    cout << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

Suppose the relative permutation is

$$
s=(1\ 2)(3\ 4\ 5).
$$

There is one 2-cycle and one longer cycle. The splice maps

$$
1\mapsto3,\quad2\mapsto4,\quad3\mapsto5,\quad4\mapsto1,\quad5\mapsto2.
$$

At each index, the image is neither itself nor its successor under $s$. Translating each image index back through $a$ produces the required third value permutation.

## Takeaway

When constraints compare several permutations position by position, relabel values through one reference permutation. The problem may become a clean statement about composing or modifying cycles of a single relative permutation.

### Related problems

Derangements avoid only the identity matching. Bipartite perfect matching also models forbidden position-value pairs, but the cycle structure here yields a direct linear construction.

