# Filling Trominos

- **Source:** [CSES 2423, Filling Trominos](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2423/)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (fillingtrominos.cpp)`](./fillingtrominos.cpp)

## Problem

Tile each requested $n\times m$ rectangle with L-trominoes, each consisting of three unit squares forming a $2\times2$ square with one corner removed. Print letters so that side-adjacent cells have the same letter exactly when they belong to the same tromino, or print `NO` when tiling is impossible.

The geometry and the coloring requirement are separate: first partition the board into trominoes, then assign locally compatible letters.

## Reasoning

Several impossibility conditions are immediate. The area must be divisible by 3. A one-cell-wide rectangle cannot contain an L shape. A $3\times w$ rectangle with odd $w$ is also impossible: color its columns alternately black and white. Every L-tromino covers either two cells in black columns and one in white columns, or the reverse. In a width-3 strip, examining how each tromino crosses the two column boundaries forces the exposed boundary profile to alternate, so a complete tiling closes only after an even number of rows. The transposed case is identical.

For every remaining case, the construction uses three ingredients.

First, a $2\times3$ block is tiled by two L-trominoes. Repeating it tiles any rectangle whose height is even and width divisible by 3. Transposing gives a $3\times2$ pattern for height divisible by 3 and even width.

Second, when at least one dimension is even, divisibility of $nm$ by 3 guarantees enough structure to combine these patterns. If height is even and width is not divisible by 3, then height must be divisible by 3. Peel a width-2 or width-4 strip so the remaining width is divisible by 3. Tile the strip with $3\times2$ blocks and the remainder with $2\times3$ blocks. The case of even width is symmetric.

Third, suppose both dimensions are odd. Since the area is divisible by 3, one dimension is divisible by 3. It cannot equal 3 because that case was rejected, so it is at least 9. The source contains an explicit tiling of a $5\times9$ rectangle by 15 trominoes and uses its transpose for $9\times5$.

- If height is divisible by 3, place a $9\times5$ block. The rectangle below it has even height, and the rectangle to its right has even width.
- Otherwise width is divisible by 3, so place a $5\times9$ block. Again, both remaining rectangles have an even side.

The recursive calls therefore reduce to the already solved even-sided cases.

After geometry is fixed, `put` chooses the smallest letter absent from already colored neighboring trominoes. A tromino has only a constant number of boundary neighbors, far fewer than 26. Future trominoes perform the symmetric check when they are placed, so two adjacent different trominoes never share a letter.

## Algorithm

For each test case:

1. Reject if the area is not divisible by 3, a dimension is 1, or one dimension is 3 while the other is odd.
2. Maintain an initially empty character grid.
3. Tile a rectangle `(x,y,h,w)` recursively:
   - if `h` is even, combine repeated $2\times3$ blocks with a width-2 or width-4 strip of $3\times2$ blocks when necessary;
   - else if `w` is even, apply the transposed decomposition;
   - else place the explicit $9\times5$ or $5\times9$ base tiling according to which odd dimension is divisible by 3, then recurse on the two rectangular remainders.
4. Whenever placing one tromino, inspect its already colored side-neighbors and assign the first unused letter from `A` onward.
5. Print `YES` and the grid.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

`p23` tiles a $2\times3$ rectangle and `p32` tiles a $3\times2$ rectangle without overlap or uncovered cells.

#### Proof

Each routine places two triples of cells. In each triple, the cells occupy three corners of a $2\times2$ square and hence form an L-tromino. The two triples are disjoint and together contain all six cells of the target rectangle. $\square$

### Lemma 2

Every accepted rectangle with an even side is completely tiled by the corresponding branch of `go`.

#### Proof

If height is even and width is divisible by 3, repeated $2\times3$ blocks cover the rectangle by Lemma 1. Otherwise, area divisibility forces height to be divisible by 3. The chosen strip width $q$ is 2 when $w\equiv2\pmod3$ and 4 when $w\equiv1\pmod3$, so $q$ is even and $w-q$ is divisible by 3. The strip is tiled by $3\times2$ blocks and the remainder by $2\times3$ blocks. They are disjoint and cover the whole rectangle. The even-width case is the transpose. $\square$

### Lemma 3

Every accepted odd-by-odd rectangle is completely tiled by `go`.

#### Proof

One dimension is divisible by 3 and, because the forbidden width-3 cases were rejected, is at least 9. The explicit `base` list consists of 15 disjoint L-trominoes covering every cell of a $5\times9$ rectangle; transposing coordinates covers $9\times5$.

After placing this base block, the two remaining rectangles are disjoint. Subtracting 9 from the divisible odd dimension leaves an even multiple of 3, while subtracting 5 from the other odd dimension leaves an even dimension. Their areas remain divisible by 3. Lemma 2 tiles both remainders. $\square$

### Lemma 4

The printed letters satisfy the adjacency rule.

#### Proof

All three cells of one placed tromino receive one letter. Before choosing it, `put` forbids every letter on an already colored side-neighbor, so the new tromino differs from every previously placed adjacent tromino. For any adjacent pair of distinct trominoes, the one placed later performs this check. Thus adjacent cells share a letter exactly when they belong to the same tromino. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm prints a valid tiling for every accepted rectangle and correctly rejects every impossible rectangle covered by the stated conditions.

#### Proof

The rejection conditions are necessary by area, L-shape geometry, and the width-3 parity obstruction. For every other rectangle, Lemmas 2 and 3 prove that the geometric construction partitions all cells into L-trominoes. Lemma 4 proves the required letter encoding. $\square$

### Complexity

Every cell belongs to one constant-size placement and is inspected a constant number of times. Time is $O(nm)$ per test case and the grid uses $O(nm)$ space. Recursion depth is bounded by the number of peeled odd base blocks, at most $O(n+m)$ and small for dimensions at most 100.

## Implementation

`f23` and `f32` repeat the two elementary patterns. Their dimension preconditions follow from the modular case analysis rather than explicit assertions.

`base` stores coordinates for the $5\times9$ exceptional block. `b95` transposes each coordinate, reusing the same verified tiling for $9\times5$.

`put` examines only already assigned neighbors. This one-directional check is sufficient because every adjacency has a later endpoint that performs the check.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T;
    cin >> T;

    vector<vector<array<int, 2>>> base = {
        {{0,0},{1,0},{1,1}},
        {{0,1},{0,2},{1,2}},
        {{0,3},{0,4},{1,4}},
        {{1,3},{2,2},{2,3}},
        {{0,5},{0,6},{1,6}},
        {{1,5},{2,4},{2,5}},
        {{0,7},{0,8},{1,8}},
        {{1,7},{2,7},{2,8}},
        {{2,6},{3,6},{3,7}},
        {{3,8},{4,7},{4,8}},
        {{3,5},{4,5},{4,6}},
        {{2,0},{2,1},{3,1}},
        {{3,0},{4,0},{4,1}},
        {{3,2},{4,2},{4,3}},
        {{3,3},{3,4},{4,4}}
    };

    while (T--) {
        int n, m;
        cin >> n >> m;

        if (n * m % 3 || n == 1 || m == 1 || (n == 3 && (m & 1)) || (m == 3 && (n & 1))) {
            cout << "NO\n";
            continue;
        }

        vector<string> a(n, string(m, '.'));
        int dx[4] = {1, -1, 0, 0};
        int dy[4] = {0, 0, 1, -1};

        auto put = [&](vector<array<int, 2>> v) {
            bool bad[26] = {};

            for (auto [x, y] : v) {
                for (int z = 0; z < 4; z++) {
                    int nx = x + dx[z], ny = y + dy[z];
                    if (nx < 0 || nx >= n || ny < 0 || ny >= m) continue;
                    if (a[nx][ny] != '.') bad[a[nx][ny] - 'A'] = 1;
                }
            }

            char c = 'A';
            while (bad[c - 'A']) c++;

            for (auto [x, y] : v) a[x][y] = c;
        };

        auto p23 = [&](int x, int y) {
            put({{{x,y},{x,y+1},{x+1,y}}});
            put({{{x+1,y+1},{x,y+2},{x+1,y+2}}});
        };

        auto p32 = [&](int x, int y) {
            put({{{x,y},{x,y+1},{x+1,y}}});
            put({{{x+1,y+1},{x+2,y},{x+2,y+1}}});
        };

        auto f23 = [&](int x, int y, int h, int w) {
            for (int i = x; i < x + h; i += 2) {
                for (int j = y; j < y + w; j += 3) p23(i, j);
            }
        };

        auto f32 = [&](int x, int y, int h, int w) {
            for (int i = x; i < x + h; i += 3) {
                for (int j = y; j < y + w; j += 2) p32(i, j);
            }
        };

        function<void(int,int,int,int)> go;

        auto b59 = [&](int x, int y) {
            for (auto v : base) {
                vector<array<int, 2>> cur;
                for (auto [i, j] : v) cur.push_back({x + i, y + j});
                put(cur);
            }
        };

        auto b95 = [&](int x, int y) {
            for (auto v : base) {
                vector<array<int, 2>> cur;
                for (auto [i, j] : v) cur.push_back({x + j, y + i});
                put(cur);
            }
        };

        go = [&](int x, int y, int h, int w) {
            if (!h || !w) return;

            if (h % 2 == 0) {
                if (w % 3 == 0) {
                    f23(x, y, h, w);
                } else {
                    int q = w % 3 == 1 ? 4 : 2;
                    f32(x, y, h, q);
                    f23(x, y + q, h, w - q);
                }
            } else if (w % 2 == 0) {
                if (h % 3 == 0) {
                    f32(x, y, h, w);
                } else {
                    int q = h % 3 == 1 ? 4 : 2;
                    f23(x, y, q, w);
                    f32(x + q, y, h - q, w);
                }
            } else {
                if (h % 3 == 0) {
                    b95(x, y);
                    go(x + 9, y, h - 9, 5);
                    go(x, y + 5, h, w - 5);
                } else {
                    b59(x, y);
                    go(x + 5, y, h - 5, 9);
                    go(x, y + 9, h, w - 9);
                }
            }
        };

        go(0, 0, n, m);

        cout << "YES\n";
        for (auto &s : a) cout << s << '\n';
    }
}
```

## Worked Example

Consider a $5\times15$ rectangle. Both dimensions are odd and width is divisible by 3. The algorithm places the explicit $5\times9$ block in the first nine columns. The remaining $5\times6$ rectangle has even width. Its height is not divisible by 3, so the even-width branch peels a height-2 strip tiled by $2\times3$ blocks and tiles the remaining $3\times6$ area with $3\times2$ blocks.

Every subrectangle is disjoint, and their union is the original $5\times15$ board.

## Takeaway

For tiling constructions, classify rectangles by modular dimensions, build tiny periodic tiles for easy residue classes, and design one finite bridge gadget that converts the hard parity class into easy subrectangles.

### Related problems

Domino tilings use similar parity invariants but simpler periodic blocks. Profile dynamic programming can decide narrow-board tilings when no closed-form construction is available.

