# Acyclic Graph Edges

- **CSES task:** [Acyclic Graph Edges](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1756)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (acyclicgraphedges.cpp)`](./acyclicgraphedges.cpp)

## Problem

Orient every edge of an undirected graph so the resulting directed graph has no cycle.

## Reasoning

Choose any strict total order of vertices and orient every edge forward in that order. Along every directed edge the order strictly increases. A directed cycle would have to return to its starting vertex after a sequence of strict increases, which is impossible.

The numeric labels already form a total order, so no graph traversal is needed.

## Algorithm

For every input edge $(a,b)$, output it from the smaller endpoint to the larger endpoint.

## Correctness

**Theorem.** The produced orientation is acyclic.

**Proof.** Every directed edge $u\to v$ satisfies $u<v$. Along a directed path, labels strictly increase. A directed cycle would imply its starting label is strictly smaller than itself after traversing the cycle, a contradiction. $\square$

### Complexity

Processing and output take $O(m)$ time and $O(m)$ buffered-output space.

## Implementation

The input endpoints are swapped when necessary. The output is buffered in one string to avoid overhead from many small writes.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n, m; cin >> n >> m;
    string out; out.reserve(m * 12);
    while(m--){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        if(a > b) swap(a, b);            // orient low -> high
        out += to_string(a); out += ' ';
        out += to_string(b); out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

Triangle edges `{1,2}`, `{2,3}`, and `{3,1}` become `1->2`, `2->3`, and `1->3`. Vertex labels increase on every edge, so the undirected cycle does not become a directed cycle.

## Takeaway

To orient an arbitrary undirected graph acyclically, pick a vertex ranking and direct every edge from lower rank to higher rank.

### Related problems

Topological sorting recovers such a ranking from an existing DAG; here the ranking is chosen first.

