# Course Schedule II

- **CSES task:** [Course Schedule II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1757)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (courseschedule2.cpp)`](./courseschedule2.cpp)

## Problem

Among all topological orders of a DAG, output the lexicographically smallest order, meaning course 1 is completed as early as possible, then course 2, and so on.

## Reasoning

Standard lexicographically smallest topological sorting repeatedly chooses the smallest current source. The implementation uses the exact reverse formulation: build reversed adjacency, repeatedly remove the largest current sink of the original graph, append it, then reverse the resulting list.

Why choose the largest sink? The final position of a topological order can contain any current sink. To make the forward order lexicographically smallest, postpone the largest available label as far right as possible. Removing it leaves the same optimization problem on the remaining DAG, yielding an inductive greedy proof.

## Algorithm

Count original outdegrees and build reverse edges. Put all zero-outdegree vertices in a max heap. Repeatedly remove the largest, append it, decrement outdegrees of its predecessors, and insert newly created sinks. Reverse the collected sequence.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Some lexicographically smallest topological order ends with the largest currently available sink.

**Proof.** If that sink appears earlier, move it to the final position. It has no outgoing edge to any remaining vertex, so this preserves validity. Removing a larger label from an earlier position cannot make the order lexicographically larger than an order ending in a smaller available sink. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the lexicographically smallest valid schedule.

**Proof.** Apply Lemma 1 to choose the last course. After its removal, the remaining prefix must itself be lexicographically smallest for the residual DAG. Induction proves that reverse sink removal constructs all positions optimally. $\square$

### Complexity

Each vertex and edge is processed once, with heap operations costing $O(\log n)$. Total time is $O((n+m)\log n)$ and space is $O(n+m)$.

## Implementation

`out[v]` is original outdegree, while `rg[v]` lists original predecessors. The final `reverse` converts sink-removal order into the requested source-to-sink schedule.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    ll n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;

    vii ed;
    ed.reserve(m);

    vector<vi> rg(n + 1);
    vi out(n + 1), ans;
    ans.reserve(n);

    for (ll i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        ll a, b;
        cin >> a >> b;
        ed.pb({a, b});
    }

    for (ii e : ed) {
        out[e.f]++;
        rg[e.s].pb(e.f);
    }

    priority_queue<ll> pq;
    for (ll i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        if (!out[i]) pq.push(i);
    }

    while (!pq.empty()) {
        ll v = pq.top();
        pq.pop();

        ans.pb(v);

        for (ll to : rg[v]) {
            out[to]--;
            if (!out[to]) pq.push(to);
        }
    }

    reverse(ans.begin(), ans.end());

    for (ll i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << ans[i] << " \n"[i + 1 == n];
    }

    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

With constraints `2->1` and `2->3`, initial sinks are 1, 3, and 4. Reverse greedy removes 4, then 3, then 1, then 2. Reversing gives `[2,1,3,4]`, the smallest valid schedule.

## Takeaway

Lexicographic topological order can be built from either end: smallest available source forward, or largest available sink backward.

### Related problems

Course Schedule asks for any topological order and does not need the priority-queue tie rule.

