# Critical Cities

- **Problem:** [CSES 1703](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1703)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (criticalcities.cpp)](./criticalcities.cpp)

## Problem

Find every vertex that occurs on every directed path from vertex $1$ to vertex $n$.

## Reasoning

A vertex $u$ dominates $v$ when every path from the source to $v$ contains $u$. The answer is therefore the dominator chain of $n$.

Lengauer-Tarjan builds the dominator tree from one DFS tree. For DFS index $v$, its semidominator is the earliest DFS vertex that can reach $v$ through a path whose internal vertices were discovered later than $v$. Processing indices backward makes these values available. A disjoint-set forest with labels returns the minimum semidominator seen along compressed DFS-tree paths.

Vertices sharing a semidominator are delayed in buckets. When that semidominator is processed, the algorithm determines a provisional dominator; one forward correction pass converts provisional links into immediate dominators.

## Algorithm

1. Iteratively DFS from $1$ and assign preorder indices.
2. Build predecessor lists in index space.
3. Process indices backward, compute semidominators with labelled DSU evaluation, resolve the current bucket, and link each vertex to its DFS parent.
4. Process forward to correct provisional dominators.
5. Follow immediate-dominator links from $n$ to $1$ and output the corresponding vertices.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The backward pass computes the semidominator of every reachable vertex.

**Proof.** Every candidate path enters through some predecessor. Labelled DSU evaluation returns the minimum semidominator on the relevant DFS-tree suffix, exactly representing paths whose internal indices are larger. Taking the minimum over predecessors matches the semidominator definition.

**Lemma 2.** After the correction pass, `dom[v]` is the immediate dominator of $v$.

**Proof.** The Lengauer-Tarjan bucket rule chooses either the semidominator or a provisional vertex whose dominator is shared with $v$. Replacing every non-sem idom candidate by its own corrected dominator yields the deepest strict dominator. Forward DFS order ensures that correction is already known.

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs exactly the critical cities.

**Proof.** Immediate dominators form a tree in which ancestors of $v$ are exactly its dominators. Thus the chain from $n$ to the root contains precisely the vertices on every source-to-$n$ path.

### Complexity

The algorithm runs in $O((n+m)\alpha(n))$ time and uses $O(n+m)$ space.

## Implementation

Only vertices reachable from $1$ receive DFS indices. All edges are converted to that index space. The DFS itself is iterative, while the short recursive `find` operates on the compressed DSU forest.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    vector<vector<int>> g(n + 1);
    vector<pair<int,int>> edges;
    for(int i = 0; i < m; ++i){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        g[a].push_back(b);
        edges.push_back({a,b});
    }

    vector<int> arr(n + 1, 0), rev(n + 1), parVertex(n + 1, 0), it(n + 1, 0);
    int timer = 1; arr[1] = 1; rev[1] = 1;
    vector<int> st{1};
    while(!st.empty()){
        int u = st.back();
        if(it[u] == (int)g[u].size()){ st.pop_back(); continue; }
        int v = g[u][it[u]++];
        if(!arr[v]){
            arr[v] = ++timer; rev[timer] = v; parVertex[v] = u;
            st.push_back(v);
        }
    }

    int N = timer;
    vector<vector<int>> pred(N + 1), bucket(N + 1);
    for(auto [u,v] : edges) if(arr[u] && arr[v]) pred[arr[v]].push_back(arr[u]);
    vector<int> parent(N + 1), sdom(N + 1), dom(N + 1), dsu(N + 1), label(N + 1);
    for(int i = 1; i <= N; ++i){
        sdom[i] = dsu[i] = label[i] = i;
        if(i > 1) parent[i] = arr[parVertex[rev[i]]];
    }

    function<int(int,int)> find = [&](int v, int depth){
        if(v == dsu[v]) return depth ? -1 : v;
        int p = find(dsu[v], depth + 1);
        if(p < 0) return v;
        if(sdom[label[dsu[v]]] < sdom[label[v]]) label[v] = label[dsu[v]];
        dsu[v] = p;
        return depth ? p : label[v];
    };

    for(int i = N; i >= 1; --i){
        for(int p : pred[i]) sdom[i] = min(sdom[i], sdom[find(p,0)]);
        if(i > 1) bucket[sdom[i]].push_back(i);
        for(int v : bucket[i]){
            int y = find(v,0);
            dom[v] = (sdom[y] == sdom[v] ? sdom[v] : y);
        }
        if(i > 1) dsu[i] = parent[i];
    }
    for(int i = 2; i <= N; ++i) if(dom[i] != sdom[i]) dom[i] = dom[dom[i]];
    dom[1] = 1;

    vector<int> ans;
    if(arr[n]){
        for(int v = arr[n]; ; v = dom[v]){
            ans.push_back(rev[v]);
            if(v == 1) break;
        }
    }
    sort(ans.begin(), ans.end());
    cout << ans.size() << '\n';
    for(int i = 0; i < (int)ans.size(); ++i) cout << ans[i] << " \n"[i + 1 == (int)ans.size()];
}
```

## Worked Example

For edges $1\to2$, $1\to3$, $2\to4$, $3\to4$, and $4\to5$, the immediate dominators are `idom(2)=1`, `idom(3)=1`, `idom(4)=1`, and `idom(5)=4`. The chain for $5$ is $5,4,1$, so those are the critical cities.

## Takeaway

“Present on every directed path” is the defining signal for dominators. General directed graphs require a dominator algorithm; path counting or undirected articulation logic is not enough.

### Related problems

Visiting Cities, Forbidden Cities, Necessary Cities.

