# Even Outdegree Edges

- **CSES task:** [Even Outdegree Edges](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2179)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (evenoutdegreeedges.cpp)`](./evenoutdegreeedges.cpp)

## Problem

Orient every edge of an undirected graph so every vertex has even outdegree, or report impossibility.

## Reasoning

Build a DFS forest. Non-tree edges may be oriented immediately when first encountered. Tree edges are delayed until postorder. When finishing nonroot vertex $u$, all incident edges except its parent edge are already oriented, so that last edge can fix $u$'s parity: orient it out of $u$ if current outdegree is odd, otherwise into $u$.

This may change only the parent's parity, which remains unfixed until later. A root has no parent edge, so its final parity determines feasibility. Equivalently, every connected component must have an even number of edges because the sum of outdegrees equals its edge count.

## Algorithm

Run iterative DFS over every component. Orient each previously unoriented non-tree edge from the current vertex to its seen neighbor. On postorder exit, orient the parent edge to make the exiting vertex even. Reject if any root remains odd.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** When a nonroot vertex exits DFS, the algorithm makes its final outdegree even and never changes it later.

**Proof.** Only its parent edge remains unoriented. Choosing its direction according to current parity makes the total even. All incident edges are then fixed permanently. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** A component is orientable exactly when its DFS root ends with even outdegree.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 fixes every other vertex. The root has no remaining edge to change. If it is even, the orientation is complete. If odd, the component edge count, equal to the sum of outdegrees, is odd, while a sum of even outdegrees would be even, proving impossibility. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm prints a valid orientation exactly when one exists.

**Proof.** Apply Lemma 2 independently to every connected component. $\square$

### Complexity

Every vertex and edge is processed a constant number of times, for $O(n+m)$ time and space.

## Implementation

Edges carry identifiers so the parent edge and already oriented back edges are distinguished correctly. The explicit DFS stack avoids recursion depth failure.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n, m; cin >> n >> m;
    vector<vector<pair<int,int>>> adj(n + 1);   // (to, edge id)
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        adj[a].pb({b, i}); adj[b].pb({a, i});
    }
    vector<int> tin(n + 1, 0), par(n + 1, 0), pare(n + 1, -1), it(n + 1, 0), outd(n + 1, 0);
    vector<pair<int,int>> ored(m);
    vector<char> done(m, 0);
    int timer = 0; bool bad = false;
    vector<int> st;

    // iterative DFS forest: back edges fixed on sight, tree edges fixed in post-order to keep each node even
    for(int s0 = 1; s0 <= n; s0++){
        if(tin[s0]) continue;
        tin[s0] = ++timer; st.pb(s0);
        while(!st.empty()){
            int u = st.back();
            if(it[u] < (int)adj[u].size()){
                auto [w, e] = adj[u][it[u]++];
                if(e == pare[u]) continue;       // parent tree edge, handled later
                if(!tin[w]){                      // tree edge
                    tin[w] = ++timer; par[w] = u; pare[w] = e;
                    st.pb(w);
                } else if(!done[e]){              // back edge: orient u -> w
                    done[e] = 1; ored[e] = {u, w}; outd[u]++;
                }
            } else {
                st.pop_back();
                int p = par[u];
                if(p){                            // post-order: fix edge u<->p
                    if(outd[u] & 1){ ored[pare[u]] = {u, p}; outd[u]++; }
                    else { ored[pare[u]] = {p, u}; outd[p]++; }
                } else if(outd[u] & 1) bad = true; // root must be even
            }
        }
    }

    if(bad){ cout << "IMPOSSIBLE\n"; return 0; }
    string out; out.reserve(m * 12);
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        out += to_string(ored[i].f); out += ' ';
        out += to_string(ored[i].s); out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

On a four-cycle, orient one non-tree edge during DFS. Postorder choices then use each parent edge to repair child parity, and the root finishes even because the component has four edges.

## Takeaway

When vertex parity constraints involve edge orientations, postpone DFS tree edges. Each parent edge becomes one final parity-control bit for its child.

### Related problems

Eulerian Subgraphs also reduces graph structure to parity equations over edges.

