# Flight Route Requests

- **Problem:** [CSES 1699](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1699)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (flightrouterequests.cpp)](./flightrouterequests.cpp)

## Problem

Starting with no flight connections, add the minimum number of directed edges so every requested reachability $(a,b)$ becomes possible.

## Reasoning

Ignore directions temporarily. Requests in different weakly connected components share no vertices and can be handled independently. Consider one component with $k$ vertices. At least $k-1$ added edges are necessary because the underlying undirected graph of any realization must connect all vertices linked by requests.

If the request graph is acyclic, take a topological ordering and add a directed chain through all $k$ vertices. Every request points forward, so the chain realizes it. This meets the lower bound.

If the requests contain a directed cycle, a realization with only $k-1$ edges would have an undirected tree as its underlying graph, which contains no directed cycle. Requested mutual reachability around the cycle forces a directed cycle, so at least $k$ edges are needed. A directed cycle through all vertices is sufficient.

Thus each weak component costs $k-1$, plus one if it contains a nontrivial strongly connected component.

## Algorithm

1. Use DSU on request endpoints to find weak components.
2. Compute strongly connected components of the directed request graph.
3. Mark a weak component cyclic when it contains an SCC of at least two vertices.
4. Start with $n-W$, where $W$ is the number of weak components, and add one per cyclic weak component.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** An acyclic weak component with $k$ vertices requires exactly $k-1$ flights.

**Proof.** Undirected connectivity gives the lower bound. A chain in topological order has $k-1$ edges and realizes every forward request.

**Lemma 2.** A cyclic weak component with $k$ vertices requires exactly $k$ flights.

**Proof.** With $k-1$ edges, connectedness forces the underlying graph to be a tree, so it cannot contain the directed cycle forced by the requests. A directed cycle through all vertices uses $k$ edges and realizes every request.

**Theorem.** The algorithm returns the minimum number of flight connections.

**Proof.** Weak components have disjoint vertex sets, so their exact costs from Lemmas 1 and 2 add independently.

### Complexity

DSU and iterative Tarjan processing take $O(n+m\alpha(n))$ time. Space is $O(n+m)$.

## Implementation

SCC IDs are used to compute component sizes. A weak component is marked when any contained SCC has size at least two. Self-requests need no added edge and are omitted from the SCC adjacency.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
typedef long long ll;

int n, m;
int p[100005];
int fnd(int x){ while(p[x]!=x){ p[x]=p[p[x]]; x=p[x]; } return x; }

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    cin >> n >> m;
    vector<int> A(m), B(m);
    vector<vector<int>> g(n + 1);
    for(int i=1;i<=n;i++) p[i]=i;
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){ int a, b; cin >> a >> b; A[i] = a; B[i] = b; if(a != b) g[a].pb(b); p[fnd(a)]=fnd(b); }

    // iterative Tarjan: SCC sizes + count
    vector<int> low(n + 1, 0), num(n + 1, 0), comp(n + 1, -1), it(n + 1, 0);
    vector<char> onst(n + 1, 0);
    vector<int> stk, dfs; stk.reserve(n); dfs.reserve(n);
    int timer = 0, nc = 0;
    for(int s = 1; s <= n; s++){
        if(num[s]) continue;
        dfs.pb(s);
        while(!dfs.empty()){
            int u = dfs.back();
            if(!num[u]){ num[u] = low[u] = ++timer; stk.pb(u); onst[u] = 1; }
            bool pushed = false;
            while(it[u] < (int)g[u].size()){
