# Graph Coloring I

- **Problem:** [CSES 3308](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3308)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (graphcolouring.cpp)`](./graphcolouring.cpp)

## Problem

Color every vertex of a small undirected graph so adjacent vertices receive different colors, using the minimum possible number of colors.

## Reasoning

One color class is exactly an independent set. Therefore a proper coloring of a vertex set $S$ is a partition of $S$ into independent subsets. With small $n$, subsets can be represented by bitmasks.

Define $dp[S]$ as the minimum number of independent sets whose disjoint union is $S$. A direct transition tries an independent subset $I\subseteq S$ and uses $1+dp[S\setminus I]$.

To avoid enumerating the same partition in many orders, require $I$ to contain the least-numbered vertex of $S$. Every partition has exactly one class containing that vertex, so this restriction preserves every solution while reducing the enumeration by half.

Independent-set status is also computed by subset DP. Remove the least bit $v$ from $S$; then $S$ is independent exactly when $S\setminus\{v\}$ is independent and $v$ has no neighbor inside $S$.

## Algorithm

1. Store each adjacency list as an $n$-bit mask.
2. Compute `ind[mask]` for every subset by removing its lowest set bit.
3. Set $dp[0]=0$.
4. For every nonempty mask, enumerate subsets containing its lowest bit. For every independent such subset `sub`, relax
   $$dp[mask]=\min(dp[mask],1+dp[mask\setminus sub]).$$
5. Store the chosen subset and backtrack to assign consecutive color numbers.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** `ind[S]` is true exactly when $S$ is an independent set.

**Proof.** Let $v$ be the lowest vertex of nonempty $S$. Independence requires both that $S\setminus\{v\}$ is independent and that $v$ has no neighbor in $S$. These are precisely the two conditions in the recurrence, with the empty set as the base case.

**Lemma 2.** $dp[S]$ equals the chromatic number of the subgraph induced by $S$.

**Proof.** Induct on $|S|$. Every transition chooses an independent set as one valid color class and combines it with an optimal coloring of the remainder, so it constructs a valid coloring. Conversely, in any optimal coloring, the class containing the lowest vertex is among the enumerated independent subsets. The transition using that class reaches no more colors than the optimum. Both bounds give equality.

**Theorem.** The reconstructed assignment is a proper coloring with the minimum number of colors.

**Proof.** Each selected subset is independent and removed exactly once, so the assigned classes partition all vertices and contain no monochromatic edge. Lemma 2 proves their count is minimum.

### Complexity

Independent-set preprocessing takes $O(2^n)$. Across all masks, subset enumeration takes $O(3^n)$. Space is $O(2^n+n)$.

## Implementation

The loop enumerates only `t` inside `rest`, then adds the mandatory lowest bit. `ch[mask]` records the selected color class, allowing reconstruction without storing an entire partition per state.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n, m;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    cin >> n >> m;
    vector<int> adj(n, 0);
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){ int a, b; cin >> a >> b; --a; --b; if(a != b){ adj[a] |= 1 << b; adj[b] |= 1 << a; } }

    int F = 1 << n;
    vector<char> ind(F, 0); ind[0] = 1;
    for(int mask = 1; mask < F; mask++){
        int low = __builtin_ctz(mask);
        ind[mask] = ind[mask ^ (1 << low)] && !(adj[low] & mask);   // drop low, check no neighbor inside
    }

    vector<int> dp(F, INT_MAX), ch(F, 0);
    dp[0] = 0;
    for(int mask = 1; mask < F; mask++){
        int low = __builtin_ctz(mask), rest = mask ^ (1 << low);
        for(int t = rest; ; t = (t - 1) & rest){
            int sub = t | (1 << low);                                // color class containing low
            if(ind[sub] && dp[mask ^ sub] != INT_MAX && dp[mask ^ sub] + 1 < dp[mask]){ dp[mask] = dp[mask ^ sub] + 1; ch[mask] = sub; }
            if(t == 0) break;
        }
    }

    vector<int> col(n);
    int mask = F - 1, c = 0;
    while(mask){ ++c; int sub = ch[mask]; for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) if(sub >> i & 1) col[i] = c; mask ^= sub; }

    cout << dp[F - 1] << "\n";
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) cout << col[i] << " \n"[i + 1 == n];
}
```

## Worked Example

For a triangle, the independent nonempty subsets are the three singletons. Starting from mask `111`, every transition removes one vertex, then another, then the last. Thus `dp[111]=3`, and reconstruction assigns a different color to each vertex.

## Takeaway

Exact coloring on small graphs is set partition DP: characterize a legal color class as an independent subset, then anchor each transition at one fixed element to remove symmetric orders.

### Related problems

Hamiltonian Flights, Elevator Rides, Meet in the Middle.

