- **CSES task:** [Graph Girth](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1707)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (graphgirth.cpp)`](./graphgirth.cpp)

## Problem

Find the length of the shortest cycle in an undirected graph with $n\le2500$ and $m\le5000$, or print -1 if the graph is acyclic.

## Reasoning

Fix a BFS root $s$. Whenever an edge $(u,v)$ joins two already discovered vertices and is not the tree edge from $u$ to its parent, the two BFS-tree paths plus this edge contain a cycle of length at most

$$dist[u]+dist[v]+1.$$

For a globally shortest cycle, choose any of its vertices as root. BFS distances to cycle vertices cannot exceed their distances along the cycle. The edge where the two wavefronts meet therefore produces a candidate no longer than that cycle. Since every candidate contains some real cycle no longer than itself, minimizing over all roots gives exact girth.

## Algorithm

Run BFS from every vertex. Store distances and BFS parents. For every examined edge to an already visited nonparent neighbor, minimize the answer with `dist[u]+dist[v]+1`.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Every candidate value is at least the length of some cycle in the graph.

**Proof.** The two root paths to the edge endpoints together with the edge form a closed walk. Removing repeated portions leaves a simple cycle no longer than the candidate. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** For a shortest cycle of length $g$, some BFS run produces a candidate at most $g$.

**Proof.** Root BFS at a cycle vertex. Follow the cycle in both directions; when its two BFS-reached sides meet across a cycle edge, their distances plus that edge are at most the two cycle arcs totaling $g$. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the graph girth or -1 when no cycle exists.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 prevents the minimum candidate from being below girth, while Lemma 2 prevents it from exceeding girth. No candidate appears in a forest. $\square$

### Complexity

Each BFS costs $O(n+m)$, so total time is $O(n(n+m))$ and auxiliary space is $O(n+m)$.

## Implementation

Only the direct parent edge is ignored. Encountering an undirected edge from both endpoints may repeat a candidate but cannot change correctness.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n, m; cin >> n >> m;
    vector<vector<int>> adj(n + 1);
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        adj[a].pb(b); adj[b].pb(a);
    }
    const int INF = 1e9;
    vector<int> dist(n + 1), par(n + 1);
    int ans = INF;

    // BFS from each source; non-parent visited neighbor closes a cycle
    for(int s0 = 1; s0 <= n; s0++){
        fill(dist.begin(), dist.end(), -1);
        dist[s0] = 0; par[s0] = 0;
        queue<int> q; q.push(s0);
        while(!q.empty()){
            int u = q.front(); q.pop();
            for(int w : adj[u]){
                if(dist[w] < 0){
                    dist[w] = dist[u] + 1; par[w] = u; q.push(w);
                } else if(w != par[u]){
                    ans = min(ans, dist[u] + dist[w] + 1);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    cout << (ans == INF ? -1 : ans) << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

In a triangle rooted at vertex 1, vertices 2 and 3 both receive distance 1. Their connecting edge yields candidate $1+1+1=3$.

## Takeaway

For moderate graphs, BFS from every root finds shortest cycles by detecting edges between competing BFS branches.

### Related problems

Shortest Routes uses one BFS because it asks for distances, while girth requires considering every possible cycle center.

