# MST Edge Set Check

- **Problem:** [CSES 3408](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3408)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (mstedgesetcheck.cpp)`](./mstedgesetcheck.cpp)

## Problem

Each query gives a set of graph edges. Determine whether some minimum spanning tree contains every edge in that set.

## Reasoning

Kruskal may choose equal-weight edges in any order. Before weight $w$, contract every component connected by edges lighter than $w$. The query's weight-$w$ edges must be insertable without a cycle in this contracted graph. If they contain a cycle, every spanning tree must omit at least one of them. If they form a forest, Kruskal can choose all of them first within this weight group and then complete the forest using other equal-weight edges.

This condition is independent for every weight. A permanent DSU represents the strictly-lighter components. For one pair `(query, weight)`, a temporary DSU checks whether that query's contracted edges form a forest. Temporary state must not leak between queries or weights.

## Algorithm

1. Sort graph edges by weight.
2. Expand every query edge into a record `(weight, query id, u, v)` and sort these records.
3. Sweep query records by increasing weight, advancing a permanent DSU with all graph edges of smaller weight.
4. For each fixed `(weight, query id)` group, map each endpoint through the permanent DSU and use a fresh temporary DSU to test its edges for a cycle.
5. A query is `YES` if none of its weight groups creates a cycle.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** At weight $w$, the permanent DSU contracts exactly the components obtainable with edges lighter than $w$.

**Proof.** The sweep inserts precisely graph edges whose weights are below the current query-record weight.

**Lemma 2.** A query can be included in an MST if and only if, at every weight $w$, its weight-$w$ edges form a forest after the lighter components are contracted.

**Proof.** A cycle in the contracted graph forces any spanning tree to omit a queried edge from that cycle. Conversely, if the queried edges form a forest, order Kruskal's equal-weight choices so those edges are selected first. They create no cycle, after which the forest can be extended maximally within the weight layer. Repeating this for all weights yields an MST containing the entire query set.

**Theorem.** The algorithm answers every query correctly.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 supplies the required contraction. The temporary DSU accepts exactly acyclic groups, so the algorithm tests the necessary and sufficient condition of Lemma 2.

### Complexity

Let $S$ be the total number of edge references across all queries. Sorting costs $O((m+S)\log(m+S))$ and DSU work costs $O((m+S)\alpha(n))$. Space is $O(n+m+S+q)$.

## Implementation

`iq[x]` stamps temporary vertices with `curq`. A new stamp makes the temporary DSU logically empty without clearing an $O(n)$ array for every group. The permanent DSU advances only through edges with weight strictly smaller than the current group.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int p[100005], sz[100005];
int fnd(int x){ while(x != p[x]) x = p[x] = p[p[x]]; return x; }

int tp[100005], iq[100005], curq;          // throwaway DSU, stamped per group
int tfnd(int x){
    if(iq[x] != curq){ iq[x] = curq; tp[x] = x; return x; }   // fresh this group
    int r = x;
    while(tp[r] != r) r = tp[r];
    while(tp[x] != r){ int nx = tp[x]; tp[x] = r; x = nx; }
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n, m, q; cin >> n >> m >> q;
    vector<array<int,3>> e(m);              // (a, b, w) by edge id
    vector<int> ord(m);
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        int a, b, w; cin >> a >> b >> w;
        e[i] = {a, b, w}; ord[i] = i;
    }
    sort(ord.begin(), ord.end(), [&](int x, int y){ return e[x][2] < e[y][2]; });

    vector<char> ans(q, 1);                 // YES until a level fails
    vector<array<int,4>> qe; qe.reserve(m); // (w, qid, a, b)
    for(int qid = 0; qid < q; qid++){
        int k; cin >> k;
        while(k--){ int id; cin >> id; --id; qe.pb({e[id][2], qid, e[id][0], e[id][1]}); }
    }
    sort(qe.begin(), qe.end(), [](const array<int,4>&x, const array<int,4>&y){
        return x[0] != y[0] ? x[0] < y[0] : x[1] < y[1];
    });

    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ p[i] = i; sz[i] = 1; }

    int gi = 0, i = 0, Q = (int)qe.size();
    while(i < Q){
        int w = qe[i][0];
        while(gi < m && e[ord[gi]][2] < w){            // advance frontier: edges < w
            int id = ord[gi++], a = fnd(e[id][0]), b = fnd(e[id][1]);
            if(a != b){ if(sz[a] < sz[b]) swap(a, b); p[b] = a; sz[a] += sz[b]; }
        }
        int j = i;
        while(j < Q && qe[j][0] == w){                 // groups of same (w, qid)
            int g = j, qid = qe[j][1];
            while(g < Q && qe[g][0] == w && qe[g][1] == qid) g++;
            curq++;
            for(int t = j; t < g; t++){                 // forest check on lighter frontier
                int x = tfnd(fnd(qe[t][2])), y = tfnd(fnd(qe[t][3]));
                if(x == y) ans[qid] = 0; else tp[x] = y;
            }
            j = g;
        }
        i = j;
    }

    string out; out.reserve(q * 4);
    for(int t = 0; t < q; t++) out += ans[t] ? "YES\n" : "NO\n";
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

In a triangle whose three edges all have weight $5$, a query containing two edges is accepted because the two contracted edges form a forest. A query containing all three is rejected because its temporary DSU detects a cycle on the third insertion.

## Takeaway

To force choices into an MST, process weights independently after contracting all lighter edges. Within one weight layer, feasibility reduces to graphic-matroid independence, which is simply cycle detection by DSU.

### Related problems

MST Edge Check, MST Edge Cost, Road Reparation.

