# Nearest Shops

- **CSES task:** [Nearest Shops](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3303)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (nearestshops.cpp)`](./nearestshops.cpp)

## Problem

For every vertex of an unweighted graph, find the nearest shop located in a different city. A shop city must ignore its own zero-distance shop.

## Reasoning

Ordinary multi-source BFS stores only the nearest source, but a shop vertex may need the second distinct source. It is sufficient to retain the two shortest distances arriving from different shop identifiers at every vertex.

Suppose a third source reaches vertex $v$ no earlier than the retained two. Extending all three routes across the same future path preserves their order, so that third source can never become one of the best two at any downstream vertex. This dominance makes two labels per vertex complete.

Run BFS over states `(vertex,distance,source)`. Unit edges ensure queue order is nondecreasing distance, while the `add` routine updates or inserts one of the two source-distinct labels.

## Algorithm

Seed every shop as a distance-zero state with its own source identifier. Propagate accepted labels through edges. For city $v$, use the first label unless its source is $v$; then use the second label. Print -1 if the required label is absent.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** At every vertex, the stored labels are the two shortest distances from distinct shop sources.

**Proof.** Multi-source BFS discovers path extensions in nondecreasing length. `add` keeps improvements for an existing source and the best two source-distinct entries. Any discarded third entry is dominated along every common continuation by both retained entries. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the nearest shop in another city for every vertex.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 gives the nearest two distinct shop sources. A nonshop city uses the first. A shop city discards its own zero-distance source and uses the next distinct source, which is exactly the requested answer. $\square$

### Complexity

Each vertex accepts at most two source labels, so each edge is relaxed a constant number of times. Time and space are $O(n+m)$.

## Implementation

Queue entries are checked against both current labels to discard stale states. The distance-source pair ordering keeps the shorter label in slot zero after every update.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

const ll INF = 4e18;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    ll n, m, k;
    cin >> n >> m >> k;

    vi shop(k);
    for (ll &x : shop) cin >> x;

    vector<vi> g(n + 1);
    for (ll i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        ll a, b;
        cin >> a >> b;
        g[a].pb(b);
        g[b].pb(a);
    }

    vector<array<ii, 2>> best(n + 1);
    for (ll i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        best[i][0] = {INF, -1};
        best[i][1] = {INF, -1};
    }

    queue<pair<ii, ll>> q;

    auto add = [&](ll v, ll d, ll src) -> bool {
        if (best[v][0].s == src) {
            if (d >= best[v][0].f) return false;
            best[v][0].f = d;
            if (best[v][1].f < best[v][0].f) swap(best[v][0], best[v][1]);
            return true;
        }

        if (best[v][1].s == src) {
            if (d >= best[v][1].f) return false;
            best[v][1].f = d;
            if (best[v][1].f < best[v][0].f) swap(best[v][0], best[v][1]);
            return true;
        }

        if (d < best[v][0].f) {
            best[v][1] = best[v][0];
            best[v][0] = {d, src};
            return true;
        }

        if (d < best[v][1].f) {
            best[v][1] = {d, src};
            return true;
        }

        return false;
    };

    for (ll x : shop) {
        if (add(x, 0, x)) q.push({{x, 0}, x});
    }

    while (!q.empty()) {
        auto cur = q.front();
        q.pop();

        ll v = cur.f.f;
        ll d = cur.f.s;
        ll src = cur.s;

        bool ok = false;
        if (best[v][0].s == src && best[v][0].f == d) ok = true;
        if (best[v][1].s == src && best[v][1].f == d) ok = true;
        if (!ok) continue;

        for (ll to : g[v]) {
            if (add(to, d + 1, src)) {
                q.push({{to, d + 1}, src});
            }
        }
    }

    for (ll i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        ll ans = -1;

        if (best[i][0].s != i && best[i][0].f < INF) ans = best[i][0].f;
        else if (best[i][1].f < INF) ans = best[i][1].f;

        cout << ans << " \n"[i == n];
    }

    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

If shops are at 2 and 4 and vertex 2 is adjacent to 4, labels at city 2 become `(0,2)` and `(1,4)`. Its own source is rejected at output, so answer 1 is chosen.

## Takeaway

When a multi-source shortest-path query excludes the source matching the destination, retain the best two distinct source labels rather than rerunning BFS.

### Related problems

Multi-source BFS for Monsters stores one best source-independent arrival; this exclusion variant needs two.

