# Network Breakdown

- **CSES task:** [Network Breakdown](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1677)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (networkbreakdown.cpp)`](./networkbreakdown.cpp)

## Problem

Roads are removed from an undirected graph one by one. After every removal, report the number of connected components.

## Reasoning

DSU supports edge insertion but not deletion. Reverse time: start from the graph after all requested removals, then add removed edges back in reverse order. Every reversed state corresponds exactly to one forward state.

Maintain the component count `cur`, initially $n$. Whenever a DSU union joins distinct roots, decrement it. Record the count after each reverse insertion at the matching forward-time index.

## Algorithm

Map each undirected edge pair to its input index and mark every removed edge. Build DSU from all surviving edges. Store the after-all-removals count. Traverse removal requests backward, reinsert each edge, and record the new count. Print states after removals 1 through $k$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Before reverse step $i$, DSU represents exactly the graph after the first $i$ forward removals.

**Proof.** Initially this is true for all $k$ removals. Readding the edge removed at step $i$ transforms that graph into the graph after only the first $i-1$ removals. Induction follows. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** `cur` equals the connected-component count of the represented graph.

**Proof.** It begins with $n$ singleton components and decreases exactly when an inserted edge joins two distinct components. Redundant edges change neither DSU partition nor count. $\square$

**Theorem.** Every printed count is correct.

**Proof.** Lemmas 1 and 2 identify every recorded reverse state with the corresponding forward graph and its exact component count. $\square$

### Complexity

Hash mapping and DSU processing take expected $O((m+k)\alpha(n))$ time and $O(n+m+k)$ space.

## Implementation

The undirected key orders endpoints and encodes them with multiplier `n+1`. `ans[k]` is the state after all removals; output begins at `ans[1]` because the initial unbroken state is not requested.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int p[100005], sz[100005];
int fnd(int x){ while(x != p[x]) x = p[x] = p[p[x]]; return x; }

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n, m, k; cin >> n >> m >> k;
    vector<ii> e(m);
    unordered_map<ll,int> id; id.reserve(2*m);
    auto key = [&](int a, int b) -> ll { if(a > b) swap(a, b); return (ll)a*(n+1) + b; };
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){ cin >> e[i].f >> e[i].s; id[key(e[i].f, e[i].s)] = i; }

    vi brk(k); vector<char> dead(m, 0);       // edge idx per breakdown
    for(int i = 0; i < k; i++){ int a, b; cin >> a >> b; int j = id[key(a, b)]; brk[i] = j; dead[j] = 1; }

    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ p[i] = i; sz[i] = 1; }
    int cur = n;
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++) if(!dead[i]){  // surviving graph = state after all k breakdowns
        int a = fnd(e[i].f), b = fnd(e[i].s);
        if(a != b){ if(sz[a] < sz[b]) swap(a, b); p[b] = a; sz[a] += sz[b]; cur--; }
    }

    vi ans(k + 1); ans[k] = cur;
    for(int i = k - 1; i >= 0; i--){          // re-add breakdown i+1 -> ans[i]
        int j = brk[i];
        int a = fnd(e[j].f), b = fnd(e[j].s);
        if(a != b){ if(sz[a] < sz[b]) swap(a, b); p[b] = a; sz[a] += sz[b]; cur--; }
        ans[i] = cur;
    }

    string out; out.reserve(k * 8);
    for(int i = 1; i <= k; i++){ out += to_string(ans[i]); out += " \n"[i == k]; }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

If removing two roads leaves three components, reverse processing starts at 3. Readding the second road may merge two components to 2; this value is the state after only the first removal.

## Takeaway

Offline deletions often become easy insertions when processed backward. DSU is the standard tool when connectivity changes only by additions in reverse time.

### Related problems

Dynamic Connectivity generalizes this reversal idea to interleaved additions and deletions using rollback DSU.

