# New Flight Routes

- **Problem:** [CSES 1685](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1685)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (newflightroutes.cpp)](./newflightroutes.cpp)

## Problem

Add the minimum number of directed edges so the entire directed graph becomes strongly connected, and output a valid construction.

## Reasoning

Contract every strongly connected component. The condensation graph is a DAG. Adding edges between representatives of its nodes is sufficient because travel inside each component is already unrestricted.

Let $S$ be the number of source components and $T$ the number of sink components. Every source needs a new incoming edge and every sink needs a new outgoing edge, so at least $\max(S,T)$ edges are necessary.

To attain the bound, pair as many sources as possible with distinct reachable sinks. Each matched source-to-sink path is then linked cyclically: add an edge from each matched sink to the next matched source. These edges fuse all matched paths into one strongly connected core. An unmatched source is fed from a matched sink, an unmatched sink is drained into a matched source, and one edge can handle one leftover of each kind simultaneously.

## Algorithm

1. Compute SCCs and construct the condensation DAG.
2. List its sources and sinks.
3. With persistent DFS visitation, greedily pair a source with an unused reachable sink.
4. Add edges from matched sink $i$ to matched source $i+1$ cyclically.
5. Pair leftover sinks with leftover sources directly.
6. Attach any remaining sources from a matched sink and remaining sinks to a matched source.
7. Translate component edges to edges between stored representative vertices.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Any solution needs at least $\max(S,T)$ new edges.

**Proof.** Every original source has indegree zero in the condensation and needs a new incoming edge. Every sink analogously needs a new outgoing edge. One new edge can satisfy at most one requirement of each type.

**Lemma 2.** The cyclic edges make every matched source-to-sink path part of one strongly connected component.

**Proof.** From a matched source, follow its DAG path to its sink, then the added edge to the next source. Repeating traverses the entire cycle of matched paths in both reachability directions around the cycle.

**Lemma 3.** After the leftover attachments, every condensation component joins that core in both directions.

**Proof.** Every DAG node is reachable from a source and can reach a sink. Leftover sources receive an incoming route from the core, and leftover sinks receive an outgoing route to the core. Direct leftover sink-to-source edges provide both attachments at once. Thus each node is reachable from the core through its source and can return through its sink.

**Theorem.** The construction is strongly connected and uses the minimum number of edges.

**Proof.** Lemmas 2 and 3 prove strong connectivity. The construction adds exactly $\max(S,T)$ edges, matching Lemma 1.

### Complexity

SCC decomposition, condensation traversal, and construction take $O(n+m)$ time and $O(n+m)$ space.

## Implementation

The iterative Tarjan traversal avoids stack overflow. Persistent visitation in the pairing DFS prevents repeated exploration; sinks terminate searches, so a visited sink is already matched. Parallel condensation edges are harmless.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD=1e9+7;
const int INF=1e9;

int n,m;
vector<vector<int>> adj;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr);
    cin>>n>>m;
    adj.assign(n+1,{});
    for(int i=0;i<m;i++){int a,b;cin>>a>>b;adj[a].pb(b);}

    // iterative Tarjan SCC  (su = dfs stack, it = current-arc, reused naming)
    vector<int> disc(n+1,0), low(n+1,0), comp(n+1,0), it(n+1,0);
    vector<char> onstk(n+1,0);
    vector<int> stk, su;
    int timer=0, C=0;
    for(int s0=1;s0<=n;s0++) if(!disc[s0]){
        su.pb(s0);
        while(!su.empty()){
            int u=su.back();
            if(!disc[u]){ disc[u]=low[u]=++timer; stk.pb(u); onstk[u]=1; }
            bool rec=false;
            while(it[u]<(int)adj[u].size()){
                int v=adj[u][it[u]++];
                if(!disc[v]){ su.pb(v); rec=true; break; }
                if(onstk[v]) low[u]=min(low[u],disc[v]);
            }
            if(rec) continue;
            if(low[u]==disc[u]){                       // root of an SCC
                ++C; int x;
                do{ x=stk.back(); stk.pop_back(); onstk[x]=0; comp[x]=C; }while(x!=u);
            }
            su.pop_back();
            if(!su.empty()) low[su.back()]=min(low[su.back()],low[u]);
        }
    }

    if(C==1){ cout<<0<<"\n"; return 0; }

    vector<int> rep(C+1,0), indeg(C+1,0), outdeg(C+1,0);
    vector<vector<int>> cadj(C+1);
    for(int u=1;u<=n;u++) rep[comp[u]]=u;
    for(int u=1;u<=n;u++) for(int v:adj[u]) if(comp[u]!=comp[v]){
        cadj[comp[u]].pb(comp[v]); outdeg[comp[u]]++; indeg[comp[v]]++;
    }

    vector<int> sources, sinks;
    for(int c=1;c<=C;c++){ if(!indeg[c]) sources.pb(c); if(!outdeg[c]) sinks.pb(c); }

    // greedy disjoint source->sink pairing (persistent visited => sinks terminate => visited sink == matched sink)
    vector<char> vis(C+1,0), used(C+1,0);
    vector<int> cit(C+1,0), pS, pT, st2;
    for(int sc:sources){
        if(vis[sc]) continue;
        st2.clear(); st2.pb(sc); int found=-1;
        while(!st2.empty()){
            int u=st2.back(); vis[u]=1;
            if(outdeg[u]==0 && !used[u]){ found=u; break; }
            bool adv=false;
            while(cit[u]<(int)cadj[u].size()){
                int v=cadj[u][cit[u]++];
                if(!vis[v]){ st2.pb(v); adv=true; break; }
            }
            if(!adv) st2.pop_back();
        }
        if(found!=-1){ used[found]=1; pS.pb(sc); pT.pb(found); }
    }

    int p=pS.size();
    vector<char> mS(C+1,0), mT(C+1,0);
    for(int x:pS) mS[x]=1;
    for(int x:pT) mT[x]=1;
    vector<int> q, r;                                  // leftover sources / sinks
    for(int c:sources) if(!mS[c]) q.pb(c);
    for(int c:sinks)   if(!mT[c]) r.pb(c);
    int a=q.size(), b=r.size();

    vector<ii> e;                                      // (fromComp, toComp)
    for(int i=0;i<p;i++) e.pb({pT[i], pS[(i+1)%p]});   // fuse matched paths into one SCC M
    int mn=min(a,b);
    for(int j=0;j<mn;j++) e.pb({r[j], q[j]});          // one edge serves a leftover sink AND source
    for(int j=mn;j<a;j++) e.pb({pT[0], q[j]});         // feed remaining extra sources
    for(int j=mn;j<b;j++) e.pb({r[j], pS[0]});         // drain remaining extra sinks

    cout<<e.size()<<"\n";
    for(auto&ed:e) cout<<rep[ed.f]<<" "<<rep[ed.s]<<"\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

Suppose the condensation has sources $A,B$ and sinks $X,Y,Z$, with matched paths $A\leadsto X$ and $B\leadsto Y$. Add $X\to B$ and $Y\to A$ to form the core, then add $Z\to A$. Three edges are used, equal to $\max(2,3)$.

## Takeaway

For strong-connectivity augmentation, always contract SCCs first. The remaining problem is governed entirely by sources and sinks of a DAG.

### Related problems

Planets and Kingdoms, Flight Routes Check, Flight Route Requests.

