# Split into Two Paths

- **Problem:** [CSES 3358](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3358)
- **Code:** [View accepted C++ solution (splitintotwopaths.cpp)](./splitintotwopaths.cpp)

## Problem

Partition all vertices of a directed acyclic graph into two vertex-disjoint directed paths. Either path may be empty. Output a partition when one exists.

## Reasoning

Take a topological order $v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_n$. After processing a prefix, the newest vertex $v_i$ must be the tail of one path: no earlier vertex can appear after it in a directed path because that would contradict the topological order.

This leaves only the tail of the other path as state. Let $G_i$ be the set of vertices $w$ such that the first $i$ vertices can be covered by two paths whose tails are $v_i$ and $w$. A special value $0$ means the other path is empty.

To insert $x=v_{i+1}$, there are exactly two possibilities:

1. Append $x$ after $v_i$. This is legal if edge $v_i\to x$ exists, and every $w\in G_i$ remains possible.
2. Append $x$ after the other tail $w$, or start the empty path. The former tail $v_i$ then becomes the new other tail. Thus $v_i$ enters $G_{i+1}$ when some $w\in G_i$ has edge $w\to x$, or when $0\in G_i$.

No other transition exists because $x$ must be appended to one of the two current paths. The set can be maintained without copying: option 1 either preserves all current members or discards them all, while option 2 adds only $v_i$.

## Algorithm

1. Compute a topological ordering with Kahn's algorithm.
2. Initialize $G_1=\{0\}$.
3. For each consecutive pair $(v_i,x)$:
   - scan incoming edges of $x$ to test whether $v_i\to x$ exists;
   - test whether any predecessor of $x$ belongs to $G_i$, also allowing state $0$;
   - preserve or clear $G_i$ according to option 1, then add $v_i$ when option 2 is possible;
   - store a witness predecessor for option 2.
4. If $G_n$ is empty, print `NO`.
5. Otherwise choose any final other tail and backtrack. At step $i$, if the other tail equals $v_i$, option 2 was used; otherwise option 1 was used.
6. Convert predecessor pointers into the two paths and print them.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** After processing $v_1,\ldots,v_i$, $G_i$ contains exactly the possible tails of the path not ending at $v_i$.

**Proof.** The base case $G_1=\{0\}$ represents the path containing $v_1$ and one empty path. For the induction step, the new topological maximum $x$ must be appended to one of the two existing paths. Appending it after $v_i$ preserves the other tail and is possible exactly when $v_i\to x$ exists. Appending it after the other tail requires the corresponding edge, or an empty second path, and makes $v_i$ the other tail. These are exactly the two update rules, so every valid cover is included and every stored state is realizable.

**Lemma 2.** Backtracking reconstructs two valid paths covering every vertex exactly once.

**Proof.** Each backward step selects one transition certified by Lemma 1. The stored witness identifies the previous other tail when option 2 was used. Assigning the corresponding predecessor edge attaches the current vertex to exactly one earlier tail. Every vertex except the two path starts receives one predecessor, and every tail receives at most one successor, yielding two disjoint directed paths over all vertices.

**Theorem.** The algorithm prints `YES` with a valid partition exactly when such a partition exists.

**Proof.** If $G_n$ is nonempty, Lemma 2 constructs a valid partition. If it is empty, Lemma 1 states that no pair of path tails can cover the complete topological order, so no partition exists.

### Complexity

The CSR graph construction, topological sort, state transitions, and reconstruction take $O(n+m)$ time. All arrays and path storage use $O(n+m)$ space.

## Implementation

Forward and reverse adjacency are stored in CSR arrays. During a transition, only predecessors of the new vertex are scanned. `inG` provides constant-time state membership, `members` supports clearing the current set, and `wit[x]` stores the exact predecessor needed for reconstruction.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int n, m;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    cin >> n >> m;
    vector<int> ea(m), eb(m), fo(n+2,0), ro(n+2,0), indeg(n+1,0);
    for(int i=0;i<m;i++){ cin>>ea[i]>>eb[i]; fo[ea[i]+1]++; ro[eb[i]+1]++; indeg[eb[i]]++; }
    for(int u=1;u<=n+1;u++){ fo[u]+=fo[u-1]; ro[u]+=ro[u-1]; }
    vector<int> fg(m), rg(m), pf(fo.begin(),fo.end()), pr(ro.begin(),ro.end());
    for(int i=0;i<m;i++){ fg[pf[ea[i]]++]=eb[i]; rg[pr[eb[i]]++]=ea[i]; }   // fg: succ of a ; rg: pred of b

    vector<int> ord; ord.reserve(n);                                        // Kahn topo order
    for(int u=1;u<=n;u++) if(!indeg[u]) ord.pb(u);
    for(size_t h=0;h<ord.size();h++){ int u=ord[h]; for(int e=fo[u];e<fo[u+1];e++) if(--indeg[fg[e]]==0) ord.pb(fg[e]); }

    // width<=2 DP: ord[i] is always a chain tail; g(i) = feasible other tails (0 = empty chain).
    // g(i+1) = (ord[i]->ord[i+1] ? g(i):{}) U (exists w in g(i): w->ord[i+1] or w=0 ? {ord[i]}:{})
    vector<char> inG(n+1,0);
    vector<int> members; members.reserve(n);
    vector<int> wit(n+1,0);                                                 // option2 witness pred (0 => starts a chain)
    bool zeroIn = true;                                                     // g(1) = {0}

    for(int i=0;i+1<n;i++){
        int cur=ord[i], nxt=ord[i+1];
        bool a=false,b=false; int w=0;
        for(int e=ro[nxt];e<ro[nxt+1];e++){ int p=rg[e]; if(p==cur) a=true; if(inG[p]&&!b){ b=true; w=p; } }
        if(zeroIn&&!b){ b=true; w=0; }                                      // empty other chain can begin anywhere
        wit[nxt]=w;
        if(a){ if(b&&!inG[cur]){ inG[cur]=1; members.pb(cur); } }           // carry g(i); option2 may also add cur
        else { for(int x:members) inG[x]=0; members.clear(); zeroIn=false; if(b){ inG[cur]=1; members.pb(cur); } }  // reset
    }

    if(members.empty()&&!zeroIn){ cout<<"NO\n"; return 0; }

    int other = members.empty()?0:members.back();                          // any element of g(n)
    vector<int> pred(n+1,0);
    for(int i=n-2;i>=0;i--){                                                // backtrack: other==cur => option2 else option1
        int cur=ord[i], nxt=ord[i+1];
        if(other==cur){ pred[nxt]=wit[nxt]; other=wit[nxt]; }
        else pred[nxt]=cur;
    }

    vector<int> nxtv(n+1,0);
    for(int v=1;v<=n;v++) if(pred[v]) nxtv[pred[v]]=v;
    vector<vector<int>> paths;
    for(int v=1;v<=n;v++) if(pred[v]==0){ vector<int> p; int c=v; while(c){ p.pb(c); c=nxtv[c]; } paths.pb(move(p)); }

    cout<<"YES\n";
    auto outp=[&](vector<int>&p){ cout<<p.size(); for(int x:p) cout<<' '<<x; cout<<"\n"; };
    outp(paths[0]);
    if(paths.size()==2) outp(paths[1]); else cout<<0<<"\n";                 // second chain may be empty
}
```

## Worked Example

For topological order $(1,3,2,4,5)$ with edges $1\to2$, $1\to4$, $3\to4$, and $4\to5$, begin with tails $(1,0)$. Vertex $3$ starts the second path, giving tails $(3,1)$. Vertex $2$ extends after $1$, giving $(2,3)$. Then $4$ extends after $3$, and $5$ extends after $4$. Backtracking returns paths $1\to2$ and $3\to4\to5$.

## Takeaway

When a DAG must be covered by a constant number of paths, process a topological order and track only current path tails. For width two, one tail is forced to be the newest vertex, collapsing the state to a dynamically maintained set.

### Related problems

Course Schedule II, Longest Flight Route, Distinct Routes II.

