# Strongly Connected Edges

- **CSES task:** [Strongly Connected Edges](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2177)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (stronglyconnectededges.cpp)`](./stronglyconnectededges.cpp)

## Problem

Orient every edge of a simple undirected graph so the directed result is strongly connected, or report impossibility.

## Reasoning

Robbins' theorem states that such an orientation exists exactly when the undirected graph is connected and has no bridge. A bridge cannot work because all traffic between its two sides would need both directions through one directed edge.

DFS constructs the orientation and tests the condition simultaneously. Orient tree edges from parent to child and non-tree edges from descendant toward ancestor. Every vertex is reachable from the root along tree edges. If no tree edge is a bridge, each child subtree has a back edge reaching above its parent edge; chaining these upward routes lets every vertex reach the root. Hence all pairs communicate through the root.

Low-link values detect bridges: tree edge $p-u$ is a bridge exactly when `low[u] > tin[p]`.

## Algorithm

Run iterative DFS from vertex 1. Orient discovery edges downward and each non-tree edge from deeper endpoint to shallower endpoint. Compute `tin` and `low` in postorder. Reject upon any bridge or an unvisited vertex; otherwise print orientations in input order.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** If the algorithm accepts, every vertex is reachable from vertex 1.

**Proof.** Every DFS tree edge is directed from parent to child, so its tree path gives reachability from the root. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** If the algorithm accepts, every vertex can reach vertex 1.

**Proof.** No parent edge is a bridge, so each subtree has a back edge from some descendant to a strict ancestor of its root. Tree edges reach that descendant downward, then the back edge moves upward. Repetition reaches the global root. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm prints a strongly connected orientation exactly when one exists.

**Proof.** Lemmas 1 and 2 give strong connectivity. If the graph is disconnected, orientation cannot connect components. If it has a bridge, its two sides cannot both cross the single directed bridge, proving rejection necessary. $\square$

### Complexity

DFS and low-link processing take $O(n+m)$ time and space.

## Implementation

Edge identifiers ensure an undirected parent edge is skipped exactly once. The iterative stack updates a child's low-link into its parent only after the child finishes.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n, m; cin >> n >> m;
    vector<vector<pair<int,int>>> adj(n + 1);   // (to, edge id)
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b;
        adj[a].pb({b, i}); adj[b].pb({a, i});
    }
    vector<int> tin(n + 1, 0), low(n + 1, 0), par(n + 1, 0), pare(n + 1, -1), it(n + 1, 0);
    vector<pair<int,int>> ored(m);
    int timer = 0; bool bad = false;

    // iterative DFS from 1: tree edges down, back edges up; flag bridges
    vector<int> st;
    tin[1] = low[1] = ++timer; st.pb(1);
    while(!st.empty()){
        int u = st.back();
        if(it[u] < (int)adj[u].size()){
            auto [w, e] = adj[u][it[u]++];
            if(e == pare[u]) continue;          // skip single parent edge once
            if(!tin[w]){                         // tree edge
                ored[e] = {u, w};
                tin[w] = low[w] = ++timer; par[w] = u; pare[w] = e;
                st.pb(w);
            } else {                             // non-tree: orient desc -> anc
                low[u] = min(low[u], tin[w]);
                ored[e] = (tin[u] > tin[w]) ? make_pair(u, w) : make_pair(w, u);
            }
        } else {
            st.pop_back();
            int p = par[u];
            if(p){
                low[p] = min(low[p], low[u]);
                if(low[u] > tin[p]) bad = true;  // bridge
            }
        }
    }
    for(int v = 1; v <= n; v++) if(!tin[v]) bad = true;   // disconnected

    if(bad){ cout << "IMPOSSIBLE\n"; return 0; }
    string out; out.reserve(m * 12);
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        out += to_string(ored[i].f); out += ' ';
        out += to_string(ored[i].s); out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

For a triangle rooted at 1, tree edges may become `1->2` and `2->3`, while the non-tree edge becomes `3->1`. This directed cycle is strongly connected and no DFS edge is a bridge.

## Takeaway

Bridge-free undirected graphs admit strong orientations: tree edges go down, back edges go up, and low links certify that upward escape always exists.

### Related problems

Necessary Roads finds the same bridges but reports them instead of using their absence constructively.

