# Tree Isomorphism I

- **CSES task:** [Tree Isomorphism I](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1700)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (treeisomorphism.cpp)`](./treeisomorphism.cpp)

## Problem

For each test, decide whether two trees rooted at vertex 1 are isomorphic as rooted unlabeled trees.

## Reasoning

A rooted tree is determined recursively by the multiset of its child subtree shapes. Assign every distinct sorted vector of child identifiers a unique integer identifier. Leaves all receive the identifier of the empty vector. Processing vertices bottom-up ensures child identifiers are known before the parent.

Both trees must share the same intern table. Then equal identifiers mean equal canonical structures across trees, not merely within one tree.

## Algorithm

Root each tree at 1 with BFS and record parent order. Traverse that order backward. Sort each vertex's collected child identifiers and intern the vector in a shared map. Compare the two root identifiers.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Two rooted subtrees receive the same identifier exactly when they are isomorphic.

**Proof.** Leaves share the empty signature. Inductively, rooted subtrees are isomorphic exactly when their roots have the same multiset of isomorphic child subtrees. Sorting child identifiers gives equal vectors exactly in that case, and interning assigns equal identifiers exactly to equal vectors. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm answers `YES` exactly when the two rooted trees are isomorphic.

**Proof.** Apply Lemma 1 to their roots, using the shared intern table. $\square$

### Complexity

Across a tree, sorting child lists costs $O(n\log n)$ in the conservative bound. Space is $O(n)$ plus canonical signatures.

## Implementation

The BFS vector doubles as a bottom-up order when traversed backward. Child identifiers are accumulated into `ch[parent]` only after the child signature is finalized.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n;

int build(vector<vector<int>>& adj, int par[], int dep[], int id[], map<vector<int>,int>& mp){
    // iterative BFS root=1: parent/depth
    vector<int> bfs; bfs.reserve(n);
    vector<char> vis(n + 1, 0);
    dep[1] = 0; par[1] = 0; vis[1] = 1; bfs.pb(1);
    for(int h = 0; h < (int)bfs.size(); h++){
        int u = bfs[h];
        for(int w : adj[u]) if(!vis[w]){ vis[w] = 1; dep[w] = dep[u] + 1; par[w] = u; bfs.pb(w); }
    }
    vector<vector<int>> ch(n + 1);            // children ids gathered bottom-up
    for(int i = (int)bfs.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--){
        int u = bfs[i];
        sort(ch[u].begin(), ch[u].end());     // sibling-order invariance
        auto it = mp.find(ch[u]);
        if(it == mp.end()) id[u] = mp[ch[u]] = (int)mp.size();
        else id[u] = it->s;
        if(u != 1) ch[par[u]].pb(id[u]);
    }
    return id[1];
}

int par1[100005], dep1[100005], idv1[100005];
int par2[100005], dep2[100005], idv2[100005];

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int t; cin >> t;
    string out;
    while(t--){
        cin >> n;
        vector<vector<int>> a1(n + 1), a2(n + 1);
        for(int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++){ int u, v; cin >> u >> v; a1[u].pb(v); a1[v].pb(u); }
        for(int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++){ int u, v; cin >> u >> v; a2[u].pb(v); a2[v].pb(u); }
        map<vector<int>,int> mp;              // shared intern table across both trees
        int r1 = build(a1, par1, dep1, idv1, mp);
        int r2 = build(a2, par2, dep2, idv2, mp);
        out += (r1 == r2) ? "YES\n" : "NO\n";
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

A root with child signatures `[leaf, path-of-two]` receives the sorted vector of those two identifiers. Reordering the children in the second input yields the same sorted signature and therefore the same root identifier.

## Takeaway

Canonicalize unordered rooted trees bottom-up by interning sorted multisets of child shapes.

### Related problems

Tree Isomorphism II first chooses canonical roots because its trees are unrooted.

