# Tree Isomorphism II

- **CSES task:** [Tree Isomorphism II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1701)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (treeisomorphism2.cpp)`](./treeisomorphism2.cpp)

## Problem

Decide whether two unrooted unlabeled trees are isomorphic.

## Reasoning

An unrooted tree has one center or two adjacent centers, obtained by repeatedly deleting all leaves. Every isomorphism maps centers to centers. Therefore it suffices to root each tree at its center candidates and compare rooted canonical forms.

For a chosen root, assign an identifier to the sorted multiset of child identifiers bottom-up. Both trees and all center choices use one shared intern table. With two centers, trying the constant number of root pairings handles their possible exchange.

## Algorithm

Peel leaves to find each tree's one or two centers. Reject if center counts differ. For every center, compute its rooted canonical identifier using shared signature interning. Accept if any identifier from the first tree equals one from the second.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Every tree isomorphism maps the center set of one tree onto the center set of the other.

**Proof.** Leaf peeling depends only on adjacency and is preserved under isomorphism. The final one or two vertices are therefore preserved. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** Equal rooted identifiers are equivalent to rooted-tree isomorphism.

**Proof.** Bottom-up sorted child signatures give the standard inductive canonical form for unordered rooted trees. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm accepts exactly the isomorphic unrooted tree pairs.

**Proof.** An unrooted isomorphism maps some center pair by Lemma 1 and then yields equal rooted identifiers by Lemma 2. Conversely, equal identifiers for a center pairing give a rooted isomorphism and therefore an unrooted one. $\square$

### Complexity

Leaf peeling is $O(n)$. Canonicalization is $O(n\log n)$ conservatively, with $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

`centers` tracks residual degree and removes layers until at most two vertices remain. The shared `map<vector<int>,int>` makes identifiers comparable across both trees and every tested center.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int n;

int build(vector<vector<int>>& adj, int root, int par[], int dep[], int id[], map<vector<int>,int>& mp){
    // iterative BFS from root: parent/depth
    vector<int> bfs; bfs.reserve(n);
    vector<char> vis(n + 1, 0);
    dep[root] = 0; par[root] = 0; vis[root] = 1; bfs.pb(root);
    for(int h = 0; h < (int)bfs.size(); h++){
        int u = bfs[h];
        for(int w : adj[u]) if(!vis[w]){ vis[w] = 1; dep[w] = dep[u] + 1; par[w] = u; bfs.pb(w); }
    }
    vector<vector<int>> ch(n + 1);            // children ids gathered bottom-up
    for(int i = (int)bfs.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--){
        int u = bfs[i];
        sort(ch[u].begin(), ch[u].end());     // sibling-order invariance
        auto it = mp.find(ch[u]);
        if(it == mp.end()) id[u] = mp[ch[u]] = (int)mp.size();
        else id[u] = it->s;
        if(u != root) ch[par[u]].pb(id[u]);
    }
    return id[root];
}

// leaf-peeling -> 1 or 2 centers
vector<int> centers(vector<vector<int>>& adj){
    vector<int> deg(n + 1), cur; cur.reserve(n);
    int rem = n;
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ deg[i] = (int)adj[i].size(); if(deg[i] <= 1) cur.pb(i); }
    while(rem > 2){
        vector<int> nxt;
        for(int u : cur){ rem--; for(int w : adj[u]) if(--deg[w] == 1) nxt.pb(w); }
        cur = move(nxt);
    }
    return cur;                               // size 1 or 2
}

int par1[100005], dep1[100005], idv1[100005];
int par2[100005], dep2[100005], idv2[100005];

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int t; cin >> t;
    string out;
    while(t--){
        cin >> n;
        vector<vector<int>> a1(n + 1), a2(n + 1);
        for(int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++){ int u, v; cin >> u >> v; a1[u].pb(v); a1[v].pb(u); }
        for(int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++){ int u, v; cin >> u >> v; a2[u].pb(v); a2[v].pb(u); }
        vector<int> c1 = centers(a1), c2 = centers(a2);
        if(c1.size() != c2.size()){ out += "NO\n"; continue; }
        map<vector<int>,int> mp;              // shared intern table across both trees
        vector<int> h1, h2;
        for(int r : c1) h1.pb(build(a1, r, par1, dep1, idv1, mp));
        for(int r : c2) h2.pb(build(a2, r, par2, dep2, idv2, mp));
        bool ok = false;                      // any center-pairing matches
        for(int x : h1) for(int y : h2) if(x == y) ok = true;
        out += ok ? "YES\n" : "NO\n";
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

A path with an odd number of vertices has one center; an even path has two. Two paths of the same size produce matching center-rooted signatures even if their input labels are reversed.

## Takeaway

Canonicalize an unrooted tree by first rooting it at its invariant center set, then apply rooted-tree hashing or exact signature interning.

### Related problems

Prüfer codes canonicalize labeled trees differently; tree centers are the key invariant for unlabeled isomorphism.

