# Tree Traversals

- **CSES task:** [Tree Traversals](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1702)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (treetraversals.cpp)`](./treetraversals.cpp)

## Problem

Given preorder and inorder traversals of a binary tree with distinct labels, output its postorder traversal for $n\le10^5$.

## Reasoning

The first element of a preorder segment is its root. Its position in inorder divides that inorder segment into left and right subtrees. The left subtree size then determines the matching preorder ranges. This uniquely reconstructs the recursive structure.

A direct recursive function may reach depth $n$ and overflow the call stack. The implementation simulates recursion with explicit tasks. A subtree task expands into root-output, right-subtree, and left-subtree tasks pushed in that order, so LIFO execution processes left, then right, then root, exactly postorder.

## Algorithm

Map every label to its inorder position. Start with one task describing both full traversal intervals. Pop tasks until empty. An output task appends its root; a subtree task finds the root split, pushes its delayed output task, then right and left subtree tasks.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Every subtree task stores the correct preorder and inorder intervals for the same subtree.

**Proof.** The preorder first value is the root. Its inorder position gives left size, which partitions both traversals into matching left and right ranges. Induction applies to pushed tasks. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the tree's postorder traversal.

**Proof.** By Lemma 1, every expanded task identifies the correct root and children. Stack push order executes the complete left subtree, then right subtree, then the delayed root output. This is the definition of postorder for every subtree, including the full tree. $\square$

### Complexity

Every node creates and processes a constant number of tasks. Time and space are $O(n)$.

## Implementation

Task field `tp=1` denotes delayed root output. Empty subtree ranges are skipped. The explicit stack prevents recursion failure on a completely skewed tree.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    ll n;
    cin >> n;

    vi pre(n), in(n), pos(n + 1), ans;
    ans.reserve(n);

    for (ll &x : pre) cin >> x;
    for (ll i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> in[i];
        pos[in[i]] = i;
    }

    vector<array<ll, 5>> st;
    st.pb({0, 0, n - 1, 0, n - 1});

    while (!st.empty()) {
        auto cur = st.back();
        st.pop_back();

        ll tp = cur[0];

        if (tp == 1) {
            ans.pb(cur[1]);
            continue;
        }

        ll pl = cur[1], pr = cur[2], il = cur[3], ir = cur[4];
        if (pl > pr) continue;

        ll root = pre[pl];
        ll mid = pos[root];
        ll ls = mid - il;

        st.pb({1, root, 0, 0, 0});

        if (pl + ls + 1 <= pr) {
            st.pb({0, pl + ls + 1, pr, mid + 1, ir});
        }

        if (ls > 0) {
            st.pb({0, pl + 1, pl + ls, il, mid - 1});
        }
    }

    for (ll i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << ans[i] << " \n"[i + 1 == n];
    }

    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

Preorder `[5,3,2,1,4]` begins with root 5. In inorder `[3,5,1,2,4]`, root 5 splits off left subtree `[3]` and right subtree rooted at 2. Their postorders are `[3]` and `[1,4,2]`, followed by 5.

## Takeaway

Traversal reconstruction is interval recursion. When depth may be linear, encode recursive calls and delayed actions explicitly on a stack.

### Related problems

Expression-tree evaluation and iterative DFS use the same delayed-output task pattern.

