# Visiting Cities

- **Problem:** [CSES 1203](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1203)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (visitingcities.cpp)`](./visitingcities.cpp)

## Problem

Find every vertex that occurs on every shortest directed path from vertex $1$ to vertex $n$.

## Reasoning

Run Dijkstra from $1$ and on the reversed graph from $n$. An edge $(u,v,w)$ belongs to some shortest path exactly when

$$d_s(u)+w+d_t(v)=d_s(n).$$

Positive edge weights make $d_s$ strictly increase along these edges, so they form a DAG. The question is now: which vertices dominate $n$ in this shortest-path DAG?

In a DAG processed topologically, the strict dominators common to all paths into $v$ are the intersection of the dominator chains of its predecessors. Dominators form a tree, and the deepest common vertex of several root-to-predecessor chains is their LCA. Therefore

$$\operatorname{idom}(v)=\operatorname{LCA}_{D}(p_1,p_2,\ldots),$$

where $p_i$ are the predecessors of $v$ and $D$ is the dominator tree built so far.

## Algorithm

1. Compute distances from the source and to the target with two Dijkstra runs.
2. Keep precisely the vertices and directed edges that lie on shortest paths.
3. Sort retained vertices by source distance, which is a topological order.
4. Process each vertex $v\ne1$. Fold LCA over all shortest-DAG predecessors to obtain its immediate dominator, then attach $v$ to the dominator tree and fill its lifting table.
5. Traverse the dominator tree to assign subtree intervals.
6. Output exactly the ancestors of $n$ in that tree.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The retained graph contains exactly all shortest paths from $1$ to $n$ and is acyclic.

**Proof.** The distance equality is necessary and sufficient for an edge to extend a shortest prefix into a shortest complete path. Along such an edge, positive weight gives $d_s(v)>d_s(u)$, precluding a cycle.

**Lemma 2.** When $v$ is processed, the LCA of all its predecessors in the current dominator tree is the immediate dominator of $v$.

**Proof.** Every path to $v$ ends through one predecessor. Thus a vertex dominates $v$ exactly when it dominates every predecessor. Each predecessor's dominators are its ancestors in the already-built dominator tree. Their common set is the ancestor chain ending at their deepest common ancestor, the LCA. That deepest strict dominator is the immediate dominator of $v$.

**Lemma 3.** A vertex occurs on every shortest source-to-target path exactly when it is an ancestor of $n$ in the constructed dominator tree.

**Proof.** By definition, such a vertex dominates $n$. Lemma 2 constructs the dominator tree, whose ancestor relation represents domination.

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs exactly the cities visited by every shortest route.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 reduces the problem to domination in the shortest-path DAG, and Lemmas 2 and 3 identify precisely the required vertices.

### Complexity

The Dijkstra runs cost $O((n+m)\log n)$. Dominator construction costs $O((n+m)\log n)$, and space is $O(n\log n+m)$.

## Implementation

The code processes vertices by increasing `ds`, so every predecessor already has a lifting row. Euler intervals `[tin, tout)` make the final ancestor test constant time. This deterministic construction avoids collision-prone path-count hashing.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;
const ll INF = (ll)4e18;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    vector<tuple<int,int,ll>> edges;
    vector<vector<pair<int,ll>>> g(n + 1), rg(n + 1);
    for(int i = 0; i < m; ++i){
        int a, b; ll w;
        cin >> a >> b >> w;
        edges.push_back({a,b,w});
        g[a].push_back({b,w});
        rg[b].push_back({a,w});
    }

    auto dijkstra = [&](int s, const vector<vector<pair<int,ll>>>& adj){
        vector<ll> d(n + 1, INF);
        priority_queue<pair<ll,int>, vector<pair<ll,int>>, greater<pair<ll,int>>> pq;
        d[s] = 0; pq.push({0,s});
        while(!pq.empty()){
            auto [du,u] = pq.top(); pq.pop();
            if(du != d[u]) continue;
            for(auto [v,w] : adj[u]) if(du + w < d[v]){
                d[v] = du + w;
                pq.push({d[v],v});
            }
        }
        return d;
    };

    vector<ll> ds = dijkstra(1,g), dt = dijkstra(n,rg);
    ll best = ds[n];
    vector<vector<int>> pred(n + 1);
    vector<int> order;
    for(int v = 1; v <= n; ++v)
        if(ds[v] < INF && dt[v] < INF && ds[v] + dt[v] == best) order.push_back(v);
    for(auto [a,b,w] : edges)
        if(ds[a] < INF && dt[b] < INF && ds[a] + w + dt[b] == best) pred[b].push_back(a);
    sort(order.begin(), order.end(), [&](int a, int b){ return ds[a] < ds[b]; });

    const int LOG = 20;
    vector<array<int,LOG>> up(n + 1);
    vector<int> depth(n + 1, 0), tin(n + 1), tout(n + 1);
    int timer = 0;
    auto lca = [&](int a, int b){
        if(depth[a] < depth[b]) swap(a,b);
        int diff = depth[a] - depth[b];
        for(int k = 0; k < LOG; ++k) if(diff >> k & 1) a = up[a][k];
        if(a == b) return a;
        for(int k = LOG - 1; k >= 0; --k) if(up[a][k] != up[b][k]){
            a = up[a][k]; b = up[b][k];
        }
        return up[a][0];
    };

    vector<vector<int>> domTree(n + 1);
    up[1].fill(1);
    for(int v : order){
        if(v == 1) continue;
        int p = pred[v][0];
        for(int u : pred[v]) p = lca(p,u);
        depth[v] = depth[p] + 1;
        up[v][0] = p;
        for(int k = 1; k < LOG; ++k) up[v][k] = up[up[v][k-1]][k-1];
        domTree[p].push_back(v);
    }

    vector<pair<int,int>> st{{1,0}};
    while(!st.empty()){
        int u = st.back().first;
        int &i = st.back().second;
        if(i == 0) tin[u] = timer++;
        if(i < (int)domTree[u].size()) st.push_back({domTree[u][i++],0});
        else { tout[u] = timer; st.pop_back(); }
    }

    vector<int> ans;
    for(int v : order) if(tin[v] <= tin[n] && tin[n] < tout[v]) ans.push_back(v);
    sort(ans.begin(), ans.end());
    cout << ans.size() << '\n';
    for(int i = 0; i < (int)ans.size(); ++i) cout << ans[i] << " \n"[i + 1 == (int)ans.size()];
}
```

## Worked Example

Suppose the shortest-path DAG has edges $1\to2$, $1\to3$, $2\to4$, $3\to4$, and $4\to5$. Vertices $2$ and $3$ have dominator $1$. Their LCA is $1$, so `idom(4)=1`. Vertex $5$ has only predecessor $4$, hence `idom(5)=4`. The ancestors of $5$ are $1,4,5$, exactly the vertices on both shortest routes.

## Takeaway

After shortest-path filtering produces a DAG, universal membership is a dominator question. On a DAG, immediate dominators can be built incrementally with LCA.

### Related problems

Critical Cities, Investigation, Longest Flight Route.

