# All Letter Subgrid Count I

- **CSES problem:** 3415
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (alllettersubgrid1.cpp)`](./alllettersubgrid1.cpp)

## Problem

Count square subgrids containing every one of the first $k$ uppercase letters.

## Reasoning

Fix a top-left corner $(i,j)$. For each letter $c$, define $S_c(i,j)$ as the minimum side length of a square beginning there that contains $c$, or infinity if no such square exists.

If the current cell is $c$, the value is 1. Otherwise the first occurrence of $c$ in an anchored square must lie in the square obtained by expanding from one of the anchors directly below, right, or diagonally below-right. This yields

$$
S_c(i,j)=1+\min(S_c(i+1,j),S_c(i,j+1),S_c(i+1,j+1)).
$$

The smallest side containing all letters is

$$
T(i,j)=\max_c S_c(i,j).
$$

If the largest square fitting at the corner has side $M=n-\max(i,j)$, then every side from $T$ through $M$ is valid, contributing $M-T+1$.

The implementation processes one letter at a time with rolling rows and stores only the accumulated maximum threshold per cell.

## Algorithm

1. Return zero if any required letter is absent globally.
2. For each letter, scan cells from bottom-right to top-left and compute its minimum containing-square side with rolling rows.
3. Maximize the stored threshold of every corner with this letter's value.
4. For each corner, add the number of fitting side lengths at least its threshold.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

$S_c(i,j)$ is the minimum anchored square side containing letter $c$.

#### Proof

If the anchor is $c$, side 1 is minimal. Otherwise, removing the top row or left column from any larger anchored square locates its first possible $c$ within one of the three neighboring anchored squares. The minimum neighboring requirement plus one is necessary. Expanding the minimizing neighboring square by one row and column is sufficient. $\square$

### Lemma 2

An anchored square contains all letters exactly when its side is at least $T(i,j)$.

#### Proof

It contains letter $c$ exactly when its side is at least $S_c$. Satisfying all such inequalities is equivalent to being at least their maximum. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm counts every square containing all letters exactly once.

#### Proof

For each top-left corner, Lemma 2 shows the valid sides are precisely the integer interval $[T,M]$. The algorithm adds its size, and every square has one unique top-left corner and side. $\square$

### Complexity

The per-letter scans take $O(kn^2)$ time. The threshold grid and rolling rows use $O(n^2+n)$ space.

## Implementation

`INF` represents absence. The recurrence guards infinity before adding one. The flat threshold array improves locality for $n=3000$.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

const ll INF = 1e9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    ll n, k;
    cin >> n >> k;

    vector<string> g(n);
    for(auto &str : g) cin >> str;

    vector<char> gr((size_t)n*n);
    vi cnt(26, 0);
    for(ll i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for(ll j = 0; j < n; j++){
            char ch = g[i][j];
            gr[(size_t)i*n+j] = ch;
            cnt[ch-'A']++;
        }

    for(ll c = 0; c < k; c++) if(!cnt[c]){ cout << 0 << '\n'; return 0; }

    vi t((size_t)n*n, 0);   // accumulated max over letters = threshold
    vi pr(n), cu(n);        // rolling rows of S_c (row i+1, row i)

    for(ll c = 0; c < k; c++){
        char ch = 'A' + c;
        for(ll j = 0; j < n; j++) pr[j] = INF;     // row i+1 = n (none)
        for(ll i = n-1; i >= 0; i--){
            ll rightS = INF;                        // cur[i][j+1]
            size_t base = (size_t)i*n;
            for(ll j = n-1; j >= 0; j--){
                ll v;
                if(gr[base+j] == ch) v = 1;
                else {
                    ll diag = (j+1<n) ? pr[j+1] : INF;
                    ll m = min(pr[j], min(rightS, diag));
                    v = (m >= INF) ? INF : m+1;
                }
                cu[j] = v;
                rightS = v;
                if(v > t[base+j]) t[base+j] = v;
            }
            swap(pr, cu);
        }
    }

    ll ans = 0;
    for(ll i = 0; i < n; i++){
        size_t base = (size_t)i*n;
        for(ll j = 0; j < n; j++){
            ll ms = n - max(i, j);
            ll tt = t[base+j];
            if(tt <= ms) ans += (ms - tt + 1);
        }
    }
    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

At a corner, suppose minimum sides for letters A, B, and C are 1, 3, and 2. Then threshold is 3. If the largest fitting square has side 5, sides 3, 4, and 5 contribute three valid squares.

## Takeaway

For nested anchored shapes, compute the minimum size satisfying each requirement, take their maximum, and count all larger sizes that still fit.

### Related problems

All Letter Subgrid Count II handles rectangles with a top-bottom sweep. Filled Subgrid Count I also anchors squares but enforces uniformity.

