# Border Subgrid Count I

- **CSES problem:** 3417
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (bordersubgrid1.cpp)`](./bordersubgrid1.cpp)

## Problem

For each letter, count square subgrids whose entire border consists of that letter.

## Reasoning

For a square with top-left corner $(i,j)$ and side $s$, the top and left borders are valid when

$$
s\le A(i,j)=\min(Right(i,j),Down(i,j)).
$$

At bottom-right corner $(r,c)$, the bottom and right borders are valid when

$$
s\le B(r,c)=\min(Left(r,c),Up(r,c)).
$$

The two corners lie on one down-right diagonal. Index positions along a diagonal by $p$ for the top-left and $q$ for the bottom-right, so $s=q-p+1$. Define

$$
RA[p]=p+A[p]-1,\qquad LB[q]=q-B[q]+1.
$$

The square is valid exactly when $q\le RA[p]$ and $p\ge LB[q]$. The four runs automatically have one common letter: top and right meet at the top-right corner, connecting the top-left letter to the bottom-right letter.

Sweep $q$ along each diagonal. Keep prior $p$ active until its expiry `RA[p]`. A Fenwick tree over positions stores active top-left candidates. After removing expired candidates and inserting $p=q$ for the side-one square, a suffix count from `LB[q]` gives all valid squares ending at $q$.

## Algorithm

1. Precompute same-letter run lengths right, down, left, and up for every cell.
2. Form top-left bound $A=\min(R,D)$ and bottom-right bound $B=\min(Left,Up)$.
3. Process every down-right diagonal independently.
4. Sweep bottom-right index $q$, removing top-left indices whose reach ended before $q$ and inserting $q$.
5. Fenwick-query active indices at least `LB[q]` and add the count to the bottom-right letter.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

Diagonal pair $(p,q)$ defines a valid monochromatic-border square exactly when $q\le RA[p]$ and $p\ge LB[q]$.

#### Proof

The first inequality is equivalent to side $s=q-p+1\le A[p]$, so the top and left borders are uniform. The second is equivalent to $s\le B[q]$, so the bottom and right borders are uniform. Adjacent borders share corner cells, forcing all four uniform letters to agree. Conversely, every valid border satisfies all four run bounds and therefore both inequalities. $\square$

### Lemma 2

At sweep position $q$, the Fenwick tree contains exactly indices $p\le q$ with $RA[p]\ge q$.

#### Proof

Each $p$ is inserted when reached and scheduled for removal immediately after its last reachable $q=RA[p]$. Thus it is active precisely over $p..RA[p]$. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm counts every valid square border exactly once under its border letter.

#### Proof

At bottom-right $q$, Lemma 2 enforces the first condition of Lemma 1. The Fenwick suffix from $LB[q]$ enforces the second. Hence exactly valid top-left corners are counted. Every square has one diagonal and unique corner pair, so no duplication occurs. $\square$

### Complexity

Run preprocessing takes $O(n^2)$. Every cell causes $O(1)$ Fenwick operations on its diagonal, for $O(n^2\log n)$ time. The directional arrays use $O(n^2)$ space and diagonal work arrays use $O(n)$.

## Implementation

Expiry buckets `remHead` and `remNext` remove all candidates sharing one reach without a priority queue. Fenwick indices are shifted by one. `alive` lets a suffix count be computed as total active minus a prefix.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

