# Counting Bishops

- **CSES problem:** 2176
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (countingbishops.cpp)`](./countingbishops.cpp)

## Problem

Count placements of $k$ nonattacking bishops on an $n\times n$ chessboard, modulo $10^9+7$.

## Reasoning

A bishop never changes square color, so black-square and white-square placements are independent. Count ways to place each possible number on one color, then convolve the two counts.

Rotate the board conceptually so diagonals of one direction become rows and the perpendicular diagonals become columns. Squares of one color form a Ferrers board: after sorting row lengths $s_1\le s_2\le\cdots$, the available column sets are nested.

Let $f[j]$ count placements of $j$ nonattacking rooks, equivalently bishops, after processed rows. On a new row of length $s$, either place none or place the $j$th rook. The previous $j-1$ rooks occupy distinct columns, all available in this nested row, leaving $s-(j-1)$ choices:

$$
f_{new}[j]=f_{old}[j]+f_{old}[j-1](s-j+1).
$$

Update $j$ downward so the right-hand state remains from the previous row.

## Algorithm

1. For each board color, list lengths of diagonals belonging to that color and sort them.
2. Run the descending rook-polynomial DP over those lengths.
3. Let the resulting arrays be $c_0$ and $c_1$.
4. Sum $c_0[a]c_1[k-a]$ over feasible splits.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

For one color, after processing any sorted prefix of diagonals, $f[j]$ counts its nonattacking bishop placements of size $j$.

#### Proof

In the rotated Ferrers board, at most one bishop may use each row and column. Placements excluding the new row contribute $f_{old}[j]$. Placements using it arise from a valid $(j-1)$-placement and one of $s-(j-1)$ unoccupied available columns. Nested row sets ensure every previously occupied column belongs to the new row's column range. The cases are disjoint and exhaustive. $\square$

### Lemma 2

Placements on opposite colors do not attack each other.

#### Proof

Every diagonal contains squares of only one color, and a bishop remains on its square color along diagonal movement. Thus no diagonal contains bishops of both colors. $\square$

### Theorem

The convolution gives the number of nonattacking $k$-bishop placements.

#### Proof

By Lemma 1, each factor counts one color's valid placement. Lemma 2 allows any pair of such placements. Every full placement has a unique split $a,k-a$ by color, so the sum counts each exactly once. $\square$

### Complexity

There are $O(n)$ diagonals per color and at most $k$ DP states, so time is $O(nk+n\log n)$ and space is $O(k+n)$.

## Implementation

Diagonal index parity identifies square color. Lengths use `min(d,2n-2-d)+1`. The DP caps its size by the number of diagonals and skips nonpositive placement factors.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    ll n, k;
    cin >> n >> k;

    auto colorCnt = [&](int col)->vi{          // ways to place j non-attacking bishops on one color
        vector<int> sz;
        for(int d=0; d<=2*n-2; d++) if((d&1)==col) sz.pb(min<int>(d, 2*n-2-d)+1);
        sort(sz.begin(), sz.end());
        int K = min<ll>(k, (ll)sz.size());
        vi f(K+1, 0); f[0]=1;
        int cntp=0;
        for(int s : sz){
            cntp++;
            for(int j=min(K,cntp); j>=1; j--){     // j-th bishop on size-s diagonal
                ll factor = s-(j-1);
                if(factor<=0) continue;            // no free perpendicular slot
                f[j]=(f[j] + f[j-1]*(factor%MOD))%MOD;
            }
        }
        return f;
    };

    vi c0 = colorCnt(0), c1 = colorCnt(1);
    ll ans=0;
    for(int a=0; a<(int)c0.size(); a++){
        int b=k-a;
        if(b>=0 && b<(int)c1.size()) ans=(ans + c0[a]*c1[b])%MOD;
    }
    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For sorted one-color row lengths 1 and 3, after the first row there is one way to place one bishop. On the second row, a second bishop has $3-1=2$ column choices, so there are two two-bishop placements on that color.

## Takeaway

Bishop placements split by color and become rook placements on Ferrers boards. Sorted nested row lengths make the rook polynomial a simple one-dimensional DP.

### Related problems

Chessboard and Queens uses backtracking because queens couple rows, columns, and both diagonals. Counting Reorders also combines independent component polynomials.

