# Grid Paths II

- **CSES problem:** 1078
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (gridpaths2.cpp)`](./gridpaths2.cpp)

## Problem

Count monotone paths from $(1,1)$ to $(n,n)$ that move only right or down and avoid given trap cells.

## Reasoning

Without traps, paths from $(y_1,x_1)$ to $(y_2,x_2)$ use fixed numbers of down and right moves, so their count is

$$
\binom{(y_2-y_1)+(x_2-x_1)}{y_2-y_1}.
$$

The grid is too large for cell DP, but the number of traps is manageable. Sort traps by coordinates and append the destination. Let $dp[i]$ count paths from the start to point $p_i$ that avoid all earlier traps, while allowing arrival at $p_i$ itself.

Start with all unrestricted paths to $p_i$. Every invalid path has a unique first trap $p_j$ encountered. There are $dp[j]$ ways to reach that first trap without an earlier trap and an unrestricted number of monotone continuations from $p_j$ to $p_i$. Subtract this product for every reachable earlier trap.

At the appended destination, the resulting value excludes every trap and is the answer.

## Algorithm

1. Precompute factorials and inverse factorials through $2n$.
2. Sort traps together with destination $(n,n)$.
3. For each point $p_i$, initialize its count to unrestricted paths from the start.
4. For every earlier coordinatewise-reachable $p_j$, subtract `dp[j]*paths(p_j,p_i)`.
5. Output the destination state.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

The binomial formula counts all monotone paths between two coordinatewise ordered points.

#### Proof

Every path is a sequence containing exactly $y_2-y_1$ down moves and $x_2-x_1$ right moves. Choosing the positions of either move type uniquely determines it. $\square$

### Lemma 2

After computing $dp[i]$, it counts paths reaching $p_i$ whose first encountered special point among earlier traps is none.

#### Proof

Begin with every unrestricted path. Any path touching traps has a unique first trap $p_j$ in sorted reachability order. By induction, its prefix to $p_j$ is counted by $dp[j]$, and Lemma 1 counts its arbitrary continuation. Subtracting each first-trap class removes every invalid path once. $\square$

### Theorem

The destination state equals the number of trap-free paths.

#### Proof

The destination is processed after all coordinatewise preceding traps. Lemma 2 therefore removes exactly all paths touching at least one trap and retains every trap-free path. $\square$

### Complexity

With $m$ traps, preprocessing takes $O(n)$ time and the DP takes $O(m^2)$. Factorials, points, and DP use $O(n+m)$ space.

## Implementation

Points are pairs `(row,column)` and lexicographic sorting respects monotone precedence. The path helper returns zero for reversed coordinates. Modular subtraction is normalized after all earlier points are processed.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

ll pw(ll a, ll b){ ll r=1; a%=MOD; while(b){ if(b&1)r=r*a%MOD; a=a*a%MOD; b>>=1; } return r; }

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    ll n; int m;
    cin >> n >> m;

    int MX = 2*n + 5;
    vector<ll> fact(MX), finv(MX);
    fact[0]=1; for(int i=1;i<MX;i++) fact[i]=fact[i-1]*i%MOD;
    finv[MX-1]=pw(fact[MX-1],MOD-2); for(int i=MX-1;i>0;i--) finv[i-1]=finv[i]*i%MOD;
    auto C=[&](ll a,ll b)->ll{ if(b<0||b>a)return 0; return fact[a]*finv[b]%MOD*finv[a-b]%MOD; };

    vector<ii> p(m);
    for(auto &t : p){ ll y,x; cin>>y>>x; t={y,x}; }
    p.pb({n,n});                                   // destination as final node
    sort(p.begin(), p.end());

    int M = p.size();
    vi dp(M);
    auto paths=[&](ll y1,ll x1,ll y2,ll x2)->ll{   // monotone right/down paths
        if(y2<y1 || x2<x1) return 0;
        return C((y2-y1)+(x2-x1), y2-y1);
    };
    for(int i=0;i<M;i++){
        ll cur = paths(1,1,p[i].f,p[i].s);         // from start, ignoring traps
        for(int j=0;j<i;j++)
            if(p[j].f<=p[i].f && p[j].s<=p[i].s)
                cur=(cur - dp[j]*paths(p[j].f,p[j].s,p[i].f,p[i].s))%MOD;
        dp[i]=(cur%MOD+MOD)%MOD;
    }
    cout << dp[M-1] << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

On a $4\times4$ grid with trap $(2,2)$, there are $\binom63=20$ unrestricted paths. Two paths reach the trap, and $\binom42=6$ continue from it, so subtract $2\cdot6=12$ and obtain 8 valid paths.

## Takeaway

When a huge monotone grid has few forbidden points, replace cell DP with combinatorial path counts and subtract paths by their unique first obstacle.

### Related problems

Grid Paths uses ordinary cell DP on a small grid. Counting Sequences illustrates classical inclusion-exclusion over missing labels.

