# Tournament Graph Distribution

- **CSES problem:** 3232
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (tournamentgraph.cpp)`](./tournamentgraph.cpp)

## Problem

For each $k=1..n$, count labeled tournaments on $n$ vertices having exactly $k$ strongly connected components.

## Reasoning

There are

$$
C_m=2^{\binom m2}
$$

tournaments on $m$ labeled vertices. Let $s_m$ count strongly connected tournaments.

The condensation of a tournament is an acyclic tournament, hence a unique total order of its strongly connected components. In particular, every nonempty tournament has a unique last component. If it has size $m-j$, choose its vertices, require it to be strongly connected, place an arbitrary tournament on the preceding $j$ vertices, and force all cross edges toward the later component. Therefore

$$
s_m=C_m-\sum_{j=1}^{m-1}\binom mj C_j s_{m-j}.
$$

Use exponential generating coefficients $a_m=s_m/m!$. A tournament with exactly $k$ components is an ordered sequence of $k$ strongly connected tournaments, so its EGF is

$$
S(x)^k,\qquad S(x)=\sum_{m\ge1}a_mx^m.
$$

The required labeled count is $n![x^n]S(x)^k$. The source builds successive powers by ordinary coefficient convolution.

## Algorithm

1. Precompute factorials, inverse factorials, and total tournament counts.
2. Derive every strongly connected count from the unique-last-component recurrence.
3. Form EGF coefficient array $a_m=s_m/m!$.
4. Starting with $S^1$, repeatedly convolve by $S$.
5. For each $k$, output $n!$ times degree-$n$ coefficient of $S^k$.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

The recurrence computes $s_m$, the strongly connected tournament count.

#### Proof

Every non-strong tournament has a unique ordered last SCC of some size $m-j<m$. Choosing the preceding $j$ vertices, their arbitrary tournament, and the last strong tournament uniquely reconstructs it because all cross edges are forced by condensation order. Subtracting all such disjoint cases from $C_m$ leaves exactly strong tournaments. $\square$

### Lemma 2

$n![x^n]S(x)^k$ counts tournaments with exactly $k$ SCCs.

#### Proof

Choosing one term from each of the $k$ ordered factors chooses component sizes and strong internal tournaments. EGF multiplication supplies the multinomial assignment of labels. Condensation order forces all edges between components, giving a bijection with tournaments having those ordered SCCs. $\square$

### Theorem

Every printed distribution value is correct.

#### Proof

Lemma 1 supplies the component coefficients, and Lemma 2 identifies each coefficient of the iteratively computed power with the required class. $\square$

### Complexity

Strong-count computation is $O(n^2)$. Building all powers by convolution is $O(n^3)$ time and $O(n)$ rolling space, within $n\le500$. Factorial arrays use $O(n)$.

## Implementation

`cur` stores one current EGF power and `lo` skips degrees below the number of nonempty components. Multiplication by `fc[n]` converts the EGF coefficient back to labeled objects.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

ll pw(ll a, ll b) {
    ll r = 1; a %= MOD;
    while (b) {
        if (b & 1) r = r * a % MOD;
        a = a * a % MOD; b >>= 1;
    }
    return r;
}

int n;
vi fc, inv;

ll C(ll a, ll b) {
    if (b < 0 || b > a || a < 0) return 0;
    return fc[a] * inv[b] % MOD * inv[a - b] % MOD;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    cin >> n;

    fc.assign(n + 1, 1); inv.assign(n + 1, 1);
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) fc[i] = fc[i - 1] * i % MOD;
    inv[n] = pw(fc[n], MOD - 2);
    for (int i = n; i > 0; i--) inv[i - 1] = inv[i] * i % MOD;

    vi Cn(n + 1);                              // C_m = 2^(m choose 2) = all tournaments
    for (int m = 0; m <= n; m++) Cn[m] = pw(2, (ll)m * (m - 1) / 2);

    vi sc(n + 1, 0);                           // strongly connected tournaments, labeled
    for (int m = 1; m <= n; m++) {
        ll v = Cn[m];
        for (int j = 1; j < m; j++)            // s_m = C_m - sum C(m,j) C_j s_{m-j}
            v = (v - C(m, j) * Cn[j] % MOD * sc[m - j]) % MOD;
        sc[m] = (v % MOD + MOD) % MOD;
    }

    vi a(n + 1, 0);                            // EGF coeffs a_m = s_m / m!
    for (int m = 1; m <= n; m++) a[m] = sc[m] * inv[m] % MOD;

    vi cur = a;                                // cur = S^k, start k=1
    int lo = 1;
    cout << fc[n] * cur[n] % MOD << "\n";       // T(n,1)
    for (int k = 2; k <= n; k++) {
        vi nx(n + 1, 0);
        lo++;                                  // S^k supported from degree k
        for (int i = lo - 1; i <= n; i++) {
            if (!cur[i]) continue;
            for (int j = 1; j + i <= n; j++)
                nx[i + j] = (nx[i + j] + cur[i] * a[j]) % MOD;
        }
        cur = move(nx);
        cout << fc[n] * cur[n] % MOD << "\n";
    }
}
```

## Worked Example

For $n=3$, two cyclic orientations are strongly connected, giving the $k=1$ answer 2. A tournament cannot have exactly two SCCs on three vertices under the ordered structure, while the six transitive tournaments have three singleton SCCs.

## Takeaway

When graph components have a canonical order, the whole labeled class is a sequence of connected components, so powers of a connected-component EGF give the component-count distribution.

### Related problems

Functional Graph Distribution uses unordered components and a $1/k!$ factor. Planets and Kingdoms computes SCCs in one graph rather than counting graphs.

