# Advertisement

- **CSES task:** [Advertisement](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1142)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (advertisement.cpp)`](./advertisement.cpp)

## Problem

A fence has $n\le2\cdot10^5$ unit width boards of heights $h_i$. Find the largest axis aligned rectangle that fits beneath consecutive boards.

## Reasoning

Fix a board of height $H$. The widest rectangle for which this board supplies the minimum height extends until the nearest strictly lower board on each side. Its area is therefore $H(R-L-1)$. Computing those boundaries independently would be quadratic.

Scan from left to right while keeping indices with strictly increasing heights. When a new height is at most the stack top, the current index is the first position to the right that is lower than or equal to that popped height. After popping, the new stack top is the nearest strictly lower position on the left. Equal heights may be popped because the later equal bar inherits the wider left boundary and will represent the same height more profitably.

A final zero height forces every remaining candidate to be evaluated.

## Algorithm

Append a zero sentinel. For every index $i$, repeatedly pop while the top height is at least $h_i$. For a popped height $H$, let $L$ be the new stack top or $-1$; test area $H(i-L-1)$. Then push $i$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** When index $j$ is popped at scan position $i$, every board from the new stack top plus one through $i-1$ has height at least $h_j$.

**Proof.** A lower board would have caused $j$ to be popped earlier. The remaining stack top is the nearest earlier index with smaller height after all heights at least $h_j$ are removed. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The area tested when $j$ is popped is the maximum area of a rectangle whose limiting height is $h_j$.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 proves the tested interval is feasible. Extending left crosses the nearest smaller stack height, and extending right reaches $i$, whose height is at most $h_j$. No wider rectangle at this height is feasible. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm returns the maximum advertisement area.

**Proof.** Every possible optimal rectangle has some minimum board height. The corresponding height candidate is eventually popped, including at the sentinel, and Lemma 2 evaluates its widest feasible rectangle. Every evaluated rectangle is feasible, so the maximum is exactly optimal. $\square$

### Complexity

Each index is pushed and popped once, for $O(n)$ time and $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The stack stores indices rather than heights because width depends on positions. Area uses `long long`: both height and width may be large enough that their product exceeds 32 bit range.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    vi h(n+1);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> h[i];
    h[n] = 0;                       // sentinel flushes stack

    vi st;                          // indices, increasing height
    ll ans = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i <= n; i++){
        while(!st.empty() && h[st.back()] >= h[i]){
            ll ht = h[st.back()]; st.pop_back();
            ll L = st.empty() ? -1 : st.back();   // nearest smaller left
            ans = max(ans, ht * (i - L - 1));
        }
        st.pb(i);
    }
    cout << ans << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

For heights `[4,1,5,3,3,2,4,1]`, reaching height 2 pops both height 3 candidates. The surviving height 3 spans indices 2 through 4 and yields area 9. Later, height 2 spans indices 2 through 6 and yields area 10, the optimum.

## Takeaway

A monotonic stack is a compact way to discover the first smaller element on both sides exactly when the right boundary becomes known.

### Related problems

Maximum Building I applies the histogram method repeatedly to rows of a binary grid.

