# Bit Inversions

- **CSES task:** [Bit Inversions](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1188)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (bitinversions.cpp)`](./bitinversions.cpp)

## Problem

Maintain a bit string of length $n\le2\cdot10^5$ under $m\le2\cdot10^5$ single bit flips. After each flip, report the longest contiguous run of equal bits.

## Reasoning

Represent the string by its boundaries. A boundary at position $i$ means positions $i$ and $i+1$ differ. With sentinels at 0 and $n$, every equal run is exactly the gap between two consecutive boundaries.

Flipping position $x$ changes only the comparisons across edges $(x-1,x)$ and $(x,x+1)$. Thus only boundaries $x-1$ and $x$ toggle. Inserting one boundary splits one run; deleting one merges two runs. An ordered set locates neighboring boundaries, while a multiset stores every gap length and exposes the maximum.

## Algorithm

Build the boundary set and its gap multiset. For each flipped position $x$, toggle boundaries $x-1$ and $x$ when they lie from 1 through $n-1$. Update affected gap lengths during each split or merge, then output the largest multiset element.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Consecutive elements $a<b$ of the boundary set delimit one maximal equal bit run of length $b-a$.

**Proof.** No internal boundary exists, so every adjacent pair inside the interval is equal. At either nonsentinel endpoint the adjacent bits differ, so the run cannot extend. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** A flip at $x$ changes no boundary except $x-1$ and $x$.

**Proof.** Every other adjacent comparison contains neither the flipped bit, so both operands remain unchanged. Each of the two incident comparisons reverses equality status. $\square$

**Theorem.** After every update, the algorithm reports the longest equal substring.

**Proof.** Initially the set contains precisely all boundaries and the multiset contains precisely their consecutive gaps. By Lemma 2, toggling the two incident boundaries performs every required change and no other one. Split and merge updates preserve the gap representation. Lemma 1 then identifies the largest stored gap with the longest equal run. $\square$

### Complexity

Each update performs a constant number of ordered set and multiset operations, taking $O(\log n)$ time. The structures use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

`toggle(i)` ignores sentinel-external indices. Removal erases the two old lengths before adding their sum; insertion erases the containing gap before adding its two parts. `lens.find` is used so only one copy of a duplicated length is removed.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string str; cin >> str;
    int n = str.size();

    set<int> B = {0, n};                      // active boundaries + sentinels
    multiset<int> lens;
    vector<char> brk(n+1, 0);                 // brk[i]: s_i != s_{i+1}, i in 1..n-1

    auto addGap = [&](int a, int b){ lens.insert(b - a); };
    auto delGap = [&](int a, int b){ lens.erase(lens.find(b - a)); };

    for(int i = 1; i < n; i++)
        if(str[i-1] != str[i]){ brk[i] = 1; B.insert(i); }

    {                                         // initial gap lengths
        int prev = 0;
        for(int b : B) if(b != 0){ lens.insert(b - prev); prev = b; }
    }

    auto toggle = [&](int i){
        if(i < 1 || i > n-1) return;
        auto it = B.find(i);
        if(it != B.end()){                    // remove boundary, merge gaps
            int lo = *prev(it), hi = *next(it);
            delGap(lo, i); delGap(i, hi); addGap(lo, hi);
            B.erase(it); brk[i] = 0;
        } else {                              // insert boundary, split gap
            auto nx = B.lower_bound(i);
            int hi = *nx, lo = *prev(nx);
            delGap(lo, hi); addGap(lo, i); addGap(i, hi);
            B.insert(i); brk[i] = 1;
        }
    };

    int m; cin >> m;
    string out; out.reserve(m*7);
    while(m--){
        int x; cin >> x;
        str[x-1] ^= 1;                        // flip toggles boundaries x-1 and x
        toggle(x-1);
        toggle(x);
        out += to_string(*lens.rbegin());
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `001011`, boundaries are `{0,2,3,4,6}` and run lengths are 2, 1, 1, 2. Flipping position 3 removes boundaries 2 and 3, producing `000011` with gaps 4 and 2. The reported maximum is 4.

## Takeaway

For dynamic runs, store change points instead of all characters. A local edit then becomes a constant number of interval splits and merges.

### Related problems

Traffic Lights uses the same ordered endpoints plus multiset of interval lengths pattern.

