# Bubble Sort Rounds I

- **CSES task:** [Bubble Sort Rounds I](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3151)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (bubblesortrounds1.cpp)`](./bubblesortrounds1.cpp)

## Problem

One bubble sort round scans left to right and swaps every adjacent inverted pair. Given $n\le 2\cdot10^5$ values, determine how many complete rounds are needed before the array is sorted.

## Reasoning

A direct simulation can take $\Theta(n^2)$ time. The useful asymmetry is that during one left to right round, a large value may travel many positions right, but a value can move at most one position left. Therefore an element initially at index $p$ needs at least $p-q$ rounds if its stable sorted index is $q$.

This lower bound is also sufficient. After $r$ rounds, every element has crossed all smaller elements lying at most $r$ positions to its left in the stable target order. Equivalently, no element whose required leftward displacement is at most $r$ remains to the right of its target. Thus the answer is the maximum leftward displacement.

Duplicates require stable order. Sorting pairs `(value, original_index)` makes equal values retain increasing original indices, exactly matching the fact that bubble sort never swaps equal elements.

## Algorithm

Store each value together with its zero based original index. Sort these pairs lexicographically. If the pair now at sorted index $i$ came from index $p$, update the answer with $p-i$. Output the maximum.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** An element can move left by at most one position in one round.

**Proof.** The scan reaches the pair immediately left of the element once. If swapped, the scan continues to the right and never revisits the element's new left neighbor. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** After $r$ rounds, every element whose stable sorted position is at least its original position minus $r$ can reach that position.

**Proof.** Whenever such an element is not yet in its stable position, some larger element is immediately to its left at the relevant point of a round, so that inversion is swapped. It consequently advances one required position left in each round until no required crossing remains. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the number of bubble sort rounds required.

**Proof.** By Lemma 1, an element displaced $p-i$ positions left needs at least $p-i$ rounds, so the reported maximum is a lower bound. By Lemma 2, after that many rounds every element has completed all required leftward crossings. Stable pair sorting identifies exactly those crossings, including duplicates. The array is then sorted, proving sufficiency. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting takes $O(n\log n)$ time. The pair array uses $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The second component of each pair is the original index. After sorting, loop index `i` is its stable destination. The cast is safe because both indices are below $n$.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    vii a;
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        ll x; cin >> x;
        a.pb({x, i});
    }
    sort(a.begin(), a.end());
    
    int ans = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        ans = max(ans, (int)a[i].s - i);
    }
    cout << ans << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

For `[3,2,4,1,4]`, stable sorting gives original indices `[3,1,0,2,4]`. Their leftward displacements are $3,0,-2,-1,0$, whose maximum is 3. The value 1 can move left only once per round, so exactly three rounds are necessary.

## Takeaway

When a process scans in one direction, measure how fast objects can move against that direction. A simulation may collapse to the maximum stable displacement.

### Related problems

Bubble Sort Rounds II applies the same directional view but reconstructs the entire array after a prescribed number of rounds.

