# Cyclic Array

- **CSES task:** [Cyclic Array](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1191)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (cyclicarray.cpp)`](./cyclicarray.cpp)

## Problem

Partition a cyclic array of $n\le2\cdot10^5$ positive values into the minimum number of contiguous parts, each having sum at most $k$.

## Reasoning

Fix a starting position and cut the cycle there. Since all values are positive, the optimal first segment extends as far as possible: shortening it cannot help later segments cover more elements. Repeating this greedy choice is optimal for the resulting linear array.

Duplicate the array so every cyclic rotation becomes a length $n$ interval. Two pointers compute `jump[i]`, the first index after the longest valid segment starting at $i$. Testing every start by following jumps directly could still be quadratic. Binary lifting composes $2^t$ greedy segments, letting us count the segments needed to reach `s+n` in logarithmic time.

## Algorithm

Duplicate the array and build prefix sums. With a monotone right pointer, compute every greedy jump. Build a binary lifting table over this functional graph. For each start $s<n$, take the largest jumps that remain strictly before $s+n$, add one final segment, and minimize the count.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** For a fixed linear starting point, an optimal partition may take the longest valid prefix as its first segment.

**Proof.** Any optimal first segment ending earlier can be extended to the greedy endpoint without exceeding $k$. Removing those extra elements from the following segments cannot increase their required count, so an equally good partition uses the greedy prefix. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** Repeated `jump` applications give the minimum segment count for a fixed cyclic start.

**Proof.** Apply Lemma 1 to the first segment, then to the remaining suffix inductively. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm returns the minimum cyclic partition size.

**Proof.** Every cyclic partition has a boundary that is one of the tested starts. Lemma 2 computes the optimum for each such cut. Binary lifting only accelerates the same jump sequence, so the minimum over all starts is the global optimum. $\square$

### Complexity

Two pointers take $O(n)$ time. Building and querying the lifting table takes $O(n\log n)$ time and $O(n\log n)$ space.

## Implementation

`jump[i]=r` is an exclusive endpoint. During lifting, a jump is accepted only if it remains strictly before `target`; the final `cnt++` counts the segment that reaches or passes the target. Prefix sums use `long long`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int LOG = 18;
 
int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
 
    int n; ll k; cin >> n >> k;
    vector<ll> a(2*n);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){ cin >> a[i]; a[i+n] = a[i]; }
 
    int M = 2*n;
    vector<ll> pre(M+1, 0);
    for(int i = 0; i < M; i++) pre[i+1] = pre[i] + a[i];
 
    // jump[i] = start of next segment when greedily packing from i
    vector<int> jump(M+1, M);
    int r = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < M; i++){
        if(r < i) r = i;
        while(r < M && pre[r+1] - pre[i] <= k) r++;   // extend while sum ≤ k
        jump[i] = r;                                   // segment = [i, r-1]
    }
    jump[M] = M;
 
    vector<vector<int>> up(LOG, vector<int>(M+1));
    up[0] = jump;
    for(int t = 1; t < LOG; t++)
        for(int i = 0; i <= M; i++)
            up[t][i] = up[t-1][up[t-1][i]];
 
    ll ans = LLONG_MAX;
    for(int s = 0; s < n; s++){
        int target = s + n, pos = s; ll cnt = 0;
        for(int t = LOG-1; t >= 0; t--)
            if(up[t][pos] < target){ pos = up[t][pos]; cnt += (1LL<<t); }
        cnt++;                                          // final segment covering target
        ans = min(ans, cnt);
    }
    cout << ans << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

For `[2,2,2,1,3,1,2,1]` with $k=5$, starting at the third element greedily forms `[2,1]`, `[3,1]`, and `[2,1,2]` across the duplicated boundary. Three jump applications cover exactly eight elements.

## Takeaway

When a greedy process repeatedly advances through an array, treat its next-position rule as a functional graph and use binary lifting to test many starting points.

### Related problems

Planet Queries uses binary lifting on an explicit functional graph; here the graph is created by a two-pointer greedy rule.

