# Distinct Values Splits

- **CSES problem:** 3190
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (distinctvaluessplit.cpp)`](./distinctvaluessplit.cpp)

## Problem

Count ways to partition an array into contiguous segments such that every segment contains pairwise distinct values.

## Reasoning

Let $dp[i]$ be the number of valid partitions of prefix $1..i$. If the final segment starts at $j$, it contributes $dp[j-1]$ exactly when subarray $[j,i]$ is distinct.

Maintain `left`, the minimum valid start of a distinct suffix ending at the current position. When value $x_i$ last appeared at $p$, any suffix beginning at or before $p$ repeats it, so set

$$
left\gets\max(left,p+1).
$$

Then every $j\in[left,i]$ is valid and no smaller $j$ is. The transition is

$$
dp[i]=\sum_{j=left}^{i}dp[j-1].
$$

Prefix sums of DP values answer this interval sum in constant time.

## Algorithm

1. Set `dp[0]=pref[0]=1` and `left=1`.
2. Scan values, advancing `left` past the current value's previous occurrence.
3. Compute `dp[i]=pref[i-1]-pref[left-2]` when the second term exists.
4. Extend the DP prefix sum and record the current occurrence.
5. Output `dp[n]`.

## Correctness

### Lemma 1

At position $i$, subarray $[j,i]$ is distinct exactly when $j\ge left$.

#### Proof

The standard sliding-window invariant keeps `left` beyond the most recent conflicting previous occurrence for every value in the suffix. Thus no value repeats from `left` onward. Any earlier start crosses at least one conflict that caused `left` to advance, so it is not distinct. $\square$

### Lemma 2

The DP transition counts every valid partition of prefix $i$ exactly once.

#### Proof

Every partition has a unique final-segment start $j$. By Lemma 1 it is valid exactly for the summed starts, and removing that segment leaves one partition counted by $dp[j-1]$. Conversely, appending the valid distinct segment to any such partition is valid. $\square$

### Theorem

The algorithm outputs the number of valid complete splits.

#### Proof

The empty prefix has one partition. Lemma 2 gives a complete, nonoverlapping recurrence for every longer prefix, so induction proves `dp[n]` exact. $\square$

### Complexity

Expected time is $O(n)$ and space is $O(n+d)$ for DP arrays and the last-occurrence map.

## Implementation

The prefix array includes `dp[0]`. When `left=1`, there is no prefix before index zero to subtract. Modular subtraction adds `MOD` before taking the remainder.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    vi dp(n+1), pref(n+1);
    unordered_map<int, int> last;

    dp[0] = 1; pref[0] = 1;
    int left = 1;

    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        int x; cin >> x;

        if(last.count(x)) left = max(left, last[x] + 1);
        dp[i] = pref[i - 1];
        if(left >= 2) dp[i] = (dp[i] - pref[left - 2] + MOD) % MOD;

        pref[i] = (pref[i - 1] + dp[i]) % MOD;
        last[x] = i;
    }
    cout << dp[n] << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

For prefix `[1,2,1]`, the minimum distinct-suffix start is 2. Final segments `[2,1]` and `[1]` beginning at positions 2 and 3 contribute `dp[1]+dp[2]` to `dp[3]`.

## Takeaway

When valid final segments form a contiguous range of starting positions, combine a sliding-window boundary with prefix sums of DP transitions.

### Related problems

Playlist maintains the same distinct-window boundary for maximum length. Word Combinations also sums ways over valid final pieces.

