# Distinct Values Sum

- **CSES problem:** 3150
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (distinctvaluessum.cpp)`](./distinctvaluessum.cpp)

## Problem

For every subarray, count its distinct values and output the sum of these counts over all subarrays.

## Reasoning

Reverse the counting order. Instead of processing each subarray, count every pair `(subarray,value)` in which the value occurs.

At occurrence position $i$ of value $x$, let `prev` be its previous occurrence or zero. Assign a pair to $i$ when $i$ is the first occurrence of $x$ inside that subarray. The left endpoint may be any position from `prev+1` through $i$, giving $i-prev$ choices. The right endpoint may be any position from $i$ through $n$, giving $n-i+1$ choices.

Thus this occurrence contributes

$$
(i-prev)(n-i+1).
$$

Every subarray containing $x$ has exactly one first occurrence of $x$, so contributions neither miss nor duplicate a distinct-value count.

## Algorithm

1. Scan positions from left to right and remember each value's last occurrence.
2. At position $i$, add `(i-last[x])*(n-i+1)`.
3. Replace `last[x]` by $i$.

## Correctness

### Lemma

The contribution of occurrence $i$ counts exactly subarrays in which it is the first occurrence of its value.

#### Proof

Such a subarray must begin after the previous occurrence and no later than $i$, and must end at or after $i$. These endpoint choices are independent and exactly the two factors. $\square$

### Theorem

The accumulated sum equals the sum of distinct counts over all subarrays.

#### Proof

For every subarray and every distinct value it contains, there is one unique first occurrence inside the subarray. By the lemma, exactly that occurrence counts the pair once. Summing all occurrences therefore counts all desired pairs. $\square$

### Complexity

Expected time is $O(n)$ using the hash map, and space is $O(d)$ for $d$ distinct values.

## Implementation

Map lookup through `last[x]` default-initializes unseen values to position zero. The answer and multiplicative contribution use `long long`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    unordered_map<int, int> last;
    ll ans = 0;

    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        int x; cin >> x;

        int prev = last[x];
        ans += 1LL * (i - prev) * (n - i + 1);
        last[x] = i;
    }
    cout << ans << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

For value 1 occurring at positions 1, 4, and 5 in an array of length 5, contributions are $1\cdot5$, $3\cdot2$, and $1\cdot1$, totaling 12 subarrays that contain 1.

## Takeaway

Global sums of distinct counts often become simple when each `(range,value)` pair is charged to the value's first or last occurrence inside the range.

### Related problems

Distinct Values Queries maintains one latest representative per value. Sum of Distinct Values Squares uses a richer range contribution.

