# Maximum Average Subarrays

- **CSES task:** [Maximum Average Subarrays](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3301)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (maxavgsubarrays.cpp)`](./maxavgsubarrays.cpp)

## Problem

For every right endpoint $i$, find the longest subarray ending at $i$ among those with maximum average. The array length is at most $2\cdot10^5$.

## Reasoning

Let $P_i$ be the prefix sum through index $i$. A subarray beginning after prefix index $a<i$ has average

$$\frac{P_i-P_a}{i-a},$$

the slope from point $(a,P_a)$ to query point $(i,P_i)$. We need the prefix point giving maximum slope. Among ties, the smallest $a$ gives the longest subarray.

Only points on the lower convex hull can maximize a slope to a query point lying to their right. Prefix points arrive in increasing $x$, so the hull is maintained by removing a middle point whenever consecutive slopes fail to increase. Along this hull, slopes to the current query are unimodal. Binary search compares adjacent candidates and finds the leftmost maximum, which also implements the length tie rule.

## Algorithm

Build prefix sums. Before answering endpoint $i$, insert point $(i-1,P_{i-1})$ into the lower hull. Binary search the hull for the leftmost maximum slope to $(i,P_i)$ using cross multiplication, then output $i-a$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Removing a point whose incoming hull slope is at least its outgoing slope cannot remove the unique best start for any future endpoint.

**Proof.** Such a point lies on or above the segment joining its two neighbors. For every query to the right, at least one neighbor forms a slope no smaller than the middle point. If equal, the earlier neighbor is preferable for length. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** Slopes from hull points to a fixed query point increase and then decrease along the lower hull.

**Proof.** Lower-hull edge slopes increase. Comparing the query slope at two consecutive vertices changes sign at most once as those edge slopes pass the direction toward the query, establishing unimodality. $\square$

**Theorem.** For every $i$, the algorithm outputs the requested subarray length.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 preserves at least one optimal prefix point. Lemma 2 makes adjacent-comparison binary search locate a maximum. On equality it keeps the left candidate, hence the smallest start and longest subarray. The slope identity proves this candidate has maximum average. $\square$

### Complexity

Each point is inserted and removed once, while each query uses binary search. Total time is $O(n\log n)$ and space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

All slope comparisons use cross products, avoiding floating point error. With prefix sums up to $2\cdot10^{11}$ and index differences up to $2\cdot10^5$, the products fit signed 64 bit integers.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    vi P(n+1, 0);
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ ll x; cin >> x; P[i] = P[i-1] + x; }

    vi hx, hy;                                  // lower hull: points (a, P[a])
    // slope(A,B) >= slope(B,C)  =>  B not on lower hull
    auto bad = [](ll ax, ll ay, ll bx, ll by, ll cx, ll cy){
        return (by-ay)*(cx-bx) >= (cy-by)*(bx-ax);
    };

    string out; out.reserve(n*7);
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        ll ax = i-1, ay = P[i-1];               // add candidate start a=i-1
        while(hx.size() >= 2 &&
              bad(hx[hx.size()-2], hy[hy.size()-2], hx.back(), hy.back(), ax, ay)){
            hx.pop_back(); hy.pop_back();
        }
        hx.pb(ax); hy.pb(ay);

        int lo = 0, hi = (int)hx.size()-1;       // peak of unimodal slope, leftmost on tie
        while(lo < hi){
            int m = (lo+hi)/2;
            ll n1 = P[i]-hy[m],   d1 = i-hx[m];
            ll n2 = P[i]-hy[m+1], d2 = i-hx[m+1];
            if(n1*d2 < n2*d1) lo = m+1;          // g(m) < g(m+1)
            else hi = m;
        }
        out += to_string(i - hx[lo]);
        out += (i==n ? '\n' : ' ');
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

For prefix sums `[0,1,7,11,17,19]` and endpoint 5, slopes from starts 0 through 4 are $19/5$, $18/4$, $12/3$, $8/2$, and $2$. The maximum is $18/4=4.5$, so the reported length is 4.

## Takeaway

Subarray averages are slopes between prefix-sum points. When one endpoint advances monotonically, convex hull geometry can answer all best-average queries exactly.

### Related problems

Convex Hull Trick problems similarly discard points that can never optimize a future slope or linear query.

