# Nearest Campsites I

- **CSES task:** [Nearest Campsites I](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3306)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (nearestcampsites1.cpp)`](./nearestcampsites1.cpp)

## Problem

Given up to $10^5$ reserved and $10^5$ free integer grid points, find the maximum, over free points, of the Manhattan distance to the nearest reserved point.

## Reasoning

For a query $q=(x,y)$ and reserved point $p=(a,b)$, choose signs $s_x,s_y\in\{-1,1\}$ so that $s_xa\le s_xx$ and $s_yb\le s_yy$. In that transformed southwest quadrant,

$$|x-a|+|y-b|=(s_xx+s_yy)-(s_xa+s_yb).$$

Thus the nearest reserved point in that quadrant is the one maximizing $s_xa+s_yb$. Four sign choices cover every relative position, reducing Manhattan nearest neighbor queries to four offline dominance sweeps.

For one sweep, sort reserved and query points by transformed $x$. Insert every reserved point with $a\le x$ into a Fenwick tree indexed by compressed $y$, storing prefix maxima of $a+b$. Querying through the query's $y$ enforces $b\le y$.

## Algorithm

For each of four sign pairs, transform all points and compress their $y$ coordinates. Sweep queries by $x$, insert eligible reserved points, and use a Fenwick prefix maximum to improve each query's answer. Output the maximum nearest distance among all free points.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** A single sign sweep computes the minimum distance from each query to reserved points in its corresponding transformed southwest quadrant.

**Proof.** Sorting and the insertion pointer enforce $a\le x$; the Fenwick prefix enforces $b\le y$. For precisely those points, maximizing $a+b$ minimizes $(x+y)-(a+b)$, which equals Manhattan distance in this quadrant. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** Every reserved point belongs to one of the four quadrants considered for a fixed query.

**Proof.** Independently choose each sign according to whether the reserved coordinate is at most or at least the query coordinate. Equal coordinates may fit multiple quadrants but yield the same distance. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the requested maximum nearest distance.

**Proof.** Lemmas 1 and 2 show that the minimum accumulated for each free point is its distance to the nearest reserved point. Taking the maximum of these exact values gives the required answer. $\square$

### Complexity

Four sweeps each sort and perform Fenwick operations, taking $O((n+m)\log(n+m))$ time and $O(n+m)$ space.

## Implementation

The Fenwick tree stores maxima rather than sums. Coordinate compression includes both reserved and query coordinates. `upper_bound` returns the number of compressed coordinates not exceeding the query coordinate, exactly the inclusive prefix needed.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const ll INF = 4e18;
 
struct P{
    ll x, y;
    int id;
};
 
struct BIT{
    int n; vi bit;
    BIT(int n = 0): n(n), bit(n+1, -INF) {}
    void upd(int i, ll v){
        // for(; i <+ n; i += i & -i) bit[i] = max(bit[i], v);
        for(; i <= n; i += i & -i) bit[i] = max(bit[i], v);
    }
    ll qry(int i){
        ll r = -INF;
        // for(; i; i -= i % -i) r = max(r, bit[i]);
        for(; i; i -= i & -i) r = max(r, bit[i]);
        return r;
    }
};
 
int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
 
    int n, m; cin >> n >> m;
    vector<P> a(n), b(m);
 
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        cin >> a[i].x >> a[i].y;
        a[i].id = -1;
    }
 
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        cin >> b[i].x >> b[i].y;
        b[i].id = i;
    }
 
    vi ans(m, INF);
    for(int sx : {-1, 1}){
        for(int sy : {-1, 1}){
            vector<P> r, q;
            vi ys;
 
            for(auto p : a){
                p.x *= sx;
                p.y *= sy;
                r.pb(p);
                ys.pb(p.y);
            }
            for(auto p : b){
                p.x *= sx;
                p.y *= sy;
                q.pb(p);
                ys.pb(p.y);
            }
 
            sort(ys.begin(), ys.end());
            ys.erase(unique(ys.begin(), ys.end()), ys.end());
 
            sort(r.begin(), r.end(), [](P a, P b){
                return a.x < b.x;
            });
 
            sort(q.begin(), q.end(), [](P a, P b){
                return a.x < b.x;
            });
 
            BIT ft(ys.size());
            int j = 0;
 
            for(auto p : q){
                while(j<n && r[j].x <= p.x){
                    int y = lower_bound(ys.begin(), ys.end(), r[j].y) - ys.begin() + 1;
                    ft.upd(y, r[j].x + r[j].y);          // store c_x + c_y
                    j++;
                }
 
                int y = upper_bound(ys.begin(), ys.end(), p.y) - ys.begin();
                ll best = ft.qry(y);
 
                // if(best != INF){
                if(best != -INF){
                    ans[p.id] = min(ans[p.id], p.x + p.y - best);
                }
            }
        }
    }
    ll res = 0;
    for(ll x : ans) res = max(res, x);
    cout << res << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

For query $(7,5)$ and reserved point $(5,2)$ in the ordinary southwest quadrant, the transformed formula gives $(7+5)-(5+2)=5$. The Fenwick entry contributes 7, so this candidate distance is recovered without examining the pair directly.

## Takeaway

Absolute values in fixed dimension can often be split by sign patterns. After fixing signs, Manhattan distance becomes a linear expression plus dominance constraints.

### Related problems

Nearest Campsites II uses the same four sweeps and reports every query value instead of their maximum.

