# Permutation Subsequence

- **CSES task:** [Permutation Subsequence](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3404)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (permutationsubsequence.cpp)`](./permutationsubsequence.cpp)

## Problem

Given two arrays whose values are distinct within each array, find and reconstruct their longest common subsequence. Their lengths are at most $2\cdot10^5$.

## Reasoning

Quadratic LCS dynamic programming is far too slow. Because the first array is a permutation, every shared value has one position in it. Replace each value of the second array by that position, discarding values absent from the first. A chosen value sequence appears left to right in the first array exactly when these positions are strictly increasing. Its order in the second array is already preserved by the scan.

The problem is therefore longest increasing subsequence with reconstruction. Patience sorting stores, for every attainable length, the index of the smallest current tail. Parent pointers remember the predecessor that produced each state.

## Algorithm

Build `pa[value]`, the position in the first array. Scan the second array to create position sequence `p` and parallel value sequence `val`. Run strict LIS on `p` using the first tail not smaller than the current position. Store parent pointers, then follow parents from the final tail and reverse the result.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Common subsequences of the input arrays correspond bijectively to strictly increasing subsequences of `p`.

**Proof.** Scanning the second array fixes its order. The selected values occur in the first array in the same order precisely when their unique mapped positions increase. Discarded values cannot belong to a common subsequence. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** `tails[l]` stores an index ending some increasing subsequence of length $l+1$ with minimum possible tail position.

**Proof.** Binary search replaces the first tail not smaller than the new position. The predecessor at the previous length is smaller, so the new state is valid, and choosing the smaller tail cannot reduce future extension possibilities. Induction over processed elements proves the invariant. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs a longest common subsequence.

**Proof.** Lemma 2 gives a longest increasing subsequence length, and parent pointers reconstruct a valid one. Lemma 1 maps it to a common subsequence and proves that no longer common subsequence exists. $\square$

### Complexity

Mapping is linear and LIS costs $O(m\log n)$ time. Arrays and parent pointers use $O(n+m)$ space.

## Implementation

The custom binary search implements `lower_bound`, which is required for strict increase. `tails` stores sequence indices, not positions, so both parent reconstruction and access to `p` remain available.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m; cin >> n >> m;
    vector<int> a(n+1), pa(n+1, 0);
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ cin >> a[i]; pa[a[i]] = i; }

    vector<int> p, val;                      // p[k]=pos_a[b_k], val[k]=value
    for(int j = 0; j < m; j++){
        int x; cin >> x;
        if(x <= n && pa[x]){ p.pb(pa[x]); val.pb(x); }   // present in a
    }
    int k = p.size();

    // LIS on p (strictly increasing) with reconstruction
    vector<int> tails;                       // tails[len] = seq index
    vector<int> par(k, -1);
    for(int i = 0; i < k; i++){
        int lo = 0, hi = tails.size();
        while(lo < hi){                      // first tail with p >= p[i]
            int md = (lo+hi)/2;
            if(p[tails[md]] < p[i]) lo = md+1; else hi = md;
        }
        if(lo > 0) par[i] = tails[lo-1];
        if(lo == (int)tails.size()) tails.pb(i);
        else tails[lo] = i;
    }

    vector<int> res;
    for(int cur = tails.empty() ? -1 : tails.back(); cur != -1; cur = par[cur])
        res.pb(val[cur]);
    reverse(res.begin(), res.end());

    cout << res.size() << '\n';
    for(int i = 0; i < (int)res.size(); i++) cout << res[i] << " \n"[i+1==(int)res.size()];
    if(res.empty()) cout << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

If the first array positions map the filtered second array to `[7,5,2,3,1,8]`, an LIS is `[2,3,8]`. Reading the parallel values at those indices gives a length 3 sequence appearing in both original arrays.

## Takeaway

LCS becomes LIS when one sequence assigns every shared value a unique rank. Recognizing uniqueness can remove an entire DP dimension.

### Related problems

Increasing Subsequence uses the same patience sorting invariant without the initial positional mapping.

