# Pyramid Array

- **CSES task:** [Pyramid Array](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1747)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (pyramidarray.cpp)`](./pyramidarray.cpp)

## Problem

Reorder the array into a pyramid using adjacent swaps, with values increasing toward the center and decreasing afterward. Find the minimum number of swaps.

## Reasoning

Process values from smallest to largest. In any valid pyramid, the next smallest remaining value must occupy one of the two exposed ends: placing it internally would leave a smaller value outside it and violate monotonicity toward the center.

If the chosen occurrence currently has $L$ remaining elements to its left and $R$ to its right, moving it to the nearer exposed end costs $\min(L,R)$ adjacent swaps. This choice does not affect the relative order of unprocessed elements. Equal values are handled in original-index order by sorting `(value,index)` pairs, which is a valid ordering because exchanging equal labels changes neither feasibility nor cost.

A Fenwick tree stores which original positions remain, allowing both side counts in logarithmic time.

## Algorithm

Initialize every position as present in a Fenwick tree. Sort `(value,position)` pairs. For each pair, query the number $L$ of present positions to its left, derive $R=present-1-L$, add $\min(L,R)$, and remove the position.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The smallest unprocessed value may be moved to either exposed end in some optimal completion.

**Proof.** It cannot lie strictly inside a smaller-to-larger slope while a greater unprocessed value lies outside it. Moving it to an end crosses exactly the elements on that side and leaves all other relative orders unchanged. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** Given the remaining positions, the minimum cost to place the current value is $\min(L,R)$.

**Proof.** Reaching the left end requires crossing each of the $L$ remaining left elements once, and these swaps suffice. The symmetric cost to the right end is $R$. No third legal placement exists by Lemma 1. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm computes the minimum adjacent swaps.

**Proof.** Repeatedly apply Lemma 1. Lemma 2 chooses the cheaper valid end placement without changing the residual relative order, so it preserves an optimal completion. Summing these optimal incremental costs yields the global minimum. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting and Fenwick operations take $O(n\log n)$ time. The stored pairs and tree use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The tree initially contains one at every index. `qry(p-1)` counts remaining positions strictly left of `p`; `present-1-L` counts those strictly right. Removal occurs only after both counts are computed.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int N;
vi bit;                                  // count of present positions
void upd(int i, ll v){ for(; i <= N; i += i & -i) bit[i] += v; }
ll qry(int i){ ll r = 0; for(; i; i -= i & -i) r += bit[i]; return r; }

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    N = n;
    bit.assign(n+1, 0);
    vii v(n);                            // (value, position)
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ cin >> v[i-1].f; v[i-1].s = i; upd(i, 1); }

    sort(v.begin(), v.end());            // process smallest value first

    ll ans = 0;
    int present = n;
    for(auto &e : v){
        int p = e.s;
        ll L = qry(p-1);                 // present elements left of p
        ll R = (present - 1) - L;        // present elements right of p
        ans += min(L, R);                // slide to nearer end
        upd(p, -1); present--;           // freeze this element
    }
    cout << ans << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

If the smallest remaining value is at original position 4 and the active positions are `{1,3,4,6,7}`, then $L=2$ and $R=2$. Either end costs two swaps. After removal, the active set is `{1,3,6,7}`, exactly the residual problem.

## Takeaway

For constructions that peel values from the outside inward, process by value and use an order-statistics structure to price removal from either end.

### Related problems

Josephus-style removals and inversion counting also use Fenwick trees to count currently active positions.

