# Sorting Methods

- **CSES task:** [Sorting Methods](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1162)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (sortingmethods.cpp)`](./sortingmethods.cpp)

## Problem

For a permutation of $1$ through $n$, find the minimum operations needed to sort it under four separate rules: adjacent swaps, arbitrary swaps, moving any element anywhere, and moving any element only to the front.

## Reasoning

Each operation exposes a different invariant.

For adjacent swaps, one swap changes the inversion count by exactly one, and swapping adjacent inversions removes all inversions in exactly that many steps. The answer is the inversion count.

For arbitrary swaps, view the permutation mapping $i\mapsto p_i$ as disjoint cycles. A cycle of length $L$ needs $L-1$ swaps, so the total is $n$ minus the number of cycles.

If an element may be moved anywhere, elements never moved must already form an increasing subsequence. Keeping a longest increasing subsequence and moving every other element is both necessary and sufficient, giving $n-\operatorname{LIS}$.

If moves go only to the front, the elements never moved must be a suffix of values $v,v+1,\ldots,n$ already appearing in increasing positional order. Keep the longest such suffix and move every smaller value to the front in descending value order.

## Algorithm

Use a Fenwick tree to count inversions. Traverse permutation cycles. Compute LIS length with patience sorting. Finally scan values downward from $n$, extending while `pos[v] < pos[v+1]`. Print the four derived values.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The first answer equals the inversion count, and the second equals $n$ minus the cycle count.

**Proof.** An adjacent swap changes only the order of its pair, so at least one swap per inversion is necessary and bubble-style swaps attain it. An arbitrary swap can increase cycle count by at most one; splitting every length $L$ cycle into fixed points takes and requires $L-1$ swaps. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The third answer is $n-\operatorname{LIS}$.

**Proof.** Unmoved elements preserve relative order and must be increasing, so at most an LIS can remain. Keeping an LIS and relocating every other value to its sorted position uses one move each. $\square$

**Lemma 3.** The fourth answer is $n-S$, where $S$ is the longest high-value suffix already in positional order.

**Proof.** Front moves do not alter the relative order of unmoved elements, and every moved value ends before all unmoved values. Thus unmoved values must be consecutive largest values in increasing order. Conversely, move the remaining values from largest to smallest; each new front insertion builds the required increasing prefix. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs all four minimum operation counts.

**Proof.** Each component follows from Lemmas 1 through 3 and is computed by its corresponding loop. $\square$

### Complexity

Inversion counting and LIS take $O(n\log n)$ time; cycle and suffix scans are linear. Total space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The Fenwick query counts previously seen values no greater than the current value, so subtracting it from the seen total counts greater values. LIS uses `lower_bound` because the input is a permutation and the desired subsequence is strict.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int N;
vi bit;
void upd(int i){ for(; i <= N; i += i & -i) bit[i]++; }
ll qry(int i){ ll r = 0; for(; i; i -= i & -i) r += bit[i]; return r; }

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    N = n;
    vector<int> p(n+1), pos(n+1, 0);
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ cin >> p[i]; pos[p[i]] = i; }

    // M1: inversions via BIT (count already-seen values greater than current)
    bit.assign(n+1, 0);
    ll inv = 0;
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        inv += qry(n) - qry(p[i]);          // seen values > p[i]
        upd(p[i]);
    }

    // M2: n - cycles
    vector<char> vis(n+1, 0);
    int cyc = 0;
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        if(!vis[i]){
            cyc++;
            for(int j = i; !vis[j]; j = p[j]) vis[j] = 1;
        }
    }
    ll m2 = n - cyc;

    // M3: n - LIS  (kept elements form an increasing subsequence; rest moved once each)
    // int L = 1, cur = 1;                      // value chain v,v+1,... with pos increasing
    // for(int v = 2; v <= n; v++){
    //     if(pos[v] > pos[v-1]) cur++; else cur = 1;
    //     L = max(L, cur);
    // }
    // ll m3 = n - L;
    vector<int> tails;                          // patience sorting, strictly increasing
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        auto it = lower_bound(tails.begin(), tails.end(), p[i]);
        if(it == tails.end()) tails.pb(p[i]); else *it = p[i];
    }
    ll m3 = n - (ll)tails.size();

    // M4: n - longest TOP suffix of values (n,n-1,...) with increasing positions
    int S = 1;                              // n-S+1..n in increasing pos order
    for(int v = n-1; v >= 1; v--){
        if(pos[v] < pos[v+1]) S++; else break;
    }
    ll m4 = n - S;

    cout << inv << " " << m2 << " " << m3 << " " << m4 << '\n';
    // if(n == 0) cout;                        // guard (n>=1 by constraints)
}
```

## Worked Example

For permutation `[2,1,4,3]`, there are two inversions. Its cycles are `(1,2)` and `(3,4)`, so arbitrary swaps need 2. An LIS has length 2, giving 2 arbitrary moves. Positions of 3 and 4 are 4 and 3, so only value 4 belongs to the ordered top suffix, giving 3 front moves.

## Takeaway

The right measure of disorder depends on the allowed operation: inversions, permutation cycles, LIS, and preserved value suffixes answer four superficially similar sorting questions.

### Related problems

Collecting Numbers and Increasing Subsequence use the positional-order and LIS invariants appearing here.

