# Special Substrings

- **CSES task:** [Special Substrings](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2186)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (specialsubstrings.cpp)`](./specialsubstrings.cpp)

## Problem

Count substrings in which every character appearing anywhere in the input string occurs the same number of times. The length is at most $2\cdot10^5$.

## Reasoning

Let the globally present characters be $c_1,\ldots,c_k$. A substring is special when its count vector is $t(1,1,\ldots,1)$ for some $t$. Deterministically storing a 25-dimensional normalized prefix vector is possible but expensive.

The implementation uses additive fingerprinting. Assign random weights $w_i$ modulo $P=2^{61}-1$, choosing the last weight so that $\sum_iw_i=0$. Equal character counts then always give weighted sum zero. With independently random preceding weights, a nonspecial count vector has probability about $1/P$ of also producing zero.

Let $H_j$ be the weighted sum of the first $j$ characters. Substring $(l,r]$ has weight zero exactly when $H_l=H_r$. Counting equal prefix fingerprints therefore counts special substrings, up to the negligible randomized collision probability.

## Algorithm

Find the distinct characters, generate their weights, and force the total to zero modulo $P$. Scan prefix fingerprints. Maintain a hash table of previous frequency for each fingerprint; add that frequency to the answer before incrementing it.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Every special substring has fingerprint zero.

**Proof.** If every present character occurs $t$ times, its fingerprint is $t\sum_iw_i=0\pmod P$. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** A nonspecial substring has fingerprint zero with probability at most $1/P$ over the random weights.

**Proof.** After eliminating the dependent last weight, the fingerprint is a nonzero linear form in independent uniform weights unless all character counts are equal. Fixing all but one coefficient leaves at most one value that makes the form zero modulo $P$. $\square$

**Theorem.** Except with negligible hash-collision probability, the algorithm counts every special substring exactly once and no other substring.

**Proof.** Equal prefix fingerprints are equivalent to a zero substring fingerprint. Lemma 1 includes all special substrings, Lemma 2 excludes nonspecial ones with the stated probability, and each endpoint pair is counted once when its right endpoint is scanned. $\square$

### Complexity

Expected time is $O(n)$ and space is $O(n)$. The result itself uses `long long` because there can be $n(n+1)/2$ substrings.

## Implementation

All fingerprint arithmetic uses `unsigned long long`. The custom SplitMix hash protects the unordered table from adversarial bucket patterns. `cnt[0]=1` represents the empty prefix.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

struct Hsh {
    static ull splm(ull x){
        x += 0x9e3779b97f4a7c15ULL;
        x = (x ^ (x>>30)) * 0xbf58476d1ce4e5b9ULL;
        x = (x ^ (x>>27)) * 0x94d049bb133111ebULL;
        return x ^ (x>>31);
    }
    size_t operator()(ull x) const {
        static const ull FIX = chrono::steady_clock::now().time_since_epoch().count();
        return splm(x + FIX);
    }
};

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    const ull P = (1ULL<<61) - 1;            // additive hash field
    string str; cin >> str;
    int n = str.size();

    vector<int> pr;                          // distinct chars present
    vector<char> seen(26, 0);
    for(char c : str) seen[c-'a'] = 1;
    for(int c = 0; c < 26; c++) if(seen[c]) pr.pb(c);

    mt19937_64 rng(chrono::steady_clock::now().time_since_epoch().count());
    vector<ull> w(26, 0);
    ull sum = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i+1 < (int)pr.size(); i++){
        w[pr[i]] = rng() % P;
        sum = (sum + w[pr[i]]) % P;
    }
    if(!pr.empty()) w[pr.back()] = (P - sum) % P;   // total weight ≡ 0 (mod P)

    unordered_map<ull, int, Hsh> cnt;
    cnt.reserve(n*2);
    cnt[0] = 1;                              // empty prefix
    ull h = 0; ll ans = 0;
    for(char c : str){
        h += w[c-'a']; if(h >= P) h -= P;
        ans += cnt[h]++;                     // equal prefix vector ⇒ special
    }
    cout << ans << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

If the present alphabet is `{a,b,c}`, weights satisfy $w_a+w_b+w_c=0$. Substring `abccab` contains each character twice, so its fingerprint is $2(w_a+w_b+w_c)=0$; its two endpoint prefixes match and contribute one count.

## Takeaway

High-dimensional equality constraints can sometimes be compressed into additive fingerprints. State the one-sided guarantee and collision probability explicitly whenever randomness replaces exact vectors.

### Related problems

Anagram substring counting also groups equal normalized prefix-frequency signatures, often with deterministic vectors when the alphabet is small.

