# Square Subsets

- **CSES task:** [Square Subsets](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3193)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (squaresubsets.cpp)`](./squaresubsets.cpp)

## Problem

Count subsets, including the empty subset, whose product is a perfect square. There are up to 5000 values, each at most 5000.

## Reasoning

An integer is a square exactly when every prime exponent is even. Replace each value by a binary vector recording exponent parity for every prime at most 5000. Multiplying selected values adds these vectors modulo two, so a subset has square product exactly when its vector sum is zero.

Arrange the $n$ vectors as columns of a linear map over $\mathbb F_2$. The desired subsets are vectors in its kernel. If the vector rank is $r$, rank-nullity gives kernel dimension $n-r$, hence exactly $2^{n-r}$ subsets.

Gaussian elimination on 669-bit bitsets finds the rank efficiently.

## Algorithm

Sieve smallest prime factors and assign every prime a bit index. Factor each input into its squarefree parity signature. Reduce that bitset against the current basis; if nonzero, add it as a new basis vector and increment the rank. Output $2^{n-r}$ modulo $10^9+7$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** A subset product is a square exactly when the xor of its signatures is zero.

**Proof.** Each signature coordinate is the corresponding prime exponent modulo two. Exponents add under multiplication, and all final exponents are even exactly when every parity coordinate is zero. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The elimination procedure computes the rank of the signature vectors over $\mathbb F_2$.

**Proof.** Each stored vector has a pivot absent from earlier basis vectors. Reducing a new vector by matching pivots preserves its span; a zero result is dependent, while a nonzero result introduces a new pivot and increases rank by one. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the number of square-product subsets.

**Proof.** By Lemma 1, valid subsets form the kernel of the signature matrix. Lemma 2 gives rank $r$, so rank-nullity makes the kernel dimension $n-r$. A binary vector space of that dimension has $2^{n-r}$ elements, including the empty subset. $\square$

### Complexity

There are 669 primes at most 5000. Factorization plus bitset elimination takes $O(n\cdot669^2/64)$ word operations in the straightforward bound and uses $O(669^2/64)$ basis storage.

## Implementation

The basis uses the least set bit as its pivot. `bitset::_Find_first()` is a GNU libstdc++ extension supported by the CSES compiler, not standard C++17. The fixed size 670 covers all 669 primes.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

const int MX = 5001;
const int B = 670;                  // # primes ≤ 5000 is 669

ll pw(ll b, ll e){
    ll r = 1; b %= MOD;
    for(; e; e>>=1){ if(e&1) r=r*b%MOD; b=b*b%MOD; }
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    vector<int> spf(MX, 0);                 // smallest prime factor
    vector<int> pid(MX, -1);                // prime -> bit index
    int pc = 0;
    for(int i = 2; i < MX; i++){
        if(!spf[i]){ pid[i] = pc++; for(int j = i; j < MX; j += i) if(!spf[j]) spf[j] = i; }
    }

    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<bitset<B>> rows;                  // basis under elimination
    int r = 0;

    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        int x; cin >> x;
        bitset<B> v;
        while(x > 1){                        // squarefree signature
            int p = spf[x], cnt = 0;
            while(x % p == 0){ x /= p; cnt ^= 1; }
            if(cnt) v.flip(pid[p]);
        }
        for(auto &b : rows){                 // reduce against current basis
            int hb = -1;
            // pivot of b = its highest set bit; reduce greedily
            if((v & b).any()){
                int p = (b._Find_first());
                if(v.test(p)) v ^= b;
            }
        }
        if(v.any()){ rows.pb(v); r++; }
    }

    cout << pw(2, n - r) << '\n';
}
```

## Worked Example

Values `[2,2,3,6]` have signatures `[10,10,01,11]` over primes 2 and 3. Their rank is 2, so the kernel has dimension $4-2=2$ and contains $2^2=4$ subsets.

## Takeaway

Parity conditions on prime exponents turn products into xor. Counting valid subsets then becomes kernel counting with binary Gaussian elimination.

### Related problems

Xor basis problems use the same rank and kernel viewpoint directly on binary integers.

