# Stack Weights

- **CSES task:** [Stack Weights](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2425)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (stackweights.cpp)`](./stackweights.cpp)

## Problem

Coins have unknown distinct weights satisfying $w_1<w_2<\cdots<w_n$. Coins are placed one by one onto a left or right stack. After every placement, report whether one stack is necessarily heavier for every valid assignment of weights, or whether the comparison is undetermined.

## Reasoning

Let $s_i$ be 1 if coin $i$ is on the left, $-1$ if it is on the right, and 0 if unused. The weight difference is

$$D=\sum_{i=1}^n s_iw_i.$$

Define positive increments $d_1=w_1$ and $d_j=w_j-w_{j-1}$ for $j>1$. Substitution gives

$$D=\sum_{j=1}^n c_jd_j,
\qquad c_j=\sum_{i=j}^n s_i.$$

The increments may be arbitrary positive numbers. Therefore $D$ is always positive exactly when every $c_j\ge0$ and at least one is positive; it is always negative under the symmetric condition. If positive and negative coefficients both occur, choosing one corresponding increment sufficiently large can force either sign.

Adding coin $c$ changes every suffix coefficient $c_j$ with $j\le c$ by 1 or $-1$. We need range addition on a prefix plus the global minimum and maximum, which a lazy segment tree supports.

## Algorithm

Initialize all coefficients to zero. For each move `(c,s)`, add 1 to range $[1,c]$ for the left stack or $-1$ for the right. Read the tree's global minimum and maximum. Report `>` if all coefficients are nonnegative and some is positive, `<` if all are nonpositive and some is negative, and `?` otherwise.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The segment-tree value at position $j$ equals $c_j=\sum_{i=j}^n s_i$ after every move.

**Proof.** Placing coin $c$ changes $s_c$ only, and $s_c$ occurs in exactly coefficients $c_j$ with $j\le c$. The prefix update applies precisely that change. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The stack comparison is forced positive exactly when $\min_j c_j\ge0$ and $\max_j c_j>0$, and forced negative symmetrically.

**Proof.** Since all $d_j>0$, coefficients of one sign with at least one strict coefficient force that sign of $D$. If both signs occur, scaling the increment paired with either sign makes that term dominate, producing two valid weight assignments with opposite comparisons. All-zero coefficients give a tie and no heavier stack. $\square$

**Theorem.** Every reported symbol is correct.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 makes the tree extrema the extrema of the true coefficients. Lemma 2 maps their sign pattern exactly to the required output cases. $\square$

### Complexity

Each move performs one lazy range update in $O(\log n)$ time. The tree uses $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The code uses zero based segment positions, so coin number `c` updates `[0,c-1]`. Root values `mx[1]` and `mn[1]` summarize the entire coefficient array after lazy propagation.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int N;
vi mx, mn, lz;                          // suffix-sum array c[], global max/min

void app(int nd, ll v){ mx[nd]+=v; mn[nd]+=v; lz[nd]+=v; }
void push(int nd){
    if(lz[nd]){ app(2*nd, lz[nd]); app(2*nd+1, lz[nd]); lz[nd]=0; }
}
void upd(int nd, int l, int r, int ql, int qr, ll v){
    if(qr < l || r < ql) return;
    if(ql <= l && r <= qr){ app(nd, v); return; }
    push(nd);
    int md = (l+r)/2;
    upd(2*nd, l, md, ql, qr, v);
    upd(2*nd+1, md+1, r, ql, qr, v);
    mx[nd] = max(mx[2*nd], mx[2*nd+1]);
    mn[nd] = min(mn[2*nd], mn[2*nd+1]);
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    N = n;
    mx.assign(4*N, 0); mn.assign(4*N, 0); lz.assign(4*N, 0);

    string out; out.reserve(n*2);
    for(int t = 0; t < n; t++){
        int c, sk; cin >> c >> sk;
        ll dv = (sk == 1) ? 1 : -1;
        upd(1, 0, N-1, 0, c-1, dv);          // c_j changes for j ≤ c
        ll M = mx[1], m = mn[1];
        char res;
        if(M > 0 && m < 0) res = '?';
        else if(M > 0)     res = '>';
        else if(m < 0)     res = '<';
        else               res = '?';        // all zero ⇒ tie
        out.pb(res); out.pb('\n');
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

After putting coin 2 left and coin 3 right, coefficients are $[0,0,-1]$. All are nonpositive and one is negative, so the right stack is necessarily heavier. Adding coin 1 left changes only the first coefficient, giving `[1,0,-1]`; mixed signs make the result undetermined.

## Takeaway

When only the order of unknown weights is known, rewrite weights as positive adjacent differences. Universal comparisons then become sign conditions on suffix coefficients.

### Related problems

Difference-array transformations frequently turn ordered-variable inequalities into range updates over coefficient sums.

