# Subarray Sum Constraints

- **CSES task:** [Subarray Sum Constraints](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3294)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (subarraysumconstraints.cpp)`](./subarraysumconstraints.cpp)

## Problem

Construct an integer array satisfying up to $2\cdot10^5$ prescribed subarray sums, or prove that the constraints are inconsistent.

## Reasoning

Introduce prefix sums $P_0=0$ and $P_i=x_1+\cdots+x_i$. Constraint $(l,r,s)$ becomes

$$P_r-P_{l-1}=s.$$

These are difference equations between vertices $0$ through $n$. A weighted disjoint-set union stores connected components together with a potential `d[v] = P_v-P_parent[v]`. Path compression accumulates each potential to the component root.

If two endpoints are already connected, their implied difference is fixed and must equal $s$. Otherwise, joining their roots with the derived offset adds the new equation without restricting unrelated components. Components may choose arbitrary root values; setting each root effectively to zero yields one valid solution.

## Algorithm

Initialize a weighted DSU on all prefix indices. For each constraint, find roots of $l-1$ and $r$. Check the existing difference if roots match; otherwise attach the latter root to the former with the offset that makes the equation true. If consistent, output $x_i=P_i-P_{i-1}$ from the stored root-relative potentials.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** After `find(v)`, `d[v]` equals $P_v-P_{root(v)}$ for all equations represented by the DSU.

**Proof.** The base case at a root is zero. Path compression adds the offset from $v$ to its parent and from that parent to the root, which telescopes to the required difference. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** A processed constraint is rejected exactly when it contradicts earlier constraints.

**Proof.** Connected endpoints already have a uniquely implied difference `d[b]-d[a]`, so disagreement is a contradiction. For separate components, their root values are still relatively free; assigning `d[rb]=s-d[b]+d[a]` makes $P_b-P_a=s$ and preserves all internal differences. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm prints `NO` exactly for inconsistent systems; otherwise it prints a valid array.

**Proof.** Lemma 2 proves the consistency decision. In the accepted case, every stored constraint holds among the chosen prefix potentials. Defining $x_i=P_i-P_{i-1}$ telescopes each requested subarray sum back to $P_r-P_{l-1}=s$. $\square$

### Complexity

Weighted DSU takes $O((n+m)\alpha(n))$ time and $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The union always attaches `rb` under `ra`; union by size is unnecessary for correctness because path compression supplies the inverse-Ackermann bound in practice. Potentials and reconstructed values use `long long`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int par[5005];
ll d[5005];                         // P_v - P_par[v]

int find(int v){
    if(par[v] == v) return v;
    int r = find(par[v]);
    d[v] += d[par[v]];              // accumulate offset to root
    par[v] = r;
    return r;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m; cin >> n >> m;
    for(int i = 0; i <= n; i++){ par[i] = i; d[i] = 0; }

    bool ok = true;
    for(int q = 0; q < m; q++){
        ll l, r, s; cin >> l >> r >> s;
        int a = l-1, b = r;                    // P_b - P_a = s
        int ra = find(a), rb = find(b);
        if(ra == rb){
            if(d[b] - d[a] != s) ok = false;   // inconsistent
        } else {
            d[rb] = s - d[b] + d[a];           // P_rb - P_ra
            par[rb] = ra;
        }
    }

    if(!ok){ cout << "NO\n"; return 0; }

    cout << "YES\n";
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        find(i); find(i-1);                    // ensure d[] are root-relative
        cout << d[i] - d[i-1] << " \n"[i==n];   // x_i = P_i - P_{i-1}
    }
}
```

## Worked Example

Constraints $(1,2,5)$ and $(2,3,4)$ state $P_2-P_0=5$ and $P_3-P_1=4$. A later constraint $(1,3,8)$ fixes $P_3-P_0=8$; the DSU accepts it only if the accumulated component potentials agree with 8.

## Takeaway

Equations of the form $X_v-X_u=c$ are the natural domain of weighted DSU. Prefix sums first convert interval equations into exactly that form.

### Related problems

Potential DSU also handles parity relations, modular differences, and relative-coordinate constraints.

