# Swap Game

- **CSES task:** [Swap Game](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1670)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (swapgame.cpp)`](./swapgame.cpp)

## Problem

A $3\times3$ grid contains the numbers 1 through 9. One move swaps horizontally or vertically adjacent cells. Find the minimum moves needed to reach row major order.

## Reasoning

The grid dimensions are fixed, so there are only $9!=362880$ arrangements. Model each arrangement as a graph vertex. Two vertices share an undirected edge exactly when one legal adjacent swap transforms one arrangement into the other. Every edge has cost one, making the required answer an unweighted shortest path.

Breadth first search is therefore sufficient. Encoding a board as a nine character string gives a compact state key. The twelve legal grid edges can be generated once, then applied to every dequeued state.

## Algorithm

Read the board into a string. Generate all horizontal and vertical neighboring index pairs. Run BFS from the input state, storing the first distance assigned to every string. Stop when `123456789` is dequeued.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The generated neighbors of a state are exactly the boards reachable in one legal move.

**Proof.** Each generated pair represents one horizontal or vertical grid adjacency, and swapping it is legal. Conversely, every legal move uses one such adjacency, all of which are generated. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** When BFS first records a state at distance $d$, no sequence of fewer than $d$ moves reaches it.

**Proof.** BFS processes the unweighted state graph in nondecreasing distance. Every newly recorded neighbor has distance one more than its predecessor, so any shorter route would have discovered it earlier. $\square$

**Theorem.** The printed value is the minimum number of moves needed.

**Proof.** By Lemma 1, paths in the state graph correspond exactly to legal move sequences. Lemma 2 makes the target's recorded distance the shortest such path length. $\square$

### Complexity

At most $9!$ states are visited, each with 12 transitions. Time and space are $O(9!)$, which is bounded by 362880 states.

## Implementation

`unordered_map<string,int>` simultaneously marks visited states and stores distances. Testing `dist.count(nxt)` before insertion prevents repeated exploration.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    string start = "";
    for(int i = 0; i < 9; i++){
        char c; cin >> c;
        start += c;
    }

    string target = "123456789";
    vector<pair<int, int>> edges;

    for(int r = 0; r < 3; r++){
        for(int c = 0; c < 3; c++){
            int id = 3 * r + c;
            
            if(r+1<3) edges.pb({id, id+3});
            if(c+1<3) edges.pb({id, id+1});
        }
    }

    queue<string> q;
    unordered_map<string, int> dist;

    q.push(start);
    dist[start] = 0;

    while(!q.empty()){
        string cur = q.front(); q.pop();

        if(cur==target){
            cout << dist[cur] << '\n';
            return 0;
        }

        for(auto e : edges){
            string nxt = cur;
            swap(nxt[e.f], nxt[e.s]);

            if(!dist.count(nxt)){
                dist[nxt] = dist[cur] + 1;
                q.push(nxt);
            }
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

From `213759846`, swapping the first two cells produces `123759846`, one of twelve distance 1 neighbors. BFS explores all such one move states before any distance 2 state, so when the target is reached at distance 4, no three move solution can have been skipped.

## Takeaway

When an apparently combinatorial puzzle has a tiny fixed state space, define moves as graph edges and let shortest path search replace ad hoc reasoning.

### Related problems

Sliding Puzzle and permutation puzzles use the same state graph model, sometimes with bidirectional BFS when the state space is larger.

