# Two Array Average

- **CSES task:** [Two Array Average](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3361)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (twoarrayavg.cpp)`](./twoarrayavg.cpp)

## Problem

Choose a nonempty prefix of each of two arrays so that the average over all chosen elements is maximum. Output the two prefix lengths for $n\le10^5$.

## Reasoning

Let $A_i$ and $B_j$ be prefix sums. Choosing lengths $(i,j)$ gives

$$\frac{A_i+B_j}{i+j},$$

the slope from the origin to point $(i+j,A_i+B_j)$. These points form the Minkowski sum of the prefix-point sets $(i,A_i)$ and $(j,B_j)$.

Only vertices of each set's upper convex hull can participate in the upper hull of the Minkowski sum. The upper hull of a Minkowski sum is obtained by merging the edge sequences of the two hulls in decreasing slope order. Starting from the sum of their first vertices, advance along whichever next edge is steeper. Every upper-hull vertex of the combined set is visited, so checking its slope from the origin finds the best average.

All comparisons can be performed exactly with cross products.

## Algorithm

Build prefix sums and the upper convex hull of points `(k,S[k])` for each array, considering $k=1$ through $n$. Merge their hull-edge sequences by slope. At every visited pair of hull vertices, compare $(A_i+B_j)/(i+j)$ with the current best and retain improving prefix lengths.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** A prefix point removed while building an upper hull cannot participate in a maximum-average pair.

**Proof.** The removed point lies on or below the segment between its neighbors. Replacing it by the corresponding convex combination cannot decrease the vertical coordinate for a given horizontal contribution. After adding any point from the other array, it therefore cannot uniquely maximize slope from the origin. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** Merging hull edges in decreasing slope order visits every vertex of the upper hull of the Minkowski sum.

**Proof.** A supporting direction selects one vertex from each summand hull. As the direction rotates, the next exposed edge is whichever summand has the next steeper edge. Advancing edges in that order is exactly the standard Minkowski-hull merge. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs prefix lengths attaining the maximum possible average.

**Proof.** By Lemma 1, an optimum exists among sums of retained hull vertices. Any such sum maximizing slope lies on the combined upper hull, whose vertices are all visited by Lemma 2. Exact cross multiplication selects the greatest slope among them. $\square$

### Complexity

Each hull is built in $O(n)$ time and their edge lists are merged in $O(n)$ time. Space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

`__int128` is required for products involving prefix sums up to $10^{14}$ and lengths up to $10^5$. The `hull` cross-product condition removes collinear middle points, which are unnecessary for maximizing the slope.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
typedef __int128 lll;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;

// upper hull of points (k, S[k]), k=1..n ; returns the indices
vector<int> hull(const vector<ll>& S, int n){
    vector<int> h;
    for(int k = 1; k <= n; k++){
        while(h.size() >= 2){
            int o = h[h.size()-2], a = h[h.size()-1];
            lll lhs = (lll)(a-o)*(S[k]-S[o]);     // cross(O,A,K) >= 0 => A below => pop
            lll rhs = (lll)(S[a]-S[o])*(k-o);
            if(lhs - rhs >= 0) h.pop_back(); else break;
        }
        h.pb(k);
    }
    return h;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<ll> A(n+1, 0), B(n+1, 0);
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ ll x; cin >> x; A[i] = A[i-1] + x; }
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ ll x; cin >> x; B[i] = B[i-1] + x; }

    vector<int> ha = hull(A, n), hb = hull(B, n);
    int La = ha.size(), Lb = hb.size();

    int ia = 0, ib = 0;
    int bi = ha[0], bj = hb[0];
    lll bP = (lll)A[bi] + B[bj], bD = (lll)bi + bj;     // best avg = bP/bD

    auto better = [&](int i, int j){
        lll P = (lll)A[i] + B[j], D = (lll)i + j;
        if(P*bD > bP*D){ bP = P; bD = D; bi = i; bj = j; }   // exact compare
    };

    while(ia < La-1 || ib < Lb-1){
        bool adA;
        if(ia == La-1) adA = false;
        else if(ib == Lb-1) adA = true;
        else{                                    // advance the steeper next edge
            ll nA = A[ha[ia+1]]-A[ha[ia]], dA = ha[ia+1]-ha[ia];
            ll nB = B[hb[ib+1]]-B[hb[ib]], dB = hb[ib+1]-hb[ib];
            adA = ( (lll)nA*dB >= (lll)nB*dA );
        }
        if(adA) ia++; else ib++;
        better(ha[ia], hb[ib]);                  // visit this Minkowski vertex
    }

    cout << bi << " " << bj << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

For arrays `[1,5,5,2]` and `[3,1,3,1]`, choosing $i=3,j=1$ gives point $(4,14)$ and slope $14/4=3.5$. The merged upper hull visits this point, and no visited supporting vertex has a larger slope.

## Takeaway

When an objective combines one independent choice from each of two sets, ask whether their feasible points form a Minkowski sum. Convex-hull edge merging can replace a quadratic pair search.

### Related problems

Maximum Average Subarrays also interprets averages as slopes between prefix-sum points.

