# K Subset Sums I

- **CSES task:** [K Subset Sums I](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3108)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (ksubsetsums1.cpp)`](./ksubsetsums1.cpp)

## Problem

Among all $2^n$ subset sums of up to $2\cdot10^5$ integers, output the $k\le2\cdot10^5$ smallest in nondecreasing order.

## Reasoning

First remove negative signs. Put every negative input into a baseline subset, adding it to `base`, and replace the value by its absolute value. Toggling membership of any original element then increases the baseline sum by that absolute value. Thus original subset sums are `base` plus all subset sums of a nonnegative array.

Sort these magnitudes. Nonempty subsets form a min-heap-ordered generation tree. Represent a subset by its sum $s$ and largest chosen index $i$. It has two children involving $i+1$: add the next value, or replace the current largest value by the next. Every nonempty subset except `{0}` has exactly one parent under the reverse operation determined by whether its previous index is present. Since children never have smaller sums, a priority queue performs a best-first traversal and emits subset sums in order, including duplicates.

## Algorithm

Compute the negative baseline, take absolute values, and sort. Output the baseline for the empty toggle set. Seed the heap with `(a[0],0)`. Repeatedly pop the minimum and output `base+sum`; if a next index exists, push the add and replace children.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The baseline transformation is a bijection preserving sums up to adding `base`.

**Proof.** For a negative value, baseline includes it and toggling removes it at cost $|x|$; for a nonnegative value, baseline excludes it and toggling adds it at the same cost. Choices remain independent. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The generation tree contains every nonempty subset of sorted magnitudes exactly once.

**Proof.** Both children have new largest index $i+1$. Reversing from a subset with largest index $j$ either removes $j$ if $j-1$ is present, or replaces $j$ by $j-1$ otherwise. This unique rule reaches one parent and eventually the root. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the $k$ smallest original subset sums in order.

**Proof.** Edge increments in the generation tree are nonnegative. Priority-queue best-first traversal therefore emits its nodes in nondecreasing sum. Lemma 2 supplies every transformed subset once, and Lemma 1 maps the sequence back to original sums. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting takes $O(n\log n)$. Generating $k$ sums takes $O(k\log k)$ time and $O(k)$ heap space.

## Implementation

The output begins with `base`, corresponding to no toggles. Pair ordering automatically gives deterministic tie handling, though only sum order matters.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n; ll k; cin >> n >> k;
    vector<ll> a(n); ll base = 0;
    for(auto& x : a){ cin >> x; if(x < 0){ base += x; x = -x; } }   // shift: sums = base + subset sums of |x|
    sort(a.begin(), a.end());

    string out; out.reserve(k * 12);
    out += to_string(base); out += ' ';                            // empty subset = base
    // states (sum, i): i = last index included; children add or swap-up the next index
    priority_queue<ii, vector<ii>, greater<ii>> pq;
    if(n) pq.push({a[0], 0});
    for(ll cnt = 1; cnt < k; cnt++){
        auto [s, i] = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        out += to_string(base + s); out += ' ';
        if(i + 1 < n){
            pq.push({s + a[i+1], i+1});                             // add next
            pq.push({s - a[i] + a[i+1], i+1});                      // swap last for next
        }
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `[1,-3,6]`, baseline is -3 and magnitudes are `[1,3,6]`. The smallest toggle sums are 0, 1, 3, 4, so the corresponding original sums begin -3, -2, 0, 1.

## Takeaway

To enumerate smallest subset sums, shift negative values into a baseline and traverse the implicit heap of subsets of sorted nonnegative costs.

### Related problems

K Subset Sums II adds a fixed subset cardinality, requiring a more compressed state representation.

