# Food Division

- **CSES task:** [Food Division](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1189)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (fooddivision.cpp)`](./fooddivision.cpp)

## Problem

Children sit around a cycle. Moving one unit of food across one neighboring edge costs one. Transform current amounts into target amounts with minimum total cost.

## Reasoning

Let $d_i=a_i-b_i$ and orient every edge clockwise. If $f_i$ units flow across edge $i$, conservation gives $f_i-f_{i-1}=d_i$. Therefore all flows are determined up to one additive constant:

$$f_i=P_i-C,\qquad P_i=\sum_{j=1}^i d_j.$$

Net flow may be negative, meaning counterclockwise movement. The cost is $\sum_i|f_i|=\sum_i|P_i-C|$. A sum of absolute deviations is minimized by any median of the prefix imbalances. Sorting the $P_i$ and choosing the middle value solves the cycle's one remaining degree of freedom.

## Algorithm

Compute prefix sums of `a[i]-b[i]`, sort them, choose their median, and sum absolute deviations from it.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Every feasible redistribution corresponds to flows $f_i=P_i-C$ for some constant $C$, and every such flow satisfies all balances.

**Proof.** Subtracting consecutive conservation equations yields the prefix relation; cycling leaves one free initial flow $C$. Conversely, these differences equal every $d_i$, so conservation holds. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** A median minimizes $\sum_i|P_i-C|$.

**Proof.** Moving $C$ right decreases the contribution of points to its right and increases that of points to its left. The slope changes from negative to nonnegative exactly at a median. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm returns the minimum number of unit moves.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 represents all feasible redistributions and their edge-flow costs. Lemma 2 minimizes that cost over the only free parameter. $\square$

### Complexity

Prefix construction is $O(n)$ and sorting is $O(n\log n)$. Space is $O(n)$.

## Implementation

The equality of total initial and target food makes the final prefix imbalance zero and ensures cyclic feasibility. `long long` stores prefix imbalances and the total cost.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<ll> a(n), b(n);
    for (auto& v : a) cin >> v;
    for (auto& v : b) cin >> v;

    vector<ll> P(n);
    ll pref = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        pref += a[i] - b[i];
        P[i] = pref;
    }

    sort(P.begin(), P.end());
    ll k = P[n / 2];   // median

    ll ans = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) ans += llabs(P[i] - k);

    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For differences `[1,1,-2]`, prefix imbalances are `[1,2,0]`. Their median is 1, and the minimum cost is $|1-1|+|2-1|+|0-1|=2$.

## Takeaway

Flow on a cycle is flow on a path plus one free circulation. Absolute transport cost turns choosing that circulation into a median problem.

### Related problems

Stick Lengths uses the same median minimization of absolute deviations.

