# Swap Round Sorting

- **CSES task:** [Swap Round Sorting](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1698)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (swaproundsorting.cpp)`](./swaproundsorting.cpp)

## Problem

Sort a permutation in the minimum number of rounds, where one round may swap any collection of pairwise disjoint index pairs. Output all swaps.

## Reasoning

One round is an involution: it consists only of fixed points and disjoint transpositions. The identity needs zero rounds, and a permutation containing only cycles of length at most two needs one. Every other permutation needs at least two.

Two rounds always suffice because every cycle is a product of two involutions. Number a cycle's positions $0,1,\ldots,L-1$ so the permutation advances $j$ to $j+1$. Define reflections

$$r_1(j)=-j\pmod L,
\qquad r_2(j)=1-j\pmod L.$$

Both are involutions, and $r_2(r_1(j))=j+1$. Each reflection decomposes into disjoint swaps, so it forms one legal round. Cycles can be handled together because their index sets are disjoint.

## Algorithm

Decompose the permutation into cycles. For each cycle, add pairs implementing $j\leftrightarrow-j$ to round 1 and $j\leftrightarrow1-j$ to round 2. Output zero, one, or two rounds according to the longest cycle length.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Every printed round is legal.

**Proof.** Each modular reflection is an involution. Its nonfixed orbits are disjoint two-element sets, and the `j<t` condition prints each orbit once. Different cycles share no indices. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** Applying the two constructed rounds realizes the permutation's action on every cycle.

**Proof.** On cycle coordinate $j$, their composition is $r_2(r_1(j))=1-(-j)=j+1\pmod L$, exactly the cycle mapping. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm sorts the permutation using the minimum number of rounds.

**Proof.** Zero rounds are possible only for the identity. One round is possible exactly for an involution, equivalently when every cycle has length at most two. Otherwise at least two are required, and Lemmas 1 and 2 construct two. $\square$

### Complexity

Cycle decomposition and swap generation take $O(n)$ time and $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The code follows mapping `u=x[u]` to list each cycle. Fixed points create no pairs. When the maximum cycle length is two, round 1 is empty and only round 2 is printed.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<int> x(n + 1);
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) cin >> x[i];

    vector<char> vis(n + 1, 0);
    vector<ii> r1, r2;                         // swap pairs of rounds 1,2 ; rho = r2 o r1
    int mx = 1;                                // longest cycle length
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) if(!vis[i]){
        vector<int> c; int u = i;
        while(!vis[u]){ vis[u] = 1; c.pb(u); u = x[u]; }      // follow f: c_{j+1}=x[c_j]
        int L = c.size(); mx = max(mx, L);
        for(int j = 0; j < L; j++){ int t = (L - j) % L;       if(j < t) r1.pb({c[j], c[t]}); }   // r1: j <-> -j
        for(int j = 0; j < L; j++){ int t = ((1 - j) % L + L) % L; if(j < t) r2.pb({c[j], c[t]}); }// r2: j <-> 1-j
    }

    auto dump = [&](vector<ii>& r){ cout << r.size() << "\n"; for(auto& p : r) cout << p.f << ' ' << p.s << "\n"; };
    if(mx == 1) cout << 0 << "\n";                          // already sorted
    else if(mx == 2){ cout << 1 << "\n"; dump(r2); }        // involution: all swaps fall in r2 (r1 empty)
    else { cout << 2 << "\n"; dump(r1); dump(r2); }
}
```

## Worked Example

For a 5-cycle, round 1 swaps coordinates 1 with 4 and 2 with 3. Round 2 swaps 0 with 1 and 2 with 4. Their composition advances every coordinate by one, realizing the cycle in two rounds.

## Takeaway

A round of disjoint swaps is an involution. Factorizing permutations into involutions turns a scheduling constraint into cycle algebra.

### Related problems

Sorting Methods uses cycle count when arbitrary swaps are performed sequentially rather than in parallel rounds.

