# School Excursion

- **CSES task:** [School Excursion](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1706)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (schoolexcursion.cpp)`](./schoolexcursion.cpp)

## Problem

Among $n\le10^5$ children, each given pair must choose the same attraction. Report every possible positive number of children who can choose the first attraction.

## Reasoning

The equality wishes are transitive, so every connected component of the wish graph must move as one indivisible group. If component sizes are $s_1,s_2,\ldots$, the attainable attendance counts are exactly their subset sums.

A scalar knapsack DP would be quadratic. A bitset stores all attainable sums simultaneously: shifting it left by $s$ represents adding one component of size $s$. Many components may share a size. Binary decomposition replaces $c$ identical copies by chunks of sizes $1,2,4,\ldots$ plus a remainder, reducing the number of bitset shifts to $O(\log c)$.

## Algorithm

Use DSU to find connected components and count how many have each size. Initialize bitset `dp` with bit 0. Binary-split the multiplicity of every size $s$ and apply `dp |= dp << (s*take)`. Print bits 1 through $n$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** A valid attraction assignment chooses whole connected components, and every choice of whole components is valid.

**Proof.** Every edge requires equal choices, so equality propagates along paths. No constraint connects distinct components, so their choices are independent. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** After processing the chunks, `dp[j]` is set exactly when components totaling $j$ can be selected.

**Proof.** Binary chunks represent every number from 0 through each multiplicity exactly as a subset of chunk counts. Each shift adds one available chunk, and the bitwise union also retains choices excluding it. Induction over chunks proves the claim. $\square$

**Theorem.** The output bit at position $i$ is one exactly when $i$ children can visit the first attraction.

**Proof.** Combine Lemma 1's component reduction with Lemma 2's exact subset-sum representation. $\square$

### Complexity

DSU takes $O((n+m)\alpha(n))$ time. At most $O(\sqrt n\log n)$ machine-bitset shifts arise from grouped sizes, each over $O(n/64)$ words; space is $O(n)$ bits plus DSU arrays.

## Implementation

The output string is zero based while the problem is one indexed, so reachability of sum `i` is written to `out[i-1]`. The static bitset size covers the maximum $n$.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;
const int MX = 100005;

int p[MX], sz[MX];
int find(int x){ while(p[x] != x) x = p[x] = p[p[x]]; return x; }

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n, m; cin >> n >> m;
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){ p[i] = i; sz[i] = 1; }
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        int a, b; cin >> a >> b; a = find(a); b = find(b);
        if(a != b){ p[a] = b; sz[b] += sz[a]; }                 // union by attaching a under b
    }

    vector<int> cnt(n + 1, 0);
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) if(find(i) == i) cnt[sz[i]]++;  // multiset of component sizes

    static bitset<MX> dp; dp[0] = 1;
    for(int s = 1; s <= n; s++) if(cnt[s]){                     // bounded knapsack, binary-split each count
        int c = cnt[s];
        for(int k = 1; c > 0; k <<= 1){
            int take = min(k, c); c -= take;
            dp |= dp << (s * take);                             // chunk of `take` components of size s
        }
    }

    string out(n, '0');
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) if(dp[i]) out[i-1] = '1';       // one-indexed
    cout << out << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

If component sizes are 4 and 1, subset sums are 0, 1, 4, and 5. Ignoring zero, the output for $n=5$ is `10011`, marking positions 1, 4, and 5.

## Takeaway

Equality constraints first suggest connected components. When component sizes then form a large subset-sum instance, bitset shifts and multiplicity grouping are a powerful combination.

### Related problems

Money Sums uses the same bitset recurrence without the DSU preprocessing.

