# Coin Grid

- **CSES task:** [Coin Grid](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1709)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (coingrid.cpp)`](./coingrid.cpp)

## Problem

Remove all coins from an $n\times n$ grid using the minimum number of operations, where an operation clears one entire row or column. Output an optimal set of rows and columns.

## Reasoning

Create a bipartite graph with one left vertex per row and one right vertex per column. A coin at $(r,c)$ is edge $r-c$. Clearing a row or column selects the corresponding endpoint, and every coin disappears exactly when every edge has at least one selected endpoint. The task is minimum vertex cover in a bipartite graph.

Konig's theorem states that its size equals maximum matching size. It also gives a construction. From every unmatched left vertex, traverse unmatched edges left to right and matched edges right to left. If $Z$ is the reached set, then

$$(L\setminus Z)\cup(R\cap Z)$$

is a minimum vertex cover.

## Algorithm

Find a maximum matching with augmenting-path DFS. Run the alternating reachability traversal from unmatched rows. Output every unreached matched row and every reached column.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The constructed vertices cover every coin edge.

**Proof.** Suppose edge $(u,v)$ were uncovered. Then $u\in Z$ and $v\notin Z$. If the edge is unmatched, traversal from $u$ reaches $v$, a contradiction. If matched, reaching $u$ through alternating traversal implies its matched edge's right endpoint was already reached. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The cover contains exactly one endpoint of every matching edge.

**Proof.** For a matched pair, alternating reachability reaches either both endpoints or neither. In the first case its right endpoint is chosen; in the second its left endpoint is chosen. $\square$

**Theorem.** The printed operations are valid and minimum.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 proves validity. Lemma 2 makes the cover size equal to maximum matching size. Every vertex cover must contain at least one endpoint of each disjoint matching edge, so no smaller cover exists. $\square$

### Complexity

Kuhn matching takes $O(VE)=O(n^3)$ in the dense worst case, acceptable for $n\le100$. Space is $O(n^2)$.

## Implementation

`mr` and `mc` store both directions of the matching. The alternating traversal starts only at unmatched rows. Output type 1 denotes a row and type 2 a column.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int n;
vector<vector<int>> adj;                 // rows -> cols (1..n each side)
vector<int> mr, mc;                      // mr[r]=matched col, mc[c]=matched row (0 = none)
vector<char> used;                       // Kuhn visited (right side per phase)

bool kuhn(int u){
    for(int v : adj[u]) if(!used[v]){
        used[v] = 1;
        if(mc[v] == 0 || kuhn(mc[v])){ mc[v] = u; mr[u] = v; return true; }
    }
    return false;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    cin >> n;
    adj.assign(n + 1, {});
    for(int r = 1; r <= n; r++){
        string row; cin >> row;
        for(int c = 1; c <= n; c++) if(row[c-1] == 'o') adj[r].pb(c);   // coin = edge r-c
    }

    mr.assign(n + 1, 0); mc.assign(n + 1, 0);
    int M = 0;
    for(int r = 1; r <= n; r++){ used.assign(n + 1, 0); if(kuhn(r)) M++; }

    // alternating-reachable from unmatched left. MVC = (L\Z) ∪ (R∩Z).
    vector<char> visL(n + 1, 0), visR(n + 1, 0);
    vector<int> st;
    for(int r = 1; r <= n; r++) if(mr[r] == 0){ visL[r] = 1; st.pb(r); }
    while(!st.empty()){
        int u = st.back(); st.pop_back();
        for(int v : adj[u]) if(!visR[v]){                 // unmatched edge L->R
            visR[v] = 1;
            int w = mc[v];                                // matched edge R->L
            if(w && !visL[w]){ visL[w] = 1; st.pb(w); }
        }
    }

    vector<ii> cover;                                     // (type, idx): 1=row, 2=col
    for(int r = 1; r <= n; r++) if(!visL[r] && mr[r]) cover.pb({1, r});   // L\Z (matched rows not reached)
    for(int c = 1; c <= n; c++) if(visR[c]) cover.pb({2, c});             // R∩Z

    cout << cover.size() << "\n";
    for(auto& p : cover) cout << p.f << ' ' << p.s << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

Coins at `(1,3)`, `(2,1)`, and `(2,3)` form three edges. A maximum matching has size 2, and one minimum cover is row 2 plus column 3. Those two clearing operations remove every coin.

## Takeaway

Selecting rows and columns to cover marked cells is bipartite vertex cover. Maximum matching supplies both the lower bound and the constructive optimum.

### Related problems

School Dance finds the matching side of Konig's theorem without reconstructing a vertex cover.

