# Grid Coloring II

- **CSES task:** [Grid Coloring II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3312)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (gridcoloring2.cpp)`](./gridcoloring2.cpp)

## Problem

Recolor every grid cell with one of `A`, `B`, or `C`, different from its original color, so adjacent cells differ. Construct a solution or report impossibility for a grid of up to $500\times500$.

## Reasoning

Each cell forbids its original color, leaving exactly two choices. Represent that choice by one Boolean variable. An adjacency constraint rules out every pair of Boolean values that would assign the same new color to its endpoints.

Forbidding assignment $(u=p,v=q)$ is the 2-CNF clause

$$(u\ne p)\lor(v\ne q),$$

implemented by implications `(u=p) -> (v!=q)` and `(v=q) -> (u!=p)`. The entire grid is therefore a 2-SAT instance with one variable per cell and at most four forbidden pairs per grid edge.

## Algorithm

Map each cell's two allowed colors to Boolean values. Add implications for every equal-color pair across horizontal and vertical neighbors. Compute strongly connected components with iterative Tarjan. Reject if a literal and its negation share an SCC; otherwise choose truth values from reverse topological SCC order and print the corresponding colors.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** The clauses are satisfied exactly when adjacent output cells have different colors.

**Proof.** For each edge, every pair producing equal colors is forbidden, and no unequal pair is forbidden. Taking all such clauses enforces precisely the adjacency condition. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The SCC test and assignment solve the constructed 2-SAT formula.

**Proof.** A variable is impossible exactly when its two literals imply each other and lie in one SCC. Otherwise assigning the literal later in implication topological order to false yields a consistent satisfying assignment, which is the standard 2-SAT SCC theorem. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm prints a valid recoloring exactly when one exists.

**Proof.** Every Boolean value maps to one of the two colors different from the original. Lemma 1 equates formula satisfaction with valid adjacency, and Lemma 2 decides and constructs formula satisfaction. $\square$

### Complexity

The implication graph has $O(nm)$ vertices and edges. Time and space are $O(nm)$.

## Implementation

Node `2*u` denotes the true-choice literal and `2*u+1` its negation, so xor with 1 flips a literal. The iterative Tarjan stack avoids recursion depth near 250000 cells.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD=1e9+7;
const int INF=1e9;

int n,m;
vector<vector<int>> adj;     // 2-SAT implication graph

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr);
    cin>>n>>m;
    vector<string> gr(n);
    for(auto&r:gr) cin>>r;

    int V=n*m, NN=2*V;
    adj.assign(NN,{});
    auto id=[&](int i,int j){ return i*m+j; };
    // var x per cell; node 2x = "x=1" (col1), 2x+1 = "x=0" (col0). col0=(o+1)%3, col1=(o+2)%3.
    vector<int> c0(V),c1(V);
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)for(int j=0;j<m;j++){ int o=gr[i][j]-'A',e=id(i,j); c0[e]=(o+1)%3; c1[e]=(o+2)%3; }
    auto col=[&](int u,int b){ return b?c1[u]:c0[u]; };
    auto lit=[&](int u,int b){ return 2*u+(b?0:1); };                 // "u=b" literal node
    auto add=[&](int a,int b){ adj[a].pb(b); };                       // implication a->b
    auto forbid=[&](int u,int bu,int w,int bw){ int a=lit(u,bu),b=lit(w,bw); add(a,b^1); add(b,a^1); };  // ¬(u=bu ∧ w=bw)
    auto edge=[&](int u,int w){ for(int bu=0;bu<2;bu++)for(int bw=0;bw<2;bw++) if(col(u,bu)==col(w,bw)) forbid(u,bu,w,bw); };

    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)for(int j=0;j<m;j++){
        int u=id(i,j);
        if(j+1<m) edge(u,id(i,j+1));
        if(i+1<n) edge(u,id(i+1,j));
    }

    // iterative Tarjan SCC (su = dfs stack, it = current-arc)  [reused from New Flight Routes]
    vector<int> disc(NN,0), low(NN,0), comp(NN,0), it(NN,0);
    vector<char> onstk(NN,0);
    vector<int> stk, su;
    int timer=0, C=0;
    for(int s0=0;s0<NN;s0++) if(!disc[s0]){
        su.pb(s0);
        while(!su.empty()){
            int u=su.back();
            if(!disc[u]){ disc[u]=low[u]=++timer; stk.pb(u); onstk[u]=1; }
            bool rec=false;
            while(it[u]<(int)adj[u].size()){
                int v=adj[u][it[u]++];
                if(!disc[v]){ su.pb(v); rec=true; break; }
                if(onstk[v]) low[u]=min(low[u],disc[v]);
            }
            if(rec) continue;
            if(low[u]==disc[u]){                       // root of an SCC
                ++C; int x;
                do{ x=stk.back(); stk.pop_back(); onstk[x]=0; comp[x]=C; }while(x!=u);
            }
            su.pop_back();
            if(!su.empty()) low[su.back()]=min(low[su.back()],low[u]);
        }
    }

    for(int x=0;x<V;x++) if(comp[2*x]==comp[2*x+1]){ cout<<"IMPOSSIBLE\n"; return 0; }

    string out; out.reserve((size_t)n*(m+1));
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        for(int j=0;j<m;j++){
            int u=id(i,j);
            int b = comp[2*u] < comp[2*u+1] ? 1 : 0;   // smaller comp = topo-later = literal true
            out += char('A'+col(u,b));
        }
        out += '\n';
    }
    cout<<out;
}
```

## Worked Example

If neighboring cells originally `A` and `B` allow colors `{B,C}` and `{A,C}`, the only equal-color combination is `(C,C)`. One 2-SAT clause forbids precisely that pair while leaving the other three combinations legal.

## Takeaway

Three colors become Boolean when each vertex forbids one fixed color. Pairwise incompatibilities between two-choice variables are exactly 2-SAT clauses.

### Related problems

Giant Pizza is the canonical direct 2-SAT formulation using the same implication-SCC criterion.

