# Programmers and Artists

- **CSES task:** [Programmers and Artists](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2426)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (programmersartists.cpp)`](./programmersartists.cpp)

## Problem

Hire exactly $a$ programmers and $b$ artists from up to $2\cdot10^5$ applicants. Applicant $i$ contributes $x_i$ in the first role or $y_i$ in the second and may take at most one role.

## Reasoning

Sort applicants by decreasing advantage $x_i-y_i$ for programming. In some optimum, every hired programmer appears before every hired artist in this order. If programmer $q$ lies after artist $p$, then

$$(x_p+y_q)-(y_p+x_q)=(x_p-y_p)-(x_q-y_q)\ge0,$$

so swapping their roles does not reduce value.

Therefore an optimum has a cut: choose the $a$ best programming scores from its prefix and the $b$ best artistic scores from its suffix. Min heaps maintain these top fixed-size sums for every cut.

## Algorithm

Sort by `x-y`. Sweep left to right to compute `leftA[c]`, the sum of the best $a$ programming scores among the first $c$ applicants. Sweep right to left for `rightB[c]`, the best $b$ artistic scores in suffix $[c,n)$. Maximize their sum over all cuts.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** An optimal assignment exists with no artist before a programmer in advantage order.

**Proof.** Any inverted pair can exchange roles with nonnegative change by the displayed inequality. Repeating removes all inversions. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** For a fixed cut, the heap sums give its optimal assignment.

**Proof.** Roles lie on disjoint sides, so independently choosing the top $a$ values of $x$ on the left and top $b$ values of $y$ on the right is necessary and sufficient. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm returns the maximum total skill.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 places some optimum at a tested cut, where Lemma 2 evaluates the best assignment. Every evaluated assignment is feasible, so the maximum equals the optimum. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting and heap maintenance take $O(n\log n)$ time and $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

Each min heap retains only the required number of scores, replacing its smallest member when a better score arrives. `NEG` marks cuts lacking enough applicants on one side.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;
const ll NEG = -(ll)4e18;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr);
    ll a, b; int n; cin >> a >> b >> n;
    vector<ii> v(n);
    for(auto& p : v) cin >> p.f >> p.s;
    sort(v.begin(), v.end(), [](const ii&A,const ii&B){ return A.f-A.s > B.f-B.s; });  // by x-y desc

    // value(S)=sum_S y + top-a (x-y) => optimum splits at a cut: left -> programmers (by x), right -> artists (by y)
    vector<ll> leftA(n+1, NEG), rightB(n+1, NEG);
    { priority_queue<ll,vector<ll>,greater<>> h; ll s=0; leftA[0]=(a==0?0:NEG);     // top-a x among first c
      for(int c=1;c<=n;c++){ ll x=v[c-1].f;
        if((ll)h.size()<a){ h.push(x); s+=x; } else if(a>0 && x>h.top()){ s+=x-h.top(); h.pop(); h.push(x); }
        leftA[c]=((ll)h.size()==a)? s : NEG; } }
    { priority_queue<ll,vector<ll>,greater<>> h; ll s=0; rightB[n]=(b==0?0:NEG);    // top-b y among [c,n)
      for(int c=n-1;c>=0;c--){ ll y=v[c].s;
        if((ll)h.size()<b){ h.push(y); s+=y; } else if(b>0 && y>h.top()){ s+=y-h.top(); h.pop(); h.push(y); }
        rightB[c]=((ll)h.size()==b)? s : NEG; } }

    ll ans=NEG;
    for(int c=0;c<=n;c++) if(leftA[c]>NEG/2 && rightB[c]>NEG/2) ans=max(ans, leftA[c]+rightB[c]);
    cout << ans << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

Applicants `(3,7)` and `(4,2)` have advantages -4 and 2, so `(4,2)` appears first. Assigning the earlier applicant as programmer and later one as artist scores 11, compared with 5 for the inverted role assignment.

## Takeaway

For two exclusive roles, sorting by score difference often creates a cut. Prefix and suffix top-k structures then replace a three-way assignment DP.

### Related problems

Scheduling and hiring problems with two roles frequently use the same exchange on score differences.

