# Removing Digits II

- **CSES task:** [Removing Digits II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2174)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (removingdigits2.cpp)`](./removingdigits2.cpp)

## Problem

Starting from $n\le10^{18}$, repeatedly subtract one digit appearing in the current number. Find the minimum steps to reach zero.

## Reasoning

An optimal move subtracts the largest present digit. A smaller available subtraction leaves a larger number after the same one step; the standard monotonicity exchange for this process replaces it by the maximum digit without increasing the remaining number of steps.

Direct simulation is still proportional to $n$. Write the current number as $10q+r$ and let $m$ be the maximum digit of $q$. Consider only the short episode until the prefix drops from $q$ to $q-1$. If $m=0$, nothing remains above the units digit. Otherwise:

- If $r<m$, subtracting $m$ crosses the decimal boundary in one step and leaves new remainder $r+10-m$.

- If $r\ge m$, first subtract $r$ to reach $10q$, then subtract $m$, taking two steps and leaving remainder $10-m$.

Thus every prefix $q$ acts as a transition on only ten possible remainders: `to[r]` and `add[r]`. Transitions compose associatively. `all[len][mx]` precomputes the composition for a complete block of `len` free decimal digits when the earlier prefix maximum is `mx`. Digit DP over the digits of $p=\lfloor n/10\rfloor$ composes exactly the blocks for prefixes from $p$ downward, reducing an enormous simulation to about 20 digit levels.

## Algorithm

Build the ten-state transition `one[m]` for every possible maximum digit. Precompute composed transitions for all suffix lengths and inherited maxima. Recursively scan the decimal digits of $p=n/10$, composing the exact digit branch and all smaller branches. Apply the resulting transition to initial remainder $n\bmod10$, then add one final step if a positive single digit remains.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** There is an optimal sequence that always subtracts the largest digit currently present.

**Proof.** Replace the first smaller subtraction by the largest available digit. It reaches a no-larger state in one step. Coupling subsequent subtractions across decimal intervals shows the larger-start process cannot reach zero earlier; repeating this exchange removes every nonmaximum choice. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** `one[m]` gives the exact remainder and step count when crossing one prefix boundary whose maximum digit is $m$.

**Proof.** The two cases $r<m$ and $r\ge m$ are exhaustive and follow the arithmetic above. In the second case, the units digit itself is the maximum until it is removed. $\square$

**Lemma 3.** `go` returns the composition of `one[maxDigit(q)]` over all required prefixes $q$.

**Proof.** At each decimal digit, the exact branch is processed recursively. Every smaller digit value represents a complete suffix block, whose transition is `all[remaining][inherited maximum]`. Concatenating branches in descending numeric order matches the order in which prefixes are crossed. Induction on remaining digits proves the claim. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the minimum number of steps to reduce $n$ to zero.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 reduces the optimum to deterministic maximum-digit simulation. Lemmas 2 and 3 show that the composed automaton performs exactly that simulation across all prefix boundaries. The final positive remainder is removed in one step, so the accumulated count is exact. $\square$

### Complexity

Precomputation and the digit recursion use a constant number of ten-state compositions per decimal digit and digit choice. Time is $O(10^2\log n)$ and space is $O(10\log n)$.

## Implementation

`merge_tr(a,b)` means apply transition `a` first and then `b`. The order of the descending digit loop is therefore significant. The special cases for one-digit values avoid a prefix of zero.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")

#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second

typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;

const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

struct Tr {
    int to[10];
    ll add[10];

    Tr(bool id = true) {
        for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            to[i] = i;
            add[i] = 0;
        }
    }
};

Tr all[20][10], one[10];

Tr merge_tr(const Tr& a, const Tr& b) {
    Tr c;
    for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        int mid = a.to[i];
        c.to[i] = b.to[mid];
        c.add[i] = a.add[i] + b.add[mid];
    }
    return c;
}

Tr build_one(int m) {
    Tr t;
    if(m == 0) return t;

    for(int r = 0; r < 10; r++) {
        if(r < m) {
            t.to[r] = r + 10 - m;
            t.add[r] = 1;
        } else {
            t.to[r] = 10 - m;
            t.add[r] = 2;
        }
    }
    return t;
}

Tr go(const string& s, int pos, int mx) {
    if(pos == (int)s.size()) return one[mx];

    int d = s[pos] - '0';
    int rem = (int)s.size() - pos - 1;

    Tr cur = go(s, pos + 1, max(mx, d));

    for(int x = d - 1; x >= 0; x--) {
        cur = merge_tr(cur, all[rem][max(mx, x)]);
    }

    return cur;
}

// ll maxd(ll v){ ll m=0; while(v){ m=max(m,v%10); v/=10; } return m; }

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    for(int m = 0; m < 10; m++) one[m] = build_one(m);

    for(int mx = 0; mx < 10; mx++) all[0][mx] = one[mx];

    for(int len = 1; len < 20; len++) {
        for(int mx = 0; mx < 10; mx++) {
            Tr cur;
            for(int d = 9; d >= 0; d--) {
                cur = merge_tr(cur, all[len - 1][max(mx, d)]);
            }
            all[len][mx] = cur;
        }
    }

    ll n;
    cin >> n;

    // ll steps = 0;
    // while(n > 0){ ll g = maxd(n); n -= g; steps++; }
    // cout << steps << "\n";

    if(n == 0) {
        cout << 0 << '\n';
        return 0;
    }

    if(n < 10) {
        cout << 1 << '\n';
        return 0;
    }

    ll p = n / 10;
    int r = n % 10;

    string sp = to_string(p);
    Tr res = go(sp, 0, 0);

    ll ans = res.add[r] + (res.to[r] > 0);

    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For 27, prefix $q=2$ has maximum digit 2 and remainder 7. Since $7\ge2$, the boundary transition takes two steps: $27\to20\to18$, leaving remainder 8 under prefix 1. Continuing gives $18\to10\to9\to0$, five steps total.

## Takeaway

When a huge deterministic process changes a high-order prefix slowly, summarize one prefix boundary as a tiny automaton and compose whole decimal blocks with digit DP.

### Related problems

Digit DP commonly composes finite-state transitions over all numbers in a decimal interval; here the transition also accumulates process cost.

