# Coin Arrangement

- **CSES task:** [Coin Arrangement](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2180)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (coinarrangement.cpp)`](./coinarrangement.cpp)

## Problem

Move coins along edges of a $2\times n$ grid until every cell contains one coin. Each coin-edge move costs one. Find the minimum total cost for $n\le10^5$.

## Reasoning

This is minimum-cost flow on a ladder, but its cuts reduce it to one dimension. Let

$$p_j=\sum_{c=1}^j(top_c+bottom_c-2)$$

be the surplus in the first $j$ columns. Exactly $p_j$ net coins must cross boundary $j$ horizontally. Any flow therefore pays at least $|p_j|$ there, and equality is attainable when the top and bottom horizontal flows have no cancellation.

Let $x_j$ be the signed top-row part of that boundary flow. To avoid cancellation, it may be any value in

$$I_j=[\min(0,p_j),\max(0,p_j)].$$

The bottom flow is then $p_j-x_j$. With outer values $x_0=x_n=0$, top-row conservation makes the vertical flow in column $j$

$$top_j-1-(x_j-x_{j-1}).$$

For fixed $x_{j-1}$, zero vertical cost would choose `ideal = x_{j-1}+top_j-1`. The best legal $x_j$ is its projection onto interval $I_j$; the distance to that interval is the unavoidable vertical cost. This projection remains globally safe because the optimal suffix cost is convex and 1-Lipschitz in the entering flow, so moving farther than the nearest feasible point cannot recover the extra current distance later.

## Algorithm

Scan columns while maintaining prefix surplus and the chosen top horizontal flow `x`. Add $|p_j|$ for every internal boundary. Form its feasible interval, project `x+top[j]-1` into it, add the projection distance, and continue. At the final outer boundary force interval `{0}`.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Every solution pays at least $\sum_{j<n}|p_j|$ horizontal cost, and flows parameterized by $x_j\in I_j$ attain exactly this cost.

**Proof.** Cut conservation forces total signed flow $p_j$. The triangle inequality bounds the sum of absolute top and bottom flows by $|p_j|$, with equality exactly when they share its sign, equivalent to $x_j\in I_j$. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** Given the previous chosen flow, projecting the zero-vertical-cost ideal onto $I_j$ is compatible with an optimal completion.

**Proof.** Vertical cost is the distance from $x_j$ to the ideal. The suffix optimum is convex with slope magnitude at most one because changing entering flow by one can be carried through at cost at most one. Therefore moving past the nearest feasible point adds at least as much current cost as it can save later. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm computes the minimum number of coin moves.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 fixes the minimum horizontal contribution and characterizes all flows attaining it. Within that corridor, repeated application of Lemma 2 minimizes vertical cost without losing an optimal suffix. The resulting conserved flow is feasible and has minimum total cost. $\square$

### Complexity

The scan takes $O(n)$ time and $O(n)$ input storage.

## Implementation

`pre` is $p_j$, while `x` is the previous top-row boundary flow. The last column uses the singleton interval zero because no flow may leave the grid.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<ll> top(n), bot(n);
    for(auto& v : top) cin >> v;
    for(auto& v : bot) cin >> v;

    // horizontal across boundary j is forced to pre_j = prefix(t-2); split between rows is free within [min(0,pre),max(0,pre)]
    // vertical = min over splits of sum |(top_j-1) - (x_j - x_{j-1})|, x_0=x_n=0 ; clamp the ideal top-prefix into the corridor
    ll h = 0, x = 0, v = 0, pre = 0;
    for(int j = 1; j <= n; j++){
        pre += top[j-1] + bot[j-1] - 2;                       // running prefix of (t-2); boundary right of col j
        ll lo, hi;
        if(j <= n-1){ lo = min(0LL, pre); hi = max(0LL, pre); h += llabs(pre); }   // free range; horizontal cost
        else { lo = hi = 0; }                                 // outer boundary carries no flow
        ll ideal = x + (top[j-1] - 1);                        // x making v_j = 0
        ll nx = max(lo, min(hi, ideal));                      // clamp into corridor
        v += llabs(ideal - nx);                               // unavoidable vertical at column j
        x = nx;
    }
    cout << h + v << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

If the first-column total surplus is 2, exactly two coins cross its right boundary and horizontal cost is 2. The top share may range from 0 to 2. If top-cell balance makes its ideal share 3, clamping chooses 2 and forces one vertical move.

## Takeaway

On a narrow grid, cut imbalances often force most transportation cost. The remaining freedom may form intervals, turning min-cost flow into projection along a corridor.

### Related problems

Food Division similarly converts local transport into prefix imbalances, with a cycle parameter minimized by a median.

