# Replace with Difference

- **CSES task:** [Replace with Difference](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3159)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (replacewithdifference.cpp)`](./replacewithdifference.cpp)

## Problem

Repeatedly replace two multiset values $a,b$ by $|a-b|$. Construct $n-1$ operations leaving zero, or report that this is impossible. Here $n,x_i\le1000$.

## Reasoning

Expanding the final nested differences expresses it as the absolute value of a signed sum of the original numbers, with every coefficient either 1 or $-1$. Reaching zero therefore requires a partition of the input into two groups of equal sum. Conversely, such a partition is sufficient.

Maintain two piles with equal total. Take one value from each and replace them by their difference. Put the difference back on the side of the larger value. If $a\ge b$, replacing $a$ on the first side by $a-b$ preserves equality of pile sums; the symmetric case does the same for the other side. Each cross reduction decreases the total number of values. When one side empties, equality forces every remaining value on the other side to be zero, and those zeros can be merged arbitrarily.

A subset-sum bitset finds and reconstructs the initial equal partition.

## Algorithm

Reject odd total sum. Build prefix subset-sum bitsets and test half the total. Backtrack one subset of that sum; the complement is the other pile. Repeatedly pair values across piles, print the operation, and return the difference to the larger side. Finally merge leftover zeros.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** A solution exists only if the input multiset has an equal-sum bipartition.

**Proof.** Recursively expand each difference, choosing the sign induced by which operand is larger. The final value is an absolute signed sum using every original number once. If it is zero, positive-sign and negative-sign elements have equal sums. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** Every cross-pile operation preserves equality of pile sums and matches a legal multiset operation.

**Proof.** If $a\ge b$, removing $a$ from pile A and $b$ from pile B makes A smaller by $a$ and B smaller by $b$. Adding $a-b$ to A leaves both decreased by $b$. The printed operation inserts exactly $|a-b|$. The other case is symmetric. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm prints a valid zero-producing sequence exactly when one exists.

**Proof.** Lemma 1 justifies rejecting when no half-sum subset exists. Otherwise Lemma 2 maintains equal piles while reducing their combined item count. If one pile empties, its sum is zero, so equality and nonnegativity make every remaining value zero. Merging them leaves one zero after exactly $n-1$ operations. $\square$

### Complexity

The prefix bitsets use $O(nS/64)$ word operations and $O(nS)$ bits, where $S$ is half the total and is at most 500000. Reconstruction and operation generation are $O(n)$. 

## Implementation

All prefix DP layers are retained because reconstruction asks whether sum `t-x[i]` was reachable before item `i`. The two piles store values, not indices, matching the required output format.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;
const int MAXS = 500001;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<int> x(n); ll T = 0;
    for(auto& v : x){ cin >> v; T += v; }

    if(T & 1){ cout << -1 << "\n"; return 0; }            // sum parity invariant under |a-b|
    int S = T / 2;

    // prefix subset-sum bitsets to reconstruct a part A summing to S
    vector<bitset<MAXS>> dp(n + 1);
    dp[0][0] = 1;
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) dp[i+1] = dp[i] | (dp[i] << x[i]);
    if(!dp[n][S]){ cout << -1 << "\n"; return 0; }         // no balanced partition (e.g. [2,2,2])

    vector<char> inA(n, 0); int t = S;
    for(int i = n; i >= 1; i--) if(t >= x[i-1] && dp[i-1][t - x[i-1]]){ inA[i-1] = 1; t -= x[i-1]; }   // backtrack A

    vector<ll> PA, PB;
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) (inA[i] ? PA : PB).pb(x[i]);

    // cross-reduce: pair across piles, |a-b| joins the larger side; sum(PA)==sum(PB) invariant => ends at single 0
    vii ops; ops.reserve(n - 1);
    while(!PA.empty() && !PB.empty()){
        ll a = PA.back(); PA.pop_back();
        ll b = PB.back(); PB.pop_back();
        ops.pb({a, b});
        ll d = llabs(a - b);
        (a >= b ? PA : PB).pb(d);
    }
    vector<ll>& R = PA.empty() ? PB : PA;                  // leftover side is all zeros
    while(R.size() > 1){ ll a = R.back(); R.pop_back(); ll b = R.back(); R.pop_back(); ops.pb({a, b}); R.pb(llabs(a - b)); }

    string out; out.reserve(ops.size() * 14);
    for(auto& o : ops){ out += to_string(o.f); out += ' '; out += to_string(o.s); out += '\n'; }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

Values `[2,7,4,12,1]` split as `{2,12}` and `{7,4,1}`, both summing to 14. Pairing 12 with 7 returns 5 to the first pile; repeated cross-pile differences preserve equal totals until two equal values produce zero.

## Takeaway

Nested absolute differences hide a signed-sum invariant. Search for an equal partition, then preserve it constructively under each operation.

### Related problems

Partition and subset-sum reconstruction problems use the same prefix-bitset backtracking.

