# Grid Puzzle I

- **CSES task:** [Grid Puzzle I](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2432)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (gridpuzzle1.cpp)`](./gridpuzzle1.cpp)

## Problem

Construct a binary $n\times n$ grid with prescribed row sums $a_i$ and column sums $b_j$, or report impossibility. Here $n\le50$.

## Reasoning

Interpret each row as a vertex that must connect to $a_i$ column vertices, while column $j$ needs degree $b_j$. This is bipartite degree-sequence realization.

Process rows in input order. For a row needing $a_i$ cells, choose columns with the largest remaining demands. This Havel-Hakimi step is safe: if some valid completion connects the current row to a lower-demand column $q$ but not to a higher-demand column $p$, then some later row connects to $p$ but not $q$. Swapping those two selected cells preserves every row and column total. Repeating exchanges produces a completion containing the greedy choices.

## Algorithm

First require equal total row and column demand. For each row, sort column indices by residual demand and select the first $a_i$, rejecting if any has no remaining demand. Decrement selected demands. At the end require every column demand to be zero.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** If the residual instance is feasible, selecting the largest-demand columns for the current row preserves feasibility.

**Proof.** Apply the exchange described above to every inversion between a greedy selected column and a nongreedy selected column. Each exchange preserves all degrees and increases agreement with the greedy set until all greedy choices occur. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm prints a valid grid exactly when one exists.

**Proof.** If it finishes with zero residual demands, construction directly satisfies all margins. If it rejects a row, fewer than $a_i$ columns have positive capacity, so no placement is possible. Otherwise Lemma 1 inductively proves that a feasible instance remains feasible after every greedy row; consequently a valid instance cannot end with leftover demand. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting $n$ columns for each row takes $O(n^2\log n)$ time. The grid and residual arrays use $O(n^2)$ space.

## Implementation

The equal-total test is necessary but not sufficient; positive residual checks and the final zero check detect the remaining impossible degree sequences.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<int> a(n), b(n);
    for(auto& v : a) cin >> v;
    for(auto& v : b) cin >> v;

    ll sa = accumulate(a.begin(), a.end(), 0LL), sb = accumulate(b.begin(), b.end(), 0LL);
    if(sa != sb){ cout << -1 << "\n"; return 0; }

    vector<string> g(n, string(n, '.'));
    vector<int> col(b);                                  // residual column demand
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        // place a[i] X's into columns of largest residual demand (Gale-Ryser greedy)
        vector<int> idx(n); iota(idx.begin(), idx.end(), 0);
        sort(idx.begin(), idx.end(), [&](int p, int q){ return col[p] > col[q]; });
        if(a[i] > n){ cout << -1 << "\n"; return 0; }
        for(int t = 0; t < a[i]; t++){
            int c = idx[t];
            if(col[c] <= 0){ cout << -1 << "\n"; return 0; }   // not enough columns with demand
            g[i][c] = 'X'; col[c]--;
        }
    }
    for(int c = 0; c < n; c++) if(col[c] != 0){ cout << -1 << "\n"; return 0; }   // leftover demand

    string out; out.reserve((size_t)n*(n+1));
    for(auto& r : g){ out += r; out += '\n'; }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

If residual column demands are `[1,2,2,0,1]` and the current row needs 3 cells, the greedy step chooses the two demand-2 columns and one demand-1 column. Any feasible solution choosing the other demand-1 column can be exchanged to this choice.

## Takeaway

Bipartite degree realization admits a Havel-Hakimi exchange: satisfy the next vertex using currently largest opposite-side demands.

### Related problems

Chess Tournament uses an analogous degree-sequence construction for a non-bipartite graph.

