# Grid Puzzle II

- **CSES task:** [Grid Puzzle II](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2131)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (gridpuzzle2.cpp)`](./gridpuzzle2.cpp)

## Problem

Choose grid cells with exact prescribed row and column counts while maximizing the sum of their coin values. Construct an optimum or report impossibility.

## Reasoning

This is a capacitated bipartite selection problem. Send $a_i$ units from a source to row $i$, at most one unit through each row-column cell edge, and $b_j$ units from column $j$ to the sink. An integral flow of total $\sum a_i$ corresponds exactly to a valid selected-cell grid.

Give cell edge $(i,j)$ cost $-c_{ij}$. Minimizing flow cost then maximizes collected coins. Unit capacities and integral augmentations guarantee a binary choice for every cell.

## Algorithm

Build the flow network with source-row capacities $a_i$, unit row-column edges of cost $-c_{ij}$, and column-sink capacities $b_j$. Repeatedly find a shortest residual path with SPFA and augment. Reject if maximum flow misses the required total. Otherwise print negative total cost and mark saturated cell edges.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Integral flows of required value correspond bijectively to valid grids.

**Proof.** Flow conservation makes each row send exactly $a_i$ units and each column receive exactly $b_j$. Unit cell capacities make each edge a binary selection. The reverse construction sends one unit through every selected cell. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The cost of a corresponding flow is the negative collected coin total.

**Proof.** Only cell edges have nonzero cost, and each selected cell contributes one unit times $-c_{ij}$. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm reports impossibility correctly or prints a maximum-value valid grid.

**Proof.** Missing required max flow means no corresponding grid by Lemma 1. Otherwise successive shortest augmenting paths produce a minimum-cost flow of that value. Lemma 2 converts its minimum cost into maximum collected value. $\square$

### Complexity

There are $O(n)$ vertices and $O(n^2)$ edges. With required flow $F\le n^2$, the SPFA implementation has a conservative $O(FVE)$ worst-case bound and $O(n^2)$ space; $n\le50$ keeps the network small.

## Implementation

Each forward cell edge index is saved before insertion. It is selected exactly when its residual capacity becomes zero. Reverse edges have negated costs, allowing later augmentations to revise earlier choices.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

struct MCMF {
    struct E{ int to, cap, cost, nxt; };
    vector<E> e; vector<int> head, dist, pre; vector<char> inq; int V;
    void init(int n){ V=n; head.assign(n,-1); e.clear(); }
    void add(int u,int v,int cap,int cost){
        e.pb({v,cap,cost,head[u]}); head[u]=e.size()-1;
        e.pb({u,0,-cost,head[v]}); head[v]=e.size()-1;
    }
    bool spfa(int s,int t){
        dist.assign(V,INF); pre.assign(V,-1); inq.assign(V,0);
        deque<int> q; dist[s]=0; q.pb(s); inq[s]=1;
        while(!q.empty()){
            int u=q.front(); q.pop_front(); inq[u]=0;
            for(int i=head[u];i!=-1;i=e[i].nxt) if(e[i].cap>0 && dist[u]+e[i].cost<dist[e[i].to]){
                dist[e[i].to]=dist[u]+e[i].cost; pre[e[i].to]=i;
                if(!inq[e[i].to]){ inq[e[i].to]=1; q.pb(e[i].to); }
            }
        }
        return dist[t]<INF;
    }
    pair<int,ll> run(int s,int t){           // (maxflow, mincost)
        int fl=0; ll cost=0;
        while(spfa(s,t)){
            int f=INF;
            for(int v=t; v!=s; v=e[pre[v]^1].to) f=min(f,e[pre[v]].cap);
            for(int v=t; v!=s; v=e[pre[v]^1].to){ e[pre[v]].cap-=f; e[pre[v]^1].cap+=f; }
            fl+=f; cost+=(ll)f*dist[t];
        }
        return {fl,cost};
    }
};

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<int> a(n), b(n);
    for(auto& v : a) cin >> v;
    for(auto& v : b) cin >> v;
    vector<vector<int>> c(n, vector<int>(n));
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++) for(int j=0;j<n;j++) cin >> c[i][j];

    ll sa=accumulate(a.begin(),a.end(),0LL), sb=accumulate(b.begin(),b.end(),0LL);
    if(sa!=sb){ cout<<-1<<"\n"; return 0; }

    // S=0, rows 1..n, cols n+1..2n, T=2n+1 ; mid edge cost -c to maximize
    int S=0, T=2*n+1;
    MCMF mc; mc.init(2*n+2);
    int eidRC[55][55];
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++) mc.add(S, 1+i, a[i], 0);
    for(int j=0;j<n;j++) mc.add(1+n+j, T, b[j], 0);
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++) for(int j=0;j<n;j++){ eidRC[i][j]=mc.e.size(); mc.add(1+i, 1+n+j, 1, -c[i][j]); }

    auto [fl, cost] = mc.run(S, T);
    if(fl != sa){ cout<<-1<<"\n"; return 0; }            // can't satisfy margins

    cout << -cost << "\n";
    string out; out.reserve((size_t)n*(n+1));
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        string row(n,'.');
        for(int j=0;j<n;j++) if(mc.e[eidRC[i][j]].cap==0) row[j]='X';   // saturated mid edge = chosen
        out += row; out += '\n';
    }
    cout << out;
}
```

## Worked Example

If one row and one column each require one cell, every source-to-sink path represents choosing a cell in their intersection structure. Negative edge costs make the shortest path choose the greatest coin value while respecting all other capacities.

## Takeaway

Exact row and column quotas form a transportation network. Adding per-cell values turns feasibility into min-cost flow without changing the model.

### Related problems

Task Assignment is another bipartite min-cost flow model with unit choices.

