# Bit Substrings

- **CSES task:** [Bit Substrings](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2115)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (bitsubstrings.cpp)`](./bitsubstrings.cpp)

## Problem

For every $k=0,\ldots,n$, count nonempty substrings of a binary string containing exactly $k$ ones. Here $n\le2\cdot10^5$.

## Reasoning

Let $p_i$ be the number of ones in the first $i$ characters, including $p_0=0$. Substring $(l,r]$ contains $k$ ones exactly when $p_r-p_l=k$.

Let `cnt[t]` be the number of prefixes with sum $t$. For $k>0$, every prefix with sum $t$ precedes every prefix with sum $t+k$ because prefix sums are nondecreasing. Thus

$$\operatorname{ans}[k]=\sum_t cnt[t]cnt[t+k].$$

These are all cross-correlations of `cnt` with itself. Reverse one copy and compute one polynomial convolution by FFT. For $k=0$, pairs must use two distinct equal-sum prefixes, contributing $\binom{cnt[t]}2$.

## Algorithm

Build prefix-sum frequencies. Compute the zero answer directly. Convolve `cnt` with its reversal using FFT and read the coefficient corresponding to each positive difference $k$. Print zeros for $k$ beyond the total number of ones.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** For $k>0$, $\sum_t cnt[t]cnt[t+k]$ counts every substring with $k$ ones exactly once.

**Proof.** Each substring corresponds to its unique endpoint-prefix pair. Since the sums differ positively and prefix sums never decrease, every chosen lower-sum prefix occurs earlier, so every frequency pair is a valid ordered endpoint pair. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The convolution coefficient read by the implementation equals this cross-correlation.

**Proof.** Reversing one frequency array converts an index difference into an index sum. Expanding coefficient `S+k` gives the same products `cnt[t]cnt[t+k]` after reindexing. $\square$

**Theorem.** All printed counts are correct.

**Proof.** Equal-sum prefix pairs are counted by the binomial formula for $k=0$. Lemmas 1 and 2 prove every positive-$k$ entry. Differences larger than the total ones are impossible and remain zero. $\square$

### Complexity

The FFT convolution takes $O(n\log n)$ time and $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

Complex coefficients are rounded to the nearest integer after the inverse FFT. Counts and products use `long long`; up to $n(n+1)/2$ substrings may contribute.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")

#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second

typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;

const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

// const ll M1 = 998244353, M2 = 1004535809, G = 3;

// ll pw(ll a, ll b, ll m){ ll r=1; a%=m; while(b){ if(b&1) r=(__int128)r*a%m; a=(__int128)a*a%m; b>>=1; } return r; }

// void ntt(vector<ll>& a, ll mod, bool inv){
//     int n=a.size();
//     for(int i=1,j=0;i<n;i++){ int bit=n>>1; for(;j&bit;bit>>=1) j^=bit; j^=bit; if(i<j) swap(a[i],a[j]); }
//     for(int len=2;len<=n;len<<=1){
//         ll w=pw(G, (mod-1)/len, mod); if(inv) w=pw(w, mod-2, mod);
//         for(int i=0;i<n;i+=len){ ll wn=1;
//             for(int k=0;k<len/2;k++){ ll u=a[i+k], v=(__int128)a[i+k+len/2]*wn%mod;
//                 a[i+k]=(u+v)%mod; a[i+k+len/2]=(u-v+mod)%mod; wn=(__int128)wn*w%mod; } }
//     }
//     if(inv){ ll ni=pw(n, mod-2, mod); for(auto& x:a) x=(__int128)x*ni%mod; }
// }

// vector<ll> mul(vector<ll> a, vector<ll> b, ll mod){
//     int rs=a.size()+b.size()-1, sz=1; while(sz<rs) sz<<=1;
//     a.resize(sz); b.resize(sz); ntt(a,mod,false); ntt(b,mod,false);
//     for(int i=0;i<sz;i++) a[i]=(__int128)a[i]*b[i]%mod;
//     ntt(a,mod,true); a.resize(rs); return a;
