# GCD Subsets

- **CSES task:** [GCD Subsets](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3161)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (gcdsubsets.cpp)`](./gcdsubsets.cpp)

## Problem

For every $d=1,\ldots,n$, count nonempty subsets whose gcd is exactly $d$. Values and $n$ are at most $2\cdot10^5$.

## Reasoning

Let $m_d$ be the number of input elements divisible by $d$. Every nonempty subset drawn from these elements has gcd divisible by $d$, so there are

$$F_d=2^{m_d}-1$$

such subsets. If `ans[e]` counts exact gcd $e$, then

$$F_d=\sum_{d\mid e}\operatorname{ans}[e].$$

Process $d$ downward. All proper multiples $2d,3d,\ldots$ have already been solved, so subtracting their exact counts isolates gcd $d$. Counts $m_d$ come from a sieve over multiples.

## Algorithm

Build value frequencies and powers of two. For every $d$, sum frequencies at its multiples. Then iterate $d$ from $n$ down to 1, initialize with $2^{m_d}-1$, and subtract answers of all larger multiples.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** $2^{m_d}-1$ counts exactly the nonempty subsets whose gcd is a multiple of $d$.

**Proof.** Such a subset may use any nonempty selection of the elements divisible by $d$, and it cannot contain any other element. $\square$

**Theorem.** `ans[d]` equals the number of subsets with gcd exactly $d$.

**Proof.** By Lemma 1, the initial count partitions disjointly by exact gcd over multiples of $d$. Descending order has already computed every proper multiple, and subtracting them leaves precisely exact gcd $d$. $\square$

### Complexity

The harmonic multiple loops take $O(n\log n)$ time. Arrays use $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

Every subtraction adds `MOD` before reduction to avoid negative residues. The empty subset is excluded in the initial `2^m-1`, so it never enters any exact-gcd class.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<int> freq(n + 1, 0);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){ int x; cin >> x; freq[x]++; }

    vector<ll> pw(n + 1); pw[0] = 1;
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) pw[i] = pw[i-1] * 2 % MOD;

    vector<ll> m(n + 1, 0);
    for(int d = 1; d <= n; d++) for(int j = d; j <= n; j += d) m[d] += freq[j];   // multiples count

    vector<ll> ans(n + 1, 0);
    for(int d = n; d >= 1; d--){
        ll F = (pw[m[d]] - 1 + MOD) % MOD;                     // 2^{m_d} - 1
        for(int e = 2*d; e <= n; e += d) F = (F - ans[e] + MOD) % MOD;   // strip exact gcd = multiple of d
        ans[d] = F;
    }

    string out; out.reserve(n * 7);
    for(int d = 1; d <= n; d++){ out += to_string(ans[d]); out += ' '; }
    cout << out << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

For values `[2,4]`, $m_2=2$, so three nonempty subsets have gcd divisible by 2. One subset, `{4}`, has exact gcd 4. Subtracting it leaves two subsets with exact gcd 2.

## Takeaway

When objects classified by exact gcd are easy to count by divisibility, invert the relation by subtracting larger multiples in descending order.

### Related problems

Counting Coprime Pairs uses Möbius inversion over the same divisor lattice.

