# Minimum Cost Pairs

- **CSES task:** [Minimum Cost Pairs](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3402)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (minimumcostpairs.cpp)`](./minimumcostpairs.cpp)

## Problem

For every $k=1,\ldots,\lfloor n/2\rfloor$, find the minimum total absolute difference of $k$ disjoint pairs chosen from $n\le2\cdot10^5$ values.

## Reasoning

Sort the values. Crossing pairs can be uncrossed: for $a\le b\le c\le d$,

$$(c-a)+(d-b)\ge(b-a)+(d-c).$$

Thus an optimum can be represented by a matching on the ordered line and improved by alternating paths between adjacent gaps.

Start with no pairs. The increase from an optimum of size $k$ to one of size $k+1$ is the cheapest augmenting path. Initially each adjacent gap is a one-edge candidate. After choosing candidate edge $i$, an interior augmenting path may later undo it and take its two neighboring candidates instead. Its reduced incremental cost is

$$w_{left}+w_{right}-w_i.$$

Contract the three candidates into one node with this weight. At a boundary, no two-sided replacement exists, so the selected edge and its only neighbor disappear. A heap always selects the least current reduced cost. This is the specialized primal-dual shortest-augmenting-path algorithm for minimum-weight matching on a line.

## Algorithm

Sort values and create adjacent gap nodes in a doubly linked list. Put every gap in a min heap. Repeatedly extract the least live weight, add it to the cumulative optimum, and output that cumulative value. For an interior node, replace it by a contracted node of weight `left+right-current` and delete its neighbors. At a boundary, delete it and the existing neighbor.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** For each cardinality, some optimal pairing is noncrossing in sorted order.

**Proof.** Replacing two crossing pairs by the outer-neighbor pairing shown above does not increase cost and removes a crossing. Repetition terminates. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The live nodes represent exactly the reduced costs of all possible next augmenting paths.

**Proof.** Initially every path is one adjacent gap. Selecting an interior path makes the only new local alternative the alternating replacement using its left and right neighbors, whose net cost is their sum minus the selected cost. Contracting stores exactly this path; other disjoint candidates are unchanged. Boundary selection has no replacement path and removes the consumed neighborhood. Induction preserves the representation. $\square$

**Theorem.** After iteration $k$, the cumulative value is the minimum cost of $k$ pairs.

**Proof.** By Lemma 1, it suffices to optimize line matchings. Minimum-cost matching augmentation chooses the least reduced-cost augmenting path. Lemma 2 makes that path the minimum live heap node, so each iteration extends an optimum of size $k-1$ to one of size $k$ with minimum possible increase. Induction proves all reported costs. $\square$

### Complexity

Sorting costs $O(n\log n)$. Each gap is inserted and deleted a constant number of times, so heap processing is $O(n\log n)$ time and $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

Arrays `L` and `R` form the linked list of contracted candidates. Heap records can become stale; `dead[i]` and the equality check against current `val[i]` discard them safely.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#pragma GCC target("avx2")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
const int MOD = 1e9+7;
int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n; cin >> n;
    vector<ll> x(n);
    for (auto& v : x) cin >> v;
    sort(x.begin(), x.end());

    int m = n - 1;                      // gap edges
    vector<int> L(m), R(m);
    vector<ll> val(m);
    vector<char> dead(m, 0);
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) { val[i] = x[i+1] - x[i]; L[i] = i - 1; R[i] = i + 1; }

    priority_queue<pair<ll,int>, vector<pair<ll,int>>, greater<>> pq;
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) pq.push({val[i], i});

    int K = n / 2, done = 0;
    ll cum = 0;
    string out;
    while (done < K && !pq.empty()) {
        auto [w, i] = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        if (dead[i] || w != val[i]) continue;       // stale heap entry
        cum += val[i];
        out += to_string(cum);
        out += (done == K - 1 ? '\n' : ' ');
        done++;

        int l = L[i], r = R[i];
        if (l >= 0 && r < m) {                       // interior: swap-back merge
            val[i] = val[l] + val[r] - val[i];
            dead[l] = dead[r] = 1;
            int ll_ = L[l], rr_ = R[r];
            L[i] = ll_; R[i] = rr_;
            if (ll_ >= 0) R[ll_] = i;
            if (rr_ < m) L[rr_] = i;
            pq.push({val[i], i});
        } else {                                     // boundary: no swap-back
            dead[i] = 1;
            if (l >= 0) { dead[l] = 1; int ll_ = L[l]; if (ll_ >= 0) R[ll_] = r; if (r < m) L[r] = ll_; }
            else if (r < m) { dead[r] = 1; int rr_ = R[r]; if (rr_ < m) L[rr_] = l; if (l >= 0) R[l] = rr_; }
        }
    }
    cout << out;
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For sorted values `[1,2,4,7]`, initial gaps are 1, 2, and 3. Choosing gap 1 gives the first optimum cost 1. The interior replacement candidate becomes $2+3-1=4$; the next cumulative optimum is $1+4=5$, corresponding to pairs `(1,2)` and `(4,7)`.

## Takeaway

Minimum matchings on a line admit local alternating-path contraction. Heap keys are marginal augmentation costs, not necessarily original edge costs.

### Related problems

General weighted matching also uses augmenting paths and reduced costs, but line order collapses the machinery to a linked list and heap.

