# Same Sum Subsets

- **CSES task:** [Same Sum Subsets](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/3425)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (samesumsubsets.cpp)`](./samesumsubsets.cpp)

## Problem

Choose two nonempty disjoint subsets with equal sum from a set of $3\le n\le40$ positive integers. The total sum is at most $2^n-2$.

## Reasoning

There are $2^n$ subsets but at most `total+1 <= 2^n-1` possible sums. Pigeonhole guarantees two distinct subsets with equal sum. Removing their common elements leaves two disjoint equal-sum subsets; positivity guarantees neither difference is empty.

We still cannot enumerate all $2^n$ subsets. Split elements into two halves and enumerate their subset sums, at most $2^{20}$ each. A duplicate sum within either half immediately solves the problem. Otherwise both half-sum arrays contain distinct values.

Every full subset sum is a pair $A_i+B_j$. There are more such pairs than values in their total integer range, so some value has two representations. To locate one without forming the Cartesian product, use `cntLE(X)`, computed in linear time by two pointers on sorted half sums. Maintain a value interval containing more pairs than integer values. At a midpoint, if the lower half has too many pairs, retain it; otherwise the upper half must retain the pigeonhole excess. Binary search ends at one value with at least two representations.

## Algorithm

Enumerate, pack, radix-sort, and unpack subset sums and masks for both halves. Check adjacent equal sums within each half. Otherwise binary-search a colliding cross-sum using pair-count queries. Find two representations with lower bounds, combine their half masks, remove common bits, and output values selected by the two remaining masks.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Two distinct equal-sum subsets yield two valid disjoint nonempty equal-sum subsets after removing their intersection.

**Proof.** Removing common elements subtracts the same sum from both. If one difference were empty, positivity would make a proper superset have strictly larger sum, contradicting equality. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The value-range binary search terminates at a sum having at least two half-pair representations.

**Proof.** Its invariant is that the current interval contains more representing pairs than integer values. If the lower interval has excess, keep it. Otherwise its pair count is at most its width, so subtracting it from the parent excess leaves excess in the upper interval. At width one, excess means at least two pairs share that value. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm always prints valid same-sum disjoint subsets.

**Proof.** The input bound guarantees a collision by pigeonhole. An internal-half collision is detected directly; otherwise Lemma 2 finds a cross collision. The two reconstructed full subset masks are distinct and equal-sum, so Lemma 1 converts them to the required output. $\square$

### Complexity

Let $N=2^{\lceil n/2\rceil}$. Enumeration and radix sorting take $O(N)$ time. Each of $O(n+\log\sum x_i)=O(n)$ value-search levels uses an $O(N)$ pair count, for $O(nN)$ time and $O(N)$ space.

## Implementation

Each radix key packs the sum above 20 mask bits; half sizes never exceed 20. `cntLE` uses one monotone pointer into `Bs`. The final xor-like set differences `fA & ~fB` and `fB & ~fA` remove the common intersection.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int n, n1, n2;
vector<ll> x, As, Bs;
vector<int> Am, Bm;

void radix(vector<ull>& a){                          // LSD radix, 4x16-bit passes (keys < 2^60)
    int sz = a.size(); vector<ull> b(sz);
    for(int p = 0; p < 4; p++){
        int sh = p*16; int cnt[65536] = {0};
        for(int i = 0; i < sz; i++) cnt[(a[i]>>sh)&0xFFFF]++;
        int s = 0; for(int j = 0; j < 65536; j++){ int t = cnt[j]; cnt[j] = s; s += t; }
        for(int i = 0; i < sz; i++){ int d = (a[i]>>sh)&0xFFFF; b[cnt[d]++] = a[i]; }
        swap(a, b);
    }
}

static inline ll cntLE(ll X){                        // pairs As[i]+Bs[j] <= X, monotone two-pointer
    ll c = 0; int j = (int)Bs.size()-1, M = (int)As.size();
    const ll* __restrict a = As.data(); const ll* __restrict b = Bs.data();
    for(int i = 0; i < M; i++){ ll t = X - a[i]; while(j >= 0 && b[j] > t) j--; c += j+1; }
    return c;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr);
    cin >> n; x.resize(n);
    for(auto& v : x) cin >> v;
    n1 = n/2; n2 = n - n1;

    // half subset sums via DP, packed as (sum<<20)|mask, radix-sorted; split into contiguous arrays
    auto build=[&](int base,int cnt,vector<ll>&Sout,vector<int>&Mout){
        int sz = 1<<cnt; vector<ull> key(sz);
        { vector<ll> S(sz,0);
          for(int m=1;m<sz;m++){ int b=__builtin_ctz(m); S[m]=S[m^(1<<b)]+x[base+b]; }
          for(int m=0;m<sz;m++) key[m]=((ull)S[m]<<20)|(ull)m; }
        radix(key);
        Sout.resize(sz); Mout.resize(sz);
        for(int i=0;i<sz;i++){ Sout[i]=(ll)(key[i]>>20); Mout[i]=(int)(key[i]&((1<<20)-1)); }
    };
    build(0,n1,As,Am); build(n1,n2,Bs,Bm);

    auto outPair=[&](ll fA,ll fB){
        ll a=fA&~fB, b=fB&~fA;                        // strip common -> disjoint, both nonempty
        string out;
        auto dump=[&](ll mk){ out+=to_string(__builtin_popcountll(mk)); for(int i=0;i<n;i++) if(mk>>i&1){ out+=' '; out+=to_string(x[i]); } out+='\n'; };
        dump(a); dump(b); cout<<out;
    };

    for(int i=1;i<(int)As.size();i++) if(As[i]==As[i-1]){ outPair((ll)Am[i],(ll)Am[i-1]); return 0; }   // internal half1
    for(int i=1;i<(int)Bs.size();i++) if(Bs[i]==Bs[i-1]){ outPair((ll)Bm[i]<<n1,(ll)Bm[i-1]<<n1); return 0; } // internal half2

    // cross: value-range bisection; one cntLE per level via maintained belowLo
    ll lo=0, hi=As.back()+Bs.back(), belowLo=0;
    while(lo<hi){
        ll mid=lo+(hi-lo)/2;
        ll le=cntLE(mid), lc=le-belowLo;             // pairs in [lo,mid]
        if(lc>mid-lo+1) hi=mid; else { lo=mid+1; belowLo=le; }   // pigeonhole: keep the half guaranteed to hold a collision
    }
    ll v=lo; int got=0; ll fa[2],fb[2];
    for(int i=0;i<(int)As.size() && got<2;i++){
        ll need=v-As[i];
        int p=(int)(lower_bound(Bs.begin(),Bs.end(),need)-Bs.begin());
        if(p<(int)Bs.size() && Bs[p]==need){ fa[got]=Am[i]; fb[got]=Bm[p]; got++; }
    }
    outPair(fa[0]|((ll)fb[0]<<n1), fa[1]|((ll)fb[1]<<n1));
    return 0;
}
```

## Worked Example

For `[1,2,3]`, subsets `{1,2}` and `{3}` both sum to 3 and are already disjoint. In a collision such as `{1,2,5}` and `{2,7}`, removing common element 2 would preserve equal sums on the two residual subsets.

## Takeaway

Pigeonhole can guarantee a collision among exponentially many subset sums. Meet in the middle plus range counting can locate that collision without materializing all pair sums.

### Related problems

Meet in the Middle enumerates half sums for a single target; here pair-count binary search finds an unknown duplicated target.

