# Stick Divisions

- **CSES task:** [Stick Divisions](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1161)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (stickdivisions.cpp)`](./stickdivisions.cpp)

## Problem

Split a stick into prescribed final lengths. Splitting a current piece costs its length. Find the minimum total cost for up to $2\cdot10^5$ pieces.

## Reasoning

Reverse time. A split of length $a+b$ into pieces $a$ and $b$ becomes a merge of $a$ and $b$ costing $a+b$. We must merge all target pieces into one with minimum total merge cost, the optimal merge pattern problem.

The two smallest available pieces can be merged first in some optimum. In the binary merge tree, take the deepest sibling leaves; replacing them by the two smallest weights cannot increase any weighted depth. Contracting that sibling pair leaves the same problem on one fewer item. This exchange argument yields Huffman's greedy rule.

## Algorithm

Insert all target lengths into a min heap. Repeatedly remove the two smallest, add their sum to the answer, and insert the sum until one piece remains.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Some optimal merge tree makes the two smallest weights siblings at maximum depth.

**Proof.** Two deepest sibling leaves exist. Swapping their weights with the two smallest leaves cannot increase weighted external path length because smaller weights move no shallower than larger ones. $\square$

**Theorem.** The greedy heap algorithm has minimum total cost.

**Proof.** By Lemma 1, an optimum first merges the two smallest pieces. Contract them into one piece of their sum; the residual task is another optimal merge problem. Induction proves every greedy merge is compatible with an optimum. Reversing merges gives the required split plan with the same cost. $\square$

### Complexity

There are $n-1$ heap merges, taking $O(n\log n)$ time and $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

The given total stick length `x` is not needed after input because the prescribed pieces already sum to it. The accumulated merge cost uses `long long`.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    ll x; int n; cin >> x >> n;
    priority_queue<ll, vector<ll>, greater<ll>> pq;       // min-heap of stick lengths
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){ ll d; cin >> d; pq.push(d); }

    ll ans = 0;
    while(pq.size() > 1){                                  // Huffman merge: combine two smallest
        ll a = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        ll b = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        ans += a + b; pq.push(a + b);
    }
    cout << ans << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

For pieces 2, 3, and 3, merge 2 and 3 for cost 5, then merge 5 and 3 for cost 8. Total 13. Reversing these operations splits 8 into 5 and 3, then 5 into 2 and 3.

## Takeaway

When an operation recursively splits an object and charges its whole size, reversing it may reveal the Huffman optimal merge pattern.

### Related problems

Huffman coding proves the same greedy rule through weighted leaf depths.

