# Coding Company

- **CSES task:** [Coding Company](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1665)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (codingcompany.cpp)`](./codingcompany.cpp)

## Problem

Partition up to 100 labeled coders into teams. A team's penalty is its maximum skill minus its minimum skill. Count partitions whose total penalty is at most $x\le5000$.

## Reasoning

Sort coders by skill and sweep from low to high. A team becomes open when its minimum member is seen and closes when its maximum member is seen. Between consecutive skill levels separated by gap $g$, every currently open team contributes $g$ additional penalty. Thus only the number of open teams and accumulated penalty matter.

For the next coder there are four roles: start a new open team, form a singleton, join one of $j$ open teams without closing it, or close one of $j$ open teams. The latter two each have $j$ choices because coders are distinct and the open teams are distinguishable by their members.

## Algorithm

Let `dp[j][p]` count partial partitions with $j$ open teams and penalty $p$. Before assigning coder $i$, add $j$ times the skill gap. Apply the four role transitions. After all coders, sum `dp[0][p]` for $p\le x$.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Charging every open team for each crossed skill gap yields exactly the sum of final team penalties.

**Proof.** A team is open from its minimum skill through its maximum skill. The telescoping sum of crossed gaps on that interval is maximum minus minimum. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** The four transitions count every partial set partition exactly once.

**Proof.** In sorted order, a coder is uniquely the first member, sole member, internal member, or last member of its team. Joining or closing chooses one of the existing open teams, giving the factor $j$. These cases are disjoint and exhaustive. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm outputs the number of valid team divisions.

**Proof.** Lemma 2 establishes exact counting of partitions, while Lemma 1 establishes their recorded penalties. Requiring zero open teams ensures completion, and summing penalties through $x$ selects exactly valid partitions. $\square$

### Complexity

There are $O(nx)$ states per layer and up to $n$ open-team counts, for $O(n^2x)$ time and $O(nx)$ space.

## Implementation

Two DP layers prevent a coder from taking multiple roles. The gap is charged before processing the new coder because all previously open teams span from the prior skill to the current one.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#pragma GCC optimize("O3,unroll-loops")
#define pb push_back
#define f first
#define s second
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> ii;
typedef vector<ll> vi;
typedef vector<ii> vii;
typedef unsigned long long ull;
const ll MOD = 1e9 + 7;
const int INF = 1e9;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n, x; cin >> n >> x;
    vector<int> t(n);
    for(auto& v : t) cin >> v;
    sort(t.begin(), t.end());

    // dp[j][p]: ways with j open teams, accumulated penalty p (<=x). gap paid on crossing.
    vector<vector<ll>> dp(n + 2, vector<ll>(x + 1, 0));
    dp[0][0] = 1;
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        int g = i ? t[i] - t[i-1] : 0;                       // gap crossed entering coder i
        vector<vector<ll>> nd(n + 2, vector<ll>(x + 1, 0));
        for(int j = 0; j <= i; j++){
            for(int p = 0; p <= x; p++){
                ll w = dp[j][p]; if(!w) continue;
                int np = p + j * g;                          // j open teams pay the gap
                if(np > x) continue;                         // exceeds budget, prune
                // role of coder i:
                nd[j+1][np] = (nd[j+1][np] + w) % MOD;        // start new open team
                nd[j][np]   = (nd[j][np]   + w) % MOD;        // singleton (open+close)
                if(j > 0){
                    nd[j][np]   = (nd[j][np]   + w * j) % MOD; // join as middle of an open team
                    nd[j-1][np] = (nd[j-1][np] + w * j) % MOD; // close an open team
                }
            }
        }
        dp = move(nd);
    }

    ll ans = 0;
    for(int p = 0; p <= x; p++) ans = (ans + dp[0][p]) % MOD;   // all teams closed
    cout << ans << "\n";
}
```

## Worked Example

For sorted skills `[2,3,5]`, suppose one team is open before reaching 5. Crossing the gap from 3 to 5 adds 2 penalty. The coder of skill 5 may close that team, join it while leaving it open for later coders, start another team, or stand alone.

## Takeaway

For partitions whose group cost is maximum minus minimum, sort the elements and track open groups. Gap charging converts endpoint costs into local DP transitions.

### Related problems

Interval sweep DPs often use the same open-component count to charge costs across coordinate gaps.

