# Two Stacks Sorting

- **CSES task:** [Two Stacks Sorting](https://cses.fi/problemset/task/2402)
- **Code:** [`View accepted C++ solution (twostackssorting.cpp)`](./twostackssorting.cpp)

## Problem

Read a permutation left to right, pushing each value onto one of two stacks. Values may be popped to produce increasing order. Assign every input value to a stack, or report impossibility.

## Reasoning

Two input positions $i<j$ are incompatible in one stack when

$$v_i<v_j
\quad\text{and}
\min_{k>j}v_k<v_i.$$

If both enter one stack, $v_j$ lies above $v_i$, but the still-unread smaller value must be output before $v_i$; this traps the required order. Build a conflict graph on values, joining every incompatible pair. A valid two-stack assignment is exactly a proper 2-coloring of this graph.

Enumerating edges is quadratic. Process current value $x=v_j$ and let $z$ be the minimum unread suffix. Its earlier conflict neighbors are exactly previously seen values in interval $(z,x)$. All these neighbors must receive the same color, opposite to $x$. A parity DSU can impose equality among the interval values and inequality between $x$ and one representative.

An ordered set stores seen values. To merge all values inside an interval efficiently, keep links between consecutive active values that have not yet been equated. Each link is consumed once when an interval spans it, giving an amortized near-linear number of DSU unions.

## Algorithm

Precompute suffix minima. Scan the permutation. For each $x$ with unread minimum below it, find seen values in `(minimum,x)`. Union consecutive values in that interval with parity zero, then union $x$ with one representative using parity one. Detect inconsistent parity equations. Insert $x$ into the ordered set and its new consecutive links. Finally output each value's parity class plus one.

## Correctness

**Lemma 1.** Two values must use different stacks exactly when they form the stated forbidden pattern.

**Proof.** The pattern traps the smaller earlier value below the larger later value while an even smaller unread value must be output first, proving necessity. If no such pattern occurs within either color, repeatedly popping the next required exposed value never gets stuck; a stuck top would identify a larger later value above a needed earlier one and an unread smaller witness, producing the pattern. $\square$

**Lemma 2.** For each current $x$, the algorithm imposes inequality with exactly all its earlier conflict neighbors.

**Proof.** By the pattern definition, those neighbors are precisely seen values $y$ satisfying `suffixMin < y < x`. Equating all interval values and making $x$ opposite their representative imposes all and only those conflict edges. $\square$

**Theorem.** The algorithm prints a valid stack assignment exactly when one exists.

**Proof.** Lemma 2 makes DSU parity consistency equivalent to bipartiteness of the conflict graph. If inconsistent, no 2-coloring exists. Otherwise DSU parities form a proper coloring, which is a valid stack assignment by Lemma 1. $\square$

### Complexity

Suffix minima take $O(n)$. Ordered-set operations and amortized DSU link processing take $O(n\log n)$ time and $O(n)$ space.

## Implementation

`xr[v]` stores parity from a DSU node to its parent. `unite(a,b,w)` enforces `color[a] xor color[b] = w`. The `bad` set stores left endpoints of still-unprocessed consecutive active links.

### Accepted C++17 implementation

